<SLUG> BC-BUSH-DEBATE-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-530(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH ANNOUNCES ALTERNATE PLAN FOR DEBATES
</HEADLINE>
 (Subs for rewriting thruout, no factual changes) 
By ALISON MITCHELL  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Trying to end questions about his willingness to
debate and turn the tables on his opponent, Gov. George W. Bush
Sunday announced a schedule of three hand-picked debates that he
would do, only one of which is guaranteed to be broadcast on the
three major networks.
</P>
<P>
   Bush pointedly challenged Vice President Al Gore to meet him on
these chosen dates and terms, with the first debate on Sept. 12.
And he tried to turn Gore's response into a referendum on the vice
president's credibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``My opponent has said he will debate anytime, anywhere, and he
has already accepted the debates that I am accepting today,'' Bush
said. ``It's important for the American people to be able to trust
the next president to keep his commitments, and therefore I take Al
Gore at his word that he will be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's proposal was a rebuff to the Commission on Presidential
Debates, which was created by both parties and has supervised the
presidential debates since 1988. That agency had proposed three
debates, all to be broadcast on the major networks, a plan Gore has
accepted.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who made his announcement at a hastily called news
conference on the lawn of the governor's mansion Sunday afternoon,
said he would debate Gore on a prime-time edition of NBC's ``Meet
the Press'' on Sept. 12, on ``Larry King Live'' on CNN on Oct. 3,
and in St. Louis on Oct. 17. The last debate, at Washington
University, was the only presidential commission debate accepted by
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The talk-show debates would last 60 minutes each, compared with
90 minutes for the commission debates.
</P>
<P>
   At his news conference, Bush played video clips of Gore in
appearances with Tim Russert on ``Meet the Press'' in July and on
``Larry King Live'' in March in which he said he would be happy to
appear in debates on their shows. As the videos played, Bush stood
at a lectern tapping his foot.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who learned of Bush's offer at a campaign appearance in
Philadelphia, instantly rejected it. His aides said that the
commission debates were the only ones likely to be carried by all
the major television networks and seen by the broadest television
audience possible.
</P>
<P>
   Another Gore aide said that Gore would agree to the CNN and NBC
sessions _ but only if he also agreed to the three commission
debates. ``We've already accepted these,'' Chris Lehane, Gore's
spokesman, said of Bush's CNN and NBC debates. ``We have no problem
with these. We just want to make sure we do the three presidential
ones.''
</P>
<P>
   While the day's posturing was ostensibly over debates, it was
also an attempt by both campaigns to make a statement about the
opponent's character.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's aides have been suggesting that Bush is afraid of a
prime-time confrontation, raising the question of whether he is up
to the presidency. Bush was trying to plant the idea Sunday that
Gore is not a man of his word.
</P>
<P>
   Gore aides also said that Bush was deliberately trying to shrink
the audience because unless there was blanket coverage on all five
networks, viewers would likely stray to other programming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless these debates are road-blocked, you don't get the kind
of viewership you do with the commission debates,'' said one aide,
noting that Bush's proposal for the NBC debate would bump up
against popular shows like ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' and
``NYPD Blue.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear how much exposure the noncommission debates
proposed by Bush would get. Donald Evans, Bush's campaign chairman,
said that NBC and CNN had offered to make their videotape available
to other networks.
</P>
<P>
   An official of one of the rival networks said it was ``highly
unlikely'' that any network would broadcast a full debate that
carries with it the branding and identity of a competing news
organization.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the Gore campaign's reaction to Bush's debate
proposal, Karen Hughes, his director of communications, said,
``We'll be there and we'll see if Al Gore will keep his word.'' She
added, ``After eight years of prevaricating, after eight years of
`no controlling legal authority' and of debate over what the
meaning of `is' is, the American people deserve a president who
will keep his word.'' Hughes said she saw no reason why the
networks would not agree to broadcast all three debates as a public
service.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who was just beginning a 24-hour Labor Day marathon tour
in Philadelphia, told reporters at Pat's Steaks, where he was
getting a cheese steak sandwich, ``I'm very disappointed in this
reaction because what's needed is to respect the rights of the
American people, to see the debates on all the networks in prime
time.'' He added: ``That's the way it's been done since 1988.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Of the commission debates, Gore said: ``It is a bipartisan,
nonpartisan tradition, and it's not about Governor Bush, it's not
about me, it's about the American people and giving the American
people the chance they deserve to make an informed judgment as to
who they want to be the next president.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's aides replied that President Clinton himself had rejected
some of the commission's proposals in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, The New York Times reported that Bush aides were
resisting the commission, because they did not want to commit to
three sessions that would be broadcast in prime time on the three
major networks. But the next morning, Bush told reporters that he
was not afraid of prime time. ``I want as many people to watch our
debates as possible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the one commission debate that Bush accepted, it
was not clear what the format would be. Evans said that still had
to be negotiated and that all the campaign had accepted was the St.
Louis venue.
</P>
<P>
   Bush Sunday also said his campaign would agree to two
vice-presidential debates, one in Winston-Salem, N.C., sponsored by
the debate commission and another one in a forum yet to be decided.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is generally considered by political strategists to be a
weaker debater than Gore and his aides had been angling for
different formats. On Friday commission officials told aides to
Bush that they would not revise the locations of schedules for the
forums because the work was too far advanced.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he had selected the three formats because they would
be varied and because he wanted one debate on the West Coast.
``This will give the American people an opportunity to see the
candidates in a wide range of locations and formats,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As the debate over debates has simmered, Bush has appeared on
the defensive, looking like he was seeking a better format for
himself. He and his aides were clearly trying to turn the tables
and use the struggle over debates to go after Gore's character and
make him look untrustworthy. After Bush's news conference, Hughes
reminded reporters that Gore had said he would debate anytime and
anywhere. ``We take him at his word,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And on CNN, before Bush's news conference, Ari Fleischer, a Bush
spokesman, also noted that the vice president had been accepting
numerous debate offers. Fleischer said, ``I predict to you, they're
going to change their position all of a sudden again.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush issued his challenge hours before flying to Chicago, where
he planned to begin the Labor Day kickoff of the general election
campaign. Polls show the race to be a dead heat or else give Gore a
slight lead. The debates are considered an important forum that
could well help undecided voters make up their mind.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and his senior advisers had been saying for weeks that they
wanted to explore options beyond those proposed by the bipartisan
debate commission, because they felt that there could be other
debates of equal or greater value to voters.
</P>
<P>
   But one adviser conceded tonight that in selecting debates that
would be moderated by the journalist Tim Russert in one case and
the talk-show host Larry King in another, Bush was guaranteeing
that he would take questions from people who had quizzed him
before, and with whom he felt familiar
</P>
<P>
   One Republican strategist in Washington said that by spurning
two of the three commission debates, which would be more
structured, Bush was showing ``that he's concerned about filling
the full two-minute answer'' in a debate with formal time
parameters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Larry will bail him out,'' said the strategist, referring to
King. ``Larry will keep it moving.''
</P>
<P>
   But several of Bush's advisers said that while journalists were
sure to deride Bush's decision, most voters would care only about
the fact that Bush was debating and would find all the noise
surrounding the negotiations to be meaningless.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not stupid. We've been looking at this,'' said one
adviser. ``Nobody knows who the commission is.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
