<SLUG> BC-LA-LABOR-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LABOR LEADERS LOOK AHEAD TO EXPANDED INFLUENCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICK ORLOV 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As the nation celebrates Labor Day, local union
leaders have been savoring their successes of the past year and
looking toward the November and April elections as the true test of
their future clout.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, several significant labor issues coming up in
Los Angeles __ in particular, a potential Metropolitan
Transportation Authority strike Tuesday _ could trigger public
backlash against union workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot at stake over the next 60 days,'' said Miguel
Contreras, executive secretary-treasurer of the Los Angeles County
Federation of Labor, AFL-CIO, an umbrella group for unions.
</P>
<P>
   ``And, I think we have to be careful to get our message out, to
let people know that these are working people and there won't be a
backlash. Look at the support the janitors received from across the
city because they were able to get their story out.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the MTA, there is the possibility of work actions
by members of the United Teachers Los Angeles against the Los
Angeles Unified School District and by county workers. And
television commercial actors have been engaged in a bitter strike
that's already been going on several months.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, labor leaders look ahead to the November elections,
throwing their support behind Democratic presidential candidate Al
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to deliver California for Al Gore, but I think
everyone realizes that if Democrats are to take back the House, it
comes through California and Los Angeles,'' Contreras said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are three key races here, and if (House Democratic
Minority Leader) Dick Gephardt wants to be speaker, it will come in
Los Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   Contreras believes organized labor will make the difference in
the congressional races of state Sen. Adam Schiff, D-Pasadena,
against incumbent Rep. James Rogan, R-Pasadena; Democratic former
congresswoman Jane Harman against Rep. Steve Kuykendall,
R-Torrance, who has held the seat since 1998; and Democrat Gerrie
Schipske against Rep. Steve Horn, R-Long Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Mulholland, political director of the state Democratic
Party, said labor is considered a key to the party's success this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thirty percent of our delegates to the convention this year
was labor,'' Mulholland said. ``In my 25 years of Democratic
politics, I've never seen the unions as strong as they are. They
are the key to us.''
</P>
<P>
   In April, the unions expect to be active in the Los Angeles city
election when voters make their selections for a new mayor, city
attorney, city controller and six open City Council seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a historic opportunity for us,'' Contreras said.
``Never again will we have a chance like this to influence the
future of the city.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Kyser, chief economist for the Economic Development Corp.
of Los Angeles, said the unions have been on a roll but also are
somewhat at a crossroads.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politically, labor is hoping for a Gore win but would be happy
if Democrats can take back the House,'' Kyser said. ``But the more
important election is next April in L.A. City Hall, where their
members can see a more direct benefit.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot at play here, and they want to be directly
involved. And they have proven their ability to mobilize Latino
voters.''
</P>
<P>
   What Kyser questions, however, is if the unions are looking to
the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an upwardly mobile society, and what happens in five
or 10 years to the children of today's union members?'' Kyser said.
``The question is, Will they join unions?''
</P>
<P>
   If last year was the year of growth for unions _ they added
85,000 members to swell the rank-and-file to 800,000 members in Los
Angeles County _ this year has been one of consolidation and
negotiations, with some of the biggest talks going on now.
</P>
<P>
   The potential MTA walkout by the nearly 7,000 union members at
the county transit agency will be the first big confrontation if
talks fail to produce an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Union leaders have pledged to give some notice before
authorizing a strike, but MTA officials took to television last
week to prepare the public for a possible work action, advising
people to seek alternative ways of getting to work.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are high, with more than 1.5 million passengers a day
relying on the MTA for bus and rail service.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 25, the 43,000 members of United Teachers Los Angeles
are scheduled to take a strike authorization vote against the LAUSD
if their talks _ which have been continuing _ break down.
</P>
<P>
   Also late this month, about 45,000 Los Angeles County government
employees who are members of the Service Employees International
Union have a vote scheduled on a possible work action.
</P>
<P>
   Since May, the unions have been working with members of the
Screen Actors Guild and American Federation of Radio and Television
Artists on their strike against the advertising agencies for
increased pay on commercials.
</P>
<P>
   SAG spokesman Greg Krizman acknowledged it has been difficult to
get much public sympathy for an industry many see as glamorous.
</P>
<P>
   ``But most people don't realize that 80 percent of SAG members
are making less than $5,000 a year,'' Krizman said, adding that the
impact of the long strike is felt far beyond SAG's 135,000 members.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the related trades and industry that are involved. We've
heard estimates that it is a loss of $1 million to $2 million a
day. It's affecting a lot of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Krizman said there are plans to hold a new round of talks in the
middle of the month.
</P>
<P>
   The SAG-AFTRA work action worries Kyser the most because of its
implications.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most critical strings of negotiations are going on in
Hollywood,'' Kyser said. ``You have SAG-AFTRA now with the
advertisers. Next year they could be striking against the studios.
And in 2002, the Directors Guild might go out.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is worrisome is that this is now an international
industry and producers can go anywhere. We are getting to the point
that they don't have to work in Hollywood and that affects a lot
more than the actors. An actor can get on a plane. The same isn't
true for all the crafts and others who depend on the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Contreras also sees the SAG-AFTRA strike as a forerunner to
talks next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``How this resolves itself will show what will happen next
year,'' Contreras said, dismissing the possibility more production
will leave the area. ``We've already had some runaway production,
but most of it will remain here.''
</P>
<P>
   The unions are indeed looking to the future, Contreras said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have strengthened ourselves internally this year,''
Contreras said. ``Next year, we will be involved politically and I
think we can be a major force. And we are going to continue to be a
model for central labor councils and go back out and do more
organizing.''
</P>
<P>
   x x x
</P>
</TEXT>
