<SLUG> BC-DEMOCRATS-MARATHON-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR LABOR DAY, CAMPAIGN MARATHON BY GORE AND LIBERMAN TARGET UNION
WORKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS dateline; ADDS location of hotel in 3rd graf; SUBS 5th graf
with updated locale)  
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Flint, Mich _ Like college students pulling an all-nighter
together, Vice President Al Gore and Sen. Joseph Lieberman Sunday
kicked off a round-the-clock Labor Day campaign swing, designed to
make the case for them as the ticket for the working class.
</P>
<P>
   On the holiday weekend traditionally seen as the start of the
stretch run to the November election, Gore continued the populist
themes on which he has based his general election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key difference in this election is we're for the people,
they're for the powerful,'' he told 100 cheering construction
workers inside the unfinished Hyatt Regency hotel in downtown
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Lieberman set a packed schedule for themselves from
Sunday afternoon through Monday night, a gimmick the campaign
dubbed ``Al and Joe's Hard Day's Night Tour,'' meant to cram in as
many appearances in as many swing-state media markets as possible,
in a little more than 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   They flew here together from Phil- adelphia for a rally at the
airport and  &UR; -------------------- &LR;  a late-night meeting with
hospital workers at Hurley Medical Center. From here they were to
fly to Tam- pa, Fla., where they planned a pre- dawn visit to an
all-night diner, fol- lowed by breakfast with firefighters and a
rally at a firehouse.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman planned to fly from Tampa to Detroit on Monday morning
for an AFL-CIO event, watch a game of the minor league Mud Hens
team in Toledo, Ohio, then wrap up the marathon in Peoria, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm beginning to think that vice presidential candidates
should have collective bargaining rights,'' Lieberman said of the
pace. ``You know, this guy's working me.''
</P>
<P>
   After stopping at Pat's, a well-known Philadelphia cheesesteak
restaurant, Gore and Lieberman made their way to the dusty
construction site, which leaked water in a driving rain. They
addressed a carefully screened group of construction workers _ some
who work on the project, and other who do not _ and tried out the
campaign's theme for the week, stewardship of the economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want a job done right, have it done by union workers,''
Gore said. ``If you want a job done right on our economic policy,
take a look at the blueprint. There are two competing blueprints.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic plan, he said, would mean a balanced budget,
securing Social Security and Medicare, investing in education, and
targeted tax cuts for the middle class.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not accept the blueprint from the other side that
proposes to give away all the surplus in a giant tax cut to the
wealthy at the expense of the middle class, that stops our
prosperity and progress,'' he said. ``We tried the other side's
approach before, and you saw what happened eight years ago, with
the high unemployment and the big deficits.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the workers at the event acknowledged they knew little
about politics or economic policy, beyond the remarkable growth
they have seen under President Clinton and Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Gore, but it's also the administration that got us to
where construction is these days, where it's booming,'' said Lee
Worthington, 50, an electrician.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Stafford, 21, also an electrician, said, ``Clinton did a
real good job with the economy, and Gore was his VP, so he's the
next-best thing to Clinton if we can't have Clinton. Also, Gore's
pro-union and Bush isn't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
