<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOSTER WORKS HARD, BUT WAS IT TOO HARD?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ DeShaun Foster seemed to run through tackles
on virtually every play Saturday afternoon, but Alabama defenders
weren't the only ones climbing on for a ride.
</P>
<P>
   Foster carried an entire team in the Bruins' stunning 35-24
victory over the third-ranked Crimson Tide.
</P>
<P>
   Foster rushed 42 times for 187 yards and had three touchdowns.
He also caught three passes for 29 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was like a soldier out there,'' said linebacker Ryan Nece.
``He put the whole team on his back and said, `Let's go.'''
</P>
<P>
   The plan, even before starting quarterback Cory Paus separated
his shoulder on the first play of the game, was to put the ball in
Foster's hands and let the offensive line do its part to establish
the run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told (offensive coordinator Al Borges) that if we don't run
(Foster) 30 times, I'm not going to be a very happy man,'' said
head coach Bob Toledo.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins, ranked 16th in the Associated Press poll and 17th in
the USA Today/ESPN poll, obviously have a good thing in Foster and
are intent on enjoying him, but they could develop a habit. The
question they may have to answer is when does use become abuse?
</P>
<P>
   Foster carried the ball on 55 percent of UCLA's plays (45 of 84)
and never ran out of bounds. Even though he says he's in the best
shape of his career, that's an extraordinary workload for someone
who's still lighter 208 pounds than most of the players trying to
hit him, has a history of injuries and has not been so depended
upon since high school.
</P>
<P>
   It's even been suggested the Bruins have a back like USC did in
its glory days with Charles White, Ricky Bell and Marcus Allen _
each of whom got the ball 40 times. But, unlike Foster, the USC
running backs were breaking their tackles in the secondary, not at
the line.
</P>
<P>
   And while Foster no longer is the stand-up runner he was in high
school, he has been hampered by ankle and knee injuries the past
two seasons. Moreover, his previous career single-game high in
carries was 24; in two previous seasons, Foster never had
back-to-back games when he's carried the ball as many as 42 times.
</P>
<P>
   One solution is to give more work to Jermaine Lewis, who carried
five times for 14 yards against Alabama. In the past, he has proven
to be a dependable back.
</P>
<P>
   Or they could turn to Akil Harris, who looked good in the spring
but in fall camp has had the look of another Keith Brown _ solid,
but without the speed, strength or agility to make yards on his
own.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Bruins have not had such a lopsided run-to-pass
ratio (57 to 24) since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   So, the player who could do the most to ease the reliance on
Foster is Ryan McCann, who with Paus' injury will likely be the
starter through the end of September.
</P>
<P>
   What he showed at the Rose Bowl on Saturday was what he's showed
in fall camp: He is unflappable and a hard worker, but there is
little consistency and he isn't as proficient as Paus at picking up
secondary receivers.
</P>
<P>
   He may throw a good pass _ like a well-placed out pattern to Jon
Dubravac on Saturday _ only to follow it up on the next play with a
poorly read slant that Alabama free safety Reggie Myles intercepted
and returned for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got spoiled with Cade (McNown),'' said Borges in explaining
why the Bruins must emphasize the run this season. ``It's time for
other people to pull the rope.''
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: UCLA received an oral commitment Sunday from Matt Mosebar,
a 6-foot-8, 260-pound offensive lineman from Santa Ynez (Calif.)
High. Mosebar is the nephew of former USC and Raiders center Don
Mosebar. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
