<SLUG> BC-FBN-COLTS-CHIEFS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLTS PROVE THEY CAN TAKE CHIEFS' HEAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHAREAN WILLIAMS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The Kansas City Chiefs had everything going
for them.
</P>
<P>
   They had an NFL-best 11-game home-opening winning streak. They
had an Arrowhead Stadium crowd of 78,357 as loud as usual. They had
a heat index of 95 degrees at kickoff. And they had an emotional
pregame tribute to linebacker Derrick Thomas, who died in February.
</P>
<P>
   But the Chiefs had Peyton Manning, Edgerrin James and Marvin
Harrison going against them, and they were too much for Kansas City
to overcome.
</P>
<P>
   Manning passed for 273 yards and a touchdown, Harrison caught
nine passes for 115 yards and James had 160 total yards and two
touchdowns as the Indianapolis Colts reestablished themselves as
AFC contenders with a 27-14 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think a lot of our young players appreciate how
difficult it is to come in here and beat these guys in this
stadium,'' Colts coach Jim Mora said. ``I do, because I've been in
this situation before. This is a big win for us, because it is a
tough place to come in and win. ...It was hot out there; the crowd
noise; it was a close game. That's when you have to execute and
perform and do what it takes to win the ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chiefs clung to the bottom of the Colts' cleats until early
in the fourth quarter when Indianapolis scored 10 points in 59
seconds to take a 24-14 lead. Mike Vanderjagt made a 23-yard field
goal _ his 27th consecutive _ with 13:37 remaining to cap a
nine-play, 27-yard drive that was set up by a 40-yard Payton
Williams punt return. That was followed by a Jeff Burris' 27-yard
interception return for a touchdown at 12:38 when Elvis Grbac, who
was being pressured by linebacker Cornelius Bennett, tried to force
a pass to Derrick Alexander.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nice in the fourth quarter to put it away and take the
game out of reach,'' said Manning, who was 22-of-32. ``This is a
tough environment to come into ... This crowd is so loud. It's hard
to hear. We had to use the silent count the entire game. This crowd
is a definite 12th man for the Chiefs. And their defense is so
good. That's what makes this win even bigger.''
</P>
<P>
   The Colts also had to vanquish a case of the early game jitters.
</P>
<P>
   On its first drive, Indianapolis went from its own 36 to the
Chiefs 3, where James fumbled. On the Colts' next possession,
Manning threw into double coverage and was picked off by linebacker
Donnie Edwards at the Kansas City 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``Edgerrin, he hardly ever fumbles, and he fumbles'' Manning
said. ``The second series, we get great field position, and I threw
it right to the guy. I was just, `Here, Donnie, take it.' It was
just a bonehead throw. We let them hang around and gave them
momentum. But at least we had opportunities. We can work on the
turnovers.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chiefs have many things to iron out on offense.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City was only 5-for-15 on third down. It got only 74
yards out of its committee of four running backs. And it dropped
seven passes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put our defense out there too much,'' said Grbac, who was
16-for-37 for 212 yards with two touchdowns and one interception.
``Offensively we could have done better ... We just didn't help out
the team too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrison was too much early, and James was too much late.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison beat cornerback Eric Warfield for 94 yards on six
catches in the first half, and James finished off the Chiefs with
68 yards on nine carries in the fourth quarter. James finished with
124 rushing yards and a touchdown on 28 carries and caught six
passes for 40 yards, including a 27-yard screen pass he scored on
in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody did their job,'' said James, who has rushed for more
than 100 yards in 11 of his 17 regular-season games. ``I just did
my job. And this is the result.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
