<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-WHITESOX-CORRECTION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS LOSE ANOTHER CLOSE ONE
</HEADLINE>
 Eds: Corrects typo in 4th graf, subs Konerko hit in 5th graf 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Maybe the Angels have become numb to these kinds of
losses. But they insisted after their 13-12 loss to the Chicago
White Sox Sunday at Comiskey Park they're not giving up.
</P>
<P>
   They say they'll just wipe off the blood and answer the bell
today when they continue their fight for a playoff berth.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it might be difficult to imagine the Angels not feeling a
bit groggy after getting swept in the three-game series. The
pitchers got pummeled, allowing 35 runs in the series and 46 runs
during what is now a four-game losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   After the Angels took a 4-0 lead in the top of the first Sunday,
starter Ramon Ortiz gave up nine runs in the bottom half and never
made it out of the inning. Still, the Angels rallied from a 9-4
deficit to take an 11-9 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels led 12-10 going into the bottom of the seventh, but
Shigetoshi Hasegawa (8-5) gave up three runs in the next two
innings, including Paul Konerko's tiebreaking sacrifice fly in the
eighth. &QL; 
The poor pitching overshadowed the performance of the Angels
offense, which had five home runs. Darin Erstad hit two, and Tim
Salmon, Scott Spiezio and Troy Glaus each hit one. For Glaus, it
was his 40th homer of the year, breaking the Angels' season-single
record he had shared with Reggie Jackson (39 in 1982).
</P>
<P>
   The Angels are in sixth place in the wild-card race, 5 1/2 back.
They trail first-place Seattle by six games. But they say they're
not out of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never give up,'' Glaus said. ``We haven't given up the
entire season. There's no reason to start now.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless I'm mistaken, we weren't eliminated today,'' Angels
manager Mike Scioscia said. ``We have games left with Oakland and
we have games left with Seattle at the end of the season. We're
within range. These things can turn quickly. We can put together a
streak and be knocking at the door where we should be.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels blew an 8-2 lead in Friday's game and got hammered
13-6 on Saturday. Sunday, Ortiz put the Angels into a big hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's simple,'' Angels catcher Bengie Molina said. ``(Ortiz)
didn't have it today. He threw the ball right down the middle. When
you throw the ball right down the middle, they're going to get
you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got eight guys playing behind me playing defense,'' Ortiz
said. ``And nobody could catch one. They were hitting the ball all
over the place.''
</P>
<P>
   Perry, Ray Durham and Frank Thomas each had three hits for the
White Sox, who had 15 hits.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Ortiz's troubles, the Angels had a chance to win it.
Spiezio's three-run homer in the third made it 9-7. Salmon's
three-run homer in the sixth made it 10-9. Glaus' solo homer in the
sixth made it 11-9. Erstad's homer in the seventh, his second of
the day, made it 12-10.
</P>
<P>
   But the weary Angels bullpen couldn't hold the lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these guys need a break,'' Scioscia said. ``We can't
continue to go to them (so early in games) or there's no chance of
finishing the race where we want to be.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels fell to 68-68, the first time they've been at .500
since June 16. And they know the only chance they have to contend
for a playoff spot is to get a big improvement from the pitchers,
particularly their starters.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're young, they're going to take their licks from time to
time,'' Salmon said. ``It's no secret this team is where it is
because of the offense. That's not a surprise. We have guys having
great offensive years. But it goes to show in this game, you need
pitching and defense.''
</P>
<P>
   And according to Salmon, the Angels still have some fight left
despite another emotionally draining loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a lot out of you, but you see the way the team keeps
fighting,'' Salmon said. ``Instead of asking what's the limit of
what we can take, look at the guys and how we're battling. We're
battling our (rears) off. Nobody expected us to be here. We're
going to do everything we can all the way down to the end.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
