<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOOTBALL, HUMILIATION GET IN CAMPO'S FACE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The nicest thing that happened to Dave Campo all
day Sunday was when he was hit in the face by a football during
pregame warmups.
</P>
<P>
   Bam, right in the kisser.
</P>
<P>
   The worst thing was when he opened his eyes and found himself
still standing on the sidelines at Texas Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong place.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong time.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong team.
</P>
<P>
   On what should have been the biggest day of his football career,
Campo was blindsided by a humiliating dose of reality in his debut
as Cowboys' head coach.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia 41, Cowboys 14 says somebody better call 9-1-1 and
fast.
</P>
<P>
   You think 109 degrees at kickoff was hot? You could have toasted
ravioli on the back of Campo's neck.
</P>
<P>
   One game into the regular season and we have a full-blown
five-alarm emergency on our hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe that [football in the face] was an omen,'' Campo sighed
after the second-worst opening day loss in the Cowboys' 41-year
history. ``Looking back, that was a high point.''
</P>
<P>
   Campo's face was still stinging from the errant ball when the
Eagles stunned the Cowboys by successfully executing an onside kick
on the opening kickoff. Nine plays later Donovan McNabb hit a wide
open Jeff Thomason from the 1-yard line for Philadelphia's first
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   The rout was under way.
</P>
<P>
   Campo could only watch in helpless horror as the never-ending
nightmare rolled on, and on, and on. With a searing sun beating
down for most of the long afternoon, what should have been a day of
celebration turned instead into a trip to the nether regions of
hell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had family and friends here today,'' Campo said after
finally emerging from a grim Cowboys' locker room. ``And I'm
completely, totally embarrassed.''
</P>
<P>
   If Campo wasn't such a nice guy, if he hadn't paid his dues in
serving 11 years as a Cowboys assistant coach and defensive
coordinator before finally getting his chance when Chan Gailey was
fired in January, there might be some small satisfaction to be
found in Sunday's humiliation. After all, it was Campo who stood up
at the team's kickoff luncheon last week and told the local media
doomsayers that most of us are out to lunch.
</P>
<P>
   But you'd have to be a sadist to wish what happened yesterday on
your worst enemy. Anyone with half a brain understood that Campo's
real target was his own team. It was a strategic psychological ploy
that failed miserably. His players obviously weren't listening and
Sunday's disgraceful performance was the result.
</P>
<P>
   The really bad news: It's going to get worse before it gets
better.
</P>
<P>
   Take Troy Aikman, for instance. The Eagles did, over and over
again.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman spent much of the afternoon at the hospital, trying to
clear cobwebs from his head after what was initially announced as
his third concussion in his past 10 games and eighthof his pro
career.
</P>
<P>
   In the nine times he ``tried'' to pass the ball before leaving
early in the second quarter, Aikman was sacked four times, threw
four incompletions and had an interception returned 27 yards for a
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Yikes.
</P>
<P>
   It may be time for Aikman to follow Steve Young's lead and quit
before his eyes are permanently crossed. He doesn't need this kind
of abuse.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys also might have lost star wide receiver Joey
Galloway for an undetermined length of time. He injured a knee late
in the game and Cowboys' owner Jerry Jones seemed much more worried
about his condition than he did Aikman's.
</P>
<P>
   Those were the two major physical blows that Cowboys suffered
yesterday, but the psychological scars from this one may last all
season.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles, led by Duce Staley's 201-yard day, gouged out huge
chunks of real estate en route to 306 yards rushing. Staley joined
Jim Brown and Greg Bell as just the third running back in history
to surpass 200 yards against the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   This, against a front seven that Jones had compared to the 1993
Super Bowl group, which speaks volumes about the owner/GM's ability
as a talent evaluator.
</P>
<P>
   Do the Cowboys have a weakness at cornerback? Sure they do, but
since they were able to run with complete immunity, the Eagles had
no reason to exploit it. Save that for another day.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' defense was hardly alone in its humiliation. The
next time the offensive line picks up a blitz will be the first
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't stop the run and we didn't protect the
quarterback,'' Campo said. ``They whipped our butts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It starts with me. Obviously I didn't have them exactly
prepared to play today. My words to them were, I ``will'' have them
ready next week.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, yes. This season is just getting started and Campo somehow
managed to find solace in that.
</P>
<P>
   ``The measure of success is how you handle adversity,'' Campo
said. ``The great thing about it is it's No. 1.; I'd feel a heck of
a lot worse about it if it was No. 16.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but Dave, if it was No. 16, at least the nightmare would be
over, not just beginning. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-00 0046EDT &QL; 
