<SLUG> BC--FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS HAVE SUNK TO NEW LOW: NO. 31
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Since the mid-'90s, the Cowboys have desperately
attempted to hang on to what they once were. But after Sunday at
Texas Stadium, as the 2000 season debuted with a 40-year,
franchise-low disgrace, there's a much bigger concern to ponder.
</P>
<P>
   What have the Cowboys now become?
</P>
<P>
   After Week 1 of a long NFL season that locally, anyway, now
appears endless, there is no question about which club has earned
the right to be called worst in the league. The next fandom chant
to be heard around here:
</P>
<P>
   ``We're No. 31. ... We're No. 31.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Cowboys were so boot-licking bad in this opener,
there might be a tendency to say they've got to be better than
this. Don't bet on it. In fact, that would also be an old echo from
the exhibition games, which in August seemed to have some validity.
But now?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, they can be this bad, at least based on what the
Philadelphia Eagles exposed in all football-related areas, starting
with superior smarts by the coaching staff, and then moving right
through offense, defense and special teams.
</P>
<P>
   Unless the Eagles were hinting that they are about to become
2000's version of the St. Louis Rams, how does a marginal-at-best
Philly outfit cause this kind of mass destruction? Two teams play
for 60 minutes, then one leaves town with new-found joy and the
other leaves a greasy spot on Jerry Jones' green carpet.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys were still adjusting their jocks as Eagles' coach
Andy Reid opened the game with a successful onside kick, the kind
of gutsy call that made Jimmy Johnson a legend. Red faces suddenly
appeared on the opposite sideline, which had nothing to do with 109
degrees. Coaches dread being snookered by other coaches. And the
Cowboys looked like bumpkins on the first kickoff of Dave Campo's
head coaching career.
</P>
<P>
   If only the humiliation had ended there. Instead, it was just
the beginning. The Cowboys never did get those jocks adjusted, or
anything else, for that matter.
</P>
<P>
   What do you say after 41-14? ``What?''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the postgame self-evaluation provided the finest local
moments of the afternoon, which, granted, didn't take much. But you
know how Jerry Jones can be _ he will sugarcoat famine and 100-year
floods if it suits his needs.
</P>
<P>
   Not this time, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had losses that hurt before, but from the standpoint of
disappointment, there's never been one like this since I've been
associated with the Cowboys,'' Jones said. ``I'm embarrassed for
our staff, for our players, and then I'm also embarrassed. I don't
put this one on Dave Campo's shoulders. This one goes on my
shoulders.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, maybe. But it was a truly awful day in Campo's coaching
life. The very worst kind of day.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, with that armadillo-in-the-headlights look on his face,
then added, ``no loss has ever been this surprising.''
</P>
<P>
   Surprising, of course, in it's depth, width and overall scope.
Only the proverbial ``not ready to play'' explanation normally
applies, and Campo said exactly that, taking the blame himself. But
it's the season opener. How could players not be ready to play for
an emotional little fireball of a new coach _ the anti-Chan, if you
will? And that's what the fans wanted, right? Do you think docile
ol' Chan was laughing when he saw this score down in Miami?
</P>
<P>
   Jones poured millions into a ``new/old'' offense, and it wasn't
worth nickels and dimes yesterday, no matter if Troy or Randall
were at the controls. The offensive line had it's collective butt
absolutely kicked, and this, friends, is listed as a ``team
strength.'' Strategy-wise, the offense was clueless in trying to
figure out what the Eagles were doing on defense. You can't block
what has already whizzed past you.
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, there was at least one consolation _ no worry about
the cornerbacks. Not with Duce Staley ripping for miles and miles
behind an Eagles' offensive line that steam rolled the front seven.
And not with a pass rush that young Donovan McNabb must have been
laughing at. But the bible of football tells us one sure thing: If
you can't stop the run, you can't stop the losses.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, here's a thought: Do you think these sweatfest training
camps held in Texas just might cause the kind of September physical
drain that some players have said? How did the Eagles look so fresh
and frisky in this blast furnace after five weeks of training in
what was described as unseasonably cool and rainy climes up at
Lehigh University? Wasn't this heat supposed to work to the
heat-tested Cowboys' advantage? Instead, they were chestnuts
roasting over a Philly fire.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, if you were thinking yesterday was the absolute worst _
that there has to be an upside from here _ then check the medical
reports due to be announced sometime today. How serious is that
Troy Aikman concussion? Regardless, there's no way he plays next
week, or even the next, is there? And Joey Galloway _ what will the
MRI being done on his damaged left knee tell us about his
availability the remainder of the season? The postgame locker room
was very concerned over Galloway's future.
</P>
<P>
   See there, it can get worse. Even if you're already No. 31 in
the NFL. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-00 0046EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
