<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-EAGLES-STALEY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCE STALEY FOUND HEAT TOUGHER OPPONENT THAN COWBOYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The Cowboys' defense almost /{killed/}
Philadelphia's Duce Staley on Sunday. After all, it allowed the
Eagles running back to run up and down the field for three hours in
the 109-degree Texas sun. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I got tired, especially toward the end,'' Staley said. ``Even
though the sun switched sides, I was still drained.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Staley rushed for 201 yards on his 26 carries, added another 61
on receptions, and plowed into Dallas' end zone once in
Philadelphia's 41-14 opening-day victory against the Cowboys on
Sunday at Texas Stadium. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not since 1949, when Steve Van Buren gained 205 yards against
Pittsburgh, had an Eagles back had a 200-yard rushing game. Not
since 1984 has a running back rushed for 200 yards on the Cowboys. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Duce went off today. He really did. He had a helluva game,''
Eagles defensive end Hugh Douglas said. ``He played hard and he
didn't give their defense a chance to rest and I think that was the
key.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys probably would not argue. Those that were not helped
off the field for heat-related cramps were gasping for air after
spending most of the game chasing Staley &AMP; Co. all over the field. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It kind of got to us because they ran a lot,'' Cowboys rookie
cornerback Kareem Larrimore said. ``But we're going to meet up with
him again, and I'm pretty sure it's not going to be as bad as
this.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Only twice in the storied history of the 'Boys has it been. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In 1984 when Buffalo's Greg Bell rushed for 206 yards and in
1963 when Cleveland's Jim Brown had a 232-yard performance. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Staley might not be the second coming of Brown, but the Cowboys
made him look like it.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At least for a day. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the type of back who is not going to let one person
tackle him,'' Eagles offensive lineman Jon Runyan said. ``He wants
to get out, shake a guy off and make two or three guys tackle him.
If you give him a big enough hole there is not going to be enough
people around to tackle him.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On a couple of his runs, namely the 60, 34 and 18-yard ones,
there weren't any.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Staley disagreed, shredding the Cowboys defense for a
career-high number of yards was not as always as easy as it looked.
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There was the time in the first quarter when he crashed into the
Eagles bench after an 8-yard run, hurting his right knee and
missing a couple of plays. He took another vicious hit after the
Eagles scored to open the fourth quarter. It was from his teammate,
quarterback Donovan McNabb, but the chest bump gone wrong at least
knocked him down.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys would have loved to have been able to do that. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' inability to stop Staley set the tone for the
Eagles. It was the beat they moved to all game. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming out with Tra [Thomas] and Big Runyan, we wanted to ...
pound, pound, pound,'' Staley said. ``They're down here in their
home town and they're getting tired. So we tried to take
advantage.'' &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
