<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOCTOR-MURDER-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE RISE AND FALL OF A DOCTOR ACCUSED OF KILLING HER PARENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  By N.R. KLEINFIELD   and IVER PETERSON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   She was a great achiever, living out the theme of success. There
was the Harvard medical education, followed by prestigious
professional appointments. There was romance. An interlude in the
Virgin Islands. There was money.
</P>
<P>
   But when Dr. Idella Kathleen Hagen appeared in Superior Court in
Morristown, N.J., last Tuesday, she was the face of failure _ gaunt
and abject. One of her lawyers told the judge that she was only
dimly aware of why she was even there.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 26, Hagen, 54, was arrested and charged with murdering
her parents, Idella Hagen, 92, and James Hagen, 86 _ apparently by
suffocating them in their twin beds in their Chatham Township,
N.J., home. For some time, she had been living in their basement
and helping to care for them. They were frail, but the authorities
do not interpret this as a mercy killing. They are unsure what it
was.
</P>
<P>
   Hagen's lawyers said they were preparing a defense based on her
questionable mental state. They suggested that she was severely
depressed, tormented by unknown demons and wearied by lack of sleep
and food. The police said she answered the door disheveled and in a
rumpled nightgown. They said that when they got there, the parents
had been dead for days, while their daughter continued to carry on
in the house.
</P>
<P>
   Hagen is being held in the Morris County Jail and has not talked
publicly about her predicament. The following picture of her was
pieced together from documents and interviews with people who know
her.
</P>
<P>
   Hagen, an only child, grew up in Chatham and attended Chatham
High School and then Douglass College, the women's college at
Rutgers, where she met Peter A. Cook, a graduate student at Rutgers
from Bedforshire, England. They were married in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   Much of their life together was compromised by the punishing
demands that went with the training of a doctor. She graduated from
Harvard Medical School in 1973, and became the first woman
appointed a urology resident at Massachusetts General Hospital. She
taught surgery at Harvard Medical School, and in 1982 became the
chief of the urology division at Rutgers Medical School, since
renamed Robert Wood Johnson Medical School and part of the
University of Medicine and Dentistry of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we came to an understanding that her principal
emotional relationship was with medicine rather than with me,''
Cook said. Their marriage lasted 10 years. There were no children.
Cook is now a statistician and lives in Brookline, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   In 1983, at a dance club at the Jersey Shore, Hagen met William
Tyrrell, an industrial engineer who worked at Motion Systems, a
small industrial components maker in Eatontown, N.J. The following
year, they were married. It was also his second marriage, and he
had two sons with his previous wife.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next few years, Hagen's life began to trace a new arc.
She worked very hard. She was a woman in what was largely a man's
specialty. And like so many doctors, she grew disenchanted with the
direction of medicine under the penny-conscious strictures of
managed care.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, Tyrrell said, she buckled under a heavy depression. She
was hospitalized for several weeks. The consensus was that she
suffered from bipolar disease, or manic depression. She was put on
medication, Tyrrell said, and resumed her career without any
obvious affects.
</P>
<P>
   According to Tyrrell, he and his wife had talked about making a
sharp change in their lives. They had taken vacations to St. Thomas
in the Virgin Islands and had built a vacation house. On and off,
they had pondered buying a business there.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, they discovered the Villa Olga, a small hotel and
restaurant in St. Thomas that had once been the Russian consulate.
Tyrrell said they acquired a long-term lease on the property for
about $600,000 from Richard Doumeng, the general manager of the
Bolongo Bay Beach Club. Doumeng said that his impression was that
the inn was more Tyrrell's dream than Hagen's, though Tyrrell said
they shared it equally.
</P>
<P>
   Hagen converted to part-time status at the medical school and
the couple moved to St. Thomas. They renamed the hotel the West
Indies Inn. At a cost of several hundred thousand dollars, they
enlarged it to 19 rooms from eight. For a while, things went well.
Then fate dealt them several bad hands.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, Hurricane Hugo ravaged the island, badly damaging the
inn. But they remained open as they repaired it. Next came the
Persian Gulf War and a jittery stock market, which disrupted many
travelers' vacation plans. A number of airlines, including Eastern
and Pan American, collapsed. The couple had guests who couldn't get
flights to the island. Grudgingly, they gave up.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Tyrrell returned to New Jersey and resumed work as
operations manager at Motion Systems. She stayed in St. Thomas to
try to sell the lease. She remained for about a year, at which
point Doumeng took it back. In the end, Tyrrell said, they wound up
losing about $250,000.
</P>
<P>
   Though they kept their St. Thomas home, the couple resurrected
their New Jersey life. They bought a clapboard house in Rumson, on
the Shrewsbury River. Hagen began doing unpaid research at Robert
Wood Johnson, using rats to develop a treatment for bladder cancer.
</P>
<P>
   But in many ways, she was dispirited. ``She quit medicine and we
had to quit the hotel business,'' Tyrrell said. ``She had to be an
achiever to do what she had done. When an achiever isn't achieving,
they aren't as happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon their marriage began to unravel.
</P>
<P>
   ``She made sure she was the center of attention in some cases,
and that didn't sit well with some people,'' Tyrrell said. If a
waiter was unresponsive, she would make it clear what she thought
of his inattentiveness.
</P>
<P>
   The event that clinched it came the day in 1995 that Tyrrell
climbed on his motorcycle to visit a friend. A few blocks from
their home he was hit by a car. The accident broke several of his
ribs and his left leg was mangled.
</P>
<P>
   In the hospital, he faced a difficult decision. The doctors
could try to save his leg, but that could mean years of operations
that might prove fruitless. Or they could simply amputate it right
away.
</P>
<P>
   Hagen, was adamant that he keep the leg, he said. ``At one
point, she said to me, `I'm not going to let anyone cut your leg
off,''' he recalled. ``I said, `Nobody is going to tell me what I
can or can't do.'''
</P>
<P>
   When he decided to have the leg amputated, she was enraged. This
drove him to the breaking point.
</P>
<P>
   He never returned home. When he left the hospital, he checked
into a motel. He declared their marriage over. It took more than a
year for them to reach a divorce agreement, slowed perhaps by a
stroke of bizarre behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Hagen was aware that her husband liked to visit a go-go bar near
his office with co-workers. It irked her. ``She felt it was
demeaning,'' said Bernard Hoffman, her divorce lawyer. ``And she
was still hoping for a reconciliation.''
</P>
<P>
   On a Friday in September 1996, she called the place and told
them that she was going to do a birthday dance on the bar for her
husband. His birthday was actually in May. The bar alerted the
police. She dressed in a go-go outfit and drove over. The police
handcuffed her and arrested her in the parking lot. Her husband was
not there. Charges against her were dismissed, but she has a
lawsuit pending against the Eatontown, N.J., police, contending
that they violated her civil liberties.
</P>
<P>
   A medical history turned over in conjunction with the suit
showed that she suffered from a thyroid condition and from bipolar
disorder. It said that she was taking lithium.
</P>
<P>
   According to court papers, the couple had net assets of $1.6
million, most of them acquired during their marriage. Of the
marital assets, she left with $780,000 and he got about $405,000.
He took the Rumson house, and she took the St. Thomas one. Coupled
with her prior assets, Hagen as a newly divorced woman was worth a
little over $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
