<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 00:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0269 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-DOCTOR-MURDER-2TAKES-     09-04 0454
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOCTOR-MURDER-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: $1 million. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hagen shuttled back and forth between St. Thomas and her
parents' home in Chatham Township. She stopped doing research. She
had an apartment built in the basement of her parents' house.
</P>
<P>
   She seemed to struggle for a sense of self. Everything had
melted _ two careers, two marriages. She began to worry about
money, more, it appears, than she had reason to.
</P>
<P>
   It is true that of her assets of more than $1 million, much was
not liquid. It included the St. Thomas house, valued at $280,000,
two Killington, Vt., condominiums of minimal net value, and
retirement accounts worth more than $550,000.
</P>
<P>
   But she had no children. She seemed frugal. Though her alimony
and health insurance were supposed to have ended by Aug. 15 under
the terms of her divorce, Tyrrell said the payment schedule had
been altered; she is still receiving alimony and is still covered
by his insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Cook, her first husband, said she called him recently,
ostensibly to discuss some possessions from their marriage, but it
was clear to him that she really wanted to talk about her problems.
She did not sound despondent to him, but she spoke of stresses.
``She said she was going to have to start supporting her parents,''
he said. ``She made some allusions to her parents' retirement
money, about it being finite, and that unless she sold the house
she was going to be in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   A person familiar with Hagen's financial holdings, who spoke on
the condition of anonymity, said that he talked with her a couple
of months ago and that she was concerned about keeping up her
parents' expenses, but she had not cashed in any assets.
</P>
<P>
   Tyrrell said he, too, had spoken to her recently. ``She had
concerns about money, but I don't think they were founded,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Real estate agents in St. Thomas said that she put her house
there up for sale on June 22 at the appealing price of $319,000,
but abruptly removed it from the market three weeks later.
</P>
<P>
   The house does not appear to have been visited recently. Weeds
have sprung up in the hand-laid blue-rock retaining walls. The
water in the small dip pool is colored with algae. Inside the
house, a floor lamp is on its side. Liquor bottles are stacked
below the circular stairs, and detritus covers the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Hagen had no more career, but it is unclear why she did not seek
to revive one. ``What do the astronauts do after they go to the
moon?'' Tyrrell said. ``A number of them have had problems. It was
hard for her to live in the aftermath of what she had achieved so
early.''
</P>
<P>
   Then on a Saturday morning, she called the Chatham Township
police. She told them who she was and said that her parents were
dead.
</P>
</TEXT>
