<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 00:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0272 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBC-OSBORNE-CONGRESS-     09-04 1636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-OSBORNE-CONGRESS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MR. OSBORNE GOES FOR WASHINGTON: EX-COACH LEADS BIG IN BID FOR
CONGRESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA, Neb. _ In small Midwestern towns like this one, they
take their county fairs seriously. The Fillmore County Fair in July
was a big deal, the 125th annual event.
</P>
<P>
   Just before noon, while the Future Farmers of America are
showing their prize hogs in the Swine Show Barn, a slender visitor
appears. He's dressed in slacks, a golf shirt and loafers, and
wears sunglasses and a ball cap. Despite his fame and his new
career's need for visibility, there is no fanfare to herald his
arrival.
</P>
<P>
   He extends his hand and quietly greets a man in overalls. ``Hi,
I'm Tom.'' The man responds, ``Well, Tom Osborne,'' his voice
reflecting as much surprise as if he had just shaken hands with
Elizabeth Hurley.
</P>
<P>
   For five minutes, Tom Osborne _ former Nebraska football coach,
current Republican candidate for the 3rd District seat in the U.S.
House of Representatives _ is just another fair goer. Then, as word
spreads, he spends the next 15 minutes signing autographs. After
the FFA members complete their showing of future breakfast meats,
Osborne makes his way inside the ring. Without introduction, he
takes the microphone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last thing you want to do right now is hear from a
politician,'' Osborne says. ``I wish some of these 10-year-olds
I've been signing stuff for could vote; I'd do really well.''
</P>
<P>
   Self-deprecating, aw-shucks humor sells at county fairs. Osborne
speaks for less than a minute, with no mention of the issues or his
opinions. A Huey Long stump speech, it's not. Then, he moves
through the bleachers, shaking hands and saying hello. This is
low-key politics. Even the bumper sticker that says ``Tom Osborne
For U.S. Congress'' is in blue and white, not Nebraska red and
white.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think of myself as a politician, but I guess if you're
running for office, you are one,'' Osborne says.
Mr. Osborne Goes To Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Headlines like that are ready to be set in type in Nebraska
newspapers. Of all the races being contested in this election year,
Osborne's Nov. 7 victory against Democratic challenger Rollie
Reynolds is the only sure thing. In this case, Dewey ``will''
defeat Truman.
</P>
<P>
   Osborne won the Republican primary with 71 percent of the vote.
He's expected to wind up with a similar percentage in the general
election. After the primaries, polls showed Osborne favored by 90
percent of the voters.
</P>
<P>
   Not only is Osborne a Republican running in a district that has
elected the GOP candidate in each election going back 70 years, he
is ``Tom Osborne.'' For 25 years, he was the state's most visible
celebrity/deity/leader as coach of the Cornhuskers. Osborne, a
native son (Hastings), won 255 games and three national titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lifetime background in agriculture, and he has a
lifetime background in football,'' Reynolds said. ``Agriculture is
in the tank. This district is in dire straits, and they're going to
vote for him, probably, because of football and not agriculture.`
</P>
<P>
   Osborne's campaign theme is ``You and Tom.'' It might just as
well be ``In Tom We Trust.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows Nebraska, and he has a wonderful moral character,''
said Pat Brinkman, a farm wife from nearby Shickley. ``I think he
represents what the people are looking for.''
</P>
<P>
   Do you plan to vote for him?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to try and be fair,'' she said. ``I need to hear
where he stands on the issues first. Farm issues are very important
to most of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Don Bristol, a farmer from Fairmont, says that the farm
situation is bleak and that the government's farm program is in
``disrepair.'' He would like to see a return to a supply-and-demand
system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom's an honest person,'' Bristol said. ``I'm supporting him
because I think there's a lack of honesty and integrity in
Congress. I consider him a coach, not a politician. I believe he
can make an impact in Washington. I'm hoping he can be
successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Bristol, though, hasn't decided who to vote for. Osborne's lack
of political experience concerns Bristol, but then he sighs and
says, ``What are our alternatives?''
</P>
<P>
   The 3rd District is the nation's largest in area, making up 80
percent of the state. West of Lincoln, the district stretches 300
miles east to west and 200 miles north and south. Osborne estimates
that by November, he will have driven 40,000 to 50,000 miles
campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   The Geneva Rotary Club in a modern facsimile of a log cabin.
Thirty Rotarians are enjoying their lunch of Sloppy Joe s, corn on
the cob, lemonade and chocolate brownies. After his fair
appearance, Osborne works his way around the room, shaking hands
and redundantly introducing himself.
</P>
<P>
   Osborne stands and joins in the singing of ``My Country 'Tis Of
Thee'' and the first stanza of ``The Battle Hymn of The Republic.''
All that's missing is Norman Rockwell, observing and sketching from
a corner. Then Honest Tom starts his 20-minute campaign speech with
some typical low-key humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been to a lot of Rotary meetings, but you guys sing
better,'' he cracks in a Steven Wright monotone.
</P>
<P>
   In his 20-minute speech, Osborne outlines his three main issues:
helping farmers and improving the agriculture; improving the
district's infrastructure so that it can better serve computers and
the Internet, which would make the district more attractive to
high-tech businesses; be more proactive when dealing with young
people and their problems.
</P>
<P>
   The Rotarians are riveted. Osborne speaks like someone who has a
doctorate in educational psychology. He is thoughtful and willing
to learn. So far, though, he's just talking the talk. Until he gets
to Washington and proves he can be effective in government, he
hasn't walked the walk.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see what happens,'' he said. ``People say I'm naive in
regard to politics, but I think dealing with the NCAA is a good
primer. So many things are done by the NCAA out of perception
rather than what was best. It's not like this is totally foreign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure there will be some who perceive me as a football
coach elected strictly because of the fact I'm a former football
coach. Over time, I hope I can demonstrate a level of competence
and commitment that \Rother lawmakers\S will appreciate.''
Osborne, 63, announced his retirement in December 1997. The Huskers
defeated Tennessee, 42-17, in the 1998 Orange Bowl to earn Nebraska
a share of the national championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``After my last game, I knew there were some things I was
leaving that would never be approximated again,'' Osborne said. ``I
don't think \Rpolitics\S will replace football. I miss football a
lot, the relationships with players and coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't consciously gone into this thinking I have to have
something to replace football. I'm not really good at retirement. I
didn't want to spend the rest of my time with a fishing rod or a
golf club.''
</P>
<P>
   In December, Osborne was tempted to return to coaching. The
University of Houston reportedly dangled a $1 million contract.
Michigan State also inquired.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty tempting,'' he said of the preliminary
discussions.
</P>
<P>
   Osborne, though, decided he didn't want to disrupt and uproot
his family. Running for office, while not the same as calling for a
two-point conversion with the national championship on the line,
was the next best thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a case of wanting to be relevant,'' Osborne said. ``I
felt I had enough energy to make one more major push. As I looked
around, I thought the 3rd District was where I could do the most
good.''
</P>
<P>
   Osborne has talked with fellow Republicans J.C. Watts and Steve
Largent, former athletes who are congressmen from Oklahoma. He
understands the potential frustration trying to wade through
partisanship and special-interest groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm prepared to be frustrated,'' said Osborne, who has placed
a limit of $300 on individual campaign contributions and who is not
accepting money from special-interest groups. ``In coaching, if you
wanted to run a play up the middle, you ran up the middle. You go
up there, and you're not going to have your opinion count for
much.''
</P>
<P>
   Osborne will come in as an outsider and plans to remain an
outsider. The House does most of its business from Tuesday through
Thursday. He plans to commute, flying to Washington, on Monday
night, back home Thursday night. His ideal schedule would have him
attending events in the 3rd District on Friday and Saturday then
spending Sunday with his family.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Kay Granger, R-Fort Worth, says Osborne has the
leadership and organizational skills to make an impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone with his kind of national recognition, he won't start
at the bottom,'' Granger said. ``He's a winner in his coaching
career, an extraordinary leader. That would put him in a special
category.''
</P>
<P>
   In cinematic fiction, Jimmy Stewart played rookie Sen. Jefferson
Smith in ``Mr. Smith Goes To Washington.'' Stewart/Smith was a Good
Guy who triumphed in the final reel. (That's the way Hollywood used
to make movies.) Osborne has never seen the Frank Capra film
starring Stewart. Coaches watch film recommended by the American
Football Coaches Association, not the American Film Institute.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a desire to serve Nebraska well,'' Osborne said in his
quiet, Midwestern monotone. ``I think the 3rd District sometimes
feels a little left out, a little bit ignored. Maybe I can raise
the visibility of what's going on with agriculture, small towns. I
think maybe we can provide some vision, optimism, belief that it's
going to be better.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I can make a difference. I hope I come out as well as
Jimmy Stewart. I probably won't. They'll probably hand my head to
me.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
