<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSBORNE-SIDER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OSBORNE FOE KNOWS HE'S FACING A JUGGERNAUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 25 seasons as Nebraska's football coach, Tom Osborne had a
67-17-1 record in November, including an 18-game winning streak in
that month to close out his career. On Election Day, Osborne
figures to add another victory by winning the congressional seat in
Nebraska's 3rd District.
</P>
<P>
   Even his Democratic opponent, Rollie Reynolds, concedes that his
odds of winning Nov. 7 are slight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a quite steep mountain to climb,'' said Reynolds, a
Grand Island resident. ``He's such a nice man. He gives the
impression he's more honest than other people. I don't know how,
but he does. He's very, very popular. Winning three national
championships his last four years as coach really makes people want
to identify with him.''
</P>
<P>
   The 3rd District has almost twice as many Republicans as
Democrats. Reynolds was unopposed in the primary; Osborne won the
Republican primary against two challengers with 71] percent of the
vote. That's the political equivalent of the Huskers' 39-10 average
scores in Osborne's 67 November victories.
</P>
<P>
   Osborne has raised about $300,000 in campaign contributions.
Reynolds estimates that he has raised $10,000. Osborne's campaign
has a Web site. Reynolds doesn't even own a computer; he used a
typewriter (a word processor that preceded the computer) to
distribute his stance on the issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a staff; it's a one-man operation,'' Reynolds
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to play Kennedy to Osborne's Nixon, Reynolds challenged
Osborne to four debates. One is scheduled Oct. 15 on Nebraska
Public Television.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suspect his advisers have told him that he's way ahead, go
sit on the porch and don't say anything,'' said Reynolds, whose
brother Don is married to Osborne's first cousin.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds claims expertise in the campaign's most critical issue:
agricultural reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he'll do like he did in football,'' Reynolds said.
``It's third and long for Nebraska agriculture, and I think he
wants to run it up the middle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a duty call for me. I'm trying to get agriculture moving
again. The current system is set up by the government with coaching
from four big companies to maintain low grain prices. I'm saying
it's time for farmers to take control. A lot of people tell me they
like what I say \Rbut\S that doesn't mean they won't vote for their
hero.''
</P>
<P>
   Of Osborne's 17 losses in the month of November, 12 came against
Oklahoma. Reynolds' best chance would appear to be hiring Barry
Switzer to run his campaign. Reynolds rejects that fantasy
scenario.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an unsavory character, and I wouldn't be caught dead in
the same room with him,'' he said with a chuckle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-00 0052EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
