<DOCNO> NYT20000904.0020 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 01:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0274 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-EAGLES-COWBOYS-TE     09-04 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-EAGLES-COWBOYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS `EMBARRASSED' AS EAGLES ADD INSULT TO INJURIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The Cowboys have more to worry about than just
global warming.
</P>
<P>
   They were sucker-punched in 109-degree heat at home Sunday in
the 2000 season opener, 41-14, by a Philadelphia Eagles team that
had lost on nine of its last 10 trips to Texas Stadium, and were
1-22-1 over the last three seasons away from Veterans Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   For the Cowboys, this loss was even worse than that:
</P>
<P>
   Troy Aikman left the game in the second quarter with a mild
concussion after being sacked four times and heavily
pressured/knocked down four other times, while failing to complete
a pass in five attempts. This now replaces a 1989 rookie-season
game in which Aikman broke his left index finger after going
1-for-6 for 11 yards against the New York Giants, as his worst NFL
start.
</P>
<P>
   Joey Galloway sprained his left knee late in the game and was on
crutches afterward. He will undergo an MRI exam today. His injury
could have a longer effect on when he can play next than Aikman's.
</P>
<P>
   This loss was only the 10th in 41 season openers for the
Cowboys, and tied the second-worst season-opening defeat, behind
only a 28-0 loss at New Orleans in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   The game began _ are you ready for this? _ with a successfully
executed onside kick by Philadelphia to start the season, proving
that the Eagles' losing the coin toss was a bad thing only for the
Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia recovered, scored on the drive to take a 7-0 lead
and never looked back.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're embarrassed,'' Cowboys coach Dave Campo said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm personally embarrassed,'' owner Jerry Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It starts with me,'' said Campo, who made his head-coaching
debut at any level Sunday. ``Obviously, I didn't have them prepared
to play today ... \Rand\S I ``will'' have them ready to play next
week.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not on Dave's shoulders ... it's mine,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   But what wasn't debatable was how the Eagles totally dominated
the six-point favorite Cowboys, who were the ones getting all the
attention for unveiling their new timing-route offense and
unleashing a rotation-ready defense that had used preseason simply
to brush up on base packages.
</P>
<P>
   But as it turned out, the Cowboys couldn't stop the run (read:
Duce Staley rushed for 201 yards to become the first 200-yard
rusher against the Cowboys in almost 16 years, or since Buffalo's
Greg Bell in November 1984.)
</P>
<P>
   And the Cowboys couldn't protect the quarterback (read: Aikman
was sacked four times on nine passing plays, and Randall Cunningham
once, by an Eagles defense that was totally in character by
blitzing.)
</P>
<P>
   ``After this,'' Jones said, ``teams are going to blitz us like
we've never seen it before.''
</P>
<P>
   The tone was set early and often.
</P>
<P>
   The onside kick off the foot of second-year kicker David Akers
worked to perfection, finding a hole between Darren Hambrick and
Barron Wortham, and bounding the necessary 10 yards until Eagles
third-string wide receiver Dameane Douglas could pounce on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``\RCoach Andy Reid\S told me what we were going to try five
minutes before the game,'' Akers said. ``He said, `Hey, we're
playing to win, that's what that shows right there.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Said Wortham: ``The \Rkicker\S took this weird angle. I thought
to myself, `Onside kick?' then I thought, `Naw,' because he squared
up like he was going to kick it deep. So, I started to turn and
then saw him take that weird angle again. I froze for just a
second. By then, I was blocked.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Hambrick: ``\RThe ball\S came close enough, I guess. But
when you're not expecting it, you're not going to get it. We're
starting to release and go back to help on the return.''
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles went 58 yards in nine plays with Donovan McNabb
throwing his only touchdown pass of the game to tight end Jeff
Thomason. McNabb completed 16 of 28 for 130 yards and added another
29 yards with his scrambling
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' first five possessions were four punts sandwiched
around an Aikman interception.
</P>
<P>
   By then, the Eagles had the ball nearly 17 minutes to less than
seven minutes for the Cowboys. The score: Eagles 24, Cowboys 0.
</P>
<P>
   Only rookie kicker Tim Seder could put points on the board for
the Cowboys in the first half, with field goals from 34 and 38
yards.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' lone touchdown didn't come until 8 minutes, 15
seconds remaining in the game, when Cunningham hit Galloway on a
quick post for a 4-yard touchdown. Cunningham and Rocket Ismail
hooked up for a two-point conversion.
</P>
<P>
   Far too little, far too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be candid with you,'' Jones said, ``this \Rloss\S
diminishes how good we thought we were. We thought we were better
than this ... and I think we are better than this right now.''
</P>
<P>
   It just didn't show Sunday. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
