<DOCNO> NYT20000904.0025 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 01:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0281 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-OLY-BASKETBALL-PREVIE     09-04 1595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-BASKETBALL-PREVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PREVIEWING THE OLYMPIC BASKETBALL TOURNAMENTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PETE ALFANO 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Basketball at a glance
</P>
<P>
   Gold medals at stake: Men's and women's team
</P>
<P>
   Events: In men and women's competition, countries are divided
into two six-team pools and play a round-robin format, featuring
five games. The top four teams in each pool advance to the
quarterfinals, which is single elimination. The men and women's
gold-medal games are Sept. 30.
</P>
<P>
   Competition dates: Every day except Sept. 26
</P>
<P>
   Venues: The Dome and Sydney Super Dome
</P>
<P>
   Year introduced: Men in 1936; women in 1976
</P>
<P>
   History: The United States has dominated Olympic basketball,
winning 11 of 14 gold medals in the men's competition. The biggest
upset in Olympic history occurred in the 1972 men's gold-medal
final in Munich when the Soviet Union defeated the American men,
51-50, on a layup in the final seconds by Aleksandr Belov. This
came after the Americans had apparently won the game, only to have
an official with the International Amateur Basketball Association
give the Soviets a second chance, ruling that the referees had not
set the clock correctly when the game ended the first time. The
Americans filed a protest, but to no avail, and they refused to
accept their silver medals. It was the first loss for the U.S.
men's team in Olympic competition.
</P>
<P>
   The American women have won three of the past four gold medals,
losing only to the Russians in the semifinals of the 1992 Olympics
in Barcelona.
</P>
<P>
   Past heroes: Until professionals were allowed to represent their
country in 1992 in Barcelona, the American men's teams were
comprised of collegiate and amateur standouts. Bill Russell was the
center on the 1956 team in Melbourne, Australia; Jerry West and
Oscar Robertson were in the same backcourt in the 1960 Games in
Rome; Bill Bradley led the 1964 team in Tokyo. The greatest team of
all time was assembled in Barcelona when Larry Bird, Magic Johnson,
Michael Jordan, Patrick Ewing, David Robinson, Scottie Pippen, Karl
Malone, Charles Barkley and John Stockton were teammates.
</P>
<P>
   No one has stood taller in the women's game than the ``Latvian
giant,'' Uljana Semjonova of the Soviet Union, who led her country
to the gold medal in the first women's Olympic basketball
competition in 1976 in Montreal. Semjonova, who was 6-10 1/2 and
284 pounds, towered over the competition and averaged more than 19
points and 12 rebounds, despite spending a great deal of time on
the bench. She might be the ``old lady'' on this year's team, but
in 1984 in Los Angeles, Teresa Edwards made her first appearance on
the women's Olympic team. She led the Americans in scoring in Seoul
in 1988 (16.6 points) and assists (eight per game) in Atlanta in
1996. She'll be looking for her fourth gold medal in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   Checking the rules: Players may touch a ball while it is
bouncing on the rim. This would be offensive goaltending in the
NBA. The 3-point line is 20 feet, 6 inches from the basket, and
only the coach is allowed to call a time out.
</P>
<P>
   1996 medalists: Men: United States, Yugoslavia, Lithuania;
Women: United States, Brazil, Australia
</P>
<P>
   Best of the Yanks: Atlanta gold medalist Gary Payton will be
expected to provide the leadership for this American men's team
that lacks some of the big-name glitter of the first two Dream
Teams. Alonzo Mourning and Kevin Garnett are the biggest of a
relatively small front line, and Allan Houston and Ray Allen give
the United States offense from the guard position. Look for a lot
of 3-point attempts.
</P>
<P>
   This is the best women's team ever fielded by the U.S. The
national team was named in 1995, thus these women have played a
great deal together in international competition and against one
another in the WNBA. Chamique Holdsclaw, Lisa Leslie, Sheryl
Swoopes, Ruthie Bolton-Holifield and Yolanda Griffith are
star-quality players. Teresa Edwards is a coach on the court, and
Swoopes, fresh off her fourth WNBA title, doesn't know how to lose.
</P>
<P>
   Rest of the blokes: There might be a smattering of players from
the NBA representing Croatia, Yugoslavia, Australia and Russia, but
even this watered-down U.S. Dream team should win handily. Luc
Longley and Chris Anstey give the Aussies the bulk to deal with
Mourning, Vin Baker and Garnett inside; Andrew Gaze is back again
to fire away from the perimeter. China has two 7-footers to clog
the middle. But if the United States loses, the players might want
to pursue free agency in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The quality of women's basketball is improving dramatically, and
Brazil (silver in Atlanta) and Australia (bronze), are capable of
an upset. Look for the Aussies _ led by WNBA players Michele Timms
and Michelle Griffiths and young center Lauren Jackson _ to be
inspired playing in front of their countrymen.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. medal chances: The U.S. men and women's teams are heavily
favored to bring home the gold. The world, however, is catching up,
and some of the games might be closer than expected. Of course for
the men, that could mean winning by 20 points instead of 35.
</P>
<P>
   Etc.: Oh, to be a fly on the wall listening to dinner
conversation at the men's camp in Hawaii. Seattle's Vin Baker
almost was traded to New York for Ewing, which would have made
Baker and Houston teammate. That's if Houston wasn't then traded as
some reports indicated would have happened. Instead, the trade fell
through and the winner was ... Olympic coach Rudy Tomjanovich. His
Houston Rockets signed free agent Maurice Taylor, who had wanted to
play with Ewing in Seattle. ... On second thought. Edwards said the
U.S. women's team was still ``head and shoulders better than
everyone.'' Then the retraction. ``Did I say `head and shoulders?'
'' Edwards said. ``I don't know if it's head and shoulders above.''
... Because his flight was canceled, Antonio McDyess (subbing for
the injured Tim Duncan) had to drive six hours from his Mississippi
home to Houston to sign his Olympic contract.
Spotlight on: The Dream Team
It's not the Dreams of the past, but it's still more than enough
for gold
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe it's a Dream Team, if you're a basketball fan in
Estonia. But from an American perspective, it's difficult to
mention Dream Team III in the same sentence with its Olympic
predecessors. In fact, the U.S. women might be more worthy of the
designation than Rudy Tomjanovich's squad, which should at least
compensate for its lack of superstars with an entertaining style of
play.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, we were spoiled in 1992 when Bird, Magic and Air Jordan
highlighted a team in which all 11 NBA players are probably headed
for the Basketball Hall of Fame. But Atlanta wasn't too shabby
either with David Robinson, Reggie Miller, Grant Hill, Hakeem
Olajuwon and Shaquille O'Neal playing for the first time. Now, it
appears that the novelty has worn off. Tim Duncan asked out because
of an injury. Hill pulled out, too, and Shaq wasn't interested. And
Kobe Bryant would rather spend the summer with his fiance and
reliving his NBA Championship.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the rest of the world should take heed: the talent pool in
the NBA is so deep that the United States could send a team of
spares to the Olympics and win the gold. But that is not the point.
The first Dream Team included Christian Laettner, who was a
collegian at the time. The second team was comprised only of pros.
Perhaps the NBA and United States Olympic Committee can tinker with
the selection process again and include two or three collegians who
were selected in the first round of the NBA Draft. It would give
fans a sneak preview of these potential stars.
</P>
<P>
   Without O'Neal or Duncan, Alonzo Mourning will have to carry the
majority of the rebounding load in Sydney. Kevin Garnett and
Antonio McDyess are leapers, not bangers, and Vin Baker plays soft
for a power forward. Thus, Tomjanovich's plan is for the Americans
to run and exploit their quickness, with Jason Kidd and Gary Payton
directing the offense.
</P>
<P>
   That certainly will be the case when Mourning leaves Sydney on
Sept. 22 to fly home to Miami, where his wife will give birth.
Mourning will then make the exhausting flight back to Sydney. He
will miss two games and might be too tired to be a factor in the
rest of the competition.
</P>
<P>
   That could enable Vince Carter, who will remind fans in Sydney
of a young Michael Jordan, to put on a one-man show from his small
forward's position. The United States also has plenty of outside
firepower.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though we are smaller on the front line than some of the
other countries like Australia, we play above the rim and we run,''
Mourning said.
</P>
<P>
   Kidd is the consummate point guard who will make sure everyone
gets his shots, but the question is, will games break down into a
series of one-on-one contests? Remember, Magic and Bird were
terrific passers who set the tone for the original Dream Team.
</P>
<P>
   That tour de force in 1992 won by an average of 43.8 points; the
1996 team won by an average of 32.3. points. So the margin is
beginning to shrink, making some other countries Daydream
Believers.
</P>
<P>
   But remember this: The U.S. record in any competition with NBA
players on the roster is 60-0. It should remain perfect in Sydney.
The question is whether the best NBA players are losing interest in
participating in an event that most of the world's athletes can
only dream about?
Some information for this preview came from ``The complete Book of
the Summer Olympics'' The Associated Press, and ESPN.com, CBS
Sportsline.com, and Fox sports.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
