<HEADLINE>
PAC-10 FOOTBALL MAKES QUICK FIX OF TARNISHED REPUTATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a famous Californian who liked to dabble in football ratings
might put it, ``We don't have the Pacific-10 Conference to kick
around anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Former president Richard Nixon, who crowned Texas as his
personal champion in 1969 after The Shootout with Arkansas, played
a little ball at Whittier College. A Division III team, Whittier
was 0-9 last season, which would have made them a perfect fit in
the Pac-10.
</P>
<P>
   Starting with highly ranked Arizona's 41-7 pratfall at Penn
State and ending with one victory in five bowl games, the league
had a 1999 season to forget. Arizona coach Dick Tomey admits the
league lost some prestige.
</P>
<P>
   One full week into the season, and some of that prestige is
returning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we were real tired of hearing the myth that Pac-10
football was done,'' Southern California defensive tackle Ennis
Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA, coming off a desultory 4-7 season, pulled the first big
shocker of the 2000 season with its 35-24 mastery of Alabama in the
Rose Bowl on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people didn't give us much credit,'' said UCLA coach
Bob Toledo, whose team went 10-2 in 1997 and '98. ``I don't know if
we're back, but I'm very excited right now for our football team
and the Pac-10.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss dropped the Crimson Tide from third to No. 13 in The
Associated Press media poll and from third to No. 14 in the USA
Today''/ESPN coaches poll. Rating drops like those have cooled the
national-championship talk in 'Bama.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly didn't play like the third-best team in the
nation,'' said Alabama coach Mike DuBose, who went from sitting
pretty to the hot seat in zero to 60 minutes of substandard
defensive football.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins' victory was a nice follow-up to crosstown rival
USC's 29-5 victory against Penn State in the Kickoff Classic on
Aug. 27. And while the Trojans' victory has been downgraded
slightly _ how good can the Nittany Lions be if they can't even
beat Toledo? _ those two victories have provided the Pac-10 with a
welcome image boost.
</P>
<P>
   In the Pac-10, UCLA and USC are similar to Texas and Texas A&AMP;M
in that the national perception of their conferences are tied to
their successes. Last season, UCLA and USC combined for 10
victories. When neither the Bruins nor the Trojans go bowling, the
Pac-10 is only a thin cut above the Mountain West Conference in
national perception.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just wanted to show the rest of the country that the Bruins
are back,'' said junior running back DeShaun Foster, who rushed for
a career-high 187 yards on 42 carries against Alabama. ``Hopefully,
we'll keep it rolling.''
</P>
<P>
   In the writers and coaches preseason polls, no Pac-10 team was
picked in the top 10. And while it is unlikely that the league will
produce a national-championship contender this season, the early
indications are that the Pac-10 will be better than last season.
</P>
<P>
   Most Pac-10 observers felt that this] Saturday's games would be
crucial to the league's image. Miami (Fla.) visits Washington, Ohio
State plays at Arizona, Colorado plays at USC, Oregon travels to
Wisconsin and Utah is at California. And while a few victories in
those games could provide some more buzz, UCLA and USC already have
done a nice job of carrying the Pac-10's banner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked to a lot of the players, and we all agree that we
want to make some noise on the national scene,'' Arizona State
senior linebacker Adam Archuleta said. ``Of course, it depends on
how good we play. If we play bad, we can't say anything.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, players in the Pac-10 can say about whatever they want.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
