<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROOKIE GLYNN THRIVES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ It wasn't 107 degrees in Detroit on Sunday. It was 78
degrees at game time, but intense humidity left manager Johnny
Oates concerned about starter Ryan Glynn. Oates even thought at one
point Glynn might be close to another one of his fainting spells.
</P>
<P>
   False alarm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was fine the whole game,'' Glynn said. ``There was just one
time where I got a bug in my face, and I was trying to wave it
away, and \Rfirst baseman Frank Catalanotto\S thought I was shaking
off a spell. Frankie thought I was bugging out. But I wasn't
speaking gibberish. I was fine the whole game.''
</P>
<P>
   Glynn, in his second start since coming off the disabled list,
held the Tigers to one run on seven hits in 61/3 innings as the
Rangers won, 4-1. He walked one and struck out two.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why we're so high on him; he was able to do what he did
today,'' Oates said. ``He pitched the ball extremely well.''
FOUR LIKELY TO BE CALLED
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers are planning to announce their September call-ups
today, and four are expected to join them from Triple-A Oklahoma:
outfielder Ruben Sierra, shortstop Kelly Dransfeldt, pitcher Darwin
Cubillan and catcher Randy Knorr.
</P>
<P>
   Sierra, a former three-time All-Star for the Rangers, is hitting
.326 with 18 home runs and 81 runs batted in, and Dransfeldt is
hitting .247 with eight homers and 42 RBI. Both aren't expected to
play much. Knorr is hitting .258 with six homers and 39 RBI and
would be recalled merely to give the Rangers an extra catcher.
</P>
<P>
   Cubillan, sent to Oklahoma on Tuesday, has a 3.86 ERA in seven
games with the Rangers. Oklahoma's last game is tonight, and the
call-ups are expected Tuesday in Chicago.
FIFTH SPOT, SOFT SPOT
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Oates used Ricky Ledee in the fifth spot Sunday, the
fourth time Ledee has batted fifth for the Rangers. The Rangers
have used nine players in the fifth spot: David Segui (67 starts),
Gabe Kapler (31), Ruben Mateo (17), Chad Curtis (5), Rusty Greer
(4), Bill Haselman (4), Dave Martinez (3), Frank Catalanotto (2)
and Ledee.
</P>
<P>
   The fifth hitter is supposed to protect the cleanup hitter,
Rafael Palmeiro, but the spot has given the Rangers mixed results.
The Rangers' No. 5 hitters, going into Sunday's game, had combined
to hit .314, the highest average from that spot in the American
League.
</P>
<P>
   But they also had combined for 12 homers, tied with Baltimore
for the fewest, and 73 RBI, tied with Oakland for the third fewest
in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what each team is getting from the fifth spot in the
order. Team Avg. HR RBI Anaheim .256 32 91 Baltimore .277 12 62
Boston .278 23 93 Chicago .274 18 91 Cleveland .285 34 98 Detroit
.252 21 89 Kansas City .266 18 87 Minnesota .284 13 66 New York
