<SLUG> BC-FBC-BURCH-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
 
Kansas coach faces heat 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
As a drought-plagued summer gives way to a steamy September, there
is no escaping the heat for Big 12 football teams and coaches.
<TEXT>
<P>
   On-field temperatures topped 100 degrees for league teams in
venues as far south as Dallas and as far north as South Bend, Ind.,
during the first full weekend of action. But the telling heat, the
type that won''t subside with the advent of cooler temperatures,
surfaced yesterday in the football offices at Texas A&AMP;M, Colorado
and Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies (0-1) and Buffaloes (0-1) dropped out of The
Associated Press' Top 25 rankings after dropping winnable season
openers to Notre Dame and Colorado State, respectively. Because of
emotional overtones surrounding both games, A&AMP;M coach R.C. Slocum
and Colorado coach Gary Barnett will be hearing howls of discontent
from angry fans and alumni until they prevail in the next
``statement'' game on the schedule.
</P>
<P>
   The upside for both coaches is that A&AMP;M and Colorado showed
enough in defeat to suggest a bounce-back could be around the next
corner.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas, on the other hand, is reeling and may not rebound. The
Jayhawks lost what coach Terry Allen described as a ``red-letter
game for us'' and did it in dismal fashion by falling to SMU,
31-17, in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   That makes Allen, a fourth-year coach in search of his first
winning record at Kansas, the owner of the hottest coaching seat in
the Big 12 as of Labor Day weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Given the Jayhawks' amount of returning talent (17 starters)
from a 5-7 team, coupled with an influx of 10 junior college
signees to provide immediate depth, Kansas was expected to spend
the season jockeying for position with Iowa State and Missouri to
land a job-saving bowl berth for one of three embattled coaches in
the North Division.
</P>
<P>
   A week ago, Allen seemed like the logical pick to withstand the
North Division's version of ``Coaching Survivor'' during the 2000
season. Now, he's the front-runner to be voted off the island.
</P>
<P>
   Both Iowa State and Missouri won their openers, capitalizing on
matchups against weak nonconference opponents. But Kansas couldn't
counter. And, with the loss to SMU, it's hard to see where the
Jayhawks _ now 1-15 on the road in Allen's tenure _ will pick up
the six victories necessary to land one of seven guaranteed bowl
berths available to Big 12 teams.
</P>
<P>
   Allen said he was ``amazed'' by his team's inept performance in
a game he had publicly identified as a potential season-maker or
season-breaker. The night began with the announced suspension of
the team's best player, free safety Carl Nesmith, and included
three first-quarter gaffes in the punting game that gift-wrapped 17
points for the Mustangs.
</P>
<P>
   After four possessions, SMU owned a 24-0 lead and coasted home,
leaving Allen perplexed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I've ever been as disappointed in one quarter
of football as I was out there,'' Allen said, referring to his
team's first-quarter meltdown in Dallas. ``We're not going to beat
anybody doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless the Jayhawks beat six teams between now and the end of
the regular season, expect a postseason coaching change. Early
feedback from players does not suggest a turnaround. One game into
the season, cornerback Andrew Davison sounds as if he's ready to
toss in the towel.
</P>
<P>
   Davison registered his disgust with the loss to SMU, a Western
Athletic Conference also-ran, in yesterday's editions of ``The
Kansas City Star''. After the game, Davison said: ``Here we go
again, just like last year. There was all this hype about how good
we were supposed to be and now we've lost to a WAC team. If we're
supposed to be better, I didn't see it.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless Allen finds a way to reverse that sort of thinking, the
Jayhawks won't experience a reversal of fortune in 2000. That's why
the hottest seat in a sizzling September can be found in the
football coach's office at Kansas. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
