<HEADLINE>
EMOTIONAL TESTAVERDE; PENALTY WOES 
</HEADLINE>
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Quarterback Vinny Testaverde felt the rush of emotion as he left
Lambeau Field and then he sat in his locker crying on Sunday, the
relief of his comeback checkered by memories of his late father Al,
who died in February 1999 and to whom he has dedicated the season.
With his 44 attempts, Testaverde passed Phil Simms to take over
15th place on the NFL's all-time pass attempts list.
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde's 23 completions also sent him past Simms into 18th
place and left him just three short of passing Jim Hart for 14th
place on the all-time completions list. Testaverde received a game
ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't any one point I thought, `I made it to this
point,'' &UR; ' &LR;  Testaverde said. ``This was probably one of my most
enjoyable victories.''
 &UR;  &LR; Penalty Woes
</P>
<P>
   If there was a downside to the Jets' performance, it was the
play of left tackle Jason Fabini. He was called for four of the
Jets' 10 penalties and accounted for 35 yards of penalties by
himself. It was an unusually error-prone effort by Fabini, who took
over the left tackle spot when Jumbo Elliott _ who has since come
out of retirement _ left after last season.
</P>
<P>
   One of Fabini's penalties nullified a play on which Wayne
Chrebet caught a touchdown pass. Fabini was benched after that, and
Kerry Jenkins, who started the game at left guard, played left
tackle while backup David Loverne played left guard.
</P>
<P>
   Fabini left the locker room quickly after the game and Coach Al
Groh would not say definitively that he would start Fabini next
week. Elliott, who was serving a one-game suspension this week,
will be available to play next week. ``We'll take some more
analysis,'' Groh said. ``No player is worth penalties.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
