<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MEDICAID-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: FINGERPRINTS FOR MEDICAID 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, Sept. 4:
</P>
<P>
   New York was among the first states to require electronic
fingerprinting of welfare recipients as a way to prevent fraud. But
as Nina Bernstein of The New York Times reported last week, there
is little solid evidence that finger imaging actually deters
welfare fraud, particularly when stringent work rules, shortened
eligibility times and other anti-fraud measures are already pushing
people off public assistance rolls at a brisk pace.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, a study conducted for the state three years ago found
that finger imaging made no difference in the approval or dropout
rates of welfare recipients. Yet despite that finding, state
officials are still pushing this strategy, and they are seeking
approval for $9.9 million to extend a contract with a finger
imaging company an additional year, to 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The state now wants to expand electronic fingerprinting to
440,000 adults who qualify for Medicaid, a proposition that makes
even less sense than fingerprinting welfare recipients. Few
patients are likely to seek extra medical treatment by posing as
two people. In fact, Medicaid fraud is largely committed by doctors
and other health care providers, a problem this measure does
nothing to address.
</P>
<P>
   Finger imaging will merely intimidate some Medicaid applicants
or cause them to stay away because of privacy concerns. The process
for getting Medicaid is already complicated and difficult. New York
City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and other officials are putting
together campaigns to encourage eligible uninsured individuals to
enroll in Medicaid. This is no time to erect a useless, expensive
hurdle that may dissuade low-income people from getting the care
they need.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-00 0119EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
