<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-OPEN-NOTEBOOK-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINNING STREAK SHOWS FEW SIGNS OF STOPPING; FROM GARDEN TO MUNICH;
LEE HITS THE TOWN; ALL WET AND LEFT OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (ADDS grafs 11-13 with McEnroe reaction; SUBS 3rd graf of 2nd item
to correct figure; ADDS 8th graf to 2nd item with Seles refusing to
play tournaments in Germany))  
 By LIZ ROBBINS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It is now 23 matches and counting, but Venus Williams
did not know much about her winning streak until a reporter
mentioned it to her last week.
</P>
<P>
   After showing a trace of vulnerability in her third-round match
Friday against Meghan Shaughnessy, the third-seeded Williams
eliminated Magui Serna, 6-2, 6-2, in 53 minutes Sunday to advance
to the quarterfinals. Her victory came after she waited around the
National Tennis Center for more than five hours during two rain
delays and wound up playing yet another late-afternoon match.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty disappointing,'' Williams said. She passed the
time by nibbling on food every hour. ``I'll never get away from
this place,'' she said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Not that she wants to do so anytime soon. ``In the first couple
of rounds I was not playing well,'' Williams said. ``But I feel
more warmed up and in a groove, more ready to compete.''
</P>
<P>
   After struggling with her serve in the third round, Williams was
much more efficient Sunday, winning 74 percent of her first-serve
points. She also had 24 winners to Serna's five.
</P>
<P>
   The last match Williams lost was to Arantxa Sanchez-Vicario, in
the quarterfinals at the French Open. But Williams will not get a
rematch because the eight-seeded Nathalie Tauziat defeated
Sanchez-Vicario, who was seeded ninth, in straight sets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has never been one of my goals to have a winning streak, so
this is nice,'' said Williams, whose streak includes her run to the
Wimbledon title.
</P>
<P>
   Williams did make it clear that one of her goals is avoiding a
battle of the sexes. After John McEnroe said that any male college
player or senior player could beat Venus or her sister, Serena, a
volley of words ensued, prompting Donald Trump to propose a $1
million match between either sister and McEnroe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that back in the '70s, Billie Jean King did it the
right way,'' Williams said, referring to King's match in the
Astrodome against Bobby Riggs. ``Right now I'm just really focusing
on trying to win this U.S. Open more than anything, just have a
good result here, just competing with the women.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some later date,'' Williams added, ``I'll be ready to think
about competing with men. At this point, I'm ready to just play the
Open.'' &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR;  Richard Williams, her father, al- ready said that neither she nor
Sere- na would participate anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew Richard was a smart guy and this only reinforces that
fact,'' McEnroe said Sunday. ``Richard knows it's best to keep his
daughters away from Johnny Mac.''
</P>
<P>
   As an aside, McEnroe added, ``By the way, Trump's offer was a
good start.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From Garden To Munich
</P>
<P>
   The Women's Tennis Association Tour will sever its 29-year
affiliation with Madison Square Garden after this year and hold its
year-end championships in Munich.
</P>
<P>
   The Chase Championships, a weeklong event beginning Nov. 13 this
year, will move to Germany and begin three weeks earlier, in
October 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The Garden's contract with the WTA was up after this year, and
while the Garden made a bid to renew the deal, the WTA made an
agreement with Munich officials worth about $1 million more prize
money. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It was disappointing,'' said Joel Fisher, senior vice
president of MSG Sports. ``We would have loved them back. We made
what we felt was a very fair offer, but we couldn't go any further
and we had to make the correct business decision. They felt they
had a better offer.''
</P>
<P>
   This will not mean the end of women's tennis in the Garden.
Fisher said the Garden was negotiating to establish an annual
exhibition with six of the top women's players at about the same
time in November, but for fewer days. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I do feel that in the end it will work out well,'' Fisher
said. ``We're pretty far along in our discussions and agreement.
We're proceeding forward as if we were having an event. I think
we're going to start asking players now.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Garden are trying to negotiate with
International Management Group, which works with several top
players, including Venus and Serena Williams, Lindsay Davenport and
Monica Seles.
</P>
<P>
   While Seles will play the coming Chase Championships in New
York, she will not play in them next year in Munich because she has
not played a tournament in Germany since being stabbed by a fan
during a crossover in a Hamburg tournament in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The tournament will be an exhibition because the WTA season will
have already ended. Fisher said he hoped the top players would be
attracted by the prize money and the opportunity to play in the
Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what the draw will be,'' he said. ``We feel the
responsibility for the fans in New York, and we think that major
women's tennis is on a real upswing. It's bittersweet, but it's
also very exciting, and a new opportunity.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lee Hits The Town
</P>
<P>
   Hyung-Taik Lee, the surprise fourth-round opponent of Pete
Sampras Monday, went on an afternoon escapade through Flushing's
Korean section Sunday after he practiced at the National Tennis
Center. At two restaurants, owners and staff showed him respectful
attention.
</P>
<P>
   When Lee, 24, a qualifier from Seoul, South Korea, walked into
the Korean-owned sushi restaurant Nam Sam, the owner quickly called
up her friends, who soon arrived en masse to get Lee's autograph.
After hors d'oeuvres there, Lee and his coaches went down Northern
Boulevard to Kum Kang San to eat Korean barbecue.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, who was ranked No. 182 in the world entering the Open, is
the first Korean man to reach the fourth round of a Grand Slam. In
1981, a Korean woman, Duk Hee Lee, advanced to the fourth round of
the U.S. Open before losing to Hana Mandlikova. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All Wet And Left Out
</P>
<P>
   For some fans, Sunday's rain was more than an exercise in
annoyance. After enduring two rain delays and waiting until Marat
Safin finally finished off Sebastien Grosjean in the fifth-set
tiebreaker, fans waiting for Venus Williams heard announcements
that her match against Magui Serna would be rescheduled.
</P>
<P>
   Officials moved her match to Louis Armstrong Stadium, giving
people little time to scurry next door. Within minutes, Armstrong
was close to capacity, and some fans were angry about being shut
out of the match.
</P>
<P>
   Officials moved the match to clear Arthur Ashe Stadium for the
featured night match, Jennifer Capriati against Monica Seles,
ensuring that if there was another rain delay during Williams'
match, she could finish it without upsetting the night schedule.
Seles went on to defeat Capriati, 6-3, 6-4. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
