<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 01:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0307 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-R-FBN-BUCS-PATRIOTS-N     09-04 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-FBN-BUCS-PATRIOTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUCCANEERS DOMINATE PATRIOTS WITH RELENTLESS PRESSURE ON BLEDSOE 
</HEADLINE>
  (REPEATING to add photo note) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBORO, Mass. _ The game's first play and its last one caused
the Tampa Bay Buccaneers to shiver.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly every play in-between, though, shook the New England
Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   The first play: Tampa Bay fumbled the game's opening kickoff at
its own 28-yard line and that led to a Patriots' field goal. The
final play: With one second remaining in the game, with New England
at the Tampa Bay 22 with a chance to win, the Patriots' final fling
from Drew Bledsoe, under siege, fell harmlessly out of the end zone
without a Patriot close to making the winning catch.
</P>
<P>
   So Tampa Bay won this lopsided scramble, 21-16. New England
scored its field goal after the game's opening turnover, scored on
a Troy Brown 66-yard punt return in the second quarter and scored
on a 39-yard pass play with 3 minutes 1 second left. Other than
that, it was complete domination by the Tampa Bay defensive line
versus the New England offensive line.
</P>
<P>
   It was a decisive and ugly domination.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe was hit so many times his head is probably still
ringing. On most Patriots' snaps, he would barely gather the ball
from center before some young Buc was in his face _ tackle Warren
Sapp or end Marcus Jones or linebacker Shelton Quarles or the
blitzing cornerback Ronde Barber among others. Bledsoe was sacked
six times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Emotionally, I'm beat up,'' Bledsoe said afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Physically, he looked beat up, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were talking to him all day, telling him it was going to be
a long day,'' said Bucs end Chidi Ahanotu. ``He said, `Yeah, yeah,
you're right, it's a long day.' When you can pin your ears back and
let it fly, well, you like games like that when you can just hound
the quarterback. They tried a version of the no-huddle to counter
us and they seemed more uncomfortable with it than we did. The
one-on-one matchups were good for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Sapp, the all-pro, said he read in a newspaper before the game
that he had been ``handled'' during the preseason. Sapp was hot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, that upset me so much, I couldn't eat breakfast,''
Sapp said. ``I was sick to my stomach. But we came out and showed
what we do. We get after the quarterback and get him, and that's
the ultimate prize. We're a team unit _ somebody strikes a match
and then everybody pours gas on it.''
</P>
<P>
   And New England's offense was singed.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots were a pitiful 4 of 17 (24 percent) in third-down
conversions. They gained more yards on kickoff and punt returns
(118) than they did rushing (88). Bledsoe was 26 of 39 for 216
yards with those six sacks, a touchdown pass to receiver Terry
Glenn and no interceptions. Even on his touchdown _ a heave, a lob
into the end zone just as he was crushed once again by the Tampa
Bay defense _ Bledsoe barely stood upright long enough to get it
off.
</P>
<P>
   A relatively immobile quarterback and a leaky offensive line
against a fierce pass rush and menacing defense.
</P>
<P>
   A wicked combination.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some trouble on pass protection,'' said Patriots Coach
Bill Belichick, who lost in his first regular-season game as the
team's head coach. ``They mixed it up some but kept us off balance.
They did a good job.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Tampa Bay offense did just enough, scoring 14
second-quarter points to lead by 14-10 at halftime. Fullback Mike
Alstott scored on a 5-yard run and receiver Reidel Anthony scored
on an 8-yard pass from quarterback Shaun King. On that play, King
acted like he was going to spike the ball but threw it into the end
zone instead, a fake-spike-play like the one the former Miami
quarterback Dan Marino performed a few seasons ago against the
Jets.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Buccaneers scored the only points of the third quarter
when Alstott started inside and then bounced outside for a 3-yard
run. That play made it 21-10 with 3:09 left in the quarter. The
score was set up by a forced fumble _ Bucs linebacker Derrick
Brooks on Patriots running back Kevin Faulk _ at the New England
24. The ball was recovered by safety John Lynch. It looked like
Tampa Bay would cruise from there, but Bledsoe to Glenn gave New
England a chance and the last play of the game could have turned
the whole affair upside down.
</P>
<P>
   The Tampa Bay defense would not let that happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in the right spot,'' Brooks, who made a game-high 15
tackles, said of his forced fumble on Faulk. ``I wanted to be
physical and finish my tackles because I had seen that some of
their backs have a tendency to put the ball on the ground.
Fortunately, we got it.''
</P>
<P>
   King said: ``If our defense can dominate like that we will be
something.''
</P>
<P>
   King (12 of 24, 167 passing yards, 1 touchdown and no
interceptions) made big plays, too, especially by converting on
seven third-down passing plays. He completed four passes to
Keyshawn Johnson for 64 yards, and Johnson opened passing lanes for
others.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did what we were supposed to do,'' Johnson said, ``and we
came out and won.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Dungy, Tampa Bay's coach, said: ``Those third-down plays
Shaun made were plays we weren't making throughout last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the Bucs have more team balance, but make no mistake, its
defense rules.
</P>
<P>
   `` I know we're going to improve,'' Ahantou said. ``But I don't
think we've ever been this far along as a defense at this point in
the season.''
</P>
<P>
   That's enough to shake up the rest of the league.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
