</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-PHILLIES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARK GIVES DODGERS REASON TO HOPE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS COCOLES  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The NFL has kicked off its season. USC's and
UCLA's big wins have L.A. excited about college football again.
</P>
<P>
   That means the Dodgers are no longer the only show in town. And
they've been gasping to keep their fans and themselves interested
in the baseball season.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, watching Chan Ho Park pitch is worth the ticket
prices. Park survived his own wildness Sunday to remain one of
baseball's hottest pitchers in leading the Dodgers to a 6-1 win
over the Philadelphia Phillies at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Park (15-8) yielded just two hits and struck out six in eight
shutout innings. He's won his last four starts, compiling an 0.84
earned-run average (three earned runs allowed in 32 innings) over
that span.
</P>
<P>
   Park matched his career high in victories and was asked about
the possibility of being a 20-win pitcher with roughly five starts
remaining in his season.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I get 20 wins I'll buy you dinner,'' Park told reporters.
``I have 15 wins now. I can't think about 20 wins. I have to worry
about right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Park was more concerned about his control Sunday. He fell behind
in the count far too much, issuing seven walks. But the Phillies
never cashed in.
</P>
<P>
   Park induced three double-play grounders. None was bigger than
his smothering of Tomas Perez's comebacker in the fifth to start a
1-6-3 double play. Pat Burrell and Marlon Anderson had drawn walks
to open the inning in what was still a 1-0 game.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how (Park's) been all year; once he gets a guy on base
he's very focused, especially when they get in scoring position,''
catcher Chad Kreuter said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knew he needed to get double-play balls in certain
situations and he did get them.''
</P>
<P>
   Park came back to strike out pitcher Robert Person to end the
fifth. His teammates provided breathing room in the bottom of the
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Person (7-5) had retired 11 in a row since the Dodgers scored a
first-inning run. But Adrian Beltre led off the fifth with an
opposite-field solo homer. Kreuter then walked and eventually
scored on the first of Mark Grudzielanek's two RBI singles.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers keep winning _ Sunday's victory was their 11th in 14
games _ while gaining modest ground in both the National League's
Western Division and wild-card playoff chases.
</P>
<P>
   When the Dodgers lost to Montreal on Aug. 21, they were 62-61,
nine games behind division-leading San Francisco. The Dodgers' hot
streak has shaved just two games off the Giants' advantage. San
Francisco won its fifth consecutive game on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' sweep of Philadelphia failed to make up any games
in their chase of the Giants. But they're just two games back of
second-place Arizona, have crept within 6 1/2 of the Mets for the
NL wild-card and are playing their best baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think of a lot of good things with this ballclub,'' manager
Davey Johnson said. ``Defensively, we're playing better. ... And we
seem to be getting a little better (starting) pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers can't afford to be anything but sensational in the
season's final 25 games in order to maintain their already-faint
hopes of the playoffs. At 73-64, the Dodgers are nine games over
.500 for the first time since ending the 1997 season 88-74.
</P>
<P>
   ``You to try to get these kinds of winning streaks when it
really counts,'' left fielder Gary Sheffield said. ``You want to
try and do this a lot earlier and then we can put pressure on
teams. If we played like this earlier, we'd probably be one or two
games ahead or behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's never too late. You've got to play the games. Nobody's
going to lay down for nobody.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
