<HEADLINE>
BELICHICK, BLEDSOE BEATEN UP BY TAMPA BAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ He often walked off the field looking as if
he'd been mugged. His shoulder pads were up in his ear, his helmet
was turned sideways, and there were often pieces of the Foxboro
Stadium turf stuck on his face.
</P>
<P>
   Often his last sight before walking off in disgust was watching
Warren Sapp's celebratory dance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Emotionally, I'm beat up,'' said Drew Bledsoe. ``Those types
of games, when you have a chance to win and you don't, hurt me.''
</P>
<P>
   As beaten as he looked, Bledsoe still had a chance to win the
Patriots' season opener Sunday. But just as it appeared the offense
was about to make some headway, time ran out, the Patriots lost the
first game of the Bill Belichick regime, 21-16, before 60,292 at
Foxboro Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unacceptable,'' said Patriots safety Lawyer Milloy. ``Our
goals were set high. Whenever you lose a game in your home stadium,
it's unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   Belichick did not look for any excuses or positives on the
dismal day. He could not find even a glimpse of praise for his
offense, though Bledsoe did connect with Terry Glenn on a 39-yard
touchdown pass with 3:01 remaining in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tampa Bay outplayed us,'' said Belichick. ``We didn't make
enough plays.''
</P>
<P>
   There weren't enough Troy Brown moments, either. The top
playmaker ran back a punt 66 yards for a touchdown (the first
touchdown return of his career) and ran back another 39 yards. He
also ran a 35-yard reverse and caught seven passes for 70 yards,
including one for 26 yards.
</P>
<P>
   There weren't enough Troy Browns, not in the receiving corps,
the running game (running backs accounted for 25 yards on 11
carries), or on the offensive line. For despite quantity _ nine
offensive linemen played _ the quality of the line's play was
lacking. It did not open holes against the tough, fast, and
superior Buccaneers defensive front. They allowed six sacks, 14
knockdowns, and 21 hurries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bledsoe is the heart and soul of New England,'' Sapp said.
``If you can beat Bledsoe, you can beat New England. We knew we had
to get in his face, but he got away a few times. He knows when
we're coming after him. But you know he's going to drop back 5 or 6
yards and then you have to get him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' offensive line had a horrific day. Max Lane tried
playing with a broken thumb, but allowed a sack and a pressure to
Sapp and he was out of the game quickly. ``I wasn't effective,''
said Lane. ``We just made a lot of mistakes. We've had six weeks to
prepare and get it right and it just didn't happen for us today.''
</P>
<P>
   The line had done a respectable job against Tampa Bay in the
fourth exhibition game Aug. 20, but it had to figure it didn't see
the best of the Buccaneers' defensive line in that one. The
Patriots used odd substitutions on the line for a regular-season
game. But the Patriots used Jason Andersen over Damien Woody on
long snaps, and Andersen played left and right guard when veteran
Grant Williams replaced rookie Greg Robinson-Randall as the
starting right tackle after Robinson-Randall had taken virtually
every snap of the exhibition season.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots had a chance to hit the jackpot at the game's
beginning, but settled for the consolation prize. Kevin Williams
fumbled the opening kickoff on a great hit by Larry Whigham and
Kato Serwanga gobbled up the loose ball at the Buccaneers 28. After
a quick sideline pass to Glenn gave the Patriots a first down at
the 16, the pressuring of Bledsoe began in earnest as he had to
throw away a third-and-6 pass intended for Eric Bjornson. Adam
Vinatieri came on to hit a 30-yard field goal, giving the Patriots
a 3-0 lead with 12:19 left in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But then the momentum began swinging the Buccaneers' way. On a
Lee Johnson punt late in the first quarter, Whigham and Tony
Simmons converged near the goal line and Whigham appeared to jump
up in the end zone and bat the ball to the 5. But the officials
ruled it was a touchback and the call survived a Patriots
challenge. The Buccaneers then drove 80 yards on 11 plays with a
pounding, tough running game featuring Mike Alstott (16 carries, 54
yards) inside and Warrick Dunn (16 carries, 56 yards) outside. The
big pass play was a 25-yard toss from Shaun King to Keyshawn
Johnson over the middle on which Tebucky Jones grabbed the
receiver's facemask advancing the spot from the 25 to the Patriots
12. Three plays later, Alstott capped it off with a rugged 5-yard
run on which his blockers knocked everyone off the line.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' offense was well into its three-and-out mode when
Brown changed the routine. Fielding a punt at the Patriots 34,
Brown shot up the middle after Harold Shaw, Ty Law, and Tony George
made big blocks to give Brown some room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just ran and didn't look back,'' said Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Leading, 10-7, the Patriots' fortunes turned to misfortune. What
had been a flawless and effective defense made backbreaking
mistakes. With less than a minute remaining in the half, King
connected on a 33-yard pass with Jacquez Green on a quick out on
which cornerback Antonio Langham went for the pickoff. With 31
seconds remaining and the ball at the 8, King faked a spike and
threw a fade to the right corner to Reidel Anthony over Serwanga
for the score.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Belichick always tells us to be alert, but we fell
asleep on that one,'' said Milloy.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots were at least playing with the Buccaneers on a
physical and emotional level into the third quarter. But the wind
went slightly out of their sails when Kevin Faulk fumbled at the
end of a 9-yard pass play on a vicious hit by Derek Brooks (15
tackles). The ball was recovered by safety John Lynch at the
Patriots 32 and he ran it to the 24. Four plays later, with left
guard Randall McDaniel lined up as a fullback, Alstott bounced off
a pile and kicked to the right for a 3-yard score, making it 21-10
with 3:09 remaining in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until late in the fourth quarter that Bledsoe
connected with Glenn, but the Patriots botched the 2-point
conversion when Michael Bishop's pitch was fumbled by Faulk.
</P>
<P>
   There was still time. The Patriots' defense made a couple of
plays, including an 11-yard sack of King by Willie McGinest at the
Buccaneers 12. After Mark Royals's punt, the Patriots took over at
the Buccaneers 45, but without any timeouts. They converted on
fourth and 1 at the 26 when Bledsoe hit Brown for 4 yards. After a
spike stopped the clock with 11 seconds left, Bledsoe rolled right
and saw Chris Calloway open in the end zone on the opposite side of
the field. But his throw didn't quite get there in time. ``For a
while it looked like I had him,'' said Bledsoe.
</P>
<P>
   After another incompletion and with one second remaining,
Bledsoe said he called a play on which there was miscommunication
with Glenn. He wanted Glenn to run a post, but he called a Q-route,
which is a comeback route (unless the defense is in a certain
coverage). Glenn ran the Q-route, curling in, and ball sailed over
the end zone. Game over.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed just one more play,'' said Chad Eaton. ``As a
defense, we were looking for one more chance to put the ball in the
offense's hands and we couldn't quite get it late in the game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
