<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 02:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0314 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ANALYSIS     09-04 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATIENCE BLEDSOE'S VIRTUE, AND DOWNFALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Drew Bledsoe had the best rushing day of his
career Sunday. That is not a good thing for the New England
Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   The suddenly scrambling Bledsoe rushed eight times for 30 yards
and the only man to outrush him (other than Tampa Bay defensive
tackle Warren Sapp, who rushed to wherever he wanted) was Patriots
wide receiver Troy Brown, who gained 33 yards on two carries.
</P>
<P>
   When your leading rushers are a wide receiver and a quarterback,
it's probably a sign that things did not go well on opening day,
and in fact, they did not.
</P>
<P>
   The Buccaneers came to Foxboro Stadium with a reputation for
having one of the league's best defenses. They left with a better
reputation for defense than the Marines.
</P>
<P>
   All day, Sapp and the six men who accompany him up front in
Tampa Bay destroyed the Patriots' offensive line and manhandled
Bledsoe, sacking him six times, knocking him down 14 times, and
hurrying him 21 times, according to unofficial statistics.
</P>
<P>
   In New England's 66 offensive plays, its quarterback ended up on
the ground 28 times. If this continues, it will be a long season
for the Patriots and a short one for Bledsoe.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Tampa Bay had escaped with a 21-16 win when
Bledsoe's last desperate pass fell out of bounds _ in part because
of a miscommunication with receiver Terry Glenn that led to Glenn
running a comeback route when Bledsoe wanted a post corner _ an
ambulance roared up Route 1, lights flashing and sirens blaring. As
fans and media wandered down toward the parking lots and locker
room, someone remarked, ``There goes Bledsoe.''
</P>
<P>
   Not this time, but soon enough if this keeps up.
</P>
<P>
   When the game was over, Bledsoe's back was scratched, his skin
was blotched red, and his face was flushed. To say he will be sore
Monday is like saying Sapp will wake up happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were talking to Bledsoe all day,'' said Tampa Bay defensive
end Chidi Ahanotu. ``We knew he wasn't the kind of quarterback to
sit in there and take hits.''
</P>
<P>
   If there is someone who could have sat in there and taken any
more hits without cracking, it would have to be a Sluggo doll.
Despite the beating, Bledsoe still finished 26 of 39 for 216 yards
with no interceptions and a 39-yard fourth-quarter touchdown pass
to Glenn that cut Tampa Bay's lead to 5 with 3:01 to play.
</P>
<P>
   When he got one last chance with 1:53 left beginning at the
Tampa Bay's 45, Bledsoe completed five passes and was sacked once,
moving the ball to the Tampa Bay 22 before that last ball fluttered
harmlessly out of bounds.
</P>
<P>
   He had not pulled off the comeback after pulling himself off the
floor but he had come close. Considering he took the kind of
beating Joe Frazier could relate to, it was a performance that
inspired.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got beat on all day but he kept giving us chances to make
plays,'' Brown said. ``He gave us a chance to win it at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   That is more than can be said of the offensive line. Rotated all
day like a carousel, with every lineman playing at one point or
another and some playing more than one position, the unit allowed
its backs to gain a total of 25 yards and got the quarterback half
decapitated. Other than that, it was a pretty good day for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hope everyone doesn't feel very good about how we
played,'' tackle Grant Williams said. ``There's no secrets with
them. They came after us and we didn't play well. If there's a
positive it was Drew. He was the consummate pro. It was good to see
some leadership like that.''
</P>
<P>
   That leader was often buried under 600 pounds of Tampa Bay
defenders but he was there somewhere _ even at the end when he was
as punchy as one of Mike Tyson's sparring partners. Still throwing,
still taking the hit, still making his reads and looking for
receivers who, frankly, weren't open often enough or quickly enough
to be effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``Emotionally I'm beat up, but physically I feel fine,'' Bledsoe
said. ``Those type of games, when you have a chance to win and
don't, those take the biggest toll emotionally. As a kid growing up
those are the situations you think of . . . Some ways I'm still
like a little kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday he was beaten up like a little kid who continues getting
up off the playground grass to fight anew. He fought until there
was no time left, fittingly being drilled on his last pass of the
day as he was on so many others.
</P>
<P>
   But he also brought his team back in the face of a hard rain of
a pass rush all around him, holding his ground behind a line that
could not hold its own and delivering no interceptions and nearly
the pass that could have won the game.
</P>
<P>
   That came with 11 seconds left when Chris Calloway somehow got
wide open in the left corner of the end zone as Bledsoe was rolling
wide to his right. At the last moment, he saw Calloway and tried to
fling the ball to him as the rush closed on him. Unable to fully
set himself to fire, the ball took too long to reach Calloway and
was knocked to the ground. For all intents and purposes, that was
the end of the game. Tampa Bay had given New England its window of
opportunity and then slammed it shut.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a minute there I thought we had it,'' Bledsoe said. ``But
I couldn't set up to throw it fully.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the case all afternoon and if it continues, he'll be
gone before the leaves are. He probably knows this. Certainly the
men trying to protect him know it. And you can bet coach Bill
Belichick knows it.
</P>
<P>
   What they do about it, not a soul knows this morning. Except
Bledsoe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll get better,'' Bledsoe said of his pass protection. ``It
has to. When you play quarterback in this league, you're going to
get hit. They're going to get their shots. You just have to be
patient.''
</P>
<P>
   If Bledsoe continues to take shots like he did Sunday, he won't
have to be patient anymore. He'll just be a patient.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
