<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS' ABBOTT FLIRTS WITH NO-HITTER 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-MARINERS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ As the esteemed former voice of the Red Sox, Ned
Martin, might say, ``Mercy.''
</P>
<P>
   It has come to this. With 29 games to go in a wild scramble
toward the postseason, the Sox Sunday &UR;  &LR; night squandered another
vital game, extending their run-production crisis in a one-hit act
of futility.
</P>
<P>
   One hit. Facing a journeyman, Seattle righthander Paul Abbott,
who had been on the disabled list 10 times and had never pitched
anything near a no-hitter, the Sox went hitless until Rico Brogna
grounded a single up the middle with one out in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   One hit. That was it, as the Sox got pancaked by the Mariners,
5-0, and dropped two games behind Cleveland in the American League
wild-card race. They languish six games behind the Yankees in the
East.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll hit (Monday),'' manager Jimy Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   That would be nice, since the alternative, with stopper Pedro
Martinez on the mound, would be near-certain disaster.
</P>
<P>
   But just one more hit Sunday &UR;  &LR; night might have made a remarkable
difference. Trailing, 3-0, in the eighth, the Sox loaded the bases,
as Brogna singled, and Scott Hatteberg and Trot Nixon drew walks
off the tiring Abbott.
</P>
<P>
   That brought up Nomar Garciaparra with two outs and Jose
Paniagua on to relieve Abbott. The ``Rocky'' theme blared. The
crowd rose.
</P>
<P>
   But Garciaparra, mired in a slump that has sent him from
flirting with .400 to third in the AL batting race, flied out to
right. It was the 15th straight game in which Garciaparra failed to
drive in a run, the longest stretch of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, he was among many reflecting on the team's drought.
The Sox have scored two runs or fewer in four of the last six
games. It was the sixth time this season they have been shut out.
</P>
<P>
   And the more they struggle, the more they press.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes everybody tries to do too much,'' Garciaparra said.
``It can snowball. They say hitting is contagious. But it can go
the other way, too. People are struggling, and saying, `I gotta do
it, I gotta do it, I gotta do it,' and they're trying to hit a
five-run home run every time at the plate. You can't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   So, the Sox are 1-2 to start a 10-game homestand they consider
the most important of the season. They have little more margin for
failure.
</P>
<P>
   They can thank Abbott for most of their sadness. Though it was
his only start this season in which he did not allow an earned run,
Abbott baffled the Sox mostly with a changeup and sharp control
until he faltered in the eighth. That was the only time a Boston
base runner reached second.
</P>
<P>
   ``No team wants to come close to getting no-hit,'' Brogna said.
``But you have to tip your hat to the guy. He pitched super.''
</P>
<P>
   The same could not be said for the Sox starter, Tomo Ohka, who
was shaky from the start.
</P>
<P>
   His trouble started with the second batter he faced, Stan
Javier, who bounced a double off the scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
   Ohka walked Alex Rodriguez, bringing up the RBI machine, Edgar
Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   He survived Martinez, who flied out to left field, but John
Olerud lined a double to right-center for a 2-0 Seattle lead.
</P>
<P>
   Triggering a smattering of boos, Ohka then walked Jay Buhner,
prompting pitching coach Joe Kerrigan to visit the mound to try to
calm the rookie.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever Kerrigan said apparently worked because Ohka retired
Carlos Guillen on a ground out. He pitched five more scoreless
innings before Rod Beck took over in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   But Ohka's recovery hardly pleased him. ``What bothers me is
that I gave up two runs in the first inning and that cost us the
game,'' he said through an interpreter.
</P>
<P>
   But catcher Jason Varitek credited him for the poise he showed
when the Mariners had him on the ropes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can go out there and hold a first-place team to two
runs when you don't have your best stuff, that's pretty good,''
Varitek said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners extended their lead off Beck in the seventh. Mark
McLemore laced a ground-rule double to right and scored on Javier's
double.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Sang Lee pitched a scoreless eighth for the Sox. But with
two out in the ninth, he walked Javier and gave up a gargantuan
home run over everything to left by Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   Later, the Sox sought to keep hope alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're far from being out of it,'' Varitek said. ``What it's
going to take is for us to get on a roll and play free and easy and
just let things happen.''
</P>
<P>
   He noted, though, that the roll needs to start soon and last
``for a long stretch.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
