<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEASON TO BELIEVE IN RED SOX 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-ANALYSIS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Unofficially, Labor Day marks the end of summer and,
for generations of Red Sox fans, the beginning of the season of
despair.
</P>
<P>
   It was that way when Red Sox receptionist Helen Robinson was a
teen and has not changed a bit, even as she begins year 60 as the
grande dame of Yawkey Way.
</P>
<P>
   Back-to-back losses to the Seattle Mariners this weekend did
nothing to lighten the predictable gloom that every year settles in
as surely as the fog on Block Island.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox collected a grand total of four hits in two games,
and were nearly no-hit Sunday by Mariners righthander Paul Abbott,
a guy who broke into the big leagues in 1990 and began this season
averaging less than one win for each year he has pitched.
</P>
<P>
   It took an eighth-inning single by Rico Brogna to give the Red
Sox as many hits off the nondescript Abbott as the Devil Rays had
last Tuesday off the incomparable Pedro.
</P>
<P>
   Even with a win from Pedro the Younger this afternoon, the Sox
can do no better than a split with the Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox are six games behind the Yankees in the AL East, two
behind the Indians in the wild-card race. They are not fighting for
the postseason as much as doing a baseball rope-a-dope, covering
up, taking some withering blows, while hoping that the other guys
tire.
</P>
<P>
   Still, when Miss Gandy welcomes a new class of third-graders
Tuesday for the start of another school year, she is advised to
pull up the shades, throw open the windows, and tell her kids that
they will not be bound by the same portents of doom their parents
see in every Sox loss.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because I am here to say the Sons of Jimy Williams are
going to win the American League pennant.
</P>
<P>
   Call me mad. Call me Nomar's bobo. Pedro's puppet. Duke's dweeb.
The loon from Lunenburg.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of those things are true,'' said one pressbox colleague,
shaking his head. ``Win the pennant? This last month is going to
look like the Iraqi retreat to Baghdad, with (Dan) Duquette as
Saddam Hussein.''
</P>
<P>
   Do you detect a slight difference of opinion? But hear me out.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, if you gave the Sox a nickel for every big hit they've
gotten lately, it would be a month before they could afford a
double decaf latte at Starbucks. Did you see that Indians-Orioles
score, 12-11? The Sox haven't scored in double figures since July
20, and that was 42 games ago.
</P>
<P>
   But I defy anyone to tell me that Nomar Garciaparra will go
another 15 games in a row without driving in a run, the way he has
the last two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Or that Dante Bichette, the new guy, won't soon be taking aim at
the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Or that Trot Nixon won't stand up again to the Yankees this
weekend, or that Troy O'Leary and Rico Brogna and Jason Varitek and
Lou Merloni and Brian Daubach (if he ever recovers the feeling in
his left arm) will deliver meaningful hits before it's over.
</P>
<P>
   I agree. It is worrisome that Bichette has hit just three home
runs since the All-Star break. And yes, his career numbers are
inflated by the years he spent hitting in the thin air of Denver.
But he has hit his whole life, he will hit here, and his addition
gives the Sox three middle-of-the-order hitters that ultimately
will be tough outs down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   It's one of the absolute truisms of the game. Hitting comes and
goes. Mostly, it has been gone this season, but while the stats say
the Sox rank 12th in the league in scoring, this team is different
than the one forced to rely on the likes of Ed Sprague earlier.
</P>
<P>
   What these Sox have now is starting pitching, and pitching
depth. Pedro Martinez, Rolando Arrojo, and Ramon Martinez are all
veteran big-game pitchers, better than any three you can name from
the other contenders, including the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Tomo Ohka, despite taking the loss Sunday, has been a dependable
fourth, and Tim Wakefield, Jeff Fassero, Pete Schourek, and
eventually Paxton Crawford give the Sox some options.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox bullpen is deeper, and Derek Lowe is better than anybody
else's closer not wearing pinstripes, and this season Lowe has been
even more reliable than Mariano Rivera of the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox are playing superb defense. They have not made an error
in their last six games, and have made just nine errors in their
last 20 games. In that stretch, they have committed more than one
error in a game just once.
</P>
<P>
   And even while it seems that some Sox types operating behind the
scenes are trying to sandbag Jimy Williams over the Izzy Alcantara
affair (as if Alcantara could ever have been more than the 24th or
25th man on the roster), that little tiff pales compared to the bad
feelings left by Boss Steinbrenner's attack on injured Yankee
second baseman Chuck Knoblauch, or the flareup between Yankee
manager Joe Torre and reliever Jeff Nelson last week.
</P>
<P>
   Say this for Williams. They have yet to invent a tempest in this
town that will cause him to stray off course.
</P>
<P>
   This is the time of year pitching and defense win games.
Duquette agrees, to a point.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole thing for us is to score enough runs to get into the
postseason,'' Duquette said, ``because if we get in the playoffs we
will be a very dangerous ballclub.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we've got to get enough run production to get there.''
</P>
<P>
   Forget about hoping for a miraculous recovery from Jose
Offerman, who has been a ghost of the leadoff man who scored 107
runs last season and had 56 extra-base hits. His sore left knee
will not permit him to be that kind of player.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needs six weeks of rest for it to heal,'' Duquette said
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But even without a healthy Offerman, the Sox have the components
to win. And for a change, they would welcome some positive vibes
down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here for only one purpose,'' Pedro Martinez said Sunday.
``Just win. That's my goal. Until I do, I won't rest. Sooner or
later, our guys step up, especially this time of year. We know how
to win. If we don't, we find a way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're going to do what we're going to do, but keeping
other people positive for longer gives more fun to the chase. It
adds a little fun to everything we do. If we don't win when people
are not negative and we lose, that doubles the pain.''
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra wants people to know that he deeply appreciates the
way they've stuck with this team.
</P>
<P>
   ``The season drains on you, it weighs on you _ you're playing
every day and everything that happens, on and off the field, it
affects you. But people have been supporting us great the whole
year, and we appreciate it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't take that for granted. We definitely have a chance,
and we ain't giving up, I can tell you that.''
</P>
<P>
   Just try it. Set aside the usual vibes.
</P>
<P>
   This year, tell yourself the Sox will win.
</P>
<P>
   And believe it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
