<SLUG> BC-BBA-RYAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOUGHTS OF A NO-NO? YES-YES! 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Did he know? What do you think? When you have been in
and out of major league baseball since 1990 and you have never
thrown a complete game, you damn well know when you're flirting
with a no-hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most definitely,'' admitted Paul Abbott. ``I knew. I started
thinking about it in the fifth inning. You're aware. If you get
that far with pretty good stuff, with good command, you just
continue your game plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Abbott and no-hitter don't quite have that
love-and-marriage/horse-and-carriage resonance, but stranger things
have happened in this game. People with far fewer credentials than
the goateed 32-year-old Paul Abbott have thrown major league
no-hitters. You just never know when you'll be attending a major
league game and a no-hitter will break out, although it seems to
happen everywhere but here.
</P>
<P>
   Through five, through six, and through seven innings Seattle's
journeyman righthander (14-15, 4.47 ERA in 47 major league starts,
interspersed with 36 relief appearances and a whopping 10 trips to
the disabled list) had his no-no. Nomar Garciaparra had stroked one
fairly deep to center in the first. Troy O'Leary had drilled one to
very deep center in the second. Dante Bichette had hit one about
two steps from the warning track in center in the seventh. And when
Jason Varitek led off the eighth inning with a shot to right that
died on the warning track in the eighth, Paul Abbott was five outs
away from both his first major league complete game and the first
Fenway Park no-hitter in 35 years, minus 13 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I honestly thought he was going to get it when Varitek's ball
stayed in the ballpark,'' observed catcher Joe Oliver. ``He hit
that ball great.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the thing about a no-hitter. It's not just about good
stuff, although Abbott certainly had that. ``Best fastball I've had
all year,'' he pointed out. ``When that happens, it makes
everything else better.'' Those other things, in this case, were a
changeup and a slider, both of which played beautifully off a
90-plus heater.
</P>
<P>
   But a no-hitter always requires luck. You need a reasonable
share of those ``right at 'em'' balls, and you've got to hope that
when someone does get hold of one it goes to the big part of the
ballpark. O'Leary really smashed that ball in the second, for
example. It wasn't much different than the ball he hit for a homer
on Saturday, except that it wasn't pulled quite as much. So all it
turned out to be was a very long ``8'' in the scorebook.
</P>
<P>
   Abbott had plenty on his mind when he started the eighth. His
lead was a hardly impregnable 3-0, and he was, after all, in Fenway
Park. But no one is foolish enough to deny that when a man takes a
no-hitter into the eighth inning, that becomes the immediate
priority. You figure if you keep that no-no going the W will kind
of take care of itself.
</P>
<P>
   Here's another reason a no-hitter was a plausible outcome. The
Red Sox have become baseball's resident Hitless Wonders. They
compressed their offense into one little outburst on Friday and
they were held to three hits on Saturday. They really haven't hit
well all year. This is currently as no-hittable as any team in
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   With Varitek retired, the next batter was Rico Brogna. He had
grounded to second and lined out hard into a double play in the
fifth. He was a very good candidate to at least get his bat on the
ball.
</P>
<P>
   Abbott fell behind, 2-0. He came in with a fastball and Brogna
bounced one hard past the mound. ``I wished I had shaded a bit more
toward the middle,'' said Alex Rodriguez. ``I gave it my best shot.
I gave it my best effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course. He's A-Rod, after all. He moved to his left and hit
the ground, but the ball skidded into center field. Bye-bye,
no-hitter. The Fenway no-hit drought continues. The Ghost of Dave
Morehead still patrols these hallowed grounds.
</P>
<P>
   There was still the matter of the complete game and, of course,
the W. Pinch hitter Midre Cummings flied to center for the second
out. He walked pinch hitter Scott Hatteberg, bringing manager Lou
Piniella and those hilarious itty-bitty steps to the mound. ``I was
able to talk him into letting me stay in,'' Abbott claimed. Let the
record show that Piniella took 41 of those baby steps between the
mound and the dugout on his return trip. That is major league
short-stepping.
</P>
<P>
   Trot Nixon was next. Abbott, now in very unfamiliar territory
with a triple-figure pitch count, lost the Boston leadoff man on 3
and 2. After a lengthy delay, Piniella made a return trip to the
mound. A disappointed, but resigned, Abbott would not be getting
that complete game. Jose Paniagua would be pitching to Nomar
Garciaparra with the bases loaded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was out of gas,'' Abbott admitted. ``I've never even had a
complete game, much less a shutout.''
</P>
<P>
   With the bases loaded and the game in the balance, the suspense
lasted all of two pitches. Nomar flied routinely to right. End of
threat.
</P>
<P>
   So Paul Abbott was left to ponder the evening's intriguing
events. This was, without question, the best game he had ever
pitched in the big leagues. But with a little more luck it might
have been something even more special. It might have been a
no-hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least it wasn't a cheap hit,'' Abbott reasoned. ``It was a
situation where I fell behind and I had to take my chances. He hit
a fastball back up the middle. It was clean. It would have been
hard to swallow if it had been a broken-bat hit. I got behind, and
I put him at an advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You always hate losing it on a little flare,'' agreed Oliver.
``This was a legitimate hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever the master of understatement, skipper Piniella allowed that
``We need to get starting pitching, and that was an excellent job
tonight.'' Sorry, Lou, but it was a little more than that. Around
these parts, we've come to the conclusion that Fenway Park has a
better chance of being hit by an asteroid than being the sight of a
no-hitter. Paul Abbott had a few pulses racing Sunday &UR;  &LR; night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
