<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX HONOR SOCIETY HAS SPECIAL MEMORIES 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It's an exclusive club. The Red Sox Social Register is
not like that of the Yankees or Celtics, who are running out of
monuments, wall space, and digits. There's no ``Loscy'' on the
right-field facade at Fenway Park and worthies such as Jimmie Foxx,
Tony Conigliaro, Harry Agganis, Jim Rice, and Luis Tiant have been
denied admission.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Williams (No. 9), Joe Cronin (No. 4), Bobby Doerr (No. 1),
and Carl Yastrzemski (No. 8) make up the Mount Crushmore of the
ancient Back Bay theater and Monday they are joined by New
Hampshire's own Carlton Fisk (No. 27).
</P>
<P>
   Fisk is the first New Englander to have his number retired by
the Red Sox. Williams, Doerr, and Cronin were all born in
California and Yaz grew up in (gulp) Southampton, N.Y. Catcher
Carlton was born in Bellows Falls, Vt., and raised in Charlestown,
N.H. He's the only member of the Fab Five who knows a frappe from a
milkshake.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox started wearing numbers on their backs in 1931 (this
would take Babe Ruth out of consideration), and first retired
numbers May 29, 1984, when they honored Williams and Cronin. Doerr
went up on the wall in 1988 and Yaz was immortalized a year later.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, the Sox insisted a player would only be considered
for the honor if he had these credentials:
</P>
<P>
   1. Membership in the Baseball Hall of Fame;
</P>
<P>
   2. At least 10 years of service with the Red Sox;
</P>
<P>
   3. He finished his career with the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, Yastrzemski, and Doerr played their entire careers in
Boston. Cronin played 6 1/2 years for the Washington Senators
before coming to Boston in 1935. Cronin managed the Red Sox for a
club-record 13 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Fisk's inclusion would appear to violate the third stipulation
of the Sox' arbitrary rules. (The Boston brass claim Fisk finished
his career with the Sox because they gave him a cheesy job last
spring.) This will no doubt provoke new lobbying for the likes of
Foxx, Conigliaro, &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Teddy Ballgame is happy to have Fisk join the club.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're damn right,'' said the splendid one. ``We've got a
pretty good crew and now we've got Carlton Fisk, who's a hell of a
player.''
</P>
<P>
   It was fitting that Williams's No. 9 was one of the first to be
retired.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tremendous honor,'' said Williams. ``It's the nicest
honor I could get in my life because I love baseball so much and it
was my life and I was lucky to have the years of good playing that
I did. I met a lot of people and I'll always be remembered as a
baseball player.''
</P>
<P>
   It was also fitting that Williams and Cronin were honored
together. Cronin was player-manager of the Red Sox when Teddy
Ballgame burst on the scene in 1939. Cronin, who retired as a
player in 1945, was the Sox manager when Williams played in his
only World Series in 1946. Cronin later became general manager of
the Sox and was named president of the American League in 1959, one
year before Williams retired.
</P>
<P>
   Cronin was 77 and his health was failing when the Sox retired
his No. 4. He was unable to be on the field with Williams and he
died less than four months after the ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was Dad's last trip to Fenway Park,'' said Maureen Cronin,
his daughter. ``He had to stay upstairs because he was failing
badly. But he was very thrilled. He made a great effort to be there
because he loved Boston and he loved the fans of Boston. That day
was overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   ``The weather was misty and rainy, but it was wonderful because
all of our friends were there. We sat with Jean Yawkey and Bowie
Kuhn. It was nice to have the Williams and Cronin entourages all
there together. It was meaningful for all of us, the passing of an
era, really. We all felt it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still see the number when I'm there. I'm very proud of my
dad. He left me a wonderful legacy. Baseball meant so much to him
and he passed it on to all of his children.''
</P>
<P>
   Doerr, who came to the Sox two years ahead of Williams, played
10 seasons under Cronin and was inducted into the Hall of Fame in
1986. Two years later, the Red Sox put his No. 1 alongside the
numbers of Williams and Cronin. The ceremony was held in May 1988
and cantankerous Sox manager John McNamara was still wearing No. 1,
but Doerr said, ``He took his shirt off and gave it to me.''
(McNamara was fired two months later and no one has worn the number
since.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great thrill, a great honor,'' said Doerr. ``It just
seems like as time goes by, there's not many numbers being retired.
I have been back to Fenway maybe three or four times since they did
that. Sometimes when I'm watching a game on television they'll show
that. It's great to be sitting in Oregon, watching it on TV, and
see the number. It's really an honor, just like making the Hall of
Fame. It's pretty hard to have it done.''
</P>
<P>
   A year after Doerr's ceremony, Yastrzemski got his ticket to
Cooperstown, and the Sox _ as they are doing with Fisk _ retired
his number later the same summer. No. 8 went on the facade Aug. 6,
1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``After I got the call about the Hall of Fame, John Harrington
called me and said they wanted to retire my number,'' said Yaz. ``I
was ecstatic. I still remember that day and the tremendous
reception I got from the fans. At that moment, it filled me even
more than going into the Hall of Fame. And the thought kept running
through my mind that I made the right decision playing my entire
career in Boston. Because of the fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Yaz had links with the three prior inductees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe Cronin was still general manager when I signed with the
Red Sox,'' he said. ``I remember going there at Thanksgiving and
meeting with Joe and putting in a call to Mr. (Tom) Yawkey. I think
one thing that struck Joe about me was my size. I think he expected
somebody about 6-2, 200 pounds, and I was barely 6 feet and 165
pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby Doerr was an instructor when I was in the minors and he
was a class guy. I was very close with him and, of course, he was
one of our coaches in 1967. He's a great guy that never changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``And, of course, there was Ted. When I first came to spring
training (in 1960), it was his last year and they lockered me next
to him. He was always talking to me about hitting and he had all
these theories. All I knew was to look for the ball and hit it. The
first time I saw him in person, I can remember him taking batting
practice. He'd take a short, quick swing and he'd be talking to
himself, saying, `OK, Teddy Ballgame, let's pop a couple out.' The
guy was amazing. I looked at him and thought, `Holy mackerel.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox' retired numbers (red digits in white circles) were
originally hung in the order in which they were retired: 9 _ 4 _ 1
_ 8. (The blue No. 42 represents baseball's across-the-board
retirement of Jackie Robinson's number and has nothing to do with
Mo Vaughn's Red Sox career.) Applied as a date, 9/4/18 represents
the eve of the first game of the 1918 World Series, which was won
by the Red Sox over the Cubs. (The Series began early because of
World War I). In 1998, the Red Sox tired of this massive reminder
of futility staring down at them, so the numbers were taken down
and reattached in numerical order.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so disappointed when they did that,'' said Maureen
Cronin. ``It was kind of spooky the way it was.''
</P>
<P>
   Now they have 1 _ 4 _ 8 _ 9 _ 27. Let's see the numerologists
make something of that.
</P>
<P>
   Yastrzemski, Fisk's longtime teammate, will be one of the
presenters at Monday's event. Williams just turned 82 and rarely
travels, but the greatest Red Sox player of them all is ever
mindful of his place in right field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've looked at it,'' he said. ``I always thought I could hit a
ball up there from home plate, but I never did.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-00 0212EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000904.0053 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 02:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0320 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-TEN-COLLINSCOLUMN-BOS     09-04 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAFIN SURVIVES SLIPPERY FIVE-SETTER? 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ This diversion called the US Open is beginning to
seem like a Russian winter to the Moscow man-child, Marat Safin.
Endless. Slippery. Chilling. Wet. Confining.
</P>
<P>
   Time and again he has appeared to be buried in a drift _ his
mind away from the business at hand, the job of punching fuzzy
yellow balls even fuzzier than his thought processes. But he has
always shoveled himself out, Sunday arriving among the last 16 men
standing at Flushing Meadows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh my God, I have a lot of headache . . . what to do with the
ball?''
</P>
<P>
   This is the irrepressible Safin, not far removed from his
teenage years, a big but quick and coordinated guy who would look
just fine laboring as a tight end: 6 feet 5 inches, 200 pounds. He
is tight, all right, as he walks onto the asphalt stage for the
third act of a gloomy drama that has covered 6 1/2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am scared. Thinking too much. Got to concentrate.''
</P>
<P>
   Could he concentrate for 90 seconds? That's what it took for
Safin to finally conclude his third-round victory over the scrappy
little Frenchman Sebastien Grosjean, 6-4, 7-6 (7-3), 1-6, 3-6, 7-6
(7-5) _ a windup as close and excruciating as they can get in this
game.
</P>
<P>
   Ninety seconds, two points. That was the difference. Somebody
was going to blink, and it was Grosjean as they returned to Arthur
Ashe Stadium after the second cloudburst intermission. They had
spent as much time in the dressing room as on court, fretting and
``going crazy,'' says Marat, dangling, waiting out thunderstorms
that halted them twice.
</P>
<P>
   Abruptly this encounter of five sets, 3 hours 9 minutes, and 326
points had come down to best-of-three points, 10 whacks. It was
commotion interruptus as they resumed in the decisive tiebreaker,
Grosjean serving at 4-points-to-5.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's terrible to have to start again like that,'' says the
skittering Grosjean, dwarfed by Safin by 7 inches and 50 pounds.
``It's a matter of luck. Coming back from two sets down, I didn't
have quite as much juice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's gonna be more lucky?'' Safin wonders. ``It's a lottery.
I'm afraid. My eyes are bigger than my face. Now I can lose,'' says
the Russian, feeling morose as he glunks a forehand into the net:
5-5. Two points from delight or the dumpster.
</P>
<P>
   But Marat rips a forehand return of a second serve down the
line: 6-5. His lead, and his serve. Now Grosjean lashes a forehand
. . . same route . . . but . . . ``I think it's going wide,'' Safin
recounts, clasping his hands together. ``I'm praying, `Please,
please go out!' ''
</P>
<P>
   It does, and ``I can stop going crazy for a while. I'm still
here. I'm here to make history, to do something special. To win.''
No Russian has conquered the US Open. But Safin, dripping with
power (25 aces) and talent, and spinning in mood swings like a guy
in a revolving door, remains in the chase. An immense and immensely
likable guy, he goes nuts, smashes rackets _ 46 in 55 matches this
season _ yet is ever sporting and laughs at himself.
</P>
<P>
   Par for this course is nine sets for three rounds. He's been
bogeying: 14 sets _ four against Thierry Guardiola, five against
Gianluca Pozzi and Grosjean, totaling more than 9 hours. Pete
Sampras has shot par, nine sets in less than six hours.
</P>
<P>
   Safin should have dusted Grosjean in under two hours. It was
good old summertime while he knocked off the first two sets. Then
Russian winter descended as his concentration fled like robins
headed south, and Safin lumbered about as though on snowshoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``One more set to win.'' He ``didn't expect (the temperature
change) so quickly. How's possible happen to me these things? I
gave Grosjean back his confidence. It's 6-1, 6-3, for him so fast.
I lose my serve to start the fifth . . . I'm crazy. But I promised
myself not to break a racket . . . they're new, just strung. But it
might have felt good.''
</P>
<P>
   He has plunged to countryman Gorky's Lower Depths. This drama is
evoking the Gershwin tune, ``But Not For Me'' _ specifically ``. .
. I've found more clouds of gray than any Russian play can
guarantee . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Thunder rumbling behind those glowering clouds like the cannons
in Tchaikovsky's ``1812 Overture,'' seems to awaken Safin, who
shoots ahead, 30-15, at 4-4 in the fifth set where raindrops halt
them for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Into the locker room for 85 minutes. Safin issues a socks
appeal. ``I didn't bring enough clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   Back again, Safin holds serve to 5-4, and they proceed into the
tense tiebreaker. More rain after nine points, during which Safin
grabbed two mini-breaks only to be caught.
</P>
<P>
   ``Again I have to shower, change. Jeff Tarango gave me clean
socks the first break. Now Nicholas Kiefer gives me socks and a
shirt the second time. I don't want to smell bad when I go back on
court.''
</P>
<P>
   Marat wants to look spiffy for his 90-second curtain call, and
ends up smelling like a winner. Russian winter thaws. Momentarily.
But look for Safin, next matched with another 20-year-old whiz,
Spaniard Juan Carlos Ferrero, to stumble through more drifts,
develop periodic frostbite of the brain, and crumple a few more
weapons as he tries to emulate the 13th century Russian warrior
Alexander Nevsky, a champion of famous icy battles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
