<HEADLINE>
NORMAN NEEDS MARATHON TO ESCAPE 
</HEADLINE>
 OPEN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Strike one. Strike two. Strike . . . hold on just a
minute.
</P>
<P>
   Just when it looked like the last of top three men's seeds at
the US Open was about to be run out of town, Magnus Norman came
alive Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Norman scratched his way out of a huge hole to hold off Max
Mirnyi, 3-6, 4-6, 7-6 (7-5), 6-4, 7-6 (11-9), in a 4-hour-6-minute
marathon that highlighted a wet and wild day at the Open.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the rain won out. At 11 p.m., tournament officials
announced that several matches had been postponed until Monday. One
was Todd Martin's clash with No. 10 seed Cedric Pioline. Martin
led, 7-6 (7-5), 6-3, 2-0, when the rains disrupted play again. No.
1 women's seed Martina Hingis was in control of her match with
Sandrine Testud, 6-2, 1-0.
</P>
<P>
   Norman took a while to get a grip on his match. He was up, 5-2,
in the third set, but squandered that lead before winning the set
in a tiebreaker. Norman got the only service break he needed in the
first game of the fourth set and it was on to the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Norman broke first in the final set. Mirnyi, chipping and
charging, got that break back.
</P>
<P>
   Norman was up, 5-2, in the tiebreaker but before it ended, each
player had match points. Mirnyi was up, 9-8, and serving when
Norman ran off the last three points.
</P>
<P>
   And then apologized to Mirnyi.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the feeling when you lose a match like that,'' Norman
said. ``But he's still young. He's going to get a lot more
opportunities. I really want to cheer him on, like say, `Come on,
great game.' It's not really the time to do it when you shake hands
at the end of the game, because maybe he's going to punch you in
the face or something. He's a great guy.''
</P>
<P>
   While Norman's escape act kept some sense of stability on the
men's side with No. 1 Andre Agassi and No. 2 Gustavo Kuerten long
gone, Venus Williams, the No. 3 seed, did her share to keep the
women's draw in line.
</P>
<P>
   Williams was not thrilled that because of the rain she had to
hang around the National Tennis Center all day. When she did get on
the court several hours after she planned, it was in Louis
Armstrong Stadium, not in the featured Arthur Ashe Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The changeup didn't throw her off much. Williams led the way
into the US Open quarterfinals with a 6-2, 6-2 win over Magui
Serna.
</P>
<P>
   Later, No. 6 seed Monica Seles joined her there with a 6-3, 6-4
win over No. 15 seed Jennifer Capriati in a rematch of a 1991
showcase semifinal here. ``She (Seles) came out real strong from
the first ball,'' Capriati said. ``She served very well and it was
tough for me to break and of course that put more pressure on my
serve.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, Seles won the battle of teenagers _ she was 17 and
Capriati 15 _ on her way to a fourth major championship title.
Capriati hasn't made it as far as the semifinal of a major since.
</P>
<P>
   Both young women missed a couple of years in the mid-1990s:
Seles after being stabbed at a tournament and Capriati with
personal problems. Seles has won two US Opens and nine majors in
her career. She last won here in 1992 and won her last major in
Australia in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Seles beat Capriati in the fourth round here last year and now
holds a 7-3 record over her. Seles will play the winner of the
Hingis-Testud match in the quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
   If it's Hingis, she knows she will be in for a test.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely have to cut down on my errors because Martina is
not going to give any free points like the other players do,''
Seles said. ``Up to this point she has been playing really well.
She hasn't really been tested. Obviously, I'm going to have to be
very aggressive out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman next gets No. 14 seed Nicolas Kiefer of Germany, a 7-5,
6-3, 6-4 winner over Sjeng Schalken. Norman isn't too worried about
coming back Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good anyway, even if it's a long match,'' he said. ``I
think I'm pretty fit. I think I can handle it.''
</P>
<P>
   He'll be looking to get off to a better start against Kiefer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was playing really, really well,'' Norman said. ``He was
playing unbelievably good in the first two sets. There was nothing
much I could do.''
</P>
<P>
   Then came the finish and the final tiebreaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had match point, I had match point,'' Norman said. ``It's
tough to have a strategy. Just try to get the ball over the net,
you know?''
</P>
</TEXT>
