<SLUG> BC-FBN-MCDONOUGH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUCS' VICTORY WELL-PLANNED 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ They knocked him down. They ran over him.
But the Buccaneers couldn't make Drew Bledsoe cower the way they
thought they would under their relentless pass rush.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the game, we looked at (Bledsoe) as a guy with happy
feet,'' said Warren Sapp, Tampa Bay's brilliant defensive tackle
who lived up to his reputation as the best lineman in the league.
``When we played him before (in 1997), when we got pressure on him,
he ducked, or he got nervous, and wanted to get rid of the ball. We
talked about this before the game. This was our goal, to get
pressure on Bledsoe.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I give him credit. We hit him, and we hit him hard. He
hung in there. Today, he was a warrior.''
</P>
<P>
   The most amazing thing about Tampa Bay's 21-16 victory over the
Patriots Sunday was the way it happened.
</P>
<P>
   On paper, Tampa's biggest edge was its defensive line _ the best
and fastest in the NFL _ against New England's suspect offensive
line.
</P>
<P>
   The Buccaneers coaching staff felt the No. 1 priority of the
Patriots coaching staff would be to figure out a way to keep
Tampa's front four off Bledsoe, to give him a chance to make some
big plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought they might try to spread their offense, and that
they might go to a no-huddle,'' said Monte Kiffin, the Buccaneers'
defensive coordinator. ``We practiced for all of that stuff. They
didn't do anything to surprise us. I'm just disappointed we didn't
get to Bledsoe more. We must have knocked him down 20 times. There
were five or six other times we should have sacked him and let him
get away.
</P>
<P>
   ``On his touchdown pass (with 3:01 left in the game), we had a
man about a foot away from him when he let the ball go. That was a
bad play for us. Our defense played well the whole game, but we
usually don't give up a big play like that near the end of the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When we saw them spread out on offense at the beginning,''
said Buccaneers head coach Tony Dungy, ``we thought they were doing
this to spread us out on defense and try to run the ball more. When
we saw they weren't going to run, we just got after Bledsoe. We
kept the pressure on him.''
</P>
<P>
   Offensively, the critical factor for Tampa Bay was its ability
to score touchdowns on all three tries inside the Patriots' 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, we were 31st and last in the league converting
inside the 20,'' said general manager Rich McKay. ``This is why we
made some moves over the winter to correct that situation. If this
was a year ago, we might have come away with three field goals
instead of three touchdowns.''
</P>
<P>
   Dungy brought in a new offensive coordinator, Les Steckel, and
McKay acquired a superstar wide receiver, Keyshawn Johnson, and two
outstanding offensive linemen, Randall McDaniel and Jeff Christy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keyshawn did what we want him to do for us; he made several
big third-down plays,'' said McKay. ``And when he isn't making
plays, they still have to respect him on defense. That opens up the
field for some of our other guys.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We opened up the offense in the second period,'' said Steckel,
talking about the quarter in which the Buccaneers scored two
touchdowns. ``This is not an easy defense to play against. (The
Patriots) did some good things on defense that made it tough for
us. But once we got the third touchdown (to lead, 21-10, in the
third) we shut their offense down. I just wanted to burn the clock.
With our defense, I didn't want our offense to make any mistakes
and help the Patriots.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' defensive front and safety Lawyer Milloy played
well. They put good pressure on Shaun King and tackled well. They
really gave up just two touchdowns, with the third Tampa score
being set up by a Kevin Faulk fumble.
</P>
<P>
   Faulk had a tough day. On several Tampa blitzes, the Patriots'
running back didn't know who to block and Bledsoe paid the price.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their offensive line has to be beat up,'' said a gracious
Sapp, when asked to assess the New England line. ``They couldn't
stop us today. We got after (Bledsoe) in a hurry. I should have had
him myself three or four more times. I came from the backside and I
didn't think he saw me coming and he just turned his shoulder. Next
time, I'm going to punch him in the back,'' said Sapp, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots won't be playing any defenses as good as Tampa
Bay's the rest of the year. But unless they figure out a way to
give Bledsoe more time to throw, he won't be around to finish the
season.
</P>
<P>
   During the game, a visiting scout was asked if he was timing how
fast Tampa got to Bledsoe: ``I don't have a stopwatch that works
that fast,'' he responded with a laugh. He wasn't far from being
right.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
