<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 02:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0324 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-BUCCANEERS-JOHNSO     09-04 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BUCCANEERS-JOHNSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEYSHAWN STILL PLAYS PATRIOT KILLER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The elegantly understated suit looked like a
giant chocolate Necco wafer. The performance and the post-mortems
were just as subdued.
</P>
<P>
   Keyshawn Johnson, maestro of the outrageous while in the media
maelstrom surrounding the New York Jets, was content to be a
peripheral figure Sunday in and after his Tampa Bay Buccaneers'
debut.
</P>
<P>
   Peripheral figure? Make that a peripheral force. While the
methodology was different, it was no less lethal to the Patriots.
Johnson killed them softly in a 21-16 victory at Foxboro Stadium,
where he had become a billboard-sized villain while wearing green
and white for the first four years of his career.
</P>
<P>
   There were no touchdowns, no histrionics, no grandiloquent
outbursts upon his return to the scene of his most cherished
infamy. But none was necessary. Johnson knows that regardless of
his role, he is genuinely appreciated up here.
</P>
<P>
   ``They hate me,'' he said with an impish smile.
</P>
<P>
   But he understands that venom is as ephemeral as a Patriots
offensive drive, that only the color of his uniform _ now pewter
and scarlet _ puts him on New England's Most Wanted list rather
than its most coveted list.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'd love to have me here,'' he said with a satisfied smile.
</P>
<P>
   Even those pronouncements were delivered without the usual
Johnson bravado. Perhaps it had been excluded from his renegotiated
contract when the Buccaneers gave him an eight-year, $56 million
deal after spending two first-round draft choices to acquire him
from the Jets, who were eager to let him go in hopes of
forestalling a tabloid-sized negotiating impasse down the road.
</P>
<P>
   Not at all. Johnson says that while his change of address
represents a case of ``two different cities, two different teams,
two different organizations, totally different people,'' he isn't
in exile off Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still gracing magazine covers,'' he said. ``I'm still on
TV, still doing all kinds of interviews.''
</P>
<P>
   And still doing whatever job is placed on his agenda, no matter
how menial. No GQ wardrobe can camouflage the blue collar Johnson
wears to work and always has.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the same offense here as in New York and college (at
Southern Cal),'' he said. ``I'm totally comfortable in this
offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, his statistical contributions were not headliners _ 4
receptions for 64 yards, 1 reverse for 3 yards. But the numbers do
not reveal that every one of his catches produced a first down,
that two of them _ a 27-yarder to the New England 25 in the second
quarter, a 6-yarder to the Patriots 3 in the third _ set up Tampa
touchdowns, that the consistent double-team attention he drew
opened up other avenues for quarterback Shaun King, and that his
relentless blocking was a vital piston in the running machine,
capped by his clear-out of Patriots cornerback Ty Law that set up
Mike Alstott's 3-yard sweep for the winning TD. This was the latest
example of his full effect: What Johnson threatens against a
defense is as vital as what he does to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of those guys who dictates things'' opponents can do,
according to coach Tony Dungy. To new offensive coordinator Les
Steckel, whose idea of offensive daring is a quick kick, even if
Johnson isn't directly involved in the play, his mere presence
``makes a lot of things happen.''
</P>
<P>
   All in a day's work, Johnson believes. ``I'd say I had a good
game,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And, as Patriots patrons must grudgingly concede, another
successful one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
