<DOCNO> NYT20000904.0058 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 02:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0325 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BROWN-BO     09-04 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BROWN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROWN BRIGHTENS GRAY DAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Troy Brown is a smart football player.
</P>
<P>
   He's smart enough to know not to do what New England running
back Kevin Faulk did with 33 seconds left in the game _ take a pass
in the right flat from quarterback Drew Bledsoe and then casually
run out of bounds for a 2-yard gain, a yard short of a first down
at the Tampa Bay 26.
</P>
<P>
   That left the Patriots with a fourth down and no timeouts left,
and as wide receiver Terry Glenn later put it, ``We only had three
downs there and we had to burn time off the clock.'' The Patriots
did get the first down, but were left with only 14 seconds after
Bledsoe spiked the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Brown was smart enough to know much earlier in the game
that the Patriots had squandered opportunities created by the
special teams, that a team with a shambles of an offensive line
must take advantage of every chance to score.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some great opportunities a couple of times in the first
half,'' said Brown, ``and we didn't take adantage of them. I'm
disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   The opportunities were created when Larry Whigham forced a
fumble on the opening kickoff and New England recovered on the
Bucs' 28, then when Brown returned a punt 39 yards after Tampa
Bay's first possession. The Patriots could get only 3 points from
those chances.
</P>
<P>
   So Brown was glum and a man of few words after the game, even
though he returned a punt 66 yards for a TD in the second quarter.
It was the Patriots' first punt return for a touchdown since Dave
Meggett ran back a 60-yarder against the New York Giants Dec. 21,
1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The Bucs) did what they wanted to do,'' said Brown of New
England's feeble offensive efforts. ``They contained us and they
brought four guys up front and . . . boom! And that's what they
did. We couldn't get them out of there.''
</P>
<P>
   On a day when the New England offensive line played worse than
advertised, the Patriots' attack could do little of anything. But
Brown went out of his way to say the offense's problems were not
limited to the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a combination of everything,'' said the Patriots
receiver. ``They played their style of play and we didn't get
physical enough with them. We didn't get open enough, we didn't
block well enough, we didn't throw well enough, and we didn't run
well enough.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Brown was as shocked as many fans that the Patriots
still had a chance to win the game in the final seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't play well at all,'' said Brown. ``Considering how we
played, it was amazing we still had a chance to win it coming down
the stretch. We just didn't get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   But Brown did. Brown displayed why he is one of the most
valuable members of this offense, a fact well known in New England,
but little known in the rest of the football world. On the four
punts he ran back, Brown totaled 118 yards, including that 66-yard
return.
</P>
<P>
   He caught seven passes for 70 yards and gained 33 yards on two
running plays, both reverses. But none of those numbers meant
anything to Brown on a day his team lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just disappointed we didn't win the game,'' said Brown.
``I don't care how we win the game, I just want to win it. That's
the most important thing. We didn't do good enough to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown's return was set up by exceptional blocking. Ty Law made a
crisp block and so did Tony George, but the block of blocks was
made by New England's Harold Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw had his back to the punt as he ran downfield, turning back
upfield just as Brown was about to catch the ball. And once Shaw
turned to see what he was facing, he acted decisively, laying low
not one, but two Buccaneers with the same block. With Shaw's block
opening up the middle, Brown was quickly able to shift into fifth
gear.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job is to block the fullback and the other guy was right
behind him,'' said Shaw. ``When I blocked him, he fell backwards
into the other guy. He sort of bumped into him.''
</P>
<P>
   The special teams had not played exceptionally well in the
exhibition season, Shaw conceded, ``and we had to go out there on
the special teams and try to do something. That's a start.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, as usual, deflected all attention away from his heroics,
saying that any running lanes he found on his two long punt returns
were opened ``by the blockers in front of me. They did a great
job.''
</P>
<P>
   So did Brown. Alas for New England, he can't touch the ball on
every play, especially on every crucial one, such as catching a
2-yard pass when 3 yards are needed. Troy Brown would know enough
not to be casual.
</P>
