<HEADLINE>
BC'S OPENING LOSS WAS QUITE A TRIP 
</HEADLINE>
 COLLEGE-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ They say West Virginia is almost heaven, but Boston
College's season-opening trip to Morgantown, W.Va., certainly
proved to be anything but for the Eagles after a sobering 34-14
loss Saturday at steamy Mountaineer Field.
</P>
<P>
   BC's hopes seemed doomed from the start when the team endured a
three-hour delay in its Friday departure, an emergency landing of
its Spirit Air charter in Pittsburgh, and a late 10:45 p.m.
check-in at the team's hotel in Washington, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   Things did not improve Saturday when, after absorbing a tough
Big East loss, the Eagles were forced to alter their plans to
depart from Clarksburg, W.Va., some 30 minutes away from
Morgantown. Because a flight crew was unable to meet BC's travel
party in Clarksburg, the team was forced to bus back to Pittsburgh,
where a crew and another weather delay greeted them. The Eagles
finally landed in Boston around 10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Almost heaven? It was more hellish, as it turned out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, God Almighty,'' BC coach Tom O'Brien sighed, when asked
what time the team finally arrived home. ``I got back to my home
around 10:30.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was happy to see Morgantown disappear from sight,
O'Brien muttered: ``Yeah, I guess so. It's been a long weekend,
that's all I can say.''
</P>
<P>
   With a veteran offense that was expected to carry a young and
inexperienced defense, O'Brien was disappointed when the offense
went AWOL Saturday. BC managed a meager 206 yards total offense (79
rushing) after committing five turnovers (three interceptions) and
nine penalties for 43 yards, prompting O'Brien to call the
performance ``probably the worst I've seen in my career.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-four hours later, O'Brien did not back off his harsh
criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't changed my mind a bit,'' he said. ``We just weren't
physical. We were too soft. We were running the ball soft, we were
tackling soft, and we were blocking soft and almost got our
quarterback killed a couple of times.''
</P>
<P>
   To make matters worse, BC's defense, which hung tough for much
of the afternoon before withering in a fourth-quarter West Virginia
frenzy, lost two starters. Junior tackle Antonio Garay and senior
cornerback D.J. Sutton suffered knee injuries and underwent MRIs
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien said the tests had not yet been evaluated, but indicated
both players were eligible to be redshirted if the injuries were
season-ending.
</P>
<P>
   While O'Brien lauded his young defense, which had at least 11
different players make their collegiate debuts, he indicated that
none of his offensive players received a passing grade following
his film evaluation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody _ nobody _ played well on offense,'' O'Brien said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to evaluate the performance of fifth-year quarterback Tim
Hasselbeck (14 of 29 for 119 yards, 1 touchdown, 3 interceptions),
O'Brien said: ``He was no worse than anyone else. I can't single
anyone out. They all played poorly.''
</P>
<P>
   So, suffice it to say, O'Brien will spend his Labor Day holiday
working to get his team battle-hardened for Saturday's game at
Army. The Eagles, though, will have one advantage: Army will open
its season Monday hosting Cincinnati, leaving the Cadets four days
to prepare.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just going to get back to work this week and get back to
being a physical football team,'' O'Brien said. ``Now if we lose
some guys along the way, we'll lose some guys, but we're not going
to lose any more games because we were not physical. We might get
beat, but we're not going to get outhit like we were Saturday.''
</P>
</TEXT>
