<SLUG> BC-FBC-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENN STATE STUMBLES OUT OF GATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Things are not so happy in Happy Valley these days.
Mighty Penn State is 0-2 on the heels of a stunning 24-6 loss to
Toledo Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Dealing with the controversy involving the legal problems of
quarterback Rashard Casey is one thing for coach Joe Paterno. He
can make decisions about right and wrong and people can agree or
disagree.
</P>
<P>
   But what is tougher to take for the Penn State faithful is the
losing, especially to Toledo, which became the first Mid-American
Conference team to beat Penn State.
</P>
<P>
   Now things are turning ugly.
</P>
<P>
   Take sophomore running back Larry Johnson's comments after the
game. ``Our coaches have been here for 20 or 30 years and it seems
like things never change,'' said Johnson. ``We run the same
offense. The teams that play us know what we're going to run. They
can pull out the tapes from 1992 or '93 and we run the same
offense. Same plays, same offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knows what we're doing. Sometimes, I don't even know
the play and I can guess what's coming. The system is too
predictable. It's been around too long.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Johnson is also the son of Paterno's defensive line coach,
Larry Sr., Sunday's staff meeting should have been a lively one.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson also took one final shot at his own teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the best backfield in the nation and we don't have an
offensive line to go with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hmmm. Now if you heard the griping at some schools, where
mouthing off is part of the game plan, you might pass it off as
normal chatter after a tough loss.
</P>
<P>
   But Penn State remains Paterno's fiefdom. Very little is said or
done without Joe Pa's consent. Johnson's remarks will no doubt lead
to a clamping down of public utterances by the Lions, who must now
face Louisiana Tech Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   And Tech, like Toledo, is another ``watch out'' game. Coached by
Jack Bicknell 3d, Tech does not back off from anyone. It beat
Alabama in Tuscaloosa a year ago and is not afraid to play with the
big boys, Kansas State's 54-10 romp Saturday not withstanding.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As it did a year ago, the Pac-10 is making an early-season
statement. Unlike a year ago, when the conference was embarrassed
by high-profile nonconference losses, there are plenty of West
Coast smiles today.
</P>
<P>
   Southern Cal's thrashing of Penn State was a harbinger a week
ago in the Kickoff Classic (though the Nittany Lions' second loss
diminishes that accomplishment somewhat).
</P>
<P>
   But there was nothing fluky about UCLA's 35-24 win over Alabama
Saturday. The Bruins were better, quicker, hungrier, and tougher
than the third-ranked Tide.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the presence of more than 20,000 Tide fans in Pasadena,
UCLA took care of business when it had to _ down the stretch. It
was Alabama's first season-opening loss since Southern Miss
prevailed, 27-24, in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   The Pac-10 can make more noise this week. Washington hosts
Miami, Colorado visits Southern Cal, and Oregon travels to
Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Only a few days ago, the gloom doomers were predicting dire
things for the Golden Domers. But Notre Dame's 24-10 win over Texas
A&AMP;M has sparked an air of optimism.
</P>
<P>
   For the time being, the death watch on Bob Davie's tenure in
South Bend is on hold.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this will all change if No. 1 Nebraska comes to town
this week and manhandles the Irish as many expect.
</P>
<P>
   Don't count on that happening. First, the Irish came out of the
opener with no major injuries, always a plus when you play a
physical team such as A&AMP;M.
</P>
<P>
   Secondly, the game is in South Bend and no one is more dangerous
than an Irish team as a home underdog in a game few people feel
they can win.
</P>
<P>
   You can almost hear Davie giving his best Knute Rockne ``us
against the world'' speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a long way to go in a short period of time,'' said
Davie, ``because the football team that is coming in next week is
probably as good a team as I've seen in a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   He's right, but count on Davie milking the underdog role the way
his predecessor, Lou Holtz, did against every team from Nebraska to
Navy.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Holtz. There were finally smiles in the Holtz family
when football was discussed Saturday night. After a winless debut
season a year ago at South Carolina, Holtz's Gamecocks won their
opener against New Mexico State, 31-0, snapping the longest losing
streak in Division 1A at 21 games.
</P>
<P>
   The event was so monumental that the fans stormed the field and
tore down the goal posts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're becoming a team,'' said Holtz. ``It's coming and coming
but not there yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Say this about Carolina fans. They are loyal to the core. They
had not won a game since 1998, but more than 80,000 fans were on
hand Saturday night at Williams-Brice Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut made a valiant effort in its 1A debut Saturday night
against Eastern Michigan. Coach Randy Edsall's Huskies overcame a
24-13 deficit going into the fourth quarter to take a 25-24 lead,
only to see Eastern come back and pull out a 32-25 victory . . .
The weather has played a factor in the first weeks of the season.
Lightning storms forced the cancellation of the Black Coaches
Association game between Virginia Tech and Georgia Tech, while
lightning storms caused a delay in Saturday's Pittsburgh-Kent game
and suspension of the Louisville-Kentucky game with 8:11 remaining
in the third quarter and Kentucky leading, 19-14. After a 74-minute
delay, Louisville came back and won a 40-34 thriller in overtime .
. . Heat, especially in the Midwest, was also a factor. Shows you
what can happen when you begin your season before Labor Day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
