<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION FAIL TO CLINCH PLAYOFF BERTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Revolution's playoff-clinching celebration was
postponed Sunday. They could have clinched a berth with two games
remaining, but a 2-0 loss to D.C. United forced them into a
position in which they likely will have to defeat either Kansas
City Wednesday or the MetroStars Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Both of those games are at Foxboro Stadium, and the combination
of its narrow dimensions, plus the return of key players, should
boost the Revolution's chances.
</P>
<P>
   Against D.C. United, the Revolution chased the game. Most of
their weaknesses were exposed by a young team which displayed
balance and composure. Second-half substitute Pete Marino converted
twice as a rainstorm moved in, knocking goalkeeper Juergen Sommer
out of the game with a possible broken right ring finger on the
second goal, coming in the 61st minute. Jeff Causey replaced Sommer
and likely will be in goal for the final two games.
</P>
<P>
   The absence of national team players Wolde Harris (Jamaica) and
William Sunsing (Costa Rica), as well as Rusty Pierce (suspended),
altered the dynamic which had launched a three-game Revolution
winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   D.C. United was even more debilitated by player absences, yet
adjusted with ease _ partially because of the lack of urgency
caused by having been eliminated from playoff contention. And the
addition of US national team members Jeff Agoos, Carlos Llamosa,
and Richie Williams gave United a balance it had lacked in a 1-0
loss to the Revolution Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could have put ourselves in a good position but we didn't
do it,'' Revolution coach Fernando Clavijo said. ``There is
absolutely nothing we can do about it now except to look ahead to
the next game. It's disappointing to lose but our fate is still in
our hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game was maybe too quick for us. We were slipping and not
concentrating, reacting to the ball two steps behind instead of
being there. The rain hurt because we don't have the fastest
players, and they were quicker to the ball than we were.''
</P>
<P>
   Eric Wynalda made his first Revolution start, and had a goal
disallowed on a close offsides call in the 18th minute. Wynalda and
Jose Luis Morales combined well in the opening minutes but were
increasingly ineffective as the match progressed, partly because of
unfamiliarity, and partly because of a lack of midfield play.
</P>
<P>
   D.C. calmly began building up its offense midway through the
first half. And the Revolution struggled to dismantle the United
attacks. Antonio Otero hit the post from close range with Sommer
out of the net in the 32d minute. Marino grazed the bar with a
sharply angled cross in the 48th minute.
</P>
<P>
   Marino's first goal resulted from an unforced error by Adam
Eyre, who took down A.J. Wood from behind in an attempt to recover.
Agoos curled a free kick to an unmarked Marino, who headed into the
side of the net in the 55th minute.
</P>
<P>
   Revolution resistance crumbled after that. Sommer stuffed a
Bobby Convey breakaway and Wood shot wide in the 59th minute. Wood
ran free on the right and sent a low cross for Marino to convert
two minutes later.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Revolution had almost no sustained or productive
possession. They had half-chances out of chaotic situations, the
best when John Harkes lifted a shot over onrushing goalkeeper Mark
Simpson that was cleared off the line by Agoos in the 73d minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our plan was to go in with experienced players and hold the
ball,'' said Ted Chronopoulos, who played defense in a 3-5-2
alignment. ``They are the younger team, and we wanted to make them
run around. We can play more defensively on the road, but we were
lacksadaisical about it. The attitude we are playing with is not
right.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a big field, and they knew how to use it. Maybe we
took them lightly. But we are not in the playoffs, yet. We can't
count on other teams to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sommer left the locker room with a splint on his right hand and
was to have X-rays Sunday &UR;  &LR; night. ``It could be dislocated but the
way it feels and judging by the swelling I think something is
broken,'' Sommer said . . . Causey, playing for the first time
since a 4-1 loss at Columbus July 12, made a spectacular kick save
on Convey in the 67th minute . . . Wynalda said he tired after 55
minutes in his first full game with the Revolution. ``He played
well enough for 60 minutes,'' Clavijo said. Wynalda scored the
first goal for the US in a 2-0 win over Guatemala in a qualifier at
RFK Stadium Nov. 3, 1996, but has not played for the national team
since the US Cup in February . . . Sunsing did not play in Costa
Rica's 3-0 victory over Barbados in San Jose, Costa Rica . . .
Harris was with Jamaica, which met St. Vincent &AMP; the Grenadines in
Kingston Sunday &UR;  &LR; night.
</P>
</TEXT>
