<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-US-GUATEMALA-BOS </SLUG>
  
 McBRIDE'S GOAL SHORT-CIRCUITS GUATEMALA  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The US slogged a step closer to the Japan/Korea
2002 World Cup finals, and Cobi Jones revived his status on the
national team in a 1-0 victory over Guatemala Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The victory moved the US within 3 points of advancing to the
final round of regional qualifying, with games remaining against
Costa Rica Oct. 11 in Columbus, Ohio, and Nov. 15 in Barbados.
</P>
<P>
   But this was an extremely difficult result to obtain, especially
considering that the US had the home-field advantage and the
well-orchestrated support of a crowd of 51,996 at RFK Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The US had to recover from a 65th-minute ejection of Eddie
Lewis, who was sent off by Mexican referee Ulises Rangel after
elbowing Fabricio Benitez. But though that play might have changed
the dynamic in the Chapines' favor, the US instead continued to set
the pace. Brian McBride converted Jones's cross from the right side
on a counterattack at the far post, just past goalkeeper Edgar
Estrada, in the 72d minute.
</P>
<P>
   Jones began the day confronting a turning point in his career.
His campaign to extract a multi-million dollar contract from the
notoriously cost-conscious MLS was losing ground quickly. His
status as a national team fixture seemed fragile. But that changed
quickly in the second half as he took advantage of space on the
right wing and made the pass that decided the game. With Lewis and
Earnie Stewart suspended, Jones is certain to make his 134th
international appearance when the US meets Costa Rica.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Bruce Arena also made the right moves. Most of Arena's
substitutions in the opening qualifiers at Guatemala and Costa Rica
failed to contribute. But in this match, the changes paid off,
despite the sending-off of Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   John O'Brien more than compensated for the injured Chris Armas
(ankle), and appears to be a solid contributor for the future.
O'Brien, who turned 23 last week, is the US team's youngest player.
But O'Brien has secured a position with Ajax Amsterdam, the first
American player to start for Holland's most famous club, and he
will be with the US Olympic team in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien added composure and creativity to the midfield, and
seemed even more comfortable than the team's leader, Claudio Reyna,
who departed with a bruised knee after a 78th-minute clash with
Evaraldo Valencia.
</P>
<P>
   The US attack, though, once again displayed its limitations.
Guatemala retreated into defense, both out of good sense and
necessity. The Chapines were missing their top two strikers _
Carlos Ruiz (suspended) and Juan Carlos Plata, who was injured in
the first half. The US found it difficult to break through,
partially because it seemed unsure whether to power through with
crosses to McBride or to allow Reyna to finesse his way.
</P>
<P>
   The match became a war of attrition in the 85-degree heat, and
the US paced itself well enough to remain composed at the end _
unlike when it squandered the lead in a 1-1 tie in Mazatenango,
Guatemala, in July.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The US extended its unbeaten streak to 15 games in World Cup
home qualifiers . . . Jones has played in 14 successive games, the
longest streak on the team.
</P>
</TEXT>
