<SLUG> BC-FBN-BUCCANEERS-SAPP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEAST DAY FOR HUNGRY SAPP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Warren Sapp weighs 303 pounds. His appetite
is precious to him. Interfere with Warren's meals at your own
peril.
</P>
<P>
   So when he awakened in his Dedham hotel room Sunday morning and
immediately suffered a case of tabloid-induced indigestion, the
Patriots _ particularly Drew Bledsoe _ were doomed. They were
innocent, but somebody had to pay after Sapp rolled out of bed,
read the pregame matchups, and tried to absorb this nauseating
tidbit:
</P>
<P>
   ``Some guy up here said they handled me pretty well in the
preseason'' when the Tampa Bay Buccaneers faced the Patriots in an
exhibition game two weeks ago. ``I was so sick to my stomach, I
couldn't eat. I was pissed. I've never been disrespected like that
in my whole career. I was already fired up this morning at 9. I
couldn't wait to get here.''
</P>
<P>
   To devour Bledsoe, the sacrificial lamb, the Patriots claim is
an offense.
</P>
<P>
   Sapp showed why he was the NFL Defensive Player of the Year last
season by spearheading a voracious Tampa rush that sacked Bledsoe
six times for 26 yards, applied a life-threatening total of ``15,
16 pressures _ no doubt about it'' in the defensive tackle's
estimation, and generally turned the quarterback into mincemeat.
</P>
<P>
   Sapp spent most of the Bucs' 21-16 victory down Bledsoe's
throat, smothering him for 1 1/2 sacks to share team honors with
left end Marcus Jones. How's that for handling?
</P>
<P>
   ``We had time,'' said Sapp. ``We didn't panic. We just did what
we were supposed to do. Our heart and soul is our defense. We knew
we have the depth at the defensive line. Our blitz just kept
coming. It was just a whole team unit. We get paid to rush the
quarterback and take real pride in it.''
</P>
<P>
   And Bledsoe got an endless beating for it, though he never once
insulted Sapp. His tormentor realized that. It was nothing
personal. In fact, he paid belated respect to Bledsoe after the
Bucs defense almost paid their last respects to him.
</P>
<P>
   This Bledsoe, Sapp discovered, was a far cry from the one who
submitted meekly during a 27-7 Tampa home romp three years ago the
last time the teams met in the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has the heart of a warrior, no doubt about that,'' said
Sapp. ``We've changed our whole perception of him. We thought he
was a happy-feet quarterback that would go down if we got around
him. But he stood in there and took the hits, got right back up and
kept moving his ball club.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a wonder Bledsoe was able to move his body parts, but
darn if he didn't throw a scare into Tampa _ one that traveled 39
yards into the end zone to Terry Glenn in the fourth quarter and
put the squeeze on the visitors by closing the gap to 5 points.
</P>
<P>
   Not to worry. The Bucs were not taken aback in the slightest by
this incursion. It seems their defense is always susceptible to a
hiccup, as if it were part of their game plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always say that there's one bad play that's going to
come,'' said Sapp. ``We just don't know when it's going to come.
One bad play is guaranteed to happen. It always does.''
</P>
<P>
   But this one wasn't critical. The Patriots' last chance died on
the Tampa 22 when Bledsoe threw the ball out of bounds. He was
under savage pressure and Sapp was right there just to make sure.
He wasn't about to let anything spoil his dinner.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
