<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    ANNE STEPHENSON'S `NEW &AMP; NOTABLE' BOOK REVIES(a) 
 &HT;    (Duplication warning: MOVING IN ``E'' and ``L'' categories) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By ANNE STEPHENSON(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 Special forThe Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are Anne Stephenson's capsule reviews of new books:
</P>
<P>
   ``THE FRAILTY MYTH''
</P>
<P>
   By Colette Dowling
</P>
<P>
   (Random House, $24.95)
</P>
<P>
   After we tell you about this book, we're going out and throw
some fastballs, just to prove that we can. Dowling (''The
Cinderella Complex'') tells us that second-grade boys throw 72
percent faster than second-grade girls when they use their dominant
arms, but with their non-dominant arms there is no difference in
throwing speeds. In other words, ``throwing like a girl'' means
throwing like a kid who hasn't had much practice, and ``running
like a girl'' and ``hitting like a girl'' belong on the same list.
Historically, girls have been discouraged from developing their
natural athleticism, and Dowling says it has sabotaged them in many
other facets of their everyday lives. She discusses the ``strength
gap'' that has closed consistently since 1972's Title IX ruling on
equal funding for girls sports and implies that soon the gap might
be gone for good. Maybe that's too much to expect, but it's hard to
argue with her indignation or with her pleasure in the fact that at
62 she has outlived the ``frailty myth'' herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``HATS IN THE RING''
</P>
<P>
   By Evan Cornog and Richard Whelan
</P>
<P>
   (Random House, $39.95)
</P>
<P>
   That's Jackie Kennedy on the cover, and she actually looks as if
she's having fun, which might be the greatest measure of how
political campaigns have changed. This volume, subtitled ``An
Illustrated History of Presidential Campaigns,'' begins with that
great anomaly, George Washington, a man
(beginitalic)e(enditalic)(beginitalic)veryone (enditalic)wanted for
president. His vice president, John Adams, was a pricklier sort
with a knack for modern-style politics - according to James
Madison, he ``made himself obnoxious to many, particularly in the
Southern states.'' Cornog and Whelan provide lively accounts of
each election, with an appreciation for the humor of it all.
``Dullness Visible'' is their title for the 1996 campaign of
Clinton, Dole and Perot, and the Bush-Dukakis showdown of 1988 is
dubbed ``Meet Willie Horton.'' Of course, there's no mention of Al
and Dubya, who are writing their chapter as we speak. We think they
should call it ``Are we having fun yet?''
</P>
<P>
   ``BODY OF A GIRL''
</P>
<P>
   By Leah Stewart
</P>
<P>
   (Viking, $23.95)
</P>
<P>
   A young Memphis newspaper reporter named Olivia Dale covers the
rape and murder of a woman much like herself. Allison Avery was 24,
a pretty girl who wanted to be famous but became so only with her
grisly death. As Olivia pursues Allison's story and interviews her
grief-stricken brother and mother, her friends, old acquaintances
and boyfriend, she gradually becoming obsessed with the victim and
with what happened to her. Olivia needs to believe that Allison's
death was not a random act. ``I want to know her,'' she says. ``I
could learn so much about what happened to her if just for a moment
I could slip inside her skin.'' At its best, this first novel has
the ominous effect of Susanna Moore's tense, violent book ``In the
Cut,'' but Stewart gives her story a melodramatic and disappointing
ending. Its strengths are in the details: realistic dialogue, a
believable narrative voice and a conviction that, as Joan Didion
once said, reporters ``are always selling somebody out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``FAITH OF MY FATHERS''
</P>
<P>
   By John McCain
</P>
<P>
   (HarperPerennial, $14)
</P>
<P>
   ``In prison, I fell in love with my country. It wasn't until I
had lost America for a time that I realized how much I loved her.''
Set off the fireworks, wave your flags, John McCain's memoir is out
in paperback. For those of you who have been in a closet for two
years, it's the story of his father's and grandfather's illustrious
naval careers and of his own evolution from a bad-boy student at
the U.S. Naval Academy to the injured flier who endured five years
of torture and isolation in a Hanoi prison during the Vietnam War.
The sections on the older men lag, but the book picks up when
McCain himself appears - a brash, rebellious and often dislikable
young man who graduated fifth from the bottom of his class at the
academy. The story of his prison years is not new to anyone who has
heard his political speeches, but McCain has never told it quite
this well, in a straightforward voice and with occasional and
unexpected moments of droll humor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
