<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000904.0066 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 04:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0353 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-BLACKCATHOLICS-AZR &LR;      09-04 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACKCATHOLICS-AZR </SLUG>
  
Black Catholics &HT;    defy their bishop
 &HT;    Service not authorized by diocese BC-BLACK-CATHOLICS-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    BLACK CATHOLICS DEFY THEIR BISHOP(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By Maureen Jenkins and Kerry Fehr-Snyder(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   About 32 Black Catholics gathered for services on Sunday,
defying the wishes of their bishop who wants them to worship with
the larger ministry.
</P>
<P>
   Faith Community of St. Monica had planned to hold Sunday service
in the parking lot of St. Pius X Mission in south Phoenix but found
the church doors unlocked and open for worship.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we're not wanted, although the bishop never gave us
official notice,'' said Keith Williams, former chairman of the
Office of Black Catholic Ministry.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Williams was dismissed from his volunteer duties - a
move he believes resulted from his outspoken stance on Black
Ministry issues. Since then, internal politics and personality
conflicts have come into play.
</P>
<P>
   For the past few years, African-American Catholics wanting a
Black-centered worship experience have gathered monthly for a
``Unity Mass.'' The service gives the Valley's scattered Black
Catholics a chance to celebrate their faith in the Black and
cultural tradition.
</P>
<P>
   But for the past several months, a Mass also has been held on
the first Sunday of the month, organized by the Faith Community of
St. Monica, a group of Black Catholics eager for more frequent
worship.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the Diocese of Phoenix suspended this service,
saying in a recent mailing that the Mass ``has become a tool in an
effort by some to move {hellip} in a direction focusing on
separatism and separation from the Diocese and Office of Black
Catholic Ministry.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the cancellation of the Mass, determined worshipers
gathered Sunday for a service at St. Pius, near Seventh Avenue and
Buckeye Road.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, the service attracts 50 to 75 worshipers, said
Phoenix resident P.J. Longoni, who goes by the name Almaz Cato.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to call people to let them know we were still having
service,'' she said. ``Some people said they'd come, but others
said they wanted to stay out of the politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Priests and churches within the Phoenix diocese were advised not
to celebrate the Eucharist or provide meeting space for groups not
officially connected to the Black Catholic Ministry office.
</P>
<P>
   The decision confounds member Mildred Perkins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be disobedient,'' she said, adding that she's
been attending the church for more than 50 years. ``Somebody is
going to say why we can't be here, and they're going to give a good
reason.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Black Catholics just want to have services.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody's trying to be secretive; nobody's trying to do
anything against the diocese or what our Catholic faith is,'' said
state representative Leah Landrum, an active member of the Faith
Community.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really see a difference from the first Sunday Mass to
the third Sunday Mass. All I see is a beautiful service, and thank
God we have a place we can go.''
</P>
<P>
   Sponsored by the Office of Black Catholic Ministry, the third
Sunday ``Unity Mass'' sometimes is a standing-room-only service,
drawing a multiracial crowd and featuring the gospel sounds of the
Freedom Singers. But it's not enough, say some in the ministry.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Richardson, who said the service is open to all races,
added that once-a-month gathering left him unsatisfied.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not trying to discriminate, we're not bigots, we don't
have a sign out there that says, `Only our own kind,''' he said.
``We've been very successful not only at reaching a lot of
African-Americans but a lot of other people.''
</P>
<P>
   Blacks - who comprise less than 4 percent of all Arizonans -
already are a minority within the Catholic Church. Within the
diocese, the 1,500 to 1,800 Blacks are just a fraction of the
440,000 Phoenix Catholics. But members of Faith Community of St.
Monica aren't looking to break away, said Williams, the former
chairman. He pointed to other ethnic ministries within the diocese,
such as Hispanic, Vietnamese, Korean and Polish, which he said are
``left in peace'' by diocesan leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're fighting to stay complete Catholics,'' he said. ``This
(cancellation of first Sunday Mass) is simply to scare people,
defame our name, and keep people away.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are those that want to have Mass once a month, do the
Black thing, and go back to their parish. The rest of us want to
have Mass in our own cultural context.''
</P>
<P>
   Canceling the service was a joint decision by Bishop Thomas J.
O'Brien and the Office of Black Catholic Ministry board, said
coordinator Marie Chavis Ausberry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't the Mass, it's what the group is doing'' that's in
conflict, she said. ``A Catholic Mass is a Catholic Mass. We'd like
to have the unity, and that's what I'm striving for.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Black Catholics don't comprise a single parish, the
diocese encourages them to be active, visible members of their
neighborhood parish.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of things we can't offer,'' Ausberry said,
``because we're not a parish and don't have the facilities.''
</P>
<P>
   But Landrum, who chooses not to belong to a parish, can't
understand why only one monthly Mass is allowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really starting to see the same faces and build a nice
community,'' Landrum said.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach the reporter at maureen.jenkins(a)arizona &QL;
</P>
<P>
   republic.com or (602) 444-7945.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-00 0401EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000904.0067 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 04:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0354 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l BC-PROFANITY-AZR &LR;      09-04 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROFANITY-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-PUBLIC-PROFANITY-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    DON'T CURSE AROUND MY KID, YOU BLEEP(a) 
 &HT;    (Duplication warning: Moving in ``K'' and ``L'' categories) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By DAVE WALKER(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'm no bleeping church lady, but all of a sudden I'm all bleeped
off about public profanity.
</P>
<P>
   It's the parent in me, surfacing at ballgames and in the mall to
spurn foul-mouthed punks who closely resemble the pre-parent Dave
to a startling degree.
</P>
<P>
   Full disclosure: I was once not so careful about self-regulation
in the a-, h-, d-, G-, s- and f-bomb departments. I have used the
worst possible language in inappropriate settings, offending
friends and relatives. They were all, for the most part, adults who
had heard the words before.
</P>
<P>
   I remember most of the exceptions. Usually they were thoughtless
outbursts of cursing around children not my own, and today they
haunt me in ways I couldn't have imagined.
</P>
<P>
   I have also cursed around my own child - no better, I know - but
that usually only happens in the car, and it's never directed at
anybody but other motorists, so it's not my bleeping fault.
</P>
<P>
   Further disclosure: In the appropriate adult settings, sailor
talk still occasionally works its way into a discussion. Newspaper
newsrooms are the only adult setting I frequent with any regularity
anymore, and, OK, it happens there more often than occasionally.
It's seriously veteran sailor talk. Sailor talk with forearm
tattoos of anchors and hula dancers.
</P>
<P>
   Call me a bleep. I don't mind. I'll call you one back, though
louder and using excruciatingly precise diction. As long as there
are no kids or grandmothers around, let's talk dirty. Let's talk
like grown-ups, rap stars, stand-up comics and Nixon aides.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, I say ``sailor talk'' and paint an entire branch of
our noble armed forces with a broad brush, probably a
rust-inhibiting hue of gray. There are no doubt a handful of
non-swearing sailors somewhere, and to them I apologize.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, I could and can and will curse with the worst of their
mop-slinging sea chums. The First Amendment, after all, is among my
top 10 favorite amendments. Let freedom bleeping ring, I say.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, I can hear the political and social conservatives among you
now: This all started with taking prayer out of school or whatever
it is you say whenever pop culture lets you down. Plus, I just
insulted the Navy and those heroic Nixon aides.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine my disappointment, however, to be suddenly aligned with
all of you bleeping prudes. For the record, I'm a single-issue
prude, and that issue suddenly is public profanity around children.
</P>
<P>
   No. I can be more specific than that. Public profanity around MY
kid is what bleeps me off. (Despite the fact that, thanks to the
likes of Eminem, there are words my 11-year-old could teach me.)
Not knowing what to do about it - aside from writing bleep-filled
essays in the Sunday paper - bleeps me off worse.
</P>
<P>
   The third quarter of another desultory Arizona Cardinals game is
not the time or place to counsel the drunk(s) around you that potty
talk around children is a social faux pas. Same goes for the
bullpen innings of another close Arizona Diamondbacks loss. Telling
someone to shut the bleep up only makes matters worse. This I know
from sad experience.
</P>
<P>
   Trying that tactic at a mall could get you killed. Sporting
events, at least, are staffed by security dudes who can save your
bleep once the fight starts. No such backup will come running
should Mr. Eyelid Ring find your impromptu deportment lesson
wanting. At the mall, the only nearby help you're likely to get
comes from a pretzel-stand assistant manager.
</P>
<P>
   So, next time, here's what's going to happen: I will keep my own
yap shut at least until I find the first available usher or cop or
security guard or authority figure above the rank of pretzel-stand
assistant manager. Then I'll demand to be moved to comparable
seats, immediately. If I'm paying for a seat at an event, I'm also
paying for air space. Clean, unobstructed-by-bleepage air.
</P>
<P>
   I'll make them move us, right now. Make a scene. Make trouble.
It's the only way. I don't want Mr. Bleep kicked out. I don't want
him to get a lecture from a timid usher, who'd rather just be
watching the ballgame anyway.
</P>
<P>
   I want to watch the game without having to cover my kid's ears.
</P>
<P>
   Then what?
</P>
<P>
   I'll relax.
</P>
<P>
   Meri Wallace, author and founder of the Heights Center for Adult
and Child Development in Brooklyn, N.Y., said that even the most
tender child is not likely to be permanently scarred by a forced
encounter with profanity. As long as you act like a grown-up
yourself when you deal with such a situation. It's hard, I know,
not to just punch the loudmouth in the nose and run. But I'll be
strong.
</P>
<P>
   When we reach our new seats, we'll talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``We walk around as interpreters of our environment,'' said
Wallace. ``With children, whatever they're seeing, we help them
understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``At a sports event, you are an interpreter of the behavior (of
others). Say, `Sometimes grown-ups use words they shouldn't, words
we don't use in our home.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately, how the child is treated in the home is the thing
that wins out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-00 0402EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000904.0068 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 04:02 </DATE_TIME>
