<SLUG> BC-R-BESTSELLERS-PAPER-S-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEST SELLERS: PAPERBACK BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release on Sunday, Sept. 10) 
(Eds: This file is the abbreviated best-seller list for paperback
books. See BESTSELLERS-PAPER-L-NYT for the full version that
includes how many weeks each book has been on the list.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rankings reflect sales figures for the week ending Aug. 26 at
almost 4,000 bookstores plus wholesalers serving 60,000 other
retailers, statistically weighted to represent sales in all such
outlets nationwide. The number of titles within the two
subdivisions of nonfiction can change from week to week, reflecting
changes in book buying.
</P>
<P>
   An (x) following a book's ranking indicates that a book's sales
are barely distinguishable from those of the book above. A (b)
indicates that some bookstores report receiving bulk orders for a
book.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. BLACK NOTICE, by Patricia Cornwell. (Berkley, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Kay Scarpetta's investigation of a ship's cargo
</P>
<P>
   involves her in an international conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   2. THE POISONWOOD BIBLE, by Barbara Kingsolver.
</P>
<P>
   (Perennial/HarperCollins, $14.) Five female characters
</P>
<P>
   narrate a novel set in the Belgian Congo during that
</P>
<P>
   country's fight for independence.
</P>
<P>
   3. THE ALIBI, by Sandra Brown. (Warner, $7.99.) Jealousy,
</P>
<P>
   intrigue and corruption beset a Charleston lawyer
</P>
<P>
   during his pursuit of public office.
</P>
<P>
   4. HEARTS IN ATLANTIS, by Stephen King. (Pocket Books,
</P>
<P>
   $7.99.) Five long, interconnected stories about an
</P>
<P>
   America haunted by the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   5. DARK LADY, by Richard North Patterson. (Ballantine,
</P>
<P>
   $7.99.) Stella Marz, a driven county prosecutor, pursues
</P>
<P>
   criminals infesting a struggling Midwestern city.
</P>
<P>
   6. TARA ROAD, by Maeve Binchy. (Dell, $7.99.) Two women _
</P>
<P>
   one from Ireland, one from England _ learn a lot about
</P>
<P>
   each other and themselves when they exchange houses for
</P>
<P>
   the summer.
</P>
<P>
   7. BLUE GOLD, by Clive Cussler with Paul Kemprecos.
</P>
<P>
   (Pocket Books, $16.) Kurt Austin tries to thwart a
</P>
<P>
   California tycoon's plan to control the world's
</P>
<P>
   freshwater supply.
</P>
<P>
   8. THE GUEST LIST, by Fern Michaels. (Zebra, $7.50.)
</P>
<P>
   Two sisters who have been reunited after years apart
</P>
<P>
   give a magnificent party, but an uninvited guest
</P>
<P>
   threatens their new-found happiness.
</P>
<P>
   9.(x) THE EDGE, by Catherine Coulter. (Jove, $7.99.) An
</P>
<P>
   FBI agent searches for his sister, whose disappearance
</P>
<P>
   is intertwined with baffling crimes.
</P>
<P>
   10. TEARS OF THE MOON, by Nora Roberts. (Jove, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   An Irish songwriter, shut off from the world, finds hope
</P>
<P>
   and happiness with a tomboy.
</P>
<P>
   11. WHILE I WAS GONE, by Sue Miller. (Ballantine, $12.95.)
</P>
<P>
   A small-town veterinarian, the wife of a minister, begins
</P>
<P>
   a flirtation with an old friend from her bohemian past.
</P>
<P>
   12. ASHES TO ASHES, by Tami Hoag. (Bantam, $7.99.) Kate
</P>
<P>
   Conlan, a former FBI agent, tracks a serial killer in
</P>
<P>
   Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   13.(x) THE EXPERIMENT, by John Darnton. (Signet, $6.99.)
</P>
<P>
   Rogue scientists clone the embryos of their own children
</P>
<P>
   in a misguided search for eternal youth.
</P>
<P>
   14. THE SAVING GRACES, by Patricia Gaffney. (HarperTorch,
</P>
<P>
   $6.99.) The close friendship that binds four women is put
</P>
<P>
   to the test.
</P>
<P>
   15. HANNIBAL, by Thomas Harris. (Dell, $7.99.) Seven years
</P>
<P>
   after his escape, the fiendish psychiatrist Hannibal Lecter
</P>
<P>
   is still at large.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NONFICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. THE TERRIBLE HOURS, by Peter Maas. (HarperTorch,
</P>
<P>
   $6.99.) The role a U.S. Navy officer played in
</P>
<P>
   rescuing the crew of a submarine in 1939.
</P>
<P>
   2. THE SEAT OF THE SOUL, by Gary Zukav. (Fireside/Simon
</P>
<P>
   &AMP; Schuster, $12.) How daily activities can be enhanced
</P>
<P>
   by feelings of meaning and purpose. (b)
</P>
<P>
   3. THE PERFECT STORM, by Sebastian Junger. (Perennial/
</P>
<P>
   HarperCollins, $14; HarperPaperbacks, $6.99.) The story
</P>
<P>
   of the northeaster of 1991, focusing on a single crew.
</P>
<P>
   4. THE HUNGRY OCEAN, by Linda Greenlaw. (Hyperion, $14.)
</P>
<P>
   A sea captain's account of her 30-day swordfishing
</P>
<P>
   voyage off the northeast coast.
</P>
<P>
   5. ISAAC'S STORM, by Erik Larson. (Vintage, $13.) An
</P>
<P>
   account of America's deadliest hurricane, which killed
</P>
<P>
   6,000 people in Galveston, Texas, in 1900, and the
</P>
<P>
   Weather Bureau scientist who failed to forecast it.
</P>
<P>
   6. A CHILD CALLED ``IT,'' by Dave Pelzer. (Health
</P>
<P>
   Communications, $9.95.) The autobiography of a man who
</P>
<P>
   survived his mother's abuse. (b)
</P>
<P>
   7. GIRL, INTERRUPTED, by Susanna Kaysen. (Vintage, $12.)
</P>
<P>
   A memoir of mental illness.
</P>
<P>
   8. THE LOST BOY, by Dave Pelzer. (Health Communications,
</P>
<P>
   $10.95.) The author of ``A Child Called `It''' recalls
</P>
<P>
   his life in foster homes. (b)
</P>
<P>
   9. THE LEXUS AND THE OLIVE TREE, by Thomas L. Friedman.
</P>
<P>
   (Anchor, $15.) A journalist explains the instant
</P>
<P>
   electronic global economy.
</P>
<P>
   10. ONE LAST TIME, by John Edward. (Berkley, $12.95.)
</P>
<P>
   A self-described psychic medium discusses his life and
</P>
<P>
   work.
</P>
<P>
   11. DIANA IN SEARCH OF HERSELF, by Sally Bedell Smith.
</P>
<P>
   (Signet, $7.99.) A biography of the princess of Wales,
</P>
<P>
   focusing on her psychological problems.
</P>
<P>
   12.(x) A WALK IN THE WOODS, by Bill Bryson. (Broadway, $13.)
</P>
<P>
   A journalist finds beauty and humor while hiking the
</P>
<P>
   Appalachian Trail.
</P>
<P>
   13. BLIND MAN'S BLUFF, by Sherry Sontag and Christopher
</P>
<P>
   Drew with Annette Lawrence Drew. (HarperPaperbacks, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   American espionage by submarine, from Cold War to the present.
</P>
<P>
   14. ANGELA'S ASHES, by Frank McCourt. (Touchstone/Simon
</P>
<P>
   &AMP; Schuster, $14 and $7.99.) An Irish-American writer
</P>
<P>
   recalls his childhood amid the miseries of Limerick.
</P>
<P>
   15.(x) INTO THIN AIR, by Jon Krakauer. (Anchor, $13 and
</P>
<P>
   $7.99.) Ascending Mount Everest in 1996, the deadliest
</P>
<P>
   season in history.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ADVICE, HOW-TO AND MISCELLANEOUS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. RICH DAD, POOR DAD, by Robert T. Kiyosaki with Sharon
</P>
<P>
   L. Lechter. (Warner, $15.95.) Teaching one's children
</P>
<P>
   how to get rich and stay rich.
</P>
<P>
   2. TAKE TIME FOR YOUR LIFE, by Cheryl Richardson.
</P>
<P>
   (Broadway, $13.) A seven-step program for enhancing
</P>
<P>
   social, financial and spiritual well-being. (b)
</P>
<P>
   3. DR. ATKINS' NEW DIET REVOLUTION, by Robert C. Atkins.
</P>
<P>
   (Avon, $14 and $6.99.) A physician recommends ways to
</P>
<P>
   lose weight and achieve a healthy body. (b)
</P>
<P>
   4. THE FOUR AGREEMENTS, by Don Miguel Ruiz. (Amber-Allen,
</P>
<P>
   $12.95.) A code of conduct based on personal freedom. (b)
</P>
<P>
   5. WHAT TO EXPECT WHEN YOU'RE EXPECTING, by Arlene Eisenberg,
</P>
<P>
   Heidi E. Murkoff and Sandee E. Hathaway. (Workman, $12.95)
</P>
<P>
   Advice for parents-to-be. (b)
</P>
</TEXT>
