</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-FOREIGN-SUITS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN JUSTICE TACKLES RIGHTS ABUSES ABROAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 By JOHN SULLIVAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the soldiers raped and beat her in front of her two children,
a Bosnian refugee recalled, they taunted her, saying there was
nowhere she could turn for help.
</P>
<P>
   They were wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, a federal jury in New York awarded the woman and a
group of other refugees from the Balkans war $745 million in their
case against the former leader of Serbian forces in Bosnia, Dr.
Radovan Karadzic, charging him with masterminding a campaign of
genocide, rape and torture in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   That is just one of a series of recent cases in which American
courts have agreed to hear civil cases involving human rights
violations outside U.S. territory.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Center for Constitutional Rights _ a nonprofit
organization in Manhattan that successfully argued the first such
case more than 20 years ago _ served papers on Li Peng, the former
Chinese premier, who was staying at the Waldorf Towers in New York.
Jennifer M. Green, a lawyer with the center who is arguing the
case, said a group of Chinese students has filed suit in federal
court in New York against Li over the Chinese government's actions
during the Tiananmen Square protests in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the U.S. courts' acceptance of human rights standards
are important steps forward in an international system in which
human rights violators can be held accountable,'' Green said. The
Chinese Embassy in Washington did not return calls requesting
comment last week.
</P>
<P>
   In 1978, the Center for Constitutional Rights sued a government
official in Paraguay on behalf of a family who claimed their son
had been tortured there. The case, Filartiga vs. Pena, was a
landmark attempt to use American courts to judge a dispute that, on
its face, had nothing to do with the United States or its citizens.
To make the argument, Peter Weiss, the center's vice president,
turned to a 1787 law called the Alien Tort Claims Act, which
allowed foreigners to use U.S. courts to sue for violations of
international law.
</P>
<P>
   Congress passed the law after an attack on a French diplomat in
Philadelphia, said Anne-Marie Slaughter, a professor of
international law at Harvard who collaborated on a recent article
about the law for the journal Foreign Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was what was called a badge of honor,'' Slaughter said.
``We wanted to proclaim we were a member of the family of
nations.''
</P>
<P>
   At that time, international law consisted of conventions between
sovereign states, and covered issues like piracy and diplomatic
immunity.
</P>
<P>
   Bert Neuborne, a New York University law professor, views the
Nuremberg Tribunals that followed World War II as a turning point
for international law, because the Nuremburg judges found that even
though the Nazis had acted within their own legal framework, they
were not immune from prosecution under a more general law.
</P>
<P>
   ``International law involves individuals and not just
governments,'' Neuborne said. ``Human rights norms trump the rights
of dictators.''
</P>
<P>
   That attitude underlies some international criminal cases, like
Spain's pursuit of the former Argentine strongman Gen. Augusto
Pinochet, and the indictments issued by the International War
Crimes Tribunal in the Hague.
</P>
<P>
   And since the Filartiga case ended in 1980 _ with a judgment of
more than $10 million for the plaintiffs _ there has been a steady
increase in the number of civil cases brought in American courts by
foreign plaintiffs against foreign defendants, Slaughter said.
</P>
<P>
   Application of the Alien Tort Claims Act, and a handful of
similar laws, has extended beyond individual human cases to broader
areas of misconduct, she said, citing as examples claims against
corporations for environmental damage and for actions during the
Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Filartiga case and the Karadzic verdict, many such
cases bring huge monetary awards, but few plaintiffs ever collect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people engaged in this type of litigation would say the
power is the power of publicity and the very important symbolic
impact of allowing the victims to tell their story,'' Slaughter
said. ``If they do recover that would be great but that is not the
point of the litigation.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the few cases likely to result in money changing hands
was filed against Ferdinand Marcos, the former leader of the
Philippines. Robert Swift, who represented 9,539 people who sued
Marcos before his death in 1989, won a $2 billion judgment in
federal court in Hawaii in 1995. The plaintiffs settled with
Marcos' estate and with the Philippines' government for $161
million, Swift said. But he said the payment has been blocked by a
judge in the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   Swift said that while he recognized the political importance of
such civil cases, that was not his main motivation. ``My
involvement in this whole line of cases is to try to get
compensation for the victims,'' he said. ``I have never been
satisfied with a simple declaration that the abuse occurred.''
</P>
<P>
   By far the largest settlements have involved the cases brought
in American courts by Holocaust survivors against banks and
corporations they accused of profiting from the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   Although concerns have been raised that the success of the
Holocaust suits could lead to other _ less legitimate _ lawsuits,
representatives of the plaintiffs say it is an important step in
the recognition that certain rights do not stop at national
borders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-00 0958EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000904.0083 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 09:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0390 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-R-SUBMARINES-REVIEW-N     09-04 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-SUBMARINES-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUBMARINES AND THE HIDDEN COSTS OF CLOAK AND DAGGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 By CHRISTOPHER DREW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before the nuclear-powered attack submarine USS Memphis embarked
on a recent spy mission _ in which, Navy officials have said, it
captured the sounds of the explosions that helped sink Russia's
Kursk submarine last month _ one unsettling precaution was taken. A
bright orange rescue buoy, designed to shoot to the surface and
summon help if the Memphis got in trouble, was welded down and
rendered unusable.
</P>
<P>
   This was standard practice during the Cold War, when the Navy
feared that the inadvertent release of a buoy could tip off the
Russians to the presence of an American spy sub and set off an
underwater chase. It also reflected the grim acceptance among
submariners that if a serious accident occurred in hostile waters,
they probably were not coming back. But now that the two nations
are friendlier, times have changed. Or have they?
</P>
<P>
   The Kursk disaster, with the loss of all 118 men on board, has
cast a harsher light on the secrecy that has continued to define
submarine operations on both sides. It has also raised the question
of whether a little less cloak and dagger _ and more cooperation
among seafaring nations _ could go a long way toward improving the
safety of those on board the vessels.
</P>
<P>
   Old habits die hard. News reports in Russia last week suggested
that the Kursk might have been secretly testing a powerful new
torpedo when it sank in the Barents Sea on Aug. 12. That might help
explain why Russian leaders delayed seeking rescue assistance from
the West, even though a few crew members might have remained alive
for two or three days inside the wrecked hull.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. authorities believe a torpedo accident caused two
explosions aboard the Kursk, with a huge blast from the torpedo's
warhead ripping a hole in the submarine. Pentagon officials said
last week that the Memphis and another U.S. submarine recorded the
explosions while secretly monitoring a Russian naval exercise.
</P>
<P>
   It is natural that the U.S. Navy wants to keep an eye on the
Russian navy. But the United States has sharply cut back the
frequency of surveillance missions since the end of the Cold War,
and the Russians rarely go to sea anymore. So, some critics ask,
why should U.S. submariners still be restricted in their ability to
seek help if a fire or flooding were to cripple their vessel?
</P>
<P>
   Submarine officers have said that if an accident occurred, they
would be much more willing to surface in international waters near
Russia than they used to be. U.S. subs also carry a tiny
communications buoy that can be ejected to transmit an SOS signal
for up to 18 hours. But even if they called for help, who would be
there to rescue them?
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials have said it would have taken two or three days
for them to rush divers and rescue craft to the scene, or about the
same amount of time that it took the British and Norwegians to get
there.
</P>
<P>
   One solution would be for the world's leading submarine navies
to work together to build a new generation of rescue vessels and
position them around the globe. Some Western navies have already
modified their old rescue equipment to work with the U.S. gear.
Experts say Russia will need to cooperate more if such a rescue
network is going to work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-00 0958EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000904.0084 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 09:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6974 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-R-FOREIGN-SUITS-REVIE     09-04 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-FOREIGN-SUITS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
