<DOCNO> NYT20000904.0085 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 09:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0391 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-R-CH &LR; E &UR; ERLEADING-TEXT     09-04 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-CH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE A TEENAGER GIVES ORDERS 
</HEADLINE>
 E ERLEADING-TEXT-REVIEW-NYT   (The Week in Review)  
 and (END ITALICS HERE)  
 By JOE SHARKEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Football season is here again, and as anyone who has been to a
high school or college game in recent years knows, this is not your
Aunt Gidget's cheerleading squad anymore. Today's cheerleaders
tumble, vault, build human pyramids _ and sometimes exhibit higher
athletic skill than the teams they're rooting for. Like gymnasts,
cheerleaders work with coaches, choreographers and physical
trainers, often attending summer boot camps to prepare for both the
sidelines and competitions with other squads.
</P>
<P>
   After years of disregard and even ridicule, cheerleading is back
and bigger than ever, with a steely, aerobicized attitude that's a
long way from old-fashioned pom-poms and sis-boom-bahs. This
summer, Hollywood released two major high-school cheerleader
movies: ``But I'm a Cheerleader!'' and ``Bring It On,'' a hit that
depicts cheerleaders as serious athletes and socially responsible
citizens. And cheerleading is being pushed as a potential Olympic
sport in 2004.
</P>
<P>
   Today's cheerleading supports an industry of fashion and sports
suppliers, instructors, sports doctors, competition organizers and
glossy publications. ``Where else can a teen-age girl stand up in
front of thousands of people and tell them what to do?'' a
cheerleader asks in an ad in American Cheerleader magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The following excerpts, gleaned from the magazine and its Web
site (www.americancheerleader.com), suggest some of the forces at
play in the brave new world of cheerleader empowerment.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) Vince Lombardi would have been proud:
Today's cheerleaders are tough as nails and can play with pain.
(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   To many, falling from stunts represents the adverse side of
cheerleading. Yet in a controlled environment, it's really not!
Cheerleaders should know that without failure there would be no
success.
</P>
<P>
   Serious knee injuries are not just for boys!
</P>
<P>
   Do you need a fun way to get in shape for the summer, but hate
those boring step classes and supermodel workout videos? Try
kickboxing!
</P>
<P>
   Hi! I'm a junior high cheerleader (and) I have an idea: Liberty
turn with advanced stunts. Start facing to the left of the crowd,
go into a lib and do an arabesque, then turn and have your flyer
kick a stretch heel, turn again and your flyer will do a waterfall,
then turn and kick a heel stretch and turn again to your starting
point and pull one more waterfall, then cradle. It's an awesome
stunt. I did it on my first try. Good luck!
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) Not that the modern cheerleader is
completely squeaky clean. A half-page ad for Glass Chalk, an ink
marker used to make washable graffiti on glass, depicts a
mischievous-looking cheerleader with marker in hand, posed beside
summer-camp snapshots showing windows scrawled with gently taunting
insults against opposing teams. The ad's text says: (END ITALICS
HERE)
</P>
<P>
   What we did last summer: Did you hear about cheer camp? ... We
left our team's mark (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) everywhere! (END ITALICS
HERE) It was sooo awesome. You can't believe what a little Glass
Chalk does for team spirit! But no worry. It washes right off any
glass window with a wet paper towel.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) A little community outreach never hurts,
especially if spreading cheer can raise your squad's visibility.
(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   You've heard the complaint time and time again: The cheerleading
team doesn't get enough support. You're athletes, so why does all
of the attention focus on football and basketball and not on you?
You're not alone.
</P>
<P>
   While the student body celebrates the biggest game of the week,
they probably don't even know that your golf team is undefeated and
your swim team is ranked first in the state. As the spirit leaders
in your school, you can help gain support for (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)
every (END ITALICS HERE) sport and bring added attention to the
cheer squad in the process. A fall sports pep rally dedicated
strictly to these athletes will show them they are important to the
school.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) And hey, don't we all want to share that
invincible team spirit? Even trumpet players and classroom
wiseacres are vulnerable.(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Stereotypes say that the cheerleaders and the band never get
along. Here are some suggestions to help make you and the band a
spirit unit: Teach them some cheers. ... Put them on the sidelines
with you. ... Invite a few down to do one of your cheers with you,
maybe in the later part of the game.
</P>
<P>
   And you know that kid in your history class who always keeps
everyone else laughing? Invite him or her to use those ``class
clowning'' skills and join you on the sidelines, running back and
forth painted in school colors and flashing ``Go! Fight! Win!''
signs to get the crowd to yell along with you.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-00 0959EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000904.0086 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 09:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6975 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-R-SUBMARINES-REVIEW-N     09-04 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-SUBMARINES-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUBMARINES AND THE HIDDEN COSTS OF CLOAK AND DAGGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 By CHRISTOPHER DREW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before the nuclear-powered attack submarine USS Memphis embarked
on a recent spy mission _ in which, Navy officials have said, it
captured the sounds of the explosions that helped sink Russia's
Kursk submarine last month _ one unsettling precaution was taken. A
bright orange rescue buoy, designed to shoot to the surface and
summon help if the Memphis got in trouble, was welded down and
rendered unusable.
</P>
<P>
   This was standard practice during the Cold War, when the Navy
feared that the inadvertent release of a buoy could tip off the
Russians to the presence of an American spy sub and set off an
underwater chase. It also reflected the grim acceptance among
submariners that if a serious accident occurred in hostile waters,
they probably were not coming back. But now that the two nations
are friendlier, times have changed. Or have they?
</P>
<P>
   The Kursk disaster, with the loss of all 118 men on board, has
cast a harsher light on the secrecy that has continued to define
submarine operations on both sides. It has also raised the question
of whether a little less cloak and dagger _ and more cooperation
among seafaring nations _ could go a long way toward improving the
safety of those on board the vessels.
</P>
<P>
   Old habits die hard. News reports in Russia last week suggested
that the Kursk might have been secretly testing a powerful new
torpedo when it sank in the Barents Sea on Aug. 12. That might help
explain why Russian leaders delayed seeking rescue assistance from
the West, even though a few crew members might have remained alive
for two or three days inside the wrecked hull.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. authorities believe a torpedo accident caused two
explosions aboard the Kursk, with a huge blast from the torpedo's
warhead ripping a hole in the submarine. Pentagon officials said
last week that the Memphis and another U.S. submarine recorded the
explosions while secretly monitoring a Russian naval exercise.
</P>
<P>
   It is natural that the U.S. Navy wants to keep an eye on the
Russian navy. But the United States has sharply cut back the
frequency of surveillance missions since the end of the Cold War,
and the Russians rarely go to sea anymore. So, some critics ask,
why should U.S. submariners still be restricted in their ability to
seek help if a fire or flooding were to cripple their vessel?
</P>
<P>
   Submarine officers have said that if an accident occurred, they
would be much more willing to surface in international waters near
Russia than they used to be. U.S. subs also carry a tiny
communications buoy that can be ejected to transmit an SOS signal
for up to 18 hours. But even if they called for help, who would be
there to rescue them?
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials have said it would have taken two or three days
for them to rush divers and rescue craft to the scene, or about the
same amount of time that it took the British and Norwegians to get
there.
</P>
<P>
   One solution would be for the world's leading submarine navies
to work together to build a new generation of rescue vessels and
position them around the globe. Some Western navies have already
modified their old rescue equipment to work with the U.S. gear.
Experts say Russia will need to cooperate more if such a rescue
network is going to work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-00 0959EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
