<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 11:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0404 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT     09-04 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWSUIT A BACK-ALLEY ATTACK ON NATIONAL MONUMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (EDITOR'S NOTE: Charles Levendosky, editorial page editor of the
Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune, has written about public lands issues
for over a decade and is respected for his insight into these
issues. His e-mail address is levendos(at)trib.com.) 
By CHARLES LEVENDOSKY   
 c.2000 Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The oil, gas and minerals industries are attempting another
strategy to abolish national monuments so they can drill and mine
on the public's land. This latest attempt is a legal shell game.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 28, Mountain States Legal Foundation (MSLF) out of
Denver filed a lawsuit in the federal district court of the
District of Columbia against President Clinton. The lawsuit
contends that Clinton does not have the constitutional authority to
create national monuments.
</P>
<P>
   So close to the presidential elections, the lawsuit's timing is
suspect.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit was filed on behalf of the members of Mountain
States Legal Foundation _ read that as Texaco, Exxon, Chevron and
other mineral industry donors _ and members of the Blue Ribbon
Coalition who want to drive their off-road vehicles on land now
protected by national monument status.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit challenges five of the most recent national
monuments that Clinton created: Cascade-Siskiyou National Monument
in Oregon, Canyons of the Ancients National Monument in Colorado,
Hanford Reach National Monument in Washington, Ironwood Forest
National Monument in Arizona and Grand Canyon Parashant National
Monument in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The MSLF admits in its lawsuit that members of MSLF ``have
concrete plans for the future to use, each of the five areas at
issue in this complaint for a variety of purposes including, but
not limited to: prospecting for minerals, exploring for and mining
for ore bodies, exploring for and drilling for oil and gas
deposits....''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit is so sweeping and general, it might as well have
challenged the creation of all 110 national monuments.
</P>
<P>
   It repeats in simplistic terms that President Clinton has
violated the Property Clause of the U.S. Constitution (Article IV,
Section 3, Paragraph 2): ``The Congress shall have the power to
dispose of and make all needful rules and regulations respecting
the territory or other property belonging to the United States...''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit claims that Clinton violated the Property Clause of
the Constitution ``because he thereby disposed of, reserved, and
made various rules and regulations respecting property belonging to
the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Not once does the lawsuit acknowledge or even mention the
Antiquities Act of 1906. The Antiquities Act specifically gives the
president the authority to reserve federal lands and put them under
the management of public lands agencies created by the Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Congress can and has given the executive branch certain
authority over public lands. The Antiquities Act is one of those
delegations of power granted to the president by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Is the Antiquities Act an unconstitutional delegation of
authority? That seems to be the unasked, invisible question in this
simple-minded lawsuit that MSLF has filed in its original
complaint.
</P>
<P>
   The Antiquities Act is constitutional if Congress inserted into
the act guidelines specific enough, so that it is Congress making
the public policy and the president merely implementing that policy
when he creates national monuments. The guidelines are there. The
fundamental policy is made by the Congress.
</P>
<P>
   And Congress has the power of the purse so that it can refuse to
fund any national monument. Congress can also, by a vote of a
majority in both Houses, abolish any national monument.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Supreme Court has no problem with the constitutionality
of the Antiquities Act. In Cameron v. U.S. (1920), Wyoming's only
U.S. Supreme Court Justice, Willis Van Devanter, delivered the
opinion of the court and upheld the national monument status of the
Grand Canyon against mining claims. Theodore Roosevelt created the
Grand Canyon National Monument in 1908. Congress later turned it
into a national park.
</P>
<P>
   There has never been a decision in federal courts where the
president's authority under the Antiquities Act has been denied.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Department of Justice will undoubtedly respond with a
request for summary judgment to dismiss the case based upon the
authority given to the president under the Antiquities Act to
create national monuments.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the shell game: The challenge was never really about
violating the Property Clause of the Constitution; it's about how
to undo national monuments through the courts.
</P>
<P>
   After the Justice Department's response, we can expect MSLF to
file an amended complaint that spells out more specific allegations
as to how the president violated the terms of the Antiquities Act
in creating the five recent national monuments. The litigation will
continue.
</P>
<P>
   Now look at the timing. Presidential elections are held in two
months. This case could very well be a calculated move to keep a
challenge to these national monuments in court until after the
elections.
</P>
<P>
   The president is named as a defendant in the case. So if George
W. Bush is elected president and the case is still in a federal
court, the new president, Bush, could simply settle the matter out
of court by abolishing the challenged five national monuments.
</P>
<P>
   Such a scenario would be a back-alley attack on the authority
that Congress has granted presidents since 1906.
</P>
<P>
   In this scenario, the president's power under the Antiquities
Act would be gutted. Other national monuments could be challenged
in federal courts and then settled in favor of the minerals
industries. All our national monuments would be at risk. For what?
For mining. For oil and gas.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, there must be room for the minerals industries, for
drilling and mining _ elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   As a matter of balance, there also must be room in our nation
for the grand vistas, scientific and cultural sites, landscapes and
special wilderness areas that are protected by national monuments.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-00 1143EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
