   (All stories moved in the ``e'' entertainment file.)
</P>
<P>
   HUGE TALENT _ AND FEAR _ KEEPS JOEL JUMPING
</P>
<P>
   FANTASTICK-JOEL-GREY-STARBEAT _ Joel Grey, famous for his star
turns in the long-running theatrical production, and now movie,
``The Fantasticks,'' and stage and screen productions of
``Cabaret,'' is a man with both a history and a future. ``For me,
it's almost always about the character, what I can learn from doing
it,'' he explains. ``If I get to a place where I think, `I can't do
this,' I know I have to do it. It's scary, but it happened with all
the plays and movies that ever won me any kind of recognition. And
that fear of `I can't do this,' is what keeps me jumping even
now.'' By Ian Spelling. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   CROSSING THE THRESHOLD FROM CHILDHOOD TO THE ROCK WORLD
</P>
<P>
   ALMOST-FAMOUS-CAMERON-CROWE-STARBEAT _ Cameron Crowe's best
friend was always music. It didn't judge him, or care that he was a
shy, chubby, geek. Often alone, he wrote obsessively about the rock
'n' roll bands of his era _ the '60s and '70s _ and at 15 was
recruited by Rolling Stone magazine. Now, at 43, he is one of the
hottest and hippest film directors in Hollywood. ``Almost Famous,''
which draws on his memories, is a movie he has wanted to do for
years. ``I think this is 90 percent my own story,'' he admits. And
today's rock scene? ``I feel, somewhere in this country, some kid
is in a garage and about to change it all.'' By Cindy Pearlman.
WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   FUNNY JULIA SWEENEY: FINDING COMEDY IN TRAGEDY
</P>
<P>
   BABYBLUES-SWEENEY-STARBEAT _ Julia Sweeney, best known as the
plump Pat in ``Saturday Night Live,'' admits that in creating Pat
she thumbed her nose at Hollywood. ``I thought, `I might not
measure up in the pretty department but I'm going to show you how
funny I can be looking really ugly.'' So she put on a 400-pound fat
suit and a wig and drew pimples on her face. ``After that, I felt a
lot better about myself!'' she laughs. Now this funny, 30-ish
comedian has found success as Wanda in TV cartoon series ``Baby
Blues. ``I've finally gotten to use my real voice in a TV show,''
she says excitedly. By Jeanne Wolf. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   EMINEM: `TRYING TO SOUND LIKE NOBODY ELSE'
</P>
<P>
   EMINEM-STARBEAT _ On his breakthrough hit ``My Name Is,'' Eminem
announced that Dr. Dre, his mentor and record company boss, ``sent
me to piss the world off.'' The Detroit rapper has more than
fulfilled his assignment. With his two multimillion-selling albums
of facile, linguistically inventive word play, Eminem _ whose real
name is Marshall Mathers _ has left a trail of scorched earth in
his wake. By Gary Graff. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   FACE VALUE: Billy Crudup
</P>
<P>
   Cartoonist Ricardo Castaneda offers his offbeat take on Billy
Crudup as he appears in ``Almost Famous.''
</P>
