<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 11:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0425 &Cx1f; tab-z
u e BC-EMINEM-STARBEAT-ART-N     09-04 1349
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMINEM-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMINEM: `TRYING TO SOUND LIKE NOBODY ELSE'
</HEADLINE>
  (A color photo of Eminem is available electronically. Call New York
Times Syndicate photo editor William Gonzalez at 800-972-3550 or
212-499-3355.) 
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's STARBEAT feature service. For more
information about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _
or becoming a client of STARBEAT _ contact one of the New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the
text.) 
 By GARY GRAFF 
 c.2000 Gary Graff 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On his breakthrough hit ``My Name Is,'' Eminem announced that
Dr. Dre, his mentor and record company boss, ``sent me to piss the
world off.''
</P>
<P>
   The Detroit rapper has more than fulfilled his assignment.
</P>
<P>
   With his two multimillion-selling albums of facile,
linguistically inventive word play, Eminem _ whose real name is
Marshall Mathers _ has left a trail of scorched earth in his wake.
</P>
<P>
   Billboard magazine editor Timothy White, for instance, attacked
the profane language, drug references and intensely violent imagery
of Eminem's songs as ``making money by exploiting the world's
misery.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gay and Lesbian Alliance Against Defamation (GLAAD) censured
this year's ``The Marshall Mathers LP'' for graphic and homophobic
lyrics, including an irreverent reference to late designer Gianni
Versace's sexuality. The organization also took to task Interscope
Records, which distributes and promotes Eminem's albums.
</P>
<P>
   Pop acts such as 'N Sync, Britney Spears and Christina Aguilera,
as well as fellow Detroit hip-hoppers Insane Clown Posse, are
brushing off the ashes from blistering attacks he's made against
them in his new songs.
</P>
<P>
   And Eminem's own mother is still pursuing a $10-million
defamation lawsuit for comments he's made about her in songs and in
interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, those who buy into what Eminem describes as simply
``vulgar humor'' speak even louder. ``The Slim Shady LP'' sold more
than 3 million copies and won two Grammy awards, including Best Rap
Album. And ``The Marshall Mathers LP'' spent eight consecutive
weeks at No. 1 on the Billboard charts.
</P>
<P>
   After that kind of success, Eminem can afford to laugh off his
critics _ even though he's still surprised at the intensity of some
of their reactions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew, when my music came out, people were gonna be like, `I
can't believe he just said that,''' says the 26-year-old rapper,
who was born in St. Joseph, Mo., a suburb of St. Louis, but moved
to Detroit with his mother when he was young.
</P>
<P>
   He now lives in the suburb of Sterling Heights, Mich., and has a
four-year-old daughter, Hailie, with his estranged wife, Kim. The
couple is in divorce proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time, I thought people would listen to it and take
it for what it was: vulgar humor. To me, I could tell what songs
were serious, all jokes aside, and what statements were too
ridiculous to even believe.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people ask me, `You joke so much, you say so much ...
When do we know you're joking and when do we know you're not? When
do we know to take you seriously?' You don't. It's your guess. It's
kind of like a mystique I want to leave around me. It's the only
real mystique I've got. As far as my personal life, it's all out
there, you know?''
</P>
<P>
   In more ways than he'd like, actually. Eminem has been in the
news most recently for felony gun and assault charges stemming from
two separate incidents during June in suburban Detroit. In one, he
allegedly pulled an unloaded pistol on an employee of the Insane
Clown Posse. A few hours later, he did the same thing as he
confronted a man he claimed was kissing his wife at a bar near the
couple's home.
</P>
<P>
   Both cases have been remanded to circuit courts, where they're
expected to be heard during September.
</P>
<P>
   The news got worse in early July, when Kim Mathers _ whom Eminem
has ``killed'' in songs on each of his albums _ was taken to a
hospital for attempting suicide, following two Detroit performances
of the ``Up in Smoke'' tour, featuring Eminem.
</P>
<P>
   This is the part Eminem says he has problems with. He can handle
the critics and the moralists, but having to deal with security
issues, media scrutiny and otherwise comport himself like a star,
he says, is not why he's making music.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a star,'' he insists. ``However anybody else with
success wants to act like a star, then that's on them, and that's
what they choose to do. I get in my car, I drive to Wendy's, I do
the same (things) that I've always done. I don't act like a star. I
don't try to wear a bunch of jewelry or flaunt that I got a bunch
of money and that. I don't need to.''
</P>
<P>
   But Eminem, who's always been accommodating to fans who approach
him for autographs and to talk, is starting to feel the strain of
trying to stay accessible. He recently asked the city of Sterling
Heights for permission to build a fence around his home because of
excessive visits by fans and reporters. The request was denied. And
he acknowledges that frequently being recognized in public ``gets a
little nerve-wracking.''
</P>
<P>
   He's loath to cloister himself too much, however, because he
feels that his very strength is his accessibility _ both in person
and through his music.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more personal I get,'' he explains, ``the more people can
relate to me, relate to my pain, relate to what I've gone through,
my little personal dilemmas, my relationship with my girl, the
things I'm going through with my wife now, with raising a daughter
and trying to juggle a rap career, whatever. I always felt like the
more personal Tupac got, the more I could relate to him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Marshall Mathers LP,'' meanwhile, continues the path of
rapid-fire destruction that Eminem began on ``The Slim Shady LP.''
Besides Versace, his other direct hits include the late Sonny Bono,
the paralyzed actor Christopher Reeve and rivals Insane Clown
Posse. He makes a baldly prurient verbal advance on actress
Jennifer Lopez and even kills off mentor Dr. Dre _ twice _ in his
lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (stuff) he comes up with is just incredible,'' says Sen
Dog of the hip-hop group Cypress Hill. ``To think like he does and
say (what) he does, and the style he brings, is really clever. It's
entertaining, it's funny, it's funky. And at the same time it's
like `Whoa, did he say that?'''
</P>
<P>
   Eminem says the Aguilera slap was retribution for something
she'd said about him on MTV.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, it galls him that he shares a significant number of
fans with the artists he attacks so venomously.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unbelievable! I see no connection with them, and I always
find myself grouped up with them, like placed in almost the same
(music) category,'' he says. ``I often find myself lashing out at
that, to show, like, don't put me in that category.
</P>
<P>
   ``I write my own lyrics. I write a lot of my own music. I do a
lot of my own production. I'm not trying to be like anybody else;
I'm trying to sound like nobody else. Nobody teaches me how to rap
or teaches me how to dance and tells me what to say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do my own (music), and they ... well, it's such a lack of
talent. It's so corny. It's sissy music, man.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world is not that happy.''
</P>
<P>
   (Gary Graff is a Detroit-based music journalist.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: For further information on Eminem consult the official web
site at www.eminem.com. And check out The New York Times Syndicate
Web site at http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on
StarBeat and other features. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ------------------------------------------------- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NONSUBSCRIBERS: To publish a ``separate-buy'' feature article,
