<HEADER>
A0426 &Cx1f; tab-z
u e BC-BABYBLUES-SWEENEY-STA     09-04 1343
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BABYBLUES-SWEENEY-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUNNY JULIA SWEENEY: FINDING COMEDY IN TRAGEDY
</HEADLINE>
  (Includes a color photo of Wanda (voice of Julia Sweeney) and her
family in the TV cartoon show, ``Baby Blues.'') 
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's STARBEAT feature service. For more
information about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _
or becoming a client of STARBEAT _ contact one of the New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the
text.) 
 By JEANNE WOLF 
 c.2000 Jeanne Wolf 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Julia Sweeney is best known as that overweight, bespectacled and
distinctly androgynous person named Pat, whom she played on
``Saturday Night Live'' and brought to the big screen in ``It's
Pat.''
</P>
<P>
   But there's nothing of the real Sweeney in Pat or most of the
other characters she's created ... until now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've finally gotten to use my real voice in a TV show,''
Sweeney says, sounding just like herself as Wanda on ``Baby
Blues,'' the new cartoon series that airs Friday nights on the WB
channel.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney was already a fan of the popular nationally-syndicated
comic strip on which ``Baby Blues'' is based. ``All my girlfriends
who are married and have babies kept telling me about it,'' she
says. ``I started reading it, never thinking it would be a cartoon
series. I thought it was very sharp and funny. Actually, our TV
version is darker and edgier. It doesn't focus as much on moms and
kids.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Baby Blues,'' Wanda (voiced by Sweeney) experiences the ups
and downs of life in suburbia along with her husband Darryl (voiced
by Mike O'Malley) and their new baby, Zoe. The young parents face
challenges from the dysfunctional family next door and Zoe's
terminally hip baby sitter, Bizzy, who is a magnet for bad boys.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the thirty-something Sweeney is still single, she's
had no trouble relating to Wanda's daily struggle to keep her own
identity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured I would react pretty much the same way Wanda does
after she quits her job and decides to be a housewife,'' she says.
``There's a lot of frustration in being a suburban wife and mother.
You want to be the best but it makes you crazy half the time. Wanda
is looking for less responsibility and more time for herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there is one big difference between Wanda and me,'' she
continues. ``Wanda says things to her husband like, `You may as
well chain me to the couch and force me to watch cooking shows,'
because she doesn't get a kick out of being in the kitchen. I
actually love to cook and I'm a big fan of The Food Network,
especially `Hot off the Grill with Bobby Flay,' and `East Meets
West with Ming Tsai.' In the last year I've gone to cooking school
in Mexico and Thailand.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooking, along with traveling, are a reflection of Sweeney's
determination to enjoy life after a devastating couple of years.
Her brother, Michael, died of non-Hodgkin's lymphoma and she was
diagnosed with cervical cancer, which is now in remission. Sweeney
brought Michael to her home and cared for him, with the help of her
parents, during his last months.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney's solution to the anger and frustration she was feeling
was to develop a comedy act based on her experience. ``God Said,
`Ha!''' played in Los Angeles and briefly on Broadway before she
made a movie version with the help of director Quentin Tarantino.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of me resists saying that laughter has the power to
heal,'' she says reflectively, ``because I don't want to think of
`God Said, `Ha!'' as some sort of good medicine. But I do think it
can be healing to find comedy in tragedy. When I discovered that I
could make audiences laugh about what I was going through, it was a
great release for me.''
</P>
<P>
   What pleases Sweeney is that ``God Said, `Ha!''' and ``Baby
Blues,'' while radically different in form, style and content, both
push the envelope of what's funny.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it when the audience gets a little nervous and wonders
whether they should laugh or not,'' she says. ``I feel my
experience in life has often been not knowing whether I should be
crying or laughing. I don't like to always make it clear whether
I'm telling a joke or not.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing I hate about a lot of comedy,'' she continues, ``is
that it tries so hard to be obvious about what's funny. It's like
here's the punch line _ and here's laugh track to cue you to know
it's a gag. I've always liked darker humor like you used to see on
`Mash.' It's horrifying and funny at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, while Sweeney has earned raves for her original
approach to humor, she didn't grow up thinking she was funny. ``I
think I did get voted `the most comedic girl' when I was in the
eighth grade,'' she remembers, ``but there was sort of a dearth of
comedy in our school anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney attended Catholic schools in her hometown of Spokane,
Wash., and went on to major in economics at the University of
Washington. ``When I went to college I was really interested in
history,'' she recalls, ``but my mother was having a fit because
she'd thought I'd end up being a waitress who'd read history books
on her break. She kept saying, `Business! That's the thing.' So I
took economics.''
</P>
<P>
   After graduation, Sweeney headed for Hollywood but not to
perform. She landed a job in the accounting department of Columbia
Pictures. ``Actually, there are a lot of very funny people in
accounting,'' she says. ``But I didn't adjust very well. There was
something wrong. I knew I could be a good accountant but never a
great accountant. After I got made manager of my department, I
thought, `That's it. You'll be a manager for the rest of your
life.'
</P>
<P>
   For about six months I would drive to work crying the whole way.
Then, one day, I read a review of The Groundlings comedy group and
it said they teach classes to nonprofessionals. I thought, `I want
to go.' And after the first class, it felt so right I could hardly
stand it. My whole life changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney admits she had one more barrier to overcome. ``I was 25
and I didn't have that classic skinny ingenue look,'' she says. ``I
think part of (thumbing my nose) to Hollywood was making myself
into Pat when I started at the Groundlings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I should say this to a therapist. It was like, `I might
not measure up in the pretty department but I'm going to show you
how funny I can be looking really ugly.' So I put on a 400-pound
fat suit and a wig and drew pimples on my face. After that, I felt
a lot better about myself!''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever lies ahead for Sweeney personally or professionally,
she doesn't deny that the trauma she made fun of in ``God Said,
`Ha!''' has changed her forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``It deepens you as person,'' she says. ``I want to work on more
important things. Life is too short after you've had cancer to do
something that you don't care about. I'd rather reduce my lifestyle
than do something that leaves me cringing inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I'm so happy about `Baby Blues' because I love the
writers, I love the cast and we're doing something good.''
</P>
<P>
   (Jeanne Wolf is a Los Angeles-based free-lance writer.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: For further information on the TV cartoon show ``Baby
Blues,'' consult the official web site at www.babyblues.com. And
check out The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL;
</P>
