</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALMOST-FAMOUS-CAMERON-CROWE-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CROSSING THE THRESHOLD FROM CHILDHOOD TO THE ROCK WORLD
</HEADLINE>
  (Includes a color photo of Cameron Crowe on the set of the movie,
``Almost Famous.'') 
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's STARBEAT feature service. For more
information about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _
or becoming a client of STARBEAT _ contact one of the New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the
text.) 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN 
 c.2000 Cindy Pearlman 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   His best friend was always music, and at many times in his life,
it was his only companion.
</P>
<P>
   The music didn't judge Cameron Crowe, or care that he was shy
and chubby, or had zits, or worse yet that his mother let him skip
two grades, which made the rest of the kids think he was a geek.
</P>
<P>
   Girls ignored him, boys taunted him. So, after school Crowe used
to sit alone in his room with his true, cool friends. The Allman
Brothers, Yes and Black Sabbath understood his pain.
</P>
<P>
   Soon he felt compelled to write about music. At age 15, he sold
his reviews to Creem Magazine and local San Diego rags who paid him
next to nothing for his opinions. A good story brought in a
whopping $10. But the money didn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   Then Rolling Stone told the kid he was good enough to go on the
road and write stories for them.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, he was the coolest guy in town.
</P>
<P>
   Now, at 43, he is one of the hottest and hippest directors in
Hollywood. His credits include ``Jerry Maguire'' (1996), ``Say
Anything'' (1989) and ``Fast Times at Ridgemont High'' (1982).
</P>
<P>
   The former geek, who is married to rock legend Nancy Wilson of
Heart, is getting the last laugh.
</P>
<P>
   His new film ``Almost Famous'' debuts on Sept. 22. ``I think
this is 90 percent my own story,'' Crowe admits.
</P>
<P>
   When he started out as a music reporter, it wasn't all sex,
drugs and rock 'n' roll.
</P>
<P>
   ``For my first assignment for Rolling Stone, I stood there
begging the guys by the backstage door at the San Diego Sports
Arena to let me in,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Crowe wore them down and he was allowed to cross the
threshold from childhood to the rock world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went wild that night. I talked to everyone backstage
including the catering people,'' Crowe recalls, laughing. ``I think
that's the night the addiction set in because I was covering the
Allman Brothers and they were a very dark, inviting situation.
Their bass player had just died. They had a press blackout going
on. And there was this intense feeling of family and togetherness.
</P>
<P>
   ``For them, it was `us against the world,''' Crowe says. ``And
to puncture that was an amazing feeling. I was allowed to go from
city to city in this cocoon ... ''
</P>
<P>
   The strong memories became the seed for a movie Crowe had wanted
to make for a decade. But he kept getting sidetracked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to do a rock movie first, but then `Say Anything'
took hold. Afterwards, I felt `Singles' (1992) was the right thing
to do,'' Crowe says.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, in retrospect, I'm glad I waited,'' he says. ``I think
the success of `Jerry Maguire' gave me the opportunity and the
budget to do this one the right way. I look back and shudder at the
thought that `Almost Famous' could have been my first film done on
the cheap with bad actors because no one would have trusted me back
then.''
</P>
<P>
   Crowe knew from the start that the subject matter was a bit
complicated. Real life rockers and their entourages were guaranteed
to ask if they were depicted in any way in the film. But Crowe
explains: ``It's not one band. It's a combination.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As a young guy on the road watching it, I couldn't believe how
complex and thrilling and dangerous this world could be ... ''
</P>
<P>
   Crowe didn't care if things got heated after his stories broke
in Rolling Stone. And occasionally, a peeved band would threaten
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny, but bands are never upset about the things you
think will upset them. I could write that someone's music was
horrible. But if I wrote that they were wearing an ugly shirt or
that their marriage had painfully dissolved, then they'd get
upset.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But I was not on the road to be friends with these bands. I
always felt I represented the fans. I was writing from the
standpoint of another normal person sitting at home in his room
wondering about this music,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Crowe grew up in San Diego with his mother who is a psychology
professor and family therapist. (His father died in 1989.)
</P>
<P>
   By age 15, Crowe was writing for Zoo World and Creem. The next
year, he met an editor from Rolling Stone who hired him to go on
the road with top bands. In 1975, when given their choice of
writers, Led Zeppelin picked ``the kid'' to do a cover story on
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still didn't feel cool,'' Crowe says, and smiles when asked
how a former geek got to marry a rock star.
</P>
<P>
   ``I met Nancy through riding in an elevator with her
then-boyfriend,'' he says. ``I was at a festival where Heart was
playing, but Nancy was very shy and protected by her people. Later,
two friends of mine attempted to set us up.'' Nervous about the
whole thing, he refused the date.
</P>
<P>
   ``Later, I ended up meeting her when I was looking for music for
`Fast Times at Ridgemont High.' I didn't find a song, but I did
find a woman who was unaffected and amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Crowe's career is also in the realm of amazing. His ``Jerry
Maguire'' grossed $154 million at the box office, and he is working
on reuniting with its star Tom Cruise, his favorite actor, for a
future project.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom was the first star who actively said to me, `I want to
play a character in one of your movies. I don't need the leading
man or golden haze around me. Just write something for me,''' Crowe
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before that, I had a hard time getting big name actors to do
my stuff,'' Crowe admits.
</P>
<P>
   Crowe says he is writing an untitled romance for Cruise to film
next year. Of course, one of his favorite tasks will come when the
script is penned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love choosing the music,'' he admits.
</P>
<P>
   He isn't upset about the sorry state of rock music these days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rock 'n' roll dies every year and then gets resurrected,'' he
says. ``Right now we're in a lull in a lot of ways. But I remember
feeling this way before Nirvana released `Smells Like Teen Spirit.'
And they re-energized everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel, somewhere in this country, some kid is in a garage and
about to change it all,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: For further information on Cameron Crowe, director of the
movie, ``Almost Famous'' consult the official web site at
www.almost-famous.com. And check out The New York Times Syndicate
Web site at http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on
StarBeat and other features. &QL;
</P>
