<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 11:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0428 &Cx1f; tab-z
u e BC-FANTASTICK-JOEL-GREY-     09-04 1256
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FANTASTICK-JOEL-GREY-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUGE TALENT _ AND FEAR _ KEEPS JOEL JUMPING
</HEADLINE>
  (A color photo of Joel Grey in the movie, ``The Fantasticks,'' is
available electronically. Call New York Times Syndicate photo
editor William Gonzalez at 800-972-3550 or 212-499-3355.) 
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's STARBEAT feature service. For more
information about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _
or becoming a client of STARBEAT _ contact one of the New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the
text.) 
 By IAN SPELLING 
 c.2000 Ian Spelling 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``It's a very odd career, isn't it?'' says Joel Grey, cracking
up even as he speaks the words.
</P>
<P>
   After all, it was 59 years ago that he made his stage debut in
``On Borrowed Time,'' 34 years since he won a Tony Award for
``Cabaret,'' 28 years since he won an Oscar for the film version of
``Cabaret'' and two years since he portrayed Joseph Goebbels in
``The Empty Mirror.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I'd known that, except for the technical preparation
one can do, the rest of one's career is up for grabs,'' says the
68-year-old, whose hair is as thin as his waist, but whose eyes and
smile still twinkle. ``You think you can control the elements of
the business and you think that if you do A, B and C, that D will
happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'd known that so much of A, B and C happens on its own, I
could have saved myself a lot of spinning. But I wouldn't change a
thing. The way my career is, it's the way it was supposed to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Grey flashes an impish grin.
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't mean I shouldn't have worked hard or been
diligent about the craft, but that I shouldn't have concerned
myself so much with planning and expectation,'' he says. ``You may
or may not be able to do that in other businesses, but it does not
apply at all for performers.''
</P>
<P>
   Grey fancies himself an actor who can sing and dance, one who
thrives on the stage, but also one who can acquit himself quite
nicely in front of a camera.
</P>
<P>
   His latest project, a big screen version of the ageless musical
``The Fantasticks,'' taps all of his talents.
</P>
<P>
   The film, which will open in limited release on Sept. 22,
follows the travails of young lovers Luisa (Jean Louisa Kelly) and
Matt (Joe McIntyre), whose relationship is almost ruined by the
machinations of El Gallo (Jonathan Morris), a traveling carnival's
magician. It seems Luisa's and Matt's fathers (Joel Grey and Brad
Sullivan, respectively) hired El Gallo to bring the lovers
together, but he instead tempts them to stray.
</P>
<P>
   Grey and company assembled in the desert near Tucson, Ariz.,
five years ago to make ``The Fantasticks.'' Michael Ritchie, the
director, revived the nearly extinct Cinemascope widescreen format
and shot several of the production numbers live. The film then
languished on a shelf at United Artists, as the studio contemplated
releasing it direct to video.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Francis Coppola, the famed ``Godfather'' director, a
friend of Ritchie's and a newly installed potentate on the United
Artists board of directors, came to the rescue. He, with Ritchie's
blessing, edited the film and fought for its theatrical release.
</P>
<P>
   ``The delay was awful for everybody involved,'' Grey says. ``The
filmmakers were so respectful and slavish, in a way, to the
original material because Tom Jones (book and lyrics) and Harvey
Schmidt (composer) were there and Michael collaborated so well with
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they thought they'd opened up the material and,
obviously, it hadn't been opened up enough. It wasn't made filmic
enough, according to the stories I heard from the studio. It's also
my understanding that Francis came in and said, `I think you missed
something here and I've maybe got some ideas about how to make it
better.'
</P>
<P>
   ``That Michael was open to that, I thought was great. Francis
cut out about 40 minutes, including several numbers, to focus more
on the story, and here we are. I really like it and I hope it finds
an audience.''
</P>
<P>
   After he wrapped ``The Fantasticks,'' Grey, who is Jewish and
was born Joel Katz, played Goebbels, the German Nazi minister of
propaganda, in the fascinating character study, ``The Empty
Mirror'' (1997).
</P>
<P>
   He also portrayed the Ghost of Christmas Past in a telemovie
version of the Charles Dickens classic, ``A Christmas Carol''
(1999), and returned to the Broadway stage last year for Brian
Friel's ``Give Me Your Answer, Do.'' He made time, too, to tackle a
supporting role in ``Dancer in the Dark,'' the new film from
director Lars von Trier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dancer,'' won the Palm D'Or at the 2000 Cannes Film Festival
and will kick off the New York Film Festival in September before
opening wider in October. It stars the Icelandic singer Bjork as
Selma, a down-on-her-luck single mother. Only her fantasies about
Hollywood musicals keep Selma sane as she goes blind, fears for her
son's vision, and is put on trial for stealing a neighbor's money.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the quirkiest, most compelling movies in a long
time,'' Grey says. ``I play a character who is talked about in the
movie and then finally appears.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a witness in a trial. I make my appearance, and then I do
a number with Bjork. Wait until you see this movie. I know people,
including a great director, who hate it, and I know other people,
including another great director, who think it's a masterpiece.''
</P>
<P>
   Grey is grinning from ear to ear as he says this. It's obvious
that he still loves the game, that he gets a kick out of mixing it
up. Again, just look a this career: films, theater and television;
comedy, drama and musicals; and starring roles, character bits and
cameos.
</P>
<P>
   He's a man with both a history and a future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I follow my intuition and 99 percent of the time I make the
right decision,'' says the actor, who makes a cameo appearance in
``Armistead Maupin's Further Tales from the City,'' a miniseries
that will air later this fall on Showtime. ``It's almost always
about the character, what I can learn from doing it, and what the
character can contribute to the film or the play.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I get to a place where I think, `I can't do this,' I know I
have to do it. It's scary, but that's what makes me jump. It
happened with `Cabaret.'''
</P>
<P>
   It also happened with ``The Music of Chance'` (1993) and ``Give
Me Your Answer, Do,'' he admits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happened with all the plays and movies that ever won me any
kind of recognition. And that fear of `I can't do this,' is what
keeps me jumping even now.''
</P>
<P>
   (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: For further information on Joel Grey in ``The Fantasticks,'
consult the official web site at www.TheFantasticks.com. And check
out The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ------------------------------------------------- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NONSUBSCRIBERS: To publish a ``separate-buy'' feature article,
it must be purchased. Please contact one of these sales
representatives:
</P>
<P>
   --U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   --Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
