   OPED/EDITORIAL
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Most all of the women I know
are single and have been for a long time. My three best friends and
I have been non-cohabiters since way before we started seriously
eyeballing the wrinkle-vanishing creams on drugstore shelves _ a
grand total of 78 years for the four of us. Do we like our single
state? Sometimes. Would we rather be married? Occasionally. Do we
think we'll ever marry again? Probably not. Why? We're not really
sure, but it's not because we haven't been asked. Not often, but
asked. (Schuett, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LANE-COLUMN _ DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Louisiana was the next state
after Florida to issue a ``Choose life'' license plate and the
first state to have a court stop plate sales. If the court's
reasoning stands, the 31-flavor specialty plate business of a lot
of states could be a thing of the past. The U.S. district court
last week made a reasonable point: When states play politics with
license plates, they have to let everyone have his say. (Lane,
Daytona Beach News-Journal) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   E-BUSINESS _ A daily column featuring the most useful Web sites
and live online events affecting Business readers. (Seward, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
