<P>
   BIZMAGS _ A rundown of the week's financial press. (Walker,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   AFLAC-ADS _ Love him or hate him, AFLAC's talking duck is
proving hard to ignore. You probably know the critter: A white duck
that insistently quacks ``AFLAC'' in commercials about the
Columbus-based supplemental health insurer. The campaign kicked off
during CNN's New Year's Eve coverage last year, and AFLAC has been
stunned by the response. (Leith, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   ANTI-ATLANTA _ The SUV-driving mayor of Jacksonville wants
voters to approve a sales-tax referendum today to combat sprawl.
His pitch: ``There's a name for a city that doesn't plan for its
future: Atlanta.'' It's a common approach throughout the South _
Atlanta bashing. Whether it's a referendum, as in Jacksonville, or
an election like last year's mayor's race in Nashville, Atlanta is
a favorite regional punching bag. (Chapman, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   DELTA-VOTE _ ATLANTA - Ramp workers this week will be getting
union election ballots _ again. The National Mediation Board is
mailing out ballots for a rerun of last spring's election in which
rampers voted against representation by the Transport Workers
Union. The NMB later ruled campaign violations by Delta and
procedural glitches warranted a new election. (Staff, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
