<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 14:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0485 &Cx1f; tad-z
r c BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A0905-COX     09-04 1521
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A0905-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Q: Will you please find the full name of the
mother of director Ron Howard? Ron gave her the role of the
astronaut's mother in ``Apollo 13.'' Did she go to college in
Oklahoma and has she been in other movies?
</P>
<P>
   _ F. Wilson
</P>
<P>
   A: Jean Speegle Howard played Jim Lovell's mother, who is crazed
by the broken TV set in her nursing home. Didn't they know the
mission coverage was being televised? Born in 1928, Speegle
appeared in several films, including ``Cocoon'' and ``The Night
Caller.'' No word on her Oklahoma roots, but Ron was born in
Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   Q: About two years ago, there was a class action suit against
the manufacturers of Synthroid. Since I signed up for the claim, we
moved and I cannot locate the paperwork to send them a new address.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cyndi Cavalier
</P>
<P>
   A: Knoll Pharmaceutical Co. received final approval of the
litigation settlement in August. More than 778,000 consumers will
receive $111 each if they began taking Synthroid, a thyroid disease
treatment, before January 1995; about $74 each after that date.
Called into question was the product's marketing, not its safety.
</P>
<P>
   Contact the Consumer's Council line at Allan Kanner &AMP;
Associates, (800) 331-1546, or by e-mail
a.kanner(at)kanner-law.com.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am looking for mustache wax. I have a handlebar mustache.
</P>
<P>
   _ D.H. Frost
</P>
<P>
   A: Barber and beauty supply companies stock it (less than $3 a
tube) _ black, blond, brown, neutral and chestnut. The longest
mustache on record, according to the Guinness Book of Records, grew
on the top lip of Kalyan Ramji Sain of India. Total span? 11 feet,
11 inches. Snidely Whiplash would be green. Q: Can you get the
address for Arnold Schwarzenegger? I want to get in touch with him
because of an article that he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   _ Willard C. Fales
</P>
<P>
   A: Write to Mr. Maria Shriver in care of Robert Stein, William
Morris Agency, 151 El Camino Drive, Beverly Hills, Calif. 90212 or
visit www.schwarzenegger.com. Q: I recently mailed letters to some
retired teachers. When I inquired about postage stamps honoring
school teachers, I was told that there weren't any. Could this
possibly be true since there seems to be a commemorative stamp for
about everything else?
</P>
<P>
   _ Jonnie Bumpas
</P>
<P>
   A: In a way, yes. ``Currently, we have no stamps honoring school
teachers,'' reports Postal System spokeswoman Barbara Pokorny. A
32-cent commemoratsive stamp featuring a child and adult reading
together, ``Helping Children Learn'' was issued in 1997. Educators
such as Johns Hopkins, Father Flanagan and Mary Lyon have been
honored in the past on ``definitive'' stamps ($1, 4 cents and 2
cents respectively). Still available, a ``definitive'' is a
regular-issue stamp sold over long periods of time. Have an idea
for a stamp? Subjects for stamps should be submitted at least three
years in advance of the proposed issue date to allow sufficient
time for consideration and, if approved, design and production.
Send submissions to: Citizens' Stamp Advisory Committee, c/o Stamp
Management, U. S. Postal Service, 475 L'Enfant Plaza S.W., Room
4474E , Washington, D.C. 20260-2437.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Last year, a friend's fiancee attended a wedding in which the
bride played Wagner's ``Bridal Chorus'' on her accordion as she
marched up the aisle. My friend's fiancee has decided she wants to
do the same thing. Is this considered taboo at a wedding, or at
least inappropriate?
</P>
<P>
   If not, should the accordion and the bride's gown be
color-coordinated? Where should she have the bridal bouquet? If her
father accompanies her down the aisle, what should he do, because
both of the bride's hands and arms will be busy moving as she plays
her squeeze box?
</P>
<P>
   _ Charles E.
</P>
<P>
   A: Anything goes at weddings _ this would not be my choice, but
if the bride and groom agree, they can do somersaults up the aisle
if they want. It is their wedding. The black-and-white accordion
fits in color-wise. Dad should be next to or trailing the bride,
depending on the width of the aisle. The bouquet can be waiting for
her at the altar. Q: I'd really like to get my hands on a jacket
like the one James Dean wears in ``Rebel Without a Cause.'' Any
suggestions?
</P>
<P>
   _ R.M.
</P>
<P>
   A: The Fairmount Historical Museum in James Dean's Indiana
hometown sells Dean memorabilia (alarm clock, shot glasses, etc.).
The bright red polyester/cotton blend jacket similar to the one he
wore over the signature white T-shirt unfortunately has ``James
Dean, Fairmount, Indiana'' embroidered on the front left side ($35
plus tax, S&AMP;H). To order call (765) 948-4555 or visit
www.jamesdeanartifacts.com. Q: Large red harvester ants are eating
all leaves off a tree and have already killed several trees. I have
been told that a bait is made to kill them, but I cannot find it.
Can you?
</P>
<P>
   _ John P.
</P>
<P>
   A: Sorry. Currently an effective bait is not available to the
general public.
</P>
<P>
   The muncher is the Texas leaf cutting ant (Atta texana) also
known as the town ant, cut ant and night ant.
</P>
<P>
   Harvester ants eat seeds and scavenge for food, but they do not
dine on leaves, according to Texas A&AMP;M entomologist John Jackman.
The leaves that leaf-cutting ants strip from green trees and shrubs
are not eaten, but rather taken back to nests and used to raise a
fungus garden (yum). Living in colonies that may exceed 2 million,
these ants feast on this garden growth.
</P>
<P>
   Jackman notes Volcano Leaf Cutter Ant Bait is available, but
only for use in pine forests, through suppliers in East Texas such
as Red River Specialties.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on this ant and other Texas insects, visit
http://insects.tamu.edu. Q: How come the president and vice
president get to use government planes for other than government
business? They showed the vice president with his whole clan _
wife, children and running mate _ arriving in Minnesota, as the
caption under the photo stated, aboard Air Force II for a campaign
stop. This was clearly not government business. The use of the
planes cost the taxpayers a lot of money that I can't justify.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tom Gothard
</P>
<P>
   A: Candidate Gore is still Vice President Gore.
</P>
<P>
   According to Dan Pfeiffer of the Gore/Lieberman campaign: ``The
vice president as both vice president and candidate requires
security. That is why he travels on Air Force II. The campaign pays
for all political expenses accrued when he is on the campaign
trail.'' No harm. No foul. No taxpayer dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have noticed through the years many women wear their
wedding rings on the right hand. Is this a tradition for widows or
divorcees?
</P>
<P>
   _ D.A.R.
</P>
<P>
   A: In some countries (Spain for example) wedding rings are worn
on the right hand by everyone. Since tradition in the United States
dictates wedding rings are worn on the left hand, moving the rings
to the right is significant. Divorcees often do this (if they have
not sold or reset the stones). Widows, on the other hand, often
continue to wear wedding rings on the left hand.
</P>
<P>
   Moving it to the right hand signals availability.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We enjoy the many exotic pleasures of a septic system. We are
anxious to learn how to clear shower drains of accumulated goop
while still protecting the delicate balance of bacteria in the
septic tank.
</P>
<P>
   Baking soda or vinegar keeps a drain smelling clean, etc., but
does not clear accumulated debris. Our plumber suggests only
occasional snaking by a professional will work. Is there any other
way?
</P>
<P>
   _ C.S.
</P>
<P>
   A: If the sink is clogged, experienced plumber Bill Kamen of
Superior Septic and Plumbing advises customers to use Liquid
Plumber before giving him a call. This may eliminate the clog. Then
restore the bacteria fighters in the system with a yeast treatment
(one package in one small drain line in each bathroom _ not the
toilet) two or three days later. On a regular basis (once a month)
this yeast treatment (same yeast used to make bread) works well.
The yeast attaches to the grease and retards build up.
</P>
<P>
   No yeast? Use 1/2 cup beer or buttermilk.
</P>
<P>
   UPSHOT/UPDATE/UPROAR:
</P>
<P>
   Although the New York legislature was the first to introduce a
bill recognizing Labor Day, Oregon was the first state to enact
such a law (February 1887). Want to celebrate the achievement of
workers more than once a year? Visit Australia Oct. 7 for Labour
Day and France, Argentina or Egypt for the May 1 celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Heard the one about the mysterious Klingerman virus or the Costa
Rican bananas causing necrotizing fasciitis? Both are false
Internet rumors that the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention
wants to quash. Before you panic or pass on unfounded stories,
check out www.cdc.gov/hoaxrumors.htm to get the lowdown on the
fabled banana bacterium or a mythical viral infection contracted by
those receiving a mysterious package marked ``A Gift to You from
the Klingerman Foundation.''
</P>
<P>
   Contact Jane Greig at P.O. Box 670, Austin, TX 78767; (512)
445-3697; e-mail jgreig(at)statesman.com or fax (512) 445-3968.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
