r f BC-NETWATCHER0905-COX     09-04 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWATCHER0905-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    VH1.com, MTV.com worth the wait _ plus, they're legal
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In some twisted way, we all have Napster to thank for
a new spate of music Web sites from a variety of major media
companies.
</P>
<P>
   While Napster, a peer-to-peer music file sharing program, may
have raised many legitimate questions regarding copyrights and fair
use of music on the Net, the 20 million-plus user base has shown
there is an appetite for online music, news and concert information
from the tiniest teenybopper to the baldest boomer.
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully, this interesting bit of information was not lost on
MTV and VH1, two of the most popular music brands online or
anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   Not too long ago we were bashing MTV for being five minutes late
to the party when it came to having a coherent Web strategy, and up
until very, very recently, that's been true. But somewhere at MTV,
the interactive light bulb finally went on. In fact, enough light
bulbs seem to have gone on over at MTV and VH1 to light up Times
Square, site of the company's corporate headquarters. The new VH1
Web site and the new site for MTV's white-hot hit ``Total Request
Live'' make listening to online music legally fun again.
</P>
<P>
   The new VH1 Web site (www.VH1.com) is a special treat for music
lovers of all ages _ and especially for that strange group in the
middle recently dubbed ``aging GenXers'' by Rolling Stone magazine.
(Memo to Douglas Coupland, author of the book that gave this group
its moniker: Where's our midlife crisis novel? It's clearly
overdue.)
</P>
<P>
   These aging GenXers, who range in age from about 25 to 39, have
been a forgotten group when it comes to online music, yet we are
out there in great numbers. The same Rolling Stone article that
declared Xers officially over the hill also complained they are
``clogging up'' Napster, presumably with all those REM, Talking
Heads, Barenaked Ladies and Sonic Youth files.
</P>
<P>
   So it's especially nice that VH1 has decided to target the GenX
demographic with its new Web site. Go directly to the ``Sound and
Vision,'' and you'll be treated to a variety of audio and video
clips from artists you've heard of (Madonna, the Clash and, yes,
even Spinal Tap) and a few you may have heard of (Shelby Lynne,
Kenny Wayne Shepard, Julianna Hatfield).
</P>
<P>
   There are also picks of the day from spoken-word artists and
comedy albums. The news section features interviews and articles on
artists as diverse as Brit Pop sensations Elastica to a new book
about John Lennon. VH1.com is a well-edited collection of new and
familiar music that should appeal to music lovers who want to
expand their horizons but also keep up with old favorites.
</P>
<P>
   While aging Xers clog up VH1.com, younger fans will want to
bookmark MTV's new site, which is miles ahead of anything they've
tried to do in the past. MTV.com may be able to take home the
trophy for most unsuccessful redesigns, but this time it looks like
they just about got it right.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the site would be pretty close to perfect if it were
easier to get to the extensive Web site for ``Total Request Live.''
For now, fans of this 21st century of ``American Bandstand'' will
have to head over to the pull-down menu for ``shows'' and click on
``TRL.'' But it's worth the journey.
</P>
<P>
   MTV makes it easy for fans to vote for their favorite videos and
possibly win a trip for you and a friend to go to a ``TRL'' taping
in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly as popular as the videos is show host Carson Daly. For
those of you unfamiliar with the show, Daly is well on his way to
becoming this generation's hipper, cuter and just as overexposed
version of Dick Clark.
</P>
<P>
   Fans can check out ``Carson's Corner'' and read his bio, or
click on a variety of pictures that will make excellent wallpaper
on any teen's computer monitor. And if pictures are your thing,
check out the ``TRL'' photo booth with new pictures of frequent
guests of the show including Jennifer Lopez, Method Man, Alanis
Morisette and Beck. The 'N Sync photos are pretty cute, too.
</P>
<P>
   The designers of ``Total Request Live'' also know their viewers
on and offline like to interact with the celebrities and rock stars
on the show as well as pick their favorite videos. There are plenty
of opportunities to do that here, from chat rooms to a place to ask
questions about MTV and ``TRL'' that are answered in an FAQ
section.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, if you'd like to download music from the MTV site,
you need to go to the ``Xtra section'' _ again more work than we'd
like. The selection is short but worth it, if you're into new
music.
</P>
<P>
   The only complaint we have with VH1.com and MTV.com is that the
navigation of each site is kind of clunky, but the content you'll
find here is worth the minor inconvenience.
</P>
<P>
   What vaudeville comic Will Rogers once said about New England
weather also seems to apply to the Web sites from MTV and VH1: ``If
you don't like it, just wait a minute.'' For music fans, these two
sites were definitely worth the wait.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
