<SLUG> BC-TECH-GAMEZONE0905-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `WinBack' not a winner for long
 &HT;    By Vox Day
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ ``Operation WinBack'' starts off with a bang. The
introductory graphics are excellent, and despite a largely
fictional setting, the story line promises a degree of realism that
offers more in common with ``Rainbow Six'' than ``Tomb Raider.''
</P>
<P>
   Realism is clearly a focus of this third-person action game,
which involves a crack anti-terrorism team going into action
against a well-organized terrorist force that has seized control of
a strategic weapons satellite.
</P>
<P>
   So far, so good, although the contrived acronym of the
anti-terrorism team, (Strategic Covert Action Team, or SCAT), is
the first hint that things may not turn out as well as they
promise.
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, within minutes of entering the actual game action,
one realizes that ``WinBack'' has all the entertainment value of
filing paperwork.
</P>
<P>
   While the graphics are actually quite nice, if leaning toward
the gritty realism end of the spectrum, both the game controls and
the game action are poorly conceived. Despite the third-person
interface, the action is conceptually most similar to that of
``Virtua Cop'' on the Sega Saturn. In ``WinBack,'' the agent makes
his way through an apparently outside environment that is actually
a bidirectional maze composed by artfully placing various objects
in places that will constrain the movement possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   This is done in a fairly subtle manner and is not bothersome.
The occasional semi-trailer laid adroitly askew creates a nice bit
of ambience in addition to constraining your freedom of movement.
However, the camera is constantly moving almost perfectly out of
sync with your own movements, thus frequently leaving you exposed
in the enemy's line of sight while you are staring at a concrete
wall 90 degrees away from where the incoming fire is coming.
</P>
<P>
   The firing action is problematic, too. It's apparently not
possible to fire over open sights, but basic sighting is required
through the laser sight first, so firing a shot is a two-step
operation. This isn't too clumsy by itself and actually is a more
accurate simulation of a real handgun-firing process, but when
combined with the movement-camera confusion, leads to a tremendous
amount of frustration.
</P>
<P>
   Since the game is linear, with the same enemies in the same
places every time, these challenges can be surmounted by
repetition, but playing an action game by rote is almost
counterproductive. At the end of the day, I say just bag the
operation and let the Crying Lions have the wretched satellite.
</P>
<P>
   `OPERATION WINBACK'
</P>
<P>
   Format: Nintendo 64
</P>
<P>
   Publisher: Koei
</P>
<P>
   Price: $49.99
</P>
<P>
   Ages: 7+
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 1.5 out of 5
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
