r f BC-TECH-SAVVY0905-COX     09-04 0486
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-SAVVY0905-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For ultimate protection, unplug cable
 &HT;    By Sue Cleere and Jacki Rudd
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   Dear Sue and Jacki:
</P>
<P>
   Is turning off my netsharing on my cable modem protection enough
for my computer files? I also have a password-protected
screensaver. Is that protection enough against cable modem hackers?
</P>
<P>
   _ Gerry Dupuis, Decatur, GA
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: Let's reiterate a few things from an earlier TechSavvy
column. There are pitfalls associated with using a cable modem. The
ultimate way to protect yourself is to unplug the cable from the
back of your PC when you don't need to surf the Web. Another layer
of protection is to turn off File and Print Sharing in the Network
Control Panel on the PC, or FileSharing on the Macintosh, when
you're cruising.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: But the best protection is a firewall. A firewall controls
traffic between your computer and the Internet and alerts you to
intruders. There is protection for Mac and PC. PC'ers can go to
www.networkice.com for BlackICE Defender and Mac'ers to
www.opendoor.com for DoorStop.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: While screensavers can prevent outsiders from accessing
your computer when they walk up to it, they don't protect you from
an open cable modem system.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: Hackers would access your computer as if it were a
directory on their computer. They look for an unprotected directory
and ``walk'' right in. Hackers can get their mitts on your files
and do a lot of damage.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Sue and Jacki:
</P>
<P>
   Where's a good place to get a rebuilt laptop? Also, I was
looking for a toast for a 60th birthday bash. Where can I find this
on the Internet?
</P>
<P>
   _ Bill Ayton
</P>
<P>
   Sue: You take the cake, Bill. Not sure anyone has asked
TechSavvy a question like this. Let's talk used equipment first.
When buying a pre-owned car, you always take a chance if you don't
know what road it's been down. The same goes for computers. Having
said that, computer resellers are worth exploring.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: Surf to IBM's Refurbished PC Warehouse
(commerce-03.www.ibm.com). The wares had a previous life as leased
computers. Mac loyalists can cruise to MacResQ (www.macresq.com/)
or Mac of all Trades (www
</P>
<P>
   .macofalltrades.com/). Of course, you also can find PC and Mac
laptops on eBay (ebay.com/). Keep your eye out for warranty
options.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: After price-checking used models, investigate new
equipment, too. I'd compare and contrast before ruling out
anything.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: Now, about that perfect toast for the birthday bash.
We're hip on tapping the power of the Web for anything and
everything, so zip over to
zinnia.umfacad.maine.edu/(tilde)donaghue/toasts.html. There's bound
to be something to your liking.
</P>
<P>
   Sue Cleere and Jacki Rudd write for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution. E-mail questions to techsavvy(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
