<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-TOOLS0905-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Long-distance mouse may solve DVD woe
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A reader has sent in a question dealing with a
peripheral matter on digital photography and in the process has
provided me with a lot more information than, I fear, I will be
able to give him.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Taylor describes himself as a ``high amateur''
photographer who once used a professional 35mm single-lens reflex
camera with multiple lenses. We all know people like him _ you look
at their pictures and say, ``Wow, you ought to be a professional.''
They smile and remark that they've already got enough problems,
thanks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have now switched entirely to digital photography,'' Taylor
writes, ``and have used it exclusively on a three-week trip to
Scandinavia and two weeks in the Canadian Rockies. The pictures are
beautiful, and I was able to use my CD writer to make CDs to share
with many of my fellow travelers.''
</P>
<P>
   That's also typical of these ``high amateur'' photographers _
they're unusually thoughtful and unsparing with their talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I use ACDSee to view these and it is quite simple, you just
use the mouse wheel to scroll between pictures without having to
load each one. It also does a small amount of editing (such as
giving the pictures names).
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a Kodak DC265 Camera, and it is great. The Sony
Mavica's pictures are not very good quality, in my opinion. I tried
one out but took it back after the trial. Incidentally, many stores
will allow you to try a camera for 30 days. I tried three different
ones before settling on my first Kodak, and I would encourage
people to do this to find the right one.''
</P>
<P>
   He mentions the Mavica because we discussed that line a few
weeks back. The Mavicas store their images on floppies instead of
memory sticks, a nice idea, but the images made with them do not
compare well with other cameras in the same price range.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as prints go, I have a HP Photosmart P1100 Printer, and
the picture quality is as good as those from my 35 mm camera. They
do 8x10 pictures of a quality that is outstanding when done on a
photo-quality paper, and 5x7s on regular paper are better than what
I was getting from my old Canon.
</P>
<P>
   ``My son and his wife come for Christmas, I take pictures, I
print them off and that afternoon, when they go to her mother's,
they have the pictures of our Christmas to share with her.''
</P>
<P>
   ``However, it's hard to get the family around a 19-inch computer
screen. Many of the newer DVD players say they will play Video CDs,
but as far as I can tell these are only for moving pictures
formats. Is there a DVD Player that will play JPEGs?''
</P>
<P>
   I don't know of one, but then I know next to nothing about DVD
players made exclusively for plugging into televisions. However, a
19-inch screen ought to be, in theory at least, nicely viewable
from a few feet away.
</P>
<P>
   Several firms, I believe, make a long-distance cordless mouse,
effective from clear across the room. Perhaps this would alleviate
your problem if not solve it, and many thanks for all the
information.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
