<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNOBUDDY0905-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    This kit should help you survive a storm power outage
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For a few days last winter, my cast iron Buck Stove
was the heighth of working technology at my house.
</P>
<P>
   My computer had been reduced to an expensive paperweight. The
big screen TV made a nice perch for Buddy my Maine Coon cat. All
six channels of the sound system were deadly quiet.
</P>
<P>
   All of this because an ice storm knocked out power at my house
for several days.
</P>
<P>
   At many homes, the computers were in better shape than the
people. Laptop computers clicked along on battery power.
Uninterruptable power supplies helped desktop machines shut down
gracefully.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, most of us humans were cold because the heat was out,
bored because there was no light to read by and no music to listen
to.
</P>
<P>
   I had about $8,000 worth of electronics gear _ computers, ham
radios, test equipment, audio stuff, television and DVD _ but I
didn't own a working flashlight.
</P>
<P>
   All that came to mind last week while I was in a fireplace store
buying replacement glass for the Buck Stove. After stoking it white
hot for the three days I had no power, the heat had became too
much, even for the special tempered glass.
</P>
<P>
   The glass was expensive, but that stove earned my eternal
admiration. It kept a three-story house above the freezing mark and
became the only way I had of cooking. I'd put an iron skillet on
the metal top and cook everything from bacon and eggs to shrimp
scampi.
</P>
<P>
   While in the fireplace store waiting to see how much I'd be
overcharged for the glass, I decided to create a survival kit.
After all, the power goes out at my house two or three times a
year. All the gadgets in the world are useless if your hands are
frozen and your stomach is empty. Besides, it's hard to find that
fancy MP3 player in the dark.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, you can divide up the kit into these categories:
</P>
<P>
   Light: At a minimum you need one flashlight for every family
member. But if you've ever tried to read or prepare a meal by the
light of a flashlight, you'll see why I also bought a small,
battery-powered fluorescent lantern. It cost just over $20 and
provides a broad, soft light. Just to be safe, add three or four
large candles.
</P>
<P>
   Communication: Generally speaking, telephone service is more
reliable than electrical service. And many of you already have a
cellular phone. It's a good idea _ in times when the weather is
dicey _ to keep the battery fully charged. And if you don't have a
battery-powered radio, an inexpensive one is a great addition.
Besides providing news about power outages and the weather, it may
end up being your only source of entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Cooking: If you have a gas range, you can skip this category. I
don't, so I picked up a butane camp stove for $32. While charcoal
and propane outdoor grills are helpful, the camp stove is a lot
less unwieldy. Just remember that you should never use an outdoor
grill (especially a charcoal one) inside _ hunger is preferable to
carbon monoxide poisioning.
</P>
<P>
   Heating: A fireplace is great. But if you really want to breeze
through a power outage, consider an electric generator. While
you'll find them for as little as $300, you'll probably end up
spending at least twice that. It won't produce enough power to
handle all your electrical needs, but it will keep the electrical
blower on your gas furnace powered up and will handle a few other
lights and appliances. Make sure that you have an electrician
install the circuitry needed to hook the generator into your
household wiring. He'll install a switch that isolates the current
from the generator from outside power lines. Otherwise, your
generator-produced electricity could kill a power company employee
working on what he believes to be dead lines.
</P>
<P>
   Other than the generator, you'll find that the total cost for
your kit is $100 or less. If you ever have to use it you'll find
that being prepared makes you feel even smarter than that computer
geek across the street.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
