<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN0905-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Courts might end auto-tag proliferation
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Louisiana was the next state after Florida
to issue a ``Choose life'' license plate and the first state to
have a court stop plate sales.
</P>
<P>
   If the court's reasoning stands, the 31-flavor specialty plate
business of a lot of states could be a thing of the past.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. district court last week made a reasonable point: When
states play politics with license plates, they have to let everyone
have his say.
</P>
<P>
   Florida has 51 specialty plates. Louisiana, in the spirit of
excess for which the state is noted, has more than 100.
</P>
<P>
   People like the tags, but legislatures like them even more.
</P>
<P>
   Only 7 percent of Florida's cars eligible for specialty plates
display one, but that' still a lot of traffic, about 860,000 cars.
</P>
<P>
   Until last year, the plates featured universities and endangered
species and veterans groups and nonprofits that don't bother
anybody.
</P>
<P>
   The tags raise money for good causes and legislators get to vote
for something that makes everyone happy.
</P>
<P>
   This pleasant arrangement changed in Florida in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Right-to-life groups, the Christian Coalition and House
Republicans successfully pushed for a ``Choose life'' plate but the
late Gov. Lawton Chiles vetoed the measure.
</P>
<P>
   He issued what I always thought was a very sensible veto
message:
</P>
<P>
   ``Simply because a particular political message is able to
garner a majority of votes in the Florida Legislature does not mean
that an official State of Florida license plate is the proper forum
for debate on this _ or any other _ political issue,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jeb Bush, however, supported the proposed plate and last year
signed a bill to make it part of Florida's specialty tag lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a pending legal challenge, the plates were stamped out
by prisoners at Raiford and arrived in county tag offices a few
weeks ago. They have been overnight tepid sellers.
</P>
<P>
   In Louisiana, though, plate opponents followed a different legal
course and blocked distribution of the plates. In siding with them,
the court ruled the Legislature had put the state on one side of a
heated issue, thus turning tags from workaday car IDs into a forum
for opinion.
</P>
<P>
   It's as though the state picked a political slogan for road
signs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state has chosen license plates as a forum for speech,''
the judge wrote. ``Once it makes this choice, it cannot
discriminate against another viewpoint.''
</P>
<P>
   The court is proving the wisdom of the Chiles' message. If you
want to do a group a favor by printing its political slogan on car
tags, you have to let everyone else have their say, too.
</P>
<P>
   So, if the Legislature wants an anti-abortion tag, it must
extend the courtesy to abortion-rights people. Or, for that matter,
anyone else with a message -death penalty foes, death-penalty
supporters (''Choose death''), notch babies, gun nuts (''Choose
assault rifles''), antifluoridation activists (''Choose
cavities''), Conch Republic separatists, prohibitionists, flat-tax
advocates, militant vegetarians and their opponents (''Choose
cheeseburgers'').
</P>
<P>
   The state can't only run messages legislators like. And if
that's true in Louisiana, it's just as true in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   If the courts rule that license plates must either be a
wide-open public forum or limited to a few strictly state-business
themes, states are going to need to make a few decisions. Either
set up print-your-own-message-here machines at tag offices or cut
back to a few carefully selected themes for license plates.
</P>
<P>
   I suspect the Legislature won't want to deal with this and would
go back to a few no-nonsense tags.
</P>
<P>
   Which is fine by me. I always stuck with the simple ``Sunshine
State'' tags. Sentiments no court or legislator would gainsay.
</P>
<P>
   I just wish they would make the orange in the middle of the
plates look more orangelike. Who ever heard of smooth, undimpled
oranges? But that's a whole different legal issue.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is a columnist for The Daytona Beach (Fla.)
News-Journal. He may be reached at mark.lane(at)news-jrnl.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
