r c BC-NFK-NEWSFLASH0905-COX     09-04 0608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFK-NEWSFLASH0905-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SATs up, but not much
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The good news: Georgia students taking the Scholastic
Aptitude Test (SAT) to get into college increased their average
score by five points this year. The bad news: Even with the higher
score, Georgia ranks next to last in the nation. Only South
Carolina students did worse.
</P>
<P>
   On average, Georgia students scored 488 out of a possible 800 on
the verbal part of the test. That's up one
</P>
<P>
   point from last year. They scored 486, also out of 800, on the
math section for a four-point increase. But students nationally
averaged 505 for verbal and 514 for math.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, results from Georgia's new Criterion-Referenced
Competency Test weren't very promising. The exams test the reading,
English and math abilities of the state's fourth-, sixth- and
eighth-graders. In fourth and sixth grade, nearly 33 percent of the
students weren't up to par in English, reading or math. In eighth
grade, about 33 percent weren't up to par in English and reading
and 46 percent failed to meet state standards for math.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. GIVES AID TO COLOMBIA
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton promised last week to give $1.3 billion in
U.S. aid to help fight drugs and rebuild the economy of Colombia.
Clinton traveled to the South American nation to meet with
Colombian President Andres Pastrana, who is working to put years of
civil war and illegal drug trading in his country's past.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the cocaine and heroin brought to the United States
comes from Colombia. The aid money from the United States is to be
used mainly to get rid of drug crops, destroy labs where drugs are
made, block shipments and train Colombian security forces to better
protect human rights. Money also will be used to help farmers grow
legal crops and improve the nation's courts.
</P>
<P>
   BLAZES BURN BUDGET
</P>
<P>
   Fires raging out West are not only destroying homes and land,
they're likely to consume more than $1 billion in federal funds
before they're extinguished.
</P>
<P>
   Already the federal government has spent $626 million to help
states fight wildfires that have scorched millions of acres from
Montana to New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Most of that money has gone to pay salaries and support more
than 27,000 firefighters and soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration guesses that the loss of businesses,
wildlife, rangeland and forests could exceed $10 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Rains and cooler temperatures helped firefighters battling
blazes in northwestern and central Montana over the weekend. The
rains were greeted as the first real relief after three months of
very hot, very dry weather.
</P>
<P>
   MORE KIDS WITH IMPRISONED PARENTS
</P>
<P>
   For nearly 1.5 million American children, a visit to see Mom or
Dad requires a jail pass. That's a huge increase since 1991, when
936,500 kids had a parent in either state or federal prison.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department, which compiled the statistics, said the
rise is due mainly to the jump in the number of men and women put
in jail during that time period. Most of the children _ 58 percent
_ were under 10 years old, though the total number includes all
kids younger than 18.
</P>
<P>
   Kids with parents in federal jails seemed to see their folks
more often than those whose parents were state inmates. About 57
percent of fathers and 54 percent of mothers in state jails said
they had never had a personal visit with their children in prison.
Forty-four percent of fathers and 42 percent of mothers in federal
prisons said their kids had never visited them in jail.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
