<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0905-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ruminating on the single life
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Most all of the women I know are single and
have been for a long time. My three best friends and I have been
non-cohabiters since way before we started seriously eyeballing the
wrinkle-vanishing creams on
</P>
<P>
   drugstore shelves _ a grand total of 78 years for the four of
us.
</P>
<P>
   Do we like our single state? Sometimes. Would we rather be
married? Occasionally. Do we think we'll ever marry again? Probably
not. Why? We're not really sure, but it's not because we haven't
been asked. Not often, but asked.
</P>
<P>
   Not that we're a quartet of femme fatales leaving heartbroken
swains beached on the low tide _ we're not. We are four average
women who married for love, handled disappointment, raised our
children, and who have grown comfortable with going it on our own.
Through the years, each of us has had a sincere offer or two, but
none tempting enough to cause us to consider changing the initials
on our luggage.
</P>
<P>
   We kid around about being irresistible to men, and weave tales
about how our answering machines are loaded with gentlemen callers
requesting our charming company over dinner _ or a Caribbean
cruise. Often, particularly on long
</P>
<P>
   winter evenings in front of the fire, we wax philosophical on
the meaning of life, global warming, and why Robert Redford hasn't
begged us to flee to the Utah hills with him. Sometimes, we wonder
aloud if maybe we're not being too picky. After all, all we want is
. . . everything.
</P>
<P>
   Much has been written lately about young women who have opted to
remain single until Mr. Perfect comes along, but vowing not to
panic if he's a no-show. They enjoy careers, buy their own homes,
and some even have families
</P>
<P>
   without a ``him'' in the picture. Good for them.
</P>
<P>
   But my friends and I are single for different reasons. We're of
an age where we think about how good it would be to have a
companion, a hand to hold, warmth in the night, but we also
consider how difficult it could be to live with
</P>
<P>
   someone whose habits were new to us. ``He and I grew up
together,'' one of us will say sadly. The others nod. ``We have
history. First house, first baby.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss of this shared history sometimes makes us angry. We
resent having no one we can turn to and say, ``Remember when we
sent Junior off to kindergarten wearing that big Mickey Mouse
watch? The one with the red plastic band? Remember the proud look
on his face the first time he climbed the stairs of the big old
blue school bus?''
</P>
<P>
   More and more, younger women are deciding they don't need a man
around to complete their lives. A ``great'' one, some say would be
okay, but the single life has its major attractions. No one to
complain about your friends or crack
</P>
<P>
   wise about the bridge club. No cooking if you're not in the
mood, and no whiskers in the wash basin. Time for a career move? No
problem. And the absolute freedom to pack a bag and go traveling
without ever having to say,
</P>
<P>
   ``May I?''
</P>
<P>
   Some solo ladies reckon that marriage would probably be worth
it, but only if the man were ``great'' or perfect. I'm not so sure.
Surely, ``average'' would be easier to love. And marriage, as we
all know, is at best an imprecise state
</P>
<P>
   that needs to be manipulated daily just to keep it running.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving my friends out of it since I can't speak for them, I
have sampled both worlds. Being single isn't bad _ sometimes it's
great fun. But if pressed to tell the absolute truth, I think I
would have to admit that I'd prefer to
</P>
<P>
   have just ``kept on dancing with the guy what brung me.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(at)nwonline.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
