<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Collarbone injury leads to more than skeletal facts
 &HT;    By Jennifer Hill
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ So much for getting back into the groove for school.
</P>
<P>
   Our first soccer game of the season turned out to be our last
for a while. A hard fall resulted in my son being sidelined for a
few weeks with a collarbone injury. He's recovering nicely, but our
normal routine is still undergoing adjustments to accommodate a
one-armed 11-year-old. The balance of power has shifted among
siblings, and were I not in the middle it would be quite amusing to
observe.
</P>
<P>
   But domestic squabbles aside, the whole episode has highlighted
once again how interwoven technology has become in the fabric of
our everyday lives.
</P>
<P>
   The cell phone, not surprisingly, was an integral player
immediately following the mishap. As I helped my son to the car, I
was swapping cell phone numbers with other parents for future
updates. To and from and at the hospital, the cell phone kept us
linked with the outside world, bringing welcome doses of the real
world in the form of droll concern from his older sibling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is he going to have to stay there?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh good, he can stop at the pet store on his way home. Monty
(the lizard) and Moe (the frog) need food.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He can only use one arm.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's OK. Their food doesn't weigh much.''
</P>
<P>
   Our team, like so many others, uses e-mail to inform parents of
practice times, game schedules and general updates. Once we got
home, lots of good wishes from his teammates and their families
also came via e-mail. So though now we're only on the field in
spirit, we're with them virtually 24/7, thanks to e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   After the initial shock, the questions began to bubble.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is my clavicle? Where is it? What does it do?''
</P>
<P>
   To assuage both his and my curiosity, I checked the Internet. I
tried several search engines. Ask Jeeves led me to
www.bartleby.com, where I checked the clavicle entry in Gray's
``Anatomy of the Human Body,'' where I discovered an intriguing but
overwhelming wealth of information.
</P>
<P>
   Through AltaVista I found several sites including
www.imcpl.lib.in.us/novind.htm that look inside the human body
showing the skeletal, circulatory, respiratory and digestive
systems along with other information that was right on my son's
level. Those sites helped him visualize where his clavicle was and
what it was connected to, explaining why it hurt when he moved
certain ways.
</P>
<P>
   We also picked up some interesting did-you-know-facts about the
skeletal system such as the fact that the smallest bones are in
your ears and the only jointless bone is in your throat.
</P>
<P>
   At the Children's Orthopaedics of Atlanta site at
www.childrensortho.com/fractures.htm and a similar one at Johns
Hopkins, I found information specific to childhood fractures. Given
my son's great fondness for physical activity, I figured I might as
well bone up on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
