 &HT;    Bundles of fun
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ For kids not content with mere ogling and cooing
over their latest bubble-gum card acquisition or setting up a
fantasy competition via linked game machines, Bandai's Gundam Wing
offer hands-on, tangible toys for imaginary-world play. Better
still, Bandai bundles two activities into one package as the toys
are also available as Gundam Wing plastic model kits ($5 to $25;
www.bandai.com). When the glue less snap-together figurines are
finished _ complete with weapons, decals and accessories _ they
become effective and interactive posturing models with some 40
points of articulation. A slightly sophisticated motor-skills
challenge and a long-term toy craze all in one. Pretty neat.
</P>
<P>
   _ Shaun Conlin
</P>
<P>
   A BOOST FOR YOUR ROOST
</P>
<P>
   If you've got one thing that serves two purposes, that's half
the battle. Fisher Price's Stow `n Go Booster Seat ($20;
www.fisher-price.com) is not only a portable bottom uplifter for
your diapered chair-sitter, it's also a handy-dandy lunch
box/picnic basket/carryall. Folding neatly into a diminutive and
colorful briefcase of sorts, the Stow `n Go is a vinyl-covered,
hard-shelled, zippered storage box with a couple of soft-side
pouches for all your stowing and going needs. Set up, the
porta-booster will strap and anchor to almost any chair, where it
unfurls to form a decently durable, low-back, wee-bum riser.
</P>
<P>
   _ Staff Reports
</P>
