<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 14:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0504 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-TRIATHALON0905-COX     09-04 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIATHALON0905-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Olympic Committee welcomes popular endurance sport
 &HT;    By Luma Muhtadie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ In September 1994, the International Olympic
Committee held its 103rd annual session. One subject of discussion
was whether to name the relatively young sport triathlon to the
Summer Olympic program as a medal sport.
</P>
<P>
   The decision was yes, and with the 2000 Summer Games
approaching, we can look forward to witnessing an iconic display of
athleticism and determination when triathlon makes its Olympic
debut in Sydney, Australia. With this international stamp of
approval _ and television ratings _ it is expected that the sport
will reach new milestones of participation and popularity.
</P>
<P>
   Australia is an ideal host for this historic occasion because
the country has long been supporting triathlon and Sydney offers a
facility of the highest caliber. The famous Sydney Opera House will
be the backdrop for the course, and the transition area _ one of
the most exciting sites for spectators _ will be in front of the
Opera House steps. The opening swim portion of the race will be in
Farm Cove, part of Sydney Harbor; the hilly six-lap bike course
will pass landmarks such as the Conservatorium of Music and
Parliament House before returning to the transition area; and the
three-lap running course will weave its way through the Royal
Botanic Gardens.
</P>
<P>
   The 1.5K swim, 40K bike route and 10K running distances (0.9,
24.8 and 6.20 miles, respectively) comprise the standard Olympic
distances. But triathlons vary in distances throughout the world.
The most famous long-distance triathlon is the Hawaii Ironman race.
Established in 1978 by U.S. Navy officer John Collins, this event
combined three of Hawaii's established endurance events _ the
Waikiki Rough Water Swim (2.4 miles), the Around the Oahu Bike (112
miles) and the Honolulu Marathon (26.2 miles) _ to form a single
ultra-endurance competition. Fifteen men entered the first Ironman
in 1978, but after Sports Illustrated featured an article about it
in May 1979, the number of entrants in the following year's race
increased to 108. These days, the Ironman attracts 1,500 male and
female competitors each year, and entrants ranging from the most
elite athletes to mothers, business people and senior citizens.
</P>
<P>
   When ABC's ``Wide World of Sports'' showed Julie Moss making an
unforgettable crawl to the finish line in the 1982 Hawaii Ironman,
the sport of triathlon started gaining participation and popularity
with furious momentum. The word ``triathlon'' was added to the
``Ninth Edition of the Webster's New Collegiate Dictionary'' in
1983. Timex released the ``Triathlon'' watch in 1984 (later renamed
the ``Ironman'') and it is now the top-selling watch in the world.
Triathlon inspired Nike to launch its cross-training ad campaign in
1985, and USA Triathlon boasted 19,060 members last year. (The
group consists of U.S. residents who entered at least one race
during the 1999 triathlon season.)
</P>
<P>
   The competitors, or triathletes, in an Olympic event are
expected to swim, bike and run continuously over varying distances.
The demands of these endurance sports are interrupted only by the
``transitions'' _ the points at which the athletes make a fast
changeover from one sport to another as the race clock continues to
tick away.
</P>
<P>
   During the first transition, competitors emerge from the
open-water swim, peel off their caps, goggles and wetsuits (which
are permitted only in water colder than 68 degrees) and run to the
transition area. There they fasten their helmets, mount their
bikes, slip into cycling shoes and head off for the bike portion of
the race. Wearing a helmet is a mandatory rule set by the
International Triathlon Union. Violating the rule is grounds for
disqualification.
</P>
<P>
   During the second transition, the triathletes dismount their
bikes, take off their helmets, slip into running shoes and head out
on the running course that ends at the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   In both local and international races, competitors race in one
of three broad categories, each of which is divided into male and
female divisions. The first is the ``elite'' or ``pro'' category.
These are the athletes eligible to compete for the overall title
and, in some cases, prize money. It will be the only medal category
at the Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   The second category is ``junior,'' which covers all athletes
younger than 20 in a given race year. The largest category is
``age-group,'' divided into five-year increments (i.e. 20-24,
25-29. . .) up to 80-84. The women's race on Sept. 16, the day
after the Opening Ceremonies, will be the first event of the Summer
Olympics. The winner will not only bring home the first gold medal
of the 2000 Games, but also the first Olympic gold in triathlon
history. The men's race take place Sept. 17.
</P>
<P>
   But for each of the 50 entrants in each race, it will be a
chance to be part of a monumental event in triathlon history.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
