<HEADER>
A0506 &Cx1f; tad-z
r c BC-TEENS-SLANG05-COX     09-04 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEENS-SLANG05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Today's slanguage: Teens have a special code all their own
 &HT;    By Ricardo Gandara
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ While paying for my coffee at the grocery store,
I tell the fiftysomething man behind the counter: ``Chi. This
coffee is butters. Here's my cheese. Peace out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Huh?'' he asked. ``What did you say?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I was saying, `Cool. This coffee is good. Here's my money.
Bye.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why didn't you say that in the first place? You didn't make
any sense,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It's slanguage, man, teen slang.
</P>
<P>
   After collecting teen slang from kids around town and trying it
on adults, I got nowhere. At the office, I told a co-worker: ``Slow
your roll (relax).'' I think she thought I was telling her she was
gaining too much weight. At school, I told a parent, ``The plan is
tight (good). Tell some other rents (parents) to volunteer.'' I got
a blank stare.
</P>
<P>
   So I went to the Drag to show off my newfound vocabulary.
College students will understand, right? I stopped Ben Aaronson,
who said he was enrolled. ``OK, Ben, can you understand this?
`Someone ganked (stole) my books. Monkeys (I messed up), I left
them on the table. It's weak (not good).'''
</P>
<P>
   Ben was perplexed, too. ``Dude, I know what you said but no one
talks like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Younger teen-agers do, and slang is their ever-evolving way to
communicate with each other. Sometimes it's their special way to
relate to their clique. Sometimes they want to exclude others,
especially their parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Slang identifies you as a member of a special group,'' said
Donna Jo Napoli, professor of linguistics and expert on slang at
Swarthmore College in Swarthmore, Pa. ``And when you're 17, you
don't want to speak like your parents or a 23-year-old or a
10-year-old. It's nice to have your own special code to keep people
out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Slang makes us,'' said Katie Baldwin, 16, a junior at Bowie
High School. ``How we talk is who we are and what we think. It's
showing a piece of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Slang isn't new; it was popularized after World War II with the
advent of television. Teens joined in. In the '50s, ``neat'' was so
ubiquitous that it must have become annoying _ but it's still used
today, so there must a lasting appeal. Fifties teens also used cool
cat, cherry (really neat), threads (clothing), kicks (shoes) and
foam domes (stuffed bras), said Mike Ellis, author of ``Slanguage''
(Hyperion, $14).
</P>
<P>
   In the '60s, ``score'' meant get some dope. Heavy, far out,
bummer and ``what a trip'' were expressions you might use after you
scored. In the '70s, the Fonz coined, ``Aaayyy.'' TV continued to
have an impact, but now the commercials were influencing the
language. Remember ``Try it, you'll like it,'' from Alka Seltzer?
</P>
<P>
   The '80s brought expressions such as totally rad, so gnarly and
totally tubular _ from the movie ``Valley Girl'' _ all meaning
cool. When Clara Pellar asked, ``Where's the beef?'' in a Wendy's
advertisement, the whole country found inventive ways to capitalize
on the phrase.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to U.S. Postal workers resorting to shooting sprees in
the '90s, ``going postal,'' came to mean, well, you know what it
meant. After the release of the movie ``Clueless'' in 1995, ``Like,
oh my God'' came out of every teen girl's mouth. And what about:
Whatever! Not! You the man.
</P>
<P>
   Although teen-agers invent some slang that's unique to their
circle of friends _ ``babe-a-luba'' is a term of endearment Bowie's
Baldwin uses for her friends _ many of their words are not new.
Phat (cool) and da bomb (awesome) originated from the jazz era in
the 1920s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Slang is recycled,'' Ellis said. ``When more people got radios
and TVs after 1930, words popped up everywhere. Now with the
Internet, it's all over.''
</P>
<P>
   But slang isn't necessarily the same everywhere. It differs from
one group to another in high schools and city to city.
Pflugerville's Matthew Bledsoe, 16, who travels the country because
he's a ballet dancer, noticed it this past year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Skaters don't use the same words as the gangsters, and the
gangsters don't use the same words as the preps, and the preps
don't talk like the nerds,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the surfer word ``groovy'' is accepted in Boca
Raton, Fla., but considered weird in Houston. ``In Houston you're
likely to hear street slang, something like `I'm chillin' (hanging)
with my homies (friends) this weekend,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Napoli advises parents not to get riled up about the slang their
kids use, aside from the nasty and degrading words. ``I know that
parents refer to adolescence as the psychotic years, but from the
kids' point of view they want to be different than their parents.
They want their own identity. Using their special language is one
way,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   So parents, slow your roll.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
