<P>
   &UR; FOR TUESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Tuesday, Sept. 5:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-SUMMIT (United Nations) _ On the three-day Millennium
Summit Meeting scheduled for this week, which more than 150
international leaders will attend. By Marc Lacey.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-SUMMIT-CLINTON (Undated) _ President Clinton's plans at
this week's United Nations summit. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA-PRESIDENT (United Nations) _ An interview with the
president of Nigeria, Olusegun Obasanjo. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   Other U.N. summit stories as warranted.
</P>
<P>
   LEBANON-ELECTION (Beirut) _ Final election results showed Monday
that the victory of billionaire tycoon Rafik Hariri was so sweeping
that his chances of being named the new prime minister have
increased _ which could put him on a collision course with the
president. By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-TWINS (London) _ A British court is expected to rule
Monday on whether a set of Siamese twins should be separated
against the wishes of the parents. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   CONCORDE-CRASH (Paris) _ A new twist in the Concorde crash
investigation suggests that a piece of metal thought to have caused
the disaster may have fallen off a Continental Airlines DC 10,
which took off on the same runway just ahead of the Concorde. By
Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-POLITICS (Belgrade) _ A split in the Serbian
opposition to the Yugoslav president, Slobodan Milosevic, is
putting at risk its main achievement so far: its control over
Serbia's major cities, including radio and television stations. By
Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-RETURN (Washington) _ Congress comes back Tuesday,
facing a mountain of legislation that is supposed to be wrapped up
in a month. By Steven A. Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-DEBATE (Undated) _ What are the campaigns' strategies
and what went into the Bush decision on the debates. Plus reaction
from the broadcast networks. By Peter Marks.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH (Chicago) _ Day developments: George W. Bush at the Labor
Day parade. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   GORE (Pittsburgh) _ Day developments: Al Gore at the parade. By
Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   LIEBERMAN (Detroit) _ Joseph Lieberman's campaign day. By
Richard Perez-Pena.
</P>
<P>
   CHENEY (Chicago) _ Dick Cheny's campaign day. By Michael Cooper.
</P>
<P>
   VOTERS-RELIGION (Denver) _ Voters can scarcely miss the overt
expressions of religious faith by candidates in this presidential
campaign. But interviews with more than three dozen voters around
the country found that they have little interest in weighing the
religious convictions of candidates when choosing the next
president. By David Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-ENVIRON (Undated) _ Friends of the Earth endorses Al Gore.
By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Notes from the hustings.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   FIRESTONE-LABOR (Undated) _ Firestone, facing a crisis over
allegations its tires caused dozens of traffic deaths, reached a
tentative agreement with steelworkers early today to avert a strike
at nine plants. The union has not yet disclosed details but said it
believed the agreement was fair for both sides. The settlement
covers more than 8,000 workers at seven plants that produce tires
and two that produce tire parts. By Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   FIRESTONE-VENEZUELA (Caracas) _ Facing a threat of legal action,
Bridgestone/Firestone Inc. will announce a formal recall of 62,000
Venezuelan-made tires alleged to have defects linked to at least 46
fatal accidents here. The government, however, says that the action
is not enough and that it will consider its legal options. By Larry
Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   DAIMLERCHRYSLER-MITSUBISHI (Munich, Germany) _ DaimlerChrysler
confirmed a Japanese report that it wants to amend the terms of its
proposed acquisition of a third of Mitsubishi Motors to obtain
greater control over the company, Japan's No. 3 automaker, which
has been buffeted by a recall scandal. DaimlerChrysler wants to
raise its Mitsubishi stake to 40 percent, altering its July plan to
buy 34 percent for almost $2 billion. It also wants more than the
current three seats on the 10-member management board.
DaimlerChrysler aims to wrest control of Mitsubishi Motors from
Mitsubishi group companies, which owned about 42 percent in March.
By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-TELECOM (Jerusalem) _ The Israeli government has ended
the state telephone company's monopoly on domestic telephone and
Internet service, taking a long-resisted deregulatory move that
sets the stage for the company, Bezeq, to sell shares to private
investors later this year. By William A. Orme Jr.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-DEBT (Tokyo) _ The collapse of Sogo, a department store,
has blown away whatever fig leaf had supposedly covered the
Japanese banking industry's bad debt problems. Other companies have
now asked for debt relief, and such requests, combined with the
recent increase in interest rates, are putting immense strain on
the banking system. The question now is whether the government will
forced to intervene as it did two years ago when the financial
system came close to collapsing. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-U.S.-ENERGY (Undated) _ On reports that National Grid
Group plc, which operates Britain's power transmission network, is
in talks to buy the U.S. firm Niagara Mohawk for about $3 billion.
The London-based National Grid has earmarked more for further
United States expansion this year, after buying New England
Electric System in March. Niagara, which has been reporting losses,
is seen as too small to compete in the deregulating American
market. By Andre Ross Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-BUSINESS (San Francisco) _ IBM, Microsoft and others
are expected to announce proposed standards this week for an
electronic directory that will make it easier for companies to
carry out business-to-business transactions. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-BOURSES (London) _ Euronext, the company that will
combine the Paris, Amsterdam and Brussels stock exchanges, has
approached French banks about the possibility of financing for a
bid for the London Stock Exchange. The London exchange was already
in merger talks with Frankfurt. By Suzanne Kapner.
</P>
<P>
   SCULLEY-BROTHERS (Undated) _ John Sculley, the former Apple
Computer chief executive, is making a quiet comeback. For the last
five years, he has run run a small venture capital firm with his
two brothers. It is his way of fulfilling a desire to work with his
family -- and to help proselytize about the virtues of the Internet
without suffering the corporate intrigue that overwhelmed him at
both Apple and at Spectrum Information Technologies. Having fun
while teaching young entrepreneurs, he says, now takes priority
over earning maximum returns. By using their own assets, they do
not subject themselves to the pressure of performing for investors.
Nonetheless, he said, they expect to earn high returns over the
long run. So far, the track record of Sculley Brothers leaves
something to be desired. Three of the five companies they backed
that have gone public _ like many other Web-based businesses since
the Nasdaq shakedown last April _ now trade at rock bottom prices.
By Hilary Rosenberg.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   Thomas L. Friedman's ``Foreign Affairs'' and Gail Collins'
``Public Interests.''
</P>
