<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following  &UR; Science
Times &LR;  stories for papers of Tuesday, Sept. 5:
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CAVE-VISITORS (Benson, Ariz.) - Take a sopping wet
underground cavern in a remote corner of Arizona. Add a man-made
entrance with heavy steel doors to keep out the hot desert air, a
misting system to keep the cavern damp and lights to show off a
wonderland of spires, flowstone, soda straws and other
phantasmagorical cave formations. Then add a human being who, in a
one-hour visit, sloughs off some 60,000 skin fragments, 160 million
dust particles, 20,000 clothing-lint particles, 25 quarts of carbon
dioxide gas and 170 watts of body heat. Multiply this by 183,000
visitors to the cave each year. The result is an ad hoc experiment
now under way at Kartchner Caverns near Benson, Ariz., to learn if
it is possible to bring thousands of people into the fragile
environment of a pristine cave without destroying the cave in the
process. By Sandra Blakeslee. (2100 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ULTIMATE-LAPTOP (Undated) _ In a paper in the current issue
of Nature, an MIT researcher describes the ultimate laptop _ a
computer as powerful as the laws of physics would allow. So
energetic is this imaginary machine that using it would be like
harnessing a thermonuclear reaction. In the most extreme version of
this computer supreme, so much computational circuitry would be
packed into so small a space that the whole thing would collapse
from its own gravity forming a tiny black hole, an object so dense
that not even light can escape its gravity. By George Johnson.
(1900 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HEART-DRUGS (Undated) _ In the 13 years since they were
introduced in the United States, the cholesterol-lowering drugs
known as statins have revolutionized the treatment of heart
disease. Repeated studies have shown they prevent heart attacks and
prolong life, with very few side effects. They have rapidly become
the best-selling prescription drugs in this country. Now, the
latest research indicates that even more people should be on
statins. By Sandeep Jauhar. (1500 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ALBATROSS (Undated) _ Researchers in France and Germany have
tracked several wandering albatrosses, and their findings are
surprising. As the researchers report in the journal Nature, the
birds do not wander aimlessly during what amounts to a sabbatical
following a year in which they hatch and raise a single chick.
Rather, the albatrosses go to a specific section of the ocean and
stay there. By Henry Fountain. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-RACE-RECOGNITION (Undated) _ After a decade of mapping
brains in tasks like recalling numbers, perceiving facial
expressions and using verbs, neuroscientists have recently honed in
on a much more controversial subject: The act of categorizing other
human beings. In recently published papers, two separate teams of
brain scanners joined by social psychologists describe how one
particular part of the brain becomes more active when people look
at members of a different race. By David Berreby. (1700 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ News and notes on science: Items on coated
seeds that might be used to help farmers overlap winter wheat and
soybeans in the same field; the prospect of genetically modifying
plants to grow coffee without the caffeine; on a die-off of tiger
salamanders at a lake in North Dakota. By Henry Fountain. (700
words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MENOPAUSE (Undated) _ For many menopausal women, the
question of whether to take hormones is one of the most crucial
health decisions of their middle years _ and one of the most
confusing. Hormone use relieves the hot flashes and night sweats
that plague many women during menopause, and protects against
brittle bones. But does it help prevent heart disease, as
researchers have long believed _ or could it actually increase the
risk, as at least one new piece of data seems to suggest. In a
package of six stories, women discuss the ways they approach the
therapy and their frustrations with unanswered questions.
</P>
<P>
   These six, approximately 375-400 words each, may be combined to
form a single coherent story:
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MENOPAUSE-QUINTANA
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MENOPAUSE-DUMONT
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MENOPAUSE-GOLDMAN
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MENOPAUSE-HILL
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MENOPAUSE-LANG
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MENOPAUSE-LAND
</P>
<P>
   SCI-VITAL-SIGNS (Undated) _ News and notes on health and
fitness:
</P>
<P>
   _ In recent months, researchers have pointed to possible signals
of Alzheimer's disease that could allow doctors to detect the
ailment before symptoms start. They have spoken of small areas of
the brain that appear to shrink, and psychological tests that yield
subtle clues. Now scientists think they may have found another
clue: smell. (230 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ With the rate of Caesarean sections on the rise, a leading
group of obstetricians has issued guidelines that may reduce the
number of operations. (220 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ People who want to start exercise programs but feel they don't
have enough time or energy to begin should think again. A new study
suggests that physical activity that lasts just 15 minutes, if done
often enough, may be as beneficial as longer workouts. The report
appeared last week in Circulation: Journal of the American Heart
Association. (260 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ Feeling sick to one's stomach may have more to do with the
brain the stomach. Researchers at Ohio State University say they
may have uncovered the reason that, often, people feel nauseated,
even though what ails them has nothing to do with their digestive
tracks. The culprit may be a brain chemical called tumor necrosis
factor, or TNF, which the immune system releases at the first sign
that the body is coming under attack.
</P>
<P>
   _ A new study finds that tough guys seem to have tougher immune
systems, the body's natural defense for fighting off infections,
viruses and the like. (270 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ The Personal Health column:
Problems of ``polypharmacy'' or dangerous cocktails of drugs are
increasing, as more and more people live into their 70s and beyond.
By Jane E. Brody. (1275 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ A science question answered: How do
scientists determine that a rock on earth came from Mars rather
than someplace else? By C. Claiborne Ray. (275 words)
</P>
