<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 14:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0518 &Cx1f; tad-z
r c BC-HUGHES-AUSTRALIA05-CO     09-04 1141
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUGHES-AUSTRALIA05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Australia through a native son's eyes
 &HT;    By Jim Auchmutey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Thirty-nine years ago, the new owner of a Sydney
newspaper summoned his political cartoonist and demanded to know
how much he made. $25 a cartoon, came the answer. Too much, the
boss said, and offered to keep him on at half the pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an outrage,'' the artist shot back. ``I resign.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's how Rupert Murdoch lost a cartoonist and the world of
letters gained Robert Hughes.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes, the witty, woolly art critic of Time magazine, looks
back at his native land in a six-hour documentary starting tonight
on public television. ``Australia: Beyond the Fatal Shore'' is a
series of lively personal essays exploring the culture of the
country he departed not long after Murdoch more or less fired him _
a country that will soon be inescapable as the Sydney Olympics
begin.
</P>
<P>
   The title recalls ``The Fatal Shore,'' the 62-year-old author's
classic history of Australia's hard birth as a British penal
colony. The name almost proved prophetic last year, when Hughes
returned to Australia to begin work on the project and was nearly
killed in a car crash. He leans on crutches during most of the film
and still hasn't completely recovered from his injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes talked about the series from his home in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Do Americans have the wrong idea about Australia?
</P>
<P>
   A:They have a whole cluster of wrong ideas. There's this
ingrained American delusion that we're something like Americans.
That your Wild West was paved over with shopping malls, but somehow
it emigrated to Australia _ the Crocodile Dundee fantasy.
</P>
<P>
   Well, we're not 6-foot-4 stringy- bark horseback riders with
great big Bowie knives who like to strangle crocodiles before
breakfast. Most Australians live in the cities; it's one of the
most highly urbanized societies in the world. The number of people
who actually live the Outback is small and getting smaller.
</P>
<P>
   Q:What's the biggest difference between the nations?
</P>
<P>
   A:America was founded by two groups of people seeking expansion
of their religious beliefs: the Spanish Catholics in the Southwest
and the Puritans in the Northeast. Both wanted to set up religious
utopias, and this gave rise to that perpetual American belief in
renewal. Nothing of that idealism and periodic looniness attaches
to the colonization of Australia. Australia was a jail. It started
off as a place of punishment, not as a place of reward.
</P>
<P>
   It affects the way landscape is experienced. In America, it's
``Go west, young man!'' _ become freer and richer and better by
going west and seeing the works of God in an unedited form. In
Australia, there was no such expectation. You go out into the bush,
you get lost, you die. The space was the prison.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Has the country changed much since you left?
</P>
<P>
   A:If you had told me in 1964 that 35 years from now, there's
going to be an enormous festival of homosexuals in Sydney (the Gay
and Lesbian Mardi Gras) and it'll be the biggest in the world, and
moreover, it will be so popular among straights that it will
outdraw the visit of the Pope _ if anyone had told me that, I would
have said, ``Yeah sure, and the dog ate your homework.'' Australia
was a deeply homophobic country in 1964. That has changed.
</P>
<P>
   Q:You've written about the sense of shame that many Australians
felt about their country starting as a penal colony. Is the
``convict stain'' still there?
</P>
<P>
   A:The stain is gone. In fact, it's rather a badge of distinction
now to say that your ancestors were convicts. My father's people
came from Ireland in 1837, and I'm very ashamed to say we were
free.
</P>
<P>
   Q:What's the hottest issue in Australia these days?
</P>
<P>
   A:When I left, it was communism. Now it's race, the whole issue
of Aborigines. Most Australians of my generation knew nothing about
Aborigines. Growing up in Sydney, I never met one. You'd
occasionally see them chucking boomerangs to make a couple of
shillings off the tourists, but you had no social contact with
them. They weren't even getting work as shoeshine boys.
</P>
<P>
   Q:And now there's a national debate over whether the government
should apologize to Aborigines for past injustices. What do you
think?
</P>
<P>
   A:A formal apology isn't going to bring anyone back to life. But
it's a reasonable thing to do given that the Aborigines want it as
a harmless starting point for future negotiations. If Australians
are prepared to accept Gallipoli and all the heroism of the past,
they should be prepared to take on the guilt, too.
</P>
<P>
   Q:You were very outspoken last year during a national referendum
that would have declared Australia a republic and severed ties with
the British monarchy. Why did that measure lose?
</P>
<P>
   A:Australians can be brave on the field of battle and ingenious
in facing off against nature but total poltroons when it comes to
electoral politics. Most Australians want a republic. But when it
came time to vote, they fudged.
</P>
<P>
   Q:You upset people recently by saying some of that in the
souvenir program of the Sydney Olympics. What happened?
</P>
<P>
   A:Sports Illustrated (which produced the program) asked me to
write a 10,000-word essay, and nowhere was it suggested that I
should avoid political matters. Now all these moldy old monarchos
are saying Mr. Hughes degraded the Olympics by introducing
political debate. Give me a break. When have the Olympics not been
political?
</P>
<P>
   Q:Australia is said to be more sports-crazy than America. Can
that possibly be true?
</P>
<P>
   A:Yes. That doesn't mean they're better at it. But they're very
passionate team-sports followers and have their own team the way
you have a political party.
</P>
<P>
   I prefer solitary sports like fishing. They used to make me play
football (rugby) when I was a kid, and I just hated it. I was a
feeble little creature, and I didn't like being trampled over by
hordes of huge country bastards from Mudgee competing for a greasy
little ball. Some of these kids were enormous, mate.
</P>
<P>
   Q:You talk about sports in the series but don't mention the
Sydney Olympics once. Why?
</P>
<P>
   A:I don't give a (randy pub expression deleted) about the
Olympics. I don't think it's important to understanding Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Q:A lot of people in Atlanta saw the Olympics as a kind of
vindication. You don't feel any of that for your hometown?
</P>
<P>
   A:People think Australia must be really pleased to be put on the
map by the Olympics. I don't think it's within the power of a
sporting event to put a great and complex city on the map. We're
already on the map.
</P>
<P>
   Q:So you won't be at the Games?
</P>
<P>
   A:Hell, no. I am going to Australia in October, but it's to go
fishing out west, not to watch athletes go around a track in so
many nanoseconds.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
