A0519 &Cx1f; tad-z
r c BC-REVIEW-HUGHES05-COX     09-04 0557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-HUGHES05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Beyond the Fatal Shore' is fun, informative TV
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Robert Hughes describes his homeland as ``spatially
huge, culturally tiny, politically insignificant.'' Not exactly a
sentiment you'll see on bumper stickers in Sydney, but it indicates
Hughes' refreshing honesty.
</P>
<P>
   That outspokenness _ plus insight, perspective, arresting
visuals and just a flat-out wonderful sense of television _ are on
display in ``Beyond the Fatal Shore,'' PBS' six-hour tour of
Australia.
</P>
<P>
   It's a grand introduction to what will be the biggest wave ever
of Aussie TV hitting these shores. Sydney's Summer Olympics start
Sept. 15, and NBC's typical saturation coverage will include
sending Katie Couric and crew Down Under for three weeks of
``Today'' shows, starting Sept. 1. And the next ``Survivor'' on CBS
will be set in the Australian Outback; it tapes in October and
starts after the Super Bowl on Jan. 28.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes, Time magazine's art critic and author of the 1987 best
seller ``The Fatal Shore,'' a history of Australia, makes this a
series of personal essays. He starts off tonight by visiting the
junkyard to see the mangled car he was driving when a crash nearly
killed him early in the filming, and he ends up Thursday, publicly
campaigning in favor of Australia leaving the British Commonwealth.
In between, he uses his own memories and opinions to talk about his
country's society, history and geography and people.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the ``Crocodile Dundee'' theme park popular in the
American imagination. He takes us to a gay pride parade, the
beaches, a fashion show, a right-wing radio talk show, rugby games,
government buildings, Aborigines digging for water, pornographers
making a movie in a field.
</P>
<P>
   Everywhere he and his camera crew turn, Hughes finds something
that is amazing. He visits a golf course in the Outback that
doesn't have a single blade of grass. The ``greens'' are made of
sand mixed with diesel oil, and the duffers carry a small patch of
Astroturf with them, placing it down to hit each shot. Even
stranger than that is ``Old Sydney,'' a tourist attraction where
faked but incredibly realistic floggings are performed while
schoolchildren watch. After that, a kangaroo just doesn't seem all
that noteworthy.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes, who's been an expatriate for 35 years and has a strong
love-hate relationship with his native land, is full of opinions.
The lobby of the national capitol looks to him ``like a really bad
Holiday Inn'' and he refers to Queen Elizabeth II as ``Queenie.''
</P>
<P>
   And Hughes' eye for art makes ``Fatal Shore'' a visual treat. He
uses fast-motion photography, extreme close-ups and saturated,
vibrant colors, so that parts look like a David Lynch film (but in
a coherent way).
</P>
<P>
   PBS documentaries (including those by way of the BBC, which this
is) have a high reputation, but sometimes they can be spinach TV _
good for you, but you're always aware you're being fed something
nutritious. Hughes has spread out a banquet that will feed your
mind, but it's yummy as well. It's what nonfiction TV ought to
always be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Australia: Beyond the Fatal Shore''
</P>
<P>
   9 tonight . 9 p.m. Wednesday and Thursday on PBS
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
