<TEXT>
<P>
   Entertainment and culture stories from The N.Y. Times News
Service for Tuesday, Sept. 5.
</P>
<P>
   READER-AUTHOR-TOURS (Undated) _ The list of writers who are
turning tours into reading vacations is dominated by self-help
authors with a spiritual bent like Neale Donald Walsch, the author
of ``Conversations With God,'' who in June took readers on an
eight-day tour of Peru timed to coincide with the summer solstice
sunrise over Machu Picchu. But there are also published historians
and even a poet who are leading people on tours ripped from their
chapters, whether it be a stroll down Shankill Road in Belfast or a
trip to Colonial Williamsburg in Virginia. By Doreen Carvajal.
</P>
<P>
   DESERT-ARTS-PILGRIMS (Black Rock Desert, Nev.) _ The Burning Man
festival has become a yearly pilgrimage for thousands of performers
and artists, as well as Internet techies, adventurous yuppies and
other counterculture aficionados, many of whom trek hundreds or
even thousands of miles to attend this alternative-arts fair that
showcases art of the obscure, the outrageous and the just plain
odd. Flags from Sweden, Israel, Italy and Ireland billowed over
camps this year, as did rainbow banners and pirate skulls. By Jesse
McKinley.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-BARD-MUSIC (Moscow) _ Every summer, thousands of Russians
make the journey to the Grushinsky Festival, which celebrates bard
music, a genre identified with the Soviet cultural thaw of the
1960s and the subsequent growth and popularity of allegorical songs
as a creative and spiritual outlet. Today conditions are different,
but the songs of contemporary bard musicians seem to serve a
similar comforting purpose. By Sophia Kishkovsky.
</P>
<P>
   PROUST-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ In his tedious new study of
Proust, ``Marcel Proust: A Life,'' Jean-Yves Tadie whines that the
adult Proust never revealed his inner life in his correspondence
and makes the odd complaint that George Painter _ the author of the
best-known biography of the writer to date _ succumbed ``without
any qualms'' to the temptation ``to draw from the novel in order to
explain, or understand, the life.'' Reviewed by Michiko Kakutani.
</P>
<P>
   TV-AUSTRALIA-REVIEW (Undated) _ On PBS, ``Australia Beyond the
Fatal Shore,'' with Robert Hughes. Reviewed by Caryn James.
</P>
<P>
   For information and repeats call the News Service at (888)
346-9867 or (212) 556-1927. And be sure to look for other
entertainment stories from our partners: The Boston Globe, Cox News
Service, Hearst Newspapers, The Houston Chronicle, The Arizona
Republic, Kansas City Star, Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Los Angeles
Daily News, San Francisco Chronicle and Seattle Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
