<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSSTAND05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dads scopes out what women want in men
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Ever since Freud raised the question (and probably for
eons before that), men have been asking, ``What do women want?''
The editors of Dads ($2.99) magazine try to provide answers in a
survey of women readers. Nearly half of respondents wanted more
(and better) sex. Others wanted more romantic gestures such as
hidden notes or surprise dates and more help around the house. When
asked what adult-education classes they would send their husbands
to, their choices were massage, ballroom dancing, money management,
cooking, minor household repairs and ``interpersonal skills.''
</P>
<P>
   Launched last Father's Day for men who take parenting seriously,
the September/October issue of Dads also features a cover story on
ESPN anchors Chris Berman and Dan Patrick talking about life on and
off camera.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Just desserts: Anne Byrn takes the cake with a flattering
article in this week's People ($2.99). Byrn is lauded for her
innovative cookbook, ``The Cake Mix Doctor'' (Workman, $14.96). By
experimenting with cake mixes, the Nashville food writer found ways
to turn standard recipes into something special by adding various
ingredients such as buttermilk or orange juice.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to sample Byrn's orange chiffon cake, St. Louis pastry
chef Tim Brennan gave the recipe a thumbs up. ``I usually have an
aftertaste for chemicals,'' he says of processed foods. ``But that
was special.'' Byrn does draw the line, however, at using canned
frosting: ``It's terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hefty reading: If magazines get any bigger, readers will have
to use luggage carts to take them home. The September In Style
($4.95) has 702 pages, not including a thick advertising insert.
Once you wade through page after page of glossy fashion and
cosmetics ads, you'll find an ample number of articles about Drew
Barrymore, Sharon Stone and other celebrities. ``NYPD Blue'' star
Kim Delaney talks about her campaign to feed hungry children, and
Heather Locklear and husband Richie Sambora show off their stunning
Pacific beach house.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Good Vibes: Women subscribers to Vibe ($2.95) will get a bonus
publication with their October issue. Written by the magazine's
female staff and free-lance editors, Home &QR; Girl addresses the areas
of lifestyle, health, beauty, fashion and travel with an
urban-music sensibility. The launch issue features Eve of the Ruff
Riders on the cover and includes articles on Carmen Elektra and
Kobe Bryant. There's also an interesting layout showing the hottest
hairstyles _ and hairstylists _ from Atlanta, Chicago, New York and
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Quick read: JazzTimes ($4.95) celebrates its 30-year
anniversary with a special edition covering three decades of music
history. Some of the country's finest jazz writers, from Nat
Hentoff to Stanley Crouch, offer their insights and criticism.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Rolling Stone ($4.95) features a two-page cover foldout of
Gisele Bundchen and an in-depth account of her rise from a
volleyball -loving 14-year-old in a small Brazilian village to that
of a supermodel who makes $7,000 an hour. Less glamorous but more
substantive is Charles M. Young's piece on Ralph Nader and why he
is willing to sacrifice Al Gore in the presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
