<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 16:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0571 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-CONGRESS-RETURNS-0905     09-04 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-RETURNS-0905-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CONGRESS RETURNS, EAGER TO PASS SPENDING BILLS
 &HT;    670&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    With CONGRESS-LIST-0905
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congress returns from its August break Tuesday with
members of both parties eager to wrap up a few compromises on
spending bills, exchange partisan barrages, and resume full-time
campaigning by the first Thursday in October.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton invited Democratic congressional leaders to
meet with him Tuesday in the White House to publicize their goals
for the upcoming end-of-session negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   In his weekly radio address Saturday, Clinton said his
priorities include raising the minimum wage, new education
programs, prescription drug coverage, a patient's bill of rights, a
small package of targeted tax cuts and paying down the debt.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental and union lobbyists are also asking him to hold
firm in his threats to veto eight of the 11 unfinished
appropriation bills unless Congress removes the portions that they
say would weaken workplace or environmental regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have counted 46 very destructive anti-environmental riders,
and we want clean bills _ with the riders out,'' said Mary Beth
Beetham, legislative affairs director at the 380,000-member
Defenders of Wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   But the Republican-controlled Senate will act on its own
priorities when it reassembles at noon Tuesday, said Majority
Leader Trent Lott of Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Senate's focus for the first two weeks in September will
be on the completion of the remaining appropriations and the China
(trade) bills, and on the votes to override the president's vetoes
of our bipartisan bills to end the marriage penalty and the death
tax,'' Lott said in a letter to all GOP senators. He also plans to
conduct votes on a Republican bill that would change the rules for
pension plans and raise the amount that savers can put into their
Individual Retirement Accounts.
</P>
<P>
   The House, which reconvenes Wednesday, will try to override
Clinton's tax-bill vetoes, finish work on appropriation bills and
pass some non-controversial measures, said Speaker Dennis Hastert,
R-Ill.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's lame duck status hasn't weakened his negotiating
skills, said Republican operative Robert Rusbuldt, executive vice
president of the Independent Insurance Agents of America.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president is going to want to milk every last cent and
every last program he cares about out of this Congress. It's his
last shot,'' Rusbuldt said. ``Members of both parties will be
itching to get out of town, but he's not going to be as concerned
about their campaigns as he is about his agenda and political
concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   He and other veteran Congress-watchers said they expect Congress
to spend the next five or six weeks negotiating compromises on its
only must-do set of laws _ the annual spending bills that will fund
the government's routine operations in the fiscal year that begins
Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Most agreed on these likely outcomes:
</P>
<P>
   _ Though only two of the 13 annual appropriation bills have been
passed and signed into law, a few more will be passed in September.
The rest will be bundled into one giant bill negotiated between the
White House and Congress in early October.
</P>
<P>
   _ Other popular measures likely to become law include a $1
increase in the $5.15 minimum wage, modest tax relief for some
targeted groups like college students and beer wholesalers,
permanent approval of normal trade relations with China, higher
immigration quotas for high-tech workers and a rollback of cuts
made several years ago in the size of Medicare payments to nursing
homes.
</P>
<P>
   _ The adjournment rush, partisan distrust and the skepticism in
Congress about details could delay action on plans to add
prescription drug benefits to Medicare and to protect the rights of
patients who use health maintenance organizations.
</P>
<P>
   _ Until a new president is elected, gridlock will prevent any
major changes in the ``non-discretionary'' two-thirds of the $2
trillion annual federal budget. That portion pays down the debt and
finances Social Security, Medicare, civil service and military
pensions and other entitlements.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Luckily, gridlock will protect the big money, which is in
entitlements, so there will be funds left for debt reduction,''
said Robert Bixby, executive director of the bipartisan, fiscally
conservative Concord Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the president wants more than the Republicans do on the
$600 billion or so in discretionary spending that is in the
appropriation bills,'' Bixby said. ``It looks like the Republicans
will fight him viciously for a few weeks, and then cave in, add the
usual amount of pork-barrel spending and go home, where they will
blame him for the amount they agreed to spend.''
</P>
<P>
   At a liberal Washington think tank, the Center on Budget and
Policy Priorities, legislative director Ellen Nissenbaum also said
she expects a compromise without a government shutdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether we have a series of short-term resolutions (to keep
the government operating in October while negotiators meet) remains
to be seen,'' she said. But with big budget surpluses forecast,
``there's simply less incentive for a fight over the numbers than
there was in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Franc, vice president for government relations at the
conservative Heritage Foundation, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1995, there was a night-and-day difference between the
parties, but today it's shades of twilight,'' Franc said.
</P>
<P>
   While anticipating ``lots of screaming and dueling press
conferences,'' he also predicted that a lot could be accomplished
in Congress from Sept. 15 to Oct. 1, when most Americans will be
more interested in the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``My instinct is, the Olympics will suck a lot of oxygen out of
Capitol Hill,'' Franc said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Congress: thomas.loc.gov
</P>
<P>
   White House: www.whitehouse.gov
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Mollison can be e-mailed at: andym(at)coxnews.com
</P>
