<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFLAC-ADS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Duck ad campaign quacks up stunning interest in AFLAC
 &HT;    By Scott Leith
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Love him or hate him, AFLAC's talking duck is proving
hard to ignore.
</P>
<P>
   You probably know the critter: A white duck that insistently
quacks ``AFLAC'' in commercials about the Columbus-based
supplemental health insurer.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign kicked off during CNN's New Year's Eve coverage
last year, and AFLAC has been stunned by the response. The third
duck commercial just appeared, and more are in production.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the first two months of 2000, we had more leads than in the
last two years,'' said Kathleen Spencer, senior vice president of
corporate communications at AFLAC. The company says it has sold
some 7,000 toy ducks on its Web site, which otherwise focuses on
long-term disability insurance and dental insurance.
</P>
<P>
   In an advertising-saturated world, having a hit ad character is
like finding gold in a salt mine. Taco Bell's Spanish-speaking
Chihuahua was a hit as a toy, as were Coca-Cola Co.'s white polar
bears, launched in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had no idea the level of carryover interest that the
campaign would create,'' Spencer said.
</P>
<P>
   AFLAC is spending about $35 million on advertising. Kaplan
Thaler Group of New York created the duck campaign, while
Fitzgerald &AMP; Co. of Atlanta handled the media buying. The TV duck
has no name, but the voice is provided by comedian Gilbert
Gottfried, while the duck itself was created by Stan Winston
Studio, a California company that worked on Jurassic Park.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of the stuffed toy ducks were boosted when the host of
CNBC's ``Power Lunch'' had one on his desk this summer.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, AFLAC's duck is limited to appearances in the
United States, even though AFLAC's biggest market is Japan.
</P>
<P>
   AFLAC will first test-market the campaign before taking it to
Japan, where a goofy U.S. ad might not work. ``Here, the idea of a
duck that is sort of persistent and a little bit pushy _ I guess
you would say it fits,'' Spencer said.
</P>
<P>
   Even a hit character doesn't assure an ad firm's future with a
company. Taco Bell dismissed the Chihuahua's creator,
TBWA/Chiat/Day, following sluggish sales.
</P>
<P>
   But success can also be enduring. Coca-Cola Co. gets $50 million
a year through licensing the Coke name and other trademarks. Coke
is happy that people want merchandise _ including toy polar bears _
but the main reason for licensing is trademark protection.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't use the brand name in categories other than soft
drinks, we can lose it,'' said spokesman Scott Jacobson. ``That's
the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacobson said Coke doesn't aim for merchandise sales. ``It's not
like the Disney-type approach, where you look at it and say, 'How
do we create this franchise that can snowball into more revenue?'''
</P>
<P>
   John Cavanagh knew the polar bears would be a hit, so the Coke
licensee asked if he could sell stuffed versions. His company,
Cavanagh Group International, still distributes hundreds of
thousands of the bears each Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The polar bear has become an icon of the company,'' said
Cavanagh.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
