r f BC-DELTA-VOTE05-COX     09-04 0413
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTA-VOTE05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delta ramp workers face new vote on union
 &HT;    By Nancy Fonti
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Delta Air Lines ramp workers checking their mailboxes
this week may suddenly feel a sense of deja vu.
</P>
<P>
   That's because the National Mediation Board is mailing a second
round of election ballots to 9,900 ramp workers eligible to vote on
whether they want to be represented by the Transport Workers Union.
</P>
<P>
   The first election, held in February, was declared invalid by
the Mediation Board because of procedural errors and actions by
Delta that the board ruled inappropriate.
</P>
<P>
   In that election, just 17 percent of nearly 10,800 eligible
workers at Atlanta-based Delta voted to join the TWU. A majority
had to return ballots to the Mediation Board for the union to win.
</P>
<P>
   The TWU appealed the results, and in July the Mediation Board
declared the vote invalid because it mistakenly disclosed to Delta
the number of election authorization cards supporting the election
and accidently sent cards marked for a different election at United
Airlines to 241 Delta workers.
</P>
<P>
   The board also said it found ``substantial evidence'' that Delta
supervisors discussed management's opposition to the TWU during
required employee meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Fewer workers will vote in the second election because some have
retired, quit or taken new posts since the first vote, said Jeff
Osborne, a TWU organizer. The Mediation Board will count ballots in
the second election Oct. 2.
</P>
<P>
   ''We think the vote is going to improve,'' Osborne said. ''There
is some possibility that this will go through.''
</P>
<P>
   The vote earlier this year was essentially the first large-scale
union vote ever at Delta, the least-unionized carrier in the
airline industry. Pilots, who joined the Air Lines Pilots
Association more than 60 years ago, are its only large organized
group.
</P>
<P>
   Delta spokesman John Kennedy said the airline believes it acted
properly in the original election and will comply with Mediation
Board rules in the rerun. ''We trust that our employees will make
their opinions known and vote overwhelmingly to remain
union-free,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The TWU had been organizing at Delta more than three years,
telling workers a union contract would provide better job security
and protection against cutbacks such as those that riddled the
company during a mid-1990s financial slump.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
