<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0578 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-ANTI-ATLANTA05-COX     09-04 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTI-ATLANTA05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida city's tax campaign rolls on theme of bashing Atlanta
 &HT;    By Dan Chapman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The mayor of Jacksonville, Fla., sits high and comfy
in the SUV and stares into the camera:
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a word for a city that doesn't plan for its future:
Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   The TV ad then cuts to the downtown Atlanta traffic at rush
hour. Traffic stalls. Horns honk. Commuting hell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their traffic congestion is among the worst in the nation,''
Mayor John Delaney intones. ``Years ago, Atlanta was called a city
on the rise.''
</P>
<P>
   He wraps up the 30-second commercial with, ``We can't let
Atlanta happen here.''
</P>
<P>
   The ad is ammunition Delaney and his allies are using to
persuade voters to support The Better Jacksonville Plan, a
half-cent sales tax referendum on the ballot today. If approved, as
expected, it would help raise more than $2 billion for traffic,
environmental and economic development projects in Jacksonville,
pop. 700,000.
</P>
<P>
   The ad is persuasive.
</P>
<P>
   But it could anger metro Atlanta residents, seeing it as a
particularly virulent strain of Atlantis bash-itis. The affliction
crops up regularly across the Southeast, particularly during
election season.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians in Jacksonville, Nashville, Tenn; Memphis, Tenn.;
Charlotte, N.C.; Raleigh, N.C.; Greenville, S.C., and beyond love
to hate Atlanta. As the Southeast's economic and cultural
juggernaut, Atlanta is an easy target for the region's second-tier
municipal strivers.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the barbs serve as friendly banter between competing
towns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of it is envy, of course,'' says Bill McCoy, director of
the Urban Institute at the University of North Carolina-Charlotte.
``Envy of the development and growth. Envy, partially, of the job
creation. And it's the New South city that got the Olympics.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the criticism, though, is dead on: Traffic is lousy
here. And metro Atlanta leaders have done such a poor job planning
for growth that the federal government cut off road-building money
for two years.
</P>
<P>
   The metro region loses 50 acres of tree cover daily. Commuters
average a nation-leading 34 miles a day behind the wheel. Daily
smog alerts are routine during the summer. And more than 880,000
newcomers flocked to the 20-county metro Atlanta region during the
1990s, crowding schools and roads.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't explain the churlish, anti-Atlanta diatribes,
like those spewed during Nashville's mayoral contest last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I talk about Atlanta, I talk about a place that people
work so that they can earn enough money so they can live somewhere
else,'' mayoral candidate Murray Philip said during the campaign.
His Web site's motto: ``Committed to stopping the move to become an
Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   Philip lost the election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atlanta has become the prime symbol for metropolitan
'sprawl,''' another candidate, Richard Fulton, wrote in his
Vision-In-Action Plan.
</P>
<P>
   Fulton lost, too.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta is ``universal shorthand for urban sprawl,'' candidate
Bill Purcell said. ``I don't have to spend a lot of time plotting
out for people what can go wrong with a city's development.''
</P>
<P>
   During a televised debate, Purcell said: ``I don't want to be
Atlanta, either. Anyone who wants to be Atlanta, obviously, could
leave right now and, assuming I-24 is open, could be there
tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Purcell won.
</P>
<P>
   Nashville's new mayor didn't return phone calls last week. But
Purcell insists he's not anti-Atlanta. ``I don't consider it
Atlanta bashing,'' he told the Wall Street Journal. ``It's simply a
shared thought.''
</P>
<P>
   Shared, obviously, by many, including Georgia politicians who
have long played the anti-Atlanta, anti-Sin City card. Every state
harbors an anti-capital bias, of course. But it's rare when a
capital area's own politicians trash the capital, as former Fulton
County Commission Chairman Mitch Skandalakis did when he ran for
lieutenant governor in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kick Atlanta's ass,'' Skandalakis said in a commercial, ``and
bring it in line before the city of Atlanta kills the state.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta boosters chuckle at the criticism. Better to be talked
about, they say, than ignored.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason we have our problems is because so many people are
attracted to the region,'' said Bill Thornton, assistant executive
director of the Georgia Municipal Association. ``We must be doing
something right.''
</P>
<P>
   Pat McCrory, the boyish mayor of Charlotte who is not above
dissing Atlanta, agrees. Along with a hundred other North Carolina
movers and shakers, McCrory visited Atlanta earlier this year to
experience firsthand the region's sprawl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have spoken both good and bad about Atlanta,'' said McCrory,
who got caught in a traffic jam during his visit. ``Charlotte has
an advantage over Atlanta because we can learn what didn't work in
Atlanta. ... I've said on the campaign trail that I don't want to
repeat Atlanta's mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynn Wheeler admits to a schizophrenic relationship with
Atlanta. The long-time Charlotte City Council member and frequent
Atlanta visitor fears Charlotte isn't learning from Atlanta's
land-use and road-building mistakes. Yet she loves Atlanta's
big-city esprit, especially the shopping amenities found at Lenox
Square and Phipps Plaza.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I take a little drive around, to find what's
redeeming about Atlanta, I can't find it,'' said Wheeler, a
Charlotte mayoral aspirant. ``The development in Buckhead is not
visually appealing and the congestion is overwhelming.''
</P>
<P>
   Worried her comments might come across as too harsh, Wheeler
backpedaled. McCrory too insisted he wasn't denigrating Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Even Jacksonville's mayor professed great affection for Atlanta
a half dozen times during a 10-minute interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love your city. I love your city. I don't love your
traffic,'' Delaney said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that he visits Atlanta maybe six times each year for
business or pleasure. Delaney said Jacksonville admires Atlanta as
a boy admires an older brother. He gushed over Atlanta's cultural
offerings. Heck, even some of his best friends, he said, live in an
Atlanta suburb.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our hope,'' Delaney said, ``is to be come Atlanta without the
warts.''
</P>
<P>
   ON THE WEB: For more information on Jacksonville's referendum,
go to www.betterjax.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
