<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMAZON-PRIVACY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMAZON.COM REVISES PRIVACY POLICY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHANIE STOUGHTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Amid growing controversy over consumer privacy online,
Amazon.com Inc. revised its privacy policy, carefully detailing how
it now uses customers' personal information and how it may sell
that data in the future.
</P>
<P>
   In a new privacy statement now posted on Amazon.com's Web site,
the Internet's biggest merchant informs shoppers that it may hand
over their information if it sold some or all of its businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the unlikely event that Amazon.com Inc., or substantially
all of its assets are acquired, customer information will of course
be one of the transferred assets,'' the company wrote last week.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com's decision comes at a time when federal regulators
are closely monitoring the information-gathering practices of Web
sites. As a leader in the online marketplace, selling everything
from books to washing machines, Amazon.com also has become known
for its skills in mining customer data.
</P>
<P>
   In July, the Federal Trade Commission sued Waltham-based
Toysmart.com Inc. after the online toy seller collapsed and then
tried to sell customer data _ despite promising its consumers it
would never do so. Both sides have agreed to a settlement, but the
case remains in limbo mainly because no serious buyer has stepped
forward.
</P>
<P>
   David Cooperstein, an analyst with Forrester Research of
Cambridge, Mass., said Amazon.com may be trying to avoid the same
sort of legal entanglements that Toysmart.com now faces.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're trying to make their policy more visible, so they
don't get slammed later,'' Cooperstein said. ``If they come clean
on what they plan to do with the data, people can't complain
later.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, industry observers have been highly critical of
Amazon.com's privacy statement, saying it was too lengthy and vague
to help online shoppers. Under the former policy, Amazon.com told
customers it did not sell or swap their personal information. But
it added that it might decided to do so in the future ``with
trustworthy third parties.''
</P>
<P>
   In Amazon.com's revamped privacy statement, the Seattle company
now provides details on its data collection practices and where
that information might end up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We value the trust our customers place in us, and we wanted
them to have as clear a picture as possible of what we're doing and
not doing when it comes to the information they give us,'' Jeff
Bezos, chief executive of Amazon.com, said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   With more than 23 million customers, Amazon.com has an enviable
database of names, addresses, e-mail addresses, and shopping
records. As a customer peruses its Web site, Amazon.com also can
track customers as they click on items such as the latest Harry
Potter book or the ``Complete Idiot's Guide to Sex on the Net.''
</P>
<P>
   In the new policy statement, Amazon.com revealed that it has
e-mailed offers to ``selected groups of Amazon.com customers on
behalf of other businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com also shares customer information with its partners,
including companies that help Amazon.com fill orders, deliver
packages and analyze data. And the company may receive information
about customers from other sources and then add that data to its
own files.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Cooperstein said Amazon.com's clarified privacy policy
should help the company in the long term as consumer advocates and
federal regulators continue to scrutinize Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   But, ``in the short term, customers may look at the policy and
decide not to do business with them,'' said Cooperstein.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
