<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, Sept. 5, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An autumnal air mass will encompass most of the Middle West and
Northeast Tuesday as sprawling high pressure moves southeast from
Ontario. Despite ample sunshine, daytime temperatures will average
10 to 15 degrees below normal over most of the region. Brisk
breezes from the Northeast will amplify the chill near the coast.
As winds diminish at night, scattered frost will develop in many
rural valleys near the central and northern Appalachians.
</P>
<P>
   Locally heavy showers and thunderstorms will persist in the
sultry air from northern Florida to the Carolina coast. Farther
west, it will not be as hot as recent days over the southern
Mississippi River Valley.
</P>
<P>
   In the West, sunny and very warm weather will cover southern
sections. Meanwhile, the interior Northwest will be cool and
showery.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: GLOOMY SUMMER &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   While heat in the South and West captured headlines throughout
the summer, the Northeast was exceptionally cool and dull. In
Binghamton, N.Y., the months of June, July and August together were
the second coolest on record. The record for summer chill was set
in 1992. The month of July was the coolest ever measured there.
Binghamton also had only 42 percent of the possible sunshine during
the three-month period, setting a new record for lack of summer
sunshine. Indeed, there were 100 fewer hours of sunshine than in
1977, the previous gloomiest summer. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
