<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0586 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-READER-AUTHOR-TOUR-2T     09-04 1250
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-READER-AUTHOR-TOUR-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF YOU LIKED THE BOOK, YOU'LL LOVE THE TOUR GUIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  By DOREEN CARVAJAL 
  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Paperback books have long made popular traveling companions, but
in this year of haute vacations truly avid readers bring their
favorite authors on journeys along with the antacid tablets and
rollaway luggage.
</P>
<P>
   For the package price of $2,650 plus additional airfare to
India, would-be travelers can glimpse one of the fabled wonders of
the world (the Taj Mahal) while led by one of the wonders of the
advice best-seller list (Deepak Chopra).
</P>
<P>
   Or they can join a roving-reading club guided personally by
Wayne W. Dyer, the author of self-help books like ``Your Erroneous
Zone,'' on an autumn trip to the Umbrian hills of Italy and the
mystical hometown of St. Francis of Assisi. On the 11-day, $3,947
tour of Italy and France, Dyer pledges to share his ``insights and
experiences of some of what life has taught me'' and an intimate
Yom Kippur dinner in the unlikely village of Lourdes, with its
Roman Catholic shrine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I generally avoid tours like the plague,'' said John McShane,
a Dallas lawyer and loyal reader of Dyer's books. Yet McShane is
poised to join the coming European trip after savoring an excursion
with Dyer to Peru's Machu Picchu in May and an earlier backpacking
safari in Tanzania with Richard J. Leider, the self-development
author.
</P>
<P>
   For McShane, these intellectual flights to far-off places are
the only chance to ``get to know your favorite author as a human
being.''
</P>
<P>
   Such curiosity is drawing travelers to locations they had no
intention of visiting. It's their opportunity to join an instant
book tour and to observe the mettle of literary heroes as they deal
with missing buses, lost tickets or a spontaneous decision by
fellow travelers to marry on the Nile.
</P>
<P>
   The list of writers who are turning tours into reading vacations
is dominated by self-help authors like Chopra and writers with a
spiritual bent like Neale Donald Walsch, the author of
``Conversations With God,'' who in June took readers on an
eight-day tour of Peru timed to coincide with the summer solstice
sunrise over Machu Picchu. But there are also published historians
and even a poet who are leading people on tours ripped from their
chapters, whether it be a stroll down Shankill Road in Belfast,
where violence erupted this summer among Protestant paramilitary
groups, a trip to Colonial Williamsburg in Virginia or a moonlit
meeting at the Jefferson Memorial in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Authors have long trolled for readers on luxury cruises,
delivering lectures and then moving on. But these tours are far
more physically and mentally demanding, with authors expected to
offer daily workshops and to play the role of host, one as genial
as Fantasy Island's Roarke.
</P>
<P>
   In November, Chopra, the best-selling sage of alternative
medicine, is taking about 350 of his readers on the road in two
separate tours, to Israel and his native India. He will lead
travelers on a pilgrimage that includes a de rigueur stop at the
Taj Mahal along with less standard perks like yoga sessions and
daily primordial sound meditation with Chopra himself.
</P>
<P>
   The tour, which is featured on the author's Web site,
www.chopra.com, also promises the possibility that participants
will meet the Dalai Lama (``subject to his holiness' schedule'').
The reading requirement for the trip is, naturally, Chopra's latest
title, ``How to Know God: The Soul's Journey Into the Mystery of
Mysteries.''
</P>
<P>
   Chopra said he started leading tours to places like Egypt, Bali
and India about six years ago. Typically his trips are a mix of
tourism and daily workshops on spiritual themes. Most of his trips
have been organized by travel operators, but his latest tour to
India is organized by the author's California-based Chopra Center
for Well Being.
</P>
<P>
   The transcontinental book tours do sap ``a lot of energy,''
Chopra said. ``But it gives me a lot of fulfillment to take people
to places where wisdom traditions were, in a sense, born. Last year
I took a group of people to Egypt, and we sailed along the Nile for
a week. I was able to explain to my readers the sources of my
information.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of these tours are organized by a handful of travel
operators like Visions Travel in Los Angeles, Power Places in St.
Croix and Cross Cultural Journeys in Sausalito, Calif. Visions
Travel started its literary matchmaking service early in 1979, but
initially it could attract only lesser-known authors, said Abbas
Nadim, the company's founder and president.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a shift in the last five years, with more
mainstream authors who are interested in doing this,'' said Nadim,
who is constantly trolling for authors to join tours. ``It's no
longer New Age per se _ the crystal and UFO authors. Before, our
clients used to be mostly middle-aged divorcees, 90 percent of them
women. But now, with a new breed of authors like Deepak Chopra and
Marianne Williamson, we're getting more professionals and
couples.''
</P>
<P>
   Typically, the authors strike individually tailored deals with
travel operators, charging a fee for participating or taking a
percentage of the profits plus, in some cases, free accommodations
for themselves and family members, Nadim said. Certain writers also
place restrictions on the number of fellow travelers, to as low as
15, but others are willing to lead tours with as many as 400.
</P>
<P>
   Such crowds can be a little disconcerting for some authors,
although the large group is divided into subsets. Walsch, a former
radio personality who has had a string of best sellers with his
``Conversations With God'' series, said he had participated in his
first tour in June at the invitation of Power Places with 150
travelers.
</P>
<P>
   He is scheduled to lead a retreat in Bali next May, but he said
that in the future he would probably limit his participation in
tours. ``It feels like it's the only one I will do; I wouldn't want
to do more than one a year,'' Walsch said. ``I want people to come
see me for $20 a lecture rather than $3,000 for a tour. It's kind
of a high-end activity, and I realized after I finished the
experience that it was lovely, but only for those readers who can
afford it, and that's a small percentage of my readers.''
</P>
<P>
   Other tours are purposely kept small. Frank Costello, the author
of three books on Irish history and a former press secretary to Ray
Flynn, the former Boston mayor, is currently helping to lead a tour
of Northern Ireland with 15 travelers who range in age from their
late 20s to early 70s and include a teacher, a judge, an investment
banker and a lawyer. The theme of the trip is the exploration of
the political divide in Northern Ireland. The seven-day tour has
taken the group on a stroll of Shankill Road with helicopters
hovering overhead, as well as to a lunch in Derry with John Hume, a
winner of the 1998 Nobel Peace Prize for his efforts to broker a
solution in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole thing is a work in progress,'' said Costello, who is
involved in a tour for the first time. ``It will give me future
ideas for writing, and it's prompting other topics I can write
about.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``If I have to describe what it's like for me, I'm
quite tired. It is a performance that requires stamina and the
focus of a lot of people asking questions and asking them sometimes
twice. It makes you a better listener because you've got to stay
ahead of the game.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Leider, the author of books like ``Repacking Your
Bags'' and ``The Power of Purpose,'' said he was reinvigorated by
his 23-day trips into the Tanzanian bush, where his dozen readers
can reflect on their lives amid the rhythms of African life,
hunting game with local tribes or digging for tubers.
</P>
<P>
   The friendships that develop between like-minded readers are
almost as critical to the trip as an author's participation.
</P>
<P>
   Beth Zacher, 39, a massage therapist from Venice, Calif., had no
desire to travel to Egypt but bought a ticket to join a tour of
more than 400 people led by Caroline Myss, author of self-help
books like ``Why People Don't Heal and How They Can'' and ``Anatomy
of the Spirit: The Seven Stages of Power and Healing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I went by myself because I had a friend who had to cancel,''
said Zacher, who will follow the same author to Ireland this month.
``I didn't want to go alone, but it turned out to be an incredible
experience for me. I was thrilled because it really brought me into
the group. I made a couple of lifelong friends on the journey.'' It
was on that trip that two of Zacher's fellow travelers
spontaneously decided to marry on a boat in the Nile.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the travelers sign up for more trips. Visions Travel
estimates that as many 70 percent of its clients return for other
book tours.
</P>
<P>
   Daisy Kennedy, a time-share saleswoman in Brigantine Island,
N.J., has joined her favorite author, Marianne Williamson, on four
trips _ to Egypt, Bali, Alaska and Greece _ and has plans to take
part in the author's ``Rebirth of a Nation'' tour of Williamsburg,
Va., and Washington in late October. That tour will also feature
the writer and historian R.B. Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've done the other kind of package tours that are like 20
different countries in 32 hours,'' Kennedy said. ``But they're not
memorable because there's no connection with the others. You tend
to be an individual, whereas with Marianne everybody knows everyone
in three days and it becomes a family.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Curtan, 59, is a veteran of three Myss tours. But Curtan, a
retired personal manager from Los Angeles, confessed that he wasn't
comfortable with some spiritual seekers drawn by the author's
message of healing. ``I come from eight years of Jesuit education,
and I'm not much into that stuff,'' he said. ``Caroline attracts
her share of the New Age seekers. I just don't hang out with
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Curtan has signed up for Myss' tour of Ireland even though he
only recently recovered from breaking an ankle on a hiking trip
during his last tour with her, in May, to Machu Picchu. He said he
would like to take more book tours because of the chance to be
``stimulated intellectually, spiritually, to have good
conversations.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like giving my spirit a real workout,'' he said. But
there's no ticket for his true desire.
</P>
<P>
   An avid fan of Harry Potter novels, Curtan said that what he
really yearned for was a magical tour: joining the young wizard's
creator, the author J.K. Rowling, for a disappearance at platform
9} for a scenic ride on the scarlet steam engine of the Hogwarts
Express.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-00 1722EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000904.0178 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0588 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-ULTIMATE-LAPTOP-2     09-04 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-ULTIMATE-LAPTOP-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAPTOPS AREN'T BLACKHOLES _ YET _ BUT THE ULTIMATE ONE MAY BE 
</HEADLINE>
   By GEORGE JOHNSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For all the corporate enthusiasm over the unveiling of each new
generation of computer chip (last month Intel announced that its
Pentium 4 would be packed with 42 million transistors performing as
many as 8.4 billion operations per second), consumers may be more
apt to feel a sense of dread. Once again the expensive desktop
computers and laptops they were so proud of have become outmoded,
destined to join the scrap piles of unsalable equipment
accumulating in closets everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Moore's law, which holds that computing power doubles
approximately every 18 months, therefore sometimes seems less a
blessing than a curse. But the law cannot hold forever, and Seth
Lloyd, an associate professor of mechanical engineering at the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology, offers hope that the end is
in sight.
</P>
<P>
   In a paper in the current issue of Nature, Lloyd describes the
ultimate laptop _ a computer as powerful as the laws of physics
would allow. So energetic is this imaginary machine that using it
would be like harnessing a thermonuclear reaction. In the most
extreme version of this computer supreme, so much computational
circuitry would be packed into so small a space that the whole
thing would collapse from its own gravity forming a tiny black
hole, an object so dense that not even light can escape its
gravity.
</P>
<P>
   If that sounds like a rather dangerous device to hold on one's
lap _ ``Opening the lid,'' Lloyd warns, ``voids the warranty'' _
there is a serious purpose to his theoretical tour de force: to
plumb the absolute limits nature sets on computation.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing like Lloyd's Ultimate Laptop is likely to ever roll off
the assembly line at some future Apple or IBM. But his effort, part
of a relatively new discipline called the physics of information,
gives computer engineers an ideal to aim for. More importantly,
this exercise in extreme computer science may help deepen the
understanding of the connections between physics and information,
and explore the notion, popular among many theorists, that the very
processes of nature can be thought of as computations.
</P>
<P>
   Moore's Law, named for its formulator Gordon Moore, a founder of
Intel, has continued to hold true because of the dexterity with
which engineers have been able to inscribe smaller and smaller
circuitry onto silicon computer chips. As the components of the
circuits are squeezed closer and closer together, they can exchange
information at increasingly faster speeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have been predicting the demise of Moore's law pretty
much since it was posited in the early '60s because some
manufacturing technology was about to run out,'' Lloyd said. ``But
Moore's law is a law of human ingenuity rather than of nature.
Predictions of its demise have been wrong because people are
ingenious.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, engineers have continued to find ways to make the
circuits smaller and faster.
</P>
<P>
   The vanishingly tiny components on a chip can be thought of as
switches that can be in two positions, either on or off _
representing a bit of information, 1 or 0. Minuscule as they seem,
each of these devices is typically made of about a billion atoms.
But laboratories are already experimenting with computers in which
a bit is stored by a single atom that can spin clockwise or
counterclockwise, indicating a 1 or a 0. And who is to say that the
grain could not someday be even finer with subatomic particles like
quarks or gluons or even the hypothetical superstrings harnessed to
encode and manipulate information?
</P>
<P>
   But ultimately the limits of nature must prevail.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we believe the laws of physics,'' Lloyd said, ``then the
fundamental constants of nature should tell us where Moore's law
absolutely has to end, where we can't miniaturize any further.''
</P>
<P>
   Lloyd approached the problem like a consumer in the market for a
new laptop. ``If you're going out to buy a computer,'' he said,
``you have two basic questions: how fast is it and how much memory
space does it have?'' Those are the ingredients of computing power.
He assumed that his laptop would have about the same dimensions as
a contemporary one, weighing a kilogram, 2.2 pounds, and occupying
1 liter of space.
</P>
<P>
   First he set out to determine how fast his ultimate laptop could
compute. The limiting factor here is energy: the faster a computer
runs, the more voracious its appetite. So what would be the maximum
possible energy available to a portable machine?
</P>
<P>
   One could speculate endlessly on the future of battery
technology. Seeking a more fundamental answer, Lloyd looked to
Einstein's special theory of relativity. If every particle of the
laptop's kilogram of mass is converted into energy according to the
equation E(EQ)mc2 , the answer is 8.9874 x 1016 joules _ or in more
familiar terms, 25 million megawatt-hours, the amount of energy
produced by all the world's nuclear power plants in 72 hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``The machine would be cannibalizing its own mass to perform its
operations,'' Lloyd mused. No engineer from Eveready or Duracell
could ever squeeze more juice from a chunk of matter.
</P>
<P>
   There would be obvious practical considerations to controlling
(and computing with) what would amount to thermonuclear fusion.
(Lloyd speculated that the computer's ``circuitry'' might consist
of electrons and antimatter positrons, signaling each other with
gamma rays.) But the details are unimportant. Ultimate computer
science is not about what is probable but what is possible. The
rest can be left to the engineers.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The next step was to determine the maximum speed one can get
from all that energy _ how rapidly the little switches can be
flipped between 1 and 0, carrying out their calculations. Here
Lloyd turned to quantum mechanics, the quirky rules that govern the
behavior of subatomic particles _ specifically, Heisenberg's
Uncertainty Principle, which shows how time is related to energy.
One multiplies pi by the number called Planck's constant and
divides by twice the available energy. Applied to the ultimate
laptop, the answer is 5.4258 x 1050 operations per second _ about
10,000 trillion trillion trillion times speedier than the Pentium
4. A computer that fast could never be obsolete _ not in this
universe, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   These limits would hold true no matter what kind of
technological breakthroughs lie ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter whether you're computing with vacuum tubes
or transistors or using quarks and gluons or something even more
exotic like superstrings,'' Lloyd said. Relativity and quantum
mechanics promise that is as fast as the ultimate laptop can be.
</P>
<P>
   Nor does it matter how the computer is designed. The energy can
be used to power one extremely fast processor or many slower ones.
Either way, the maximum possible number of operations per second is
the same.
</P>
<P>
   Now that he had put an upper limit on speed, Lloyd wanted to see
how big he could make the machine's memory _ how many bits of
information could be stored and manipulated at those blazing
speeds. Every atom or even every electron could be used to register
a 1 or a 0, depending on which way it was spinning. But to store
the maximum amount of information, the little processors would have
to be free to assume as many different states as possible. At
intense energies, information might be encoded not just by the spin
of a particle but also by the speed and direction in which it was
moving inside the machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to take full advantage of the memory space available,
the ultimate laptop must turn all its matter into energy,'' Lloyd
explained. ``A typical state of the ultimate laptop's memory looks
like a thermonuclear explosion or a little piece of the Big Bang!
Clearly, packaging issues alone make it unlikely that this limit
can be obtained, even setting aside the difficulties of stability
and control.''
</P>
<P>
   An object like this, so packed with energy that its particles
are as free as they can possibly be, is said to be in a state of
maximum entropy. Though more commonly thought of as a measure of
disorder _ a vaporized laptop being less orderly than one at room
temperature _ entropy can also be used to calculate the amount of
information something can hold. (The orderly atoms in a crystal can
occupy fewer possible states and hold less information than the
swarming atoms in a gas.)
</P>
<P>
   For the ultimate laptop, the maximum entropy corresponds to an
information capacity of about 2.13 x 1031 bits _ a billion trillion
times more than today's laptops.
</P>
<P>
   Achieving so vast a memory might not be as unrealistic as it
sounds. In a kilogram of matter there are approximately 1,025
atomic nuclei, each of which could store a bit without vaporizing
the entire mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``One can get quite close to the ultimate physical limit of
memory without having to resort to thermonuclear explosions,''
Lloyd said.
</P>
<P>
   Until this point, Lloyd had been constraining himself to a
laptop with a volume of one liter. By imagining it even smaller, he
knew, he could pack the kilogram of particle-size components even
tighter, speeding up the information flow and shortening the time
it takes to do long, step-by-step calculations. He would be
sacrificing memory (there would be less room to store information)
for speed _ a common tradeoff in designing computers.
</P>
<P>
   So in the final act of his thought experiment, he programmed the
ultimate laptop to solve a formidable problem (cracking a secret
code or something like that) and imagined it shrinking and
shrinking _ to the size of a wallet, then a credit card, then a
postage stamp. Smaller and smaller until its radius is a mere
centimeter (10-2 meters), then a millionth of a meter (10-6 ), then
a billionth (10-9 ).
</P>
<P>
   When the laptop has shrunk to 10-27 meters (a billionth the size
of a proton), it crosses what is called the Schwarzschild radius:
So much mass is packed into so little space that the whole thing
collapses, sucking itself into a tiny black hole.
</P>
<P>
   Some people may be convinced that they already own a black hole
laptop, imploding at the worst possible moments and irretrievably
swallowing data. Owning the real thing would surely be even worse.
</P>
<P>
   According to some theories, however, information thrown down a
black hole does not disappear, but is displayed on the hole's
surface. Each pixel of this screen would occupy one square Planck
length, 10-35 by 10-35 square meters, the smallest area conceivable
by the laws of physics.
</P>
<P>
   Some theorists, in fact, believe that the information about
everything that falls into any black hole is projected in this
manner _ that each one of these sink holes is, in a sense,
processing information. Taking the vision even further, some
imagine all the particles in the universe trading bits of data as
readily as they trade energy _ the universe as a computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hope that the long-term consequence of this work is
not building a black hole computer, which would be a dangerous
thing to do,'' Lloyd said, ``but seeing whether we can understand
how nature itself processes information.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
