<HEADLINE>
HINTS OF ALZHEIMER'S FOUND IN THE NOSE 
</HEADLINE>
 
 (ATTN: Pa., Ohio, Mass.)  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In recent months, researchers have pointed to possible signals
of Alzheimer's disease that could allow doctors to detect the
ailment before symptoms start. They have spoken of small areas of
the brain that appear to shrink, and psychological tests that yield
subtle clues.
</P>
<P>
   Now scientists think they may have found another clue: smell.
</P>
<P>
   Writing in this month's American Journal of Psychiatry,
researchers say that problems identifying aromas may indicate early
Alzheimer's, but only when the patients do not realize that
something is amiss with the sense of smell. A sense of smell often
declines with age.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. D.P. Devanand, who practices at the New York State
Psychiatric Institute and teaches at Columbia, based the theory on
a study of 90 patients who were suffering memory problems or
cognitive impairment.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers kept track of 77 of the patients for about two years
and found that 19 ended up with Alzheimer's.
</P>
<P>
   The patients were given a multiple-choice test in which they
were exposed to 40 smells, among them peanuts and menthol, and
asked to identify them.
</P>
<P>
   After analyzing the results, Devanand observed that while a poor
sense of smell was not a predictor for Alzheimer's, patients who
did badly on the test, but said they had no problems with their
sense of smell, appeared more likely to develop the disease.
</P>
<P>
   CHILDBIRTH: New Guidelines for Reducing Caesareans &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With the rate of Caesarean sections on the rise, a leading group
of obstetricians has issued guidelines that may reduce the number
of operations.
</P>
<P>
   This month, the federal Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention announced that, for the third year in a row, surgically
assisted deliveries were up, after a period of decline that began
in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 3.9 million births in this country in 1999, 22 percent
were Caesarean, the study found. That represented a 17 percent
decline in vaginal deliveries.
</P>
<P>
   The study prompted a series of recommendations by the American
College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists. The group cautioned
that simply comparing Caesarean rates from hospital to hospital was
unwise, because some hospitals have a higher concentration of
at-risk women more likely to require the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   But the group said there were steps hospitals could take to
reduce the number of such operations. Among them: improved training
for residents and postresidents in how to assist vaginal delivery
with tools like forceps and vacuum devices.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, the group said, hospital management decisions may
affect the Caesarean rates. Increasing the presence of nurses and
other employees who support women in labor can also increase the
number of natural deliveries, the researchers said.
</P>
<P>
   OUTCOMES: For Exercise, Every Minute Counts
</P>
<P>
   People who want to start exercise programs but feel they don't
have enough time or energy to begin should think again.
</P>
<P>
   A new study suggests that physical activity that lasts just 15
minutes, if done often enough, may be as beneficial as longer
workouts. The report appeared last week in Circulation: Journal of
the American Heart Association.
</P>
<P>
   The total amount of time spent exercising, not the length of
each session, appears to be most important, the researchers said.
</P>
<P>
   They said they hoped their findings would encourage out-of-shape
people daunted at the prospect of one-hour or even half-hour
workouts.
</P>
<P>
   The findings were based on surveys taken in 1988 and 1993 of
more than 7,000 men with an average age of 66. The men were asked
to give their medical histories and to describe their exercise
routines.
</P>
<P>
   The surveys suggested that those who worked out in short
sessions had the same heart-disease risk as those who worked out
longer, as long as the same amount of energy was expended in the
short sessions.
</P>
<P>
   In a second study published in Circulation, researchers found
that people who reported engaging in more intense forms of physical
activity had a lower risk of heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   People who reported walking three or more miles per week,
considered moderate, had a 10 percent reduction in risk, the study
said.
</P>
<P>
   But those who engaged in activities like jogging, tennis,
swimming or aerobics showed decreases in risk of as much as 20
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The studies involved participants in the Harvard Alumni Study.
</P>
<P>
   SYMPTOMS: Sick in the Head, and in the Stomach
</P>
<P>
   Feeling sick to one's stomach may have more to do with the brain
than the stomach. Researchers at Ohio State University say in a new
study that they may have uncovered the reason that, often, people
feel nauseated, even though what ails them has nothing to do with
their digestive tracts.
</P>
<P>
   The culprit may be a brain chemical called tumor necrosis
factor, or TNF, which the immune system releases at the first sign
that the body is coming under attack. The factor acts on a part of
the brain stem that regulates the digestive tract, including
vomiting, said the study published in The American Journal of
Physiology: Gastrointestinal and Liver Physiology.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think probably the mechanism evolved to protect us from
eating fairly nasty things,'' said Dr. Richard C. Rogers, a
neuroscientist at the university, who wrote the paper with his
wife, Gerlinda Hermann, a research scientist.
</P>
<P>
   While that trait is useful for illnesses caused by poor food, it
is unclear how, if at all, it affects people suffering from other
ailments that commonly cause nausea, like chronic arthritis, AIDS
and cancer.
</P>
<P>
   BEHAVIOR: Fighting Off Fevers, Aggressively
</P>
<P>
   Real men don't get colds.
</P>
<P>
   Or they should be less susceptible to them, anyway, because a
new study finds that tough guys seem to have tougher immune
systems, the body's natural defense for fighting off infections,
viruses and the like.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers from Pennsylvania State University and the
University of Nebraska have found that moderately aggressive men
had higher levels of two types of lymphocytes that help control the
immune response.
</P>
<P>
   The findings, published in a recent issue of Psychosomatic
Medicine, were based on a study of 4,415 men ages 30 to 48.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers asked the men a series of questions to determine
how aggressive they were. The men were asked about actions as
diverse as skipping school and fighting with weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Although the men who were more aggressive were found to have
stronger immune systems, highly aggressive men appeared to lose the
benefit.
</P>
<P>
   There are several possible explanations. Historically, man in
the wild fared best by being aggressive in finding food and
protecting his family. But those behaviors, the researchers said,
risked injury _ and infection. Perhaps in response, stronger immune
systems evolved.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Douglas A. Granger, an author of the paper who teaches
biobehavioral health at Penn State, said the researchers' data was
limited to men, but he noted that, in general, women appeared to
have stronger immune systems than men.
</P>
</TEXT>
