   CAMPAIGN-DEBATE (Undated) _ Developments on plans for the
presidential candidates' debate. By Peter Marks.
</P>
<P>
   FIRES-INMATES (Yellow Pine, Idaho) _ Back in Utah, they are
inmates at Bluffdale State Prison. But out here in the fire zone,
they strut proudly in black T-shirts proclaiming themselves members
of the Flame 'N Go Hotshots. Convicts make up a surprising portion
of the armies of men battling wildfires across the West this
summer. One in six of the firefighting teams now deployed across
the region in this devastating fire season is drawn from a state
prison, according to federal officials, with convicts from places
like California and Nevada paid just $1 an hour. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   LEBANON-ELECTION (Beirut) _ Final election results showed Monday
that the victory of billionaire tycoon Rafik Hariri was so sweeping
that his chances of being named the new prime minister have
increased _ which could put him on a collision course with the
president. By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-JAPAN-GYMNAST (Tokyo) _ On Naoya Tsukahara, whose
performance in Sydney may help restore some of the glory Japan
found when the country seemed to be a breeding ground for top male
gymnastic talent. That was in the 1960s and '70s, when Mitsuo
Tsukahara, Naoya's father, was a member of the men's team that was
the only real challenger to the powerful, state-supported gymnasts
from behind the Iron Curtain. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
