<DOCNO> NYT20000904.0184 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 17:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0594 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-PROUST-BOOK-REVIEW-NY     09-04 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROUST-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
` MARCEL PROUST ' :   A LIFE TRANSFORMED, MARCEL'S WAY 
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds.: Publication notes are at end of review.) 
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Marcel Proust never cared much for the art of biography. ``A
book,'' he wrote, ``is the product of a different self from the one
we manifest in our habits, our social life and our vices.'' In his
own case, certainly, there was a ludicrous gap between his life and
art. A sycophantic snob and posturing dandy, he frittered away his
youth _ and his father's money _ trying to ingratiate himself with
the idle rich; in his masterpiece, ``Remembrance of Things Past,''
he would transform those frivolous experiences into a luminous
meditation on the nature of time and memory and loss.
</P>
<P>
   In his tedious new study of Proust, Jean-Yves Tadie _ the editor
of the Pleiade edition of ``Remembrance of Things Past'' _ seems to
share his subject's suspicion of biography. He whines that the
adult Proust never revealed his inner life in his correspondence,
and makes the odd complaint that George Painter, the author of the
best-known biography of the writer to date, succumbed ``without any
qualms'' to the temptation ``to draw from the novel in order to
explain, or understand, the life.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Tadie's own biography, it turns out to be quite devoid of
any compelling insight into Proust's character or work. Tadie
writes that he has tried ``to depict the individual in so far as he
is a type: the child of a middle-class family, a pupil at the Lycee
Condorcet, a student at the Ecole des Sciences Politiques, an
asthmatic, a `young poet' who wrote more letters than he received,
a person who took the waters at seaside resorts.'' In doing so, he
adds, he has tried to avoid ``the tedium of anecdotes that are too
specific'' _ a decidedly bizarre approach for any biographer, never
mind one writing the life of an author whose entire work was
grounded in a specificity of social and psychological detail.
</P>
<P>
   Although Tadie has done a persuasive job of explicating the
intellectual influences on Proust's work _ from Balzac and Zola
through Ruskin, Wagner and Carlyle _ he has failed in this volume
to give the reader an appreciation of ``Remembrance of Things
Past'' or the workings of the novelist's imagination. ``Marcel
Proust,'' which has been clumsily translated from the French by
Euan Cameron, lacks the eloquence and evocative power of Painter's
two-volume biography (originally published in 1959 and 1965) and
even pales next to William C. Carter's plodding biography (``Marcel
Proust,'' Yale University Press), published earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   The author's claim that ``nowhere in this lengthy book will you
come across a single insignificant fact'' is credible only if you
think of this volume as a kind of doctoral thesis on the
step-by-step evolution of ``Remembrance of Things Past'' _ that is,
a blow by blow by blow account of how the novel developed from one
draft to another; how friends, acquaintances, trips and
observations were gradually worked into the ever-expanding
manuscript. Tadie assumes that the reader not only is familiar with
every aspect of the 3,000-page ``Remembrance of Things Past'' but
also possesses a working knowledge of such earlier works as ``Jean
Santeuil'' and ``Contre Sainte-Beuve.'' He does nothing to convey
the power _ or weaknesses _ of Proust's books; nor does he
illuminate the author's compulsive need to translate his
experiences into words.
</P>
<P>
   As for his observations on Proust's emotional life, they tend to
fall into two categories. Bland generalization: ``like all
parents,'' Tadie observes, ``his own inspired in him love as well
as hatred, imitation and opposition, inspiration and the will to
destroy.'' And patronizing speculation: of the novelist's fear of
rats, he writes, ``Had Proust been psychoanalyzed, which he never
was, the psychoanalysts would no doubt furnish an explanation for
it, linking it to anality and masochism.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to many earlier biographers who have emphasized the
role that Proust's obsessive relationship with his mother played in
shaping his sensibility, Tadie argues that it was his father, an
eminent physician, who was ``present throughout his work.'' He
notes that Proust adopted his father's medical outlook in defining
love as an illness or disease and that many of his descriptions
were couched in the language of symptoms and diagnoses.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Tadie's other observations will be highly familiar to
readers of earlier biographies. Once again we hear about Proust's
efforts to insinuate himself into high society. Once again we hear
about his frustrating pursuit of young men, who withdrew from his
suffocating need for control (the most notable, perhaps, being the
mechanic Alfred Agostinelli, who became a primary inspiration for
the character Albertine). And once again we hear about his
asthmatic retreat into a cork-lined room from which he would emerge
with increasing infrequency.
</P>
<P>
   Like Painter, Tadie tries to show the real-life antecedents of
characters in ``Remembrance of Things Past'' and trace the genesis
of particular novelistic incidents. And like Ronald Hayman (the
author of a succinct one-volume life of Proust that appeared in
1990) he emphasizes the role that World War I had on the shape of
the novel: by forcing a delay in publication, it gave him time to
expand and elaborate his story, to create the famously layered
architectural edifice the book became.
</P>
<P>
   Painter and Hayman, however, said all this with considerably
more style and acuity in their respective books. In contrast,
Tadie's biography feels like a ponderous academic exercise _ an
exercise designed not for the reader's edification or pleasure but
to showcase the author's own erudition and prodigious capacity for
research.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   MARCEL PROUST: A Life.
</P>
<P>
   By Jean-Yves Tadie.
</P>
<P>
   Translated by Euan Cameron. 986 pages. Viking. $40.00
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
