<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0596 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-DESERT-ARTS-PILGRIMS-     09-04 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DESERT-ARTS-PILGRIMS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEON SURREALISM REQUIRED; CLOTHING OPTIONAL 
</HEADLINE>
 
 (ATTN: Nev.)  By JESSE MCKINLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLACK ROCK DESERT, Nev. _ It was the middle of the night in the
middle of nowhere, and under a frigid Nevada sky about 75 men and
women wearing nothing but body paint and their own bravado were
cavorting on the barren lake bed here in temperatures that would
make your average coyote flinch.
</P>
<P>
   The occasion was the first _ and only _ performance of ``Phallus
of the Man and Yoni Gate,'' an electronic opera composed by Pepe
Ozan, dealing with the complex relationships between men and women
and of course the lost city of Atlantis. Besides the naked dancers,
the opera featured two abstract sculptures of genitals, a calypso
band and a narrator prone to lines like ``We now must consult the
Atlantian mystic.'' All of which left its standing-room-only crowd
_ there are no seats in the desert _ with a profound sense of awe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what it means,'' said one smiling spectator who
would not divulge his name. ``But it sure is different.''
</P>
<P>
   That sentiment was the common refrain and attraction of many of
the 25,000 visitors who flooded this year's Burning Man festival,
the annual alternative-arts fair that has steadily become one of
the nation's foremost showcases for art of the obscure, the
outrageous and the just plain odd.
</P>
<P>
   The festival, which ended on Monday after a weeklong run on this
arid strip of desert some 120 miles north of Reno, has an artistic
manifesto of ``radical self-expression.'' Visitors looking for
surreal sights were not likely to be disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   The festival was founded in 1986 by Larry Harvey, a Bay Area
artist who built and cremated an 8-foot-tall effigy of a man on
Baker Beach in San Francisco. The annual ritual quickly evolved
into a popular summer festival for artists and hipsters, and, over
the years, Harvey's simple effigy has grown into a 40-foot wood and
neon extravaganza, burned to the cheers of thousands of rabid fans
on the Saturday before Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   The gathering moved here in 1990 after crowds and fire worries
prompted organizers to seek more wide open spaces. As news of the
festival has spread, Burning Man has become a yearly pilgrimage for
thousands of performers and artists as well as Internet techies,
adventurous yuppies and other counterculture aficionados, many of
whom trek hundreds or even thousands of miles to attend. Flags from
Sweden, Israel, Italy and Ireland billowed over camps this year, as
did rainbow banners and pirate skulls.
</P>
<P>
   On a walk across the desert fairgrounds, called ``the playa,'' a
casual visitor might encounter anything from a school of neon fish
suspended by wire on the heads of a dozen bicyclists to a
50-foot-long mechanical dragon replete with fire-breathing skills
and a New Orleans brass band playing ``You Are My Sunshine'' inside
its metal gut. Turn the other way, and you may find yourself facing
a satyr, an angel or maybe just another naked person. (It's not
just opera anymore.)
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere cars with complete cocktail lounges mounted on their
frames zipped across the desert plain and an RV outfitted with a
pair of 15-foot Tesla coils spit tendrils of lightning into the
air. There was even more traditional work like ``The Faces of
Man,'' by Dan Das Mann, with a series of three tall sculptures made
of wood, copper and grass. Turned toward the center of the camp,
the copper face also included a pair of burning eyes from which a
steady stream of burning fuel fell. And there were the spontaneous
entertainments, ranging from campfire conga sessions to heartfelt
post-Beat poetry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the ultimate in freedom and expression,'' said Darin
Greyerbiehl, a San Franciscan who was standing outside his campsite
watching some 300 topless women, all decorated with variously
colored swirls of the festival's ubiquitous body paint, ride by on
bicycles. ``You can either go look for it, or wait and it'll come
to you. Either way it's something you're not going to see anywhere
else.''
</P>
<P>
   One Burning Man volunteer who went by the name Swervegirl said:
``Gearheads, punks, freaks, geeks, hippies _ they all come here. It
is radically inclusive.''
</P>
<P>
   The festival's free-to-be-you-and-me attitude attracts a variety
of other pleasure seekers, namely middle-aged nudists and other
sexual adventurers. Not surprisingly it also draws many fans of
illegal psychedelic drugs like LSD and ecstasy. Officers from the
Bureau of Land Management, which shares jurisdiction over the land
where the festival is held with the local police, issued about
three dozen citations for drug use, said Jim Graham, a festival
spokesman. He said there were also a handful of arrests on drug
charges.
</P>
<P>
   Burning Man officials say their event is unique among
alternative events, pointing out its duration _ a week, not a night
_ and its emphasis on community. The age range of Burning Man
visitors also tends to be older, with about half falling between 25
and 35 and at least 10 percent older than 45. That range might be a
result of the festival's sometimes steep entrance fees _ this
year's latecomers paid $250 _ a price that Burning Man officials
say is justified by the cost of renting the land, fulfilling
federal environmental obligations and running the camp.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most significant, there are the daily challenges of the
desert, where temperatures can soar above 110 degrees by midday and
then plummet to near freezing at night. (Burning Man may be the
only festival in the world where the ticket stub reads, ``You
voluntarily assume the risk of serious injury or death by
attending.'')
</P>
<P>
   The weather during the weekend festivities included torrential
rains, a six-hour dust storm and overnight temperatures in the low
40s. About 1,000 people left on Friday after 50-mph winds ripped up
tent stakes and sent desert detritus flying. Several events were
postponed or canceled because of weather.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Being desert bound, Burning Man visitors also trade amenities
like indoor plumbing and running water for the less glamorous
trappings of propane stoves and overflowing Port-a-Potties. Ice and
water are at a premium. Dust-caked hair and mud-battered shoes are
the norm, as are dust masks when the wind kicks up billowing clouds
of white sand. Tents are packed side to side, and noise often
echoes through the night.
</P>
<P>
   Laid out on a giant circular grid stretching across 5 square
miles, the festival campgrounds, called Black Rock City, include a
24-hour cafe (latte: $3), an airstrip, a pair of daily newspapers,
a medical area and more than half a dozen ham radio stations. The
city is divided into streets and avenues, complete with street
signs. In the center of the circle is a large area devoted &UR;  &LR; to the
outdoor sculpture that is the festival's defining symbol, the
40-foot Burning Man.
</P>
<P>
   Those near the center of the circle are asked to establish
``theme camps,'' with attractions ranging from trampoline sports to
a yoga center devoted to Elvis. Many of these camps are elaborate,
with mini-nightclubs and lounges tucked into tents and outdoor
stages flowing from the fronts of trailers. Other theme camps
include steel towers, wooden pyramids or makeshift movie houses.
What results is a giant circular promenade dotting the desert night
with flashing lights and pounding music.
</P>
<P>
   As the mishmash of images might suggest, there is little stock
put in creating a cohesive message about the festival. Press
material for the festival, in fact, goes to lengths to say what
Burning Man is  &UR; not,  &LR; including ``a pagan event,'' ``a '90s
Woodstock'' or ``a hippie festival.'' Organizers prefer to call the
festival ``a populist phenomenon,'' ``a social experiment'' and
``an alternative to mass culture and consumer society.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday night, however, the only populist phenomenon at work
seemed to be pyromania. After ``the Burn,'' as the immolation of
the Burning Man is called, artists took turns torching their own
work, all to raucous cheers. Crowds roamed across the playa from
fire to fire, warming their hands against the flames and basking in
the satisfaction of another successful festival. In the distance
neon fish zipped and Tesla coils zapped, and primitive screams
filled the night. It was, in short, a scene to inspire big
thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you carry nothing else away from this,'' said Greyerbiehl,
``it's that this is a shining beacon for where the world could
go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
