<HEADER>
A0598 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-ALBATROSS-NYT &LR;      09-04 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-ALBATROSS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENTIST'S STUDY OF WANDERING ALBATROSSES MAY HELP THEIR
SURVIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
   By HENRY FOUNTAIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The wandering albatross did not earn its name by just sitting
around. The seabirds, the largest in the world, spend more than 90
percent of their life over the oceans of the Southern Hemisphere,
and through banding and satellite tracking, they have been shown to
travel tens of thousands of miles in a breeding season foraging for
food.
</P>
<P>
   But wandering albatrosses breed only once every two years, and
much less has been known about where they spend their nonbreeding,
or ``sabbatical,'' year in the Southern Ocean, the great unbroken
ring of water south of Africa, Australia and South America.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a French researcher has started to fill in some of the gaps
in the wandering albatross' existence. The birds, he discovered, do
not quite live up to their name: they do not wander aimlessly
during their sabbatical year. Rather, each tends to fly to its own
part of the ocean, often thousands of miles from its nesting
ground, and stays there until it is time to breed once again.
</P>
<P>
   ``From band recovery, we knew a few things about where these
birds were going,'' said the researcher, Henri Weimerskirch, of the
French Institute for Polar Research and Technology in Beauvoir,
France. ``But we hadn't known what the birds were doing during the
whole year.''
</P>
<P>
   Weimerskirch's work, reported in the journal Nature, is in the
preliminary stages, with data from only a few albatrosses collected
so far. But as more is learned about their travels, he said, more
might be done to protect them.
</P>
<P>
   For these days, wandering albatrosses often do not return from
their journeys. Instead, they become the incidental victims of
commercial fishers, including those for bluefin tuna and Antarctic
sea bass. The birds go after baited hooks on long lines as they are
played out by the fishing boats, and are dragged underwater to
their deaths as the lines sink.
</P>
<P>
   Mitigation measures, like weighting the lines so they sink more
quickly, have been practiced in some fisheries over the past
decade, but they have not been enough to protect the wandering
albatross or others of the roughly 20 albatross species in both the
northern and southern hemispheres.
</P>
<P>
   Wandering albatrosses have declined in all seven of their major
breeding grounds during the past several decades, to the point
where there are only about 15,000 pairs left (the birds mate for
life).
</P>
<P>
   Rosemary Gales, a marine biologist with the Tasmanian Fish and
Wildlife Service in Hobart, Australia, and an expert on the effect
of long-lines fishing on seabirds, said that knowledge of where the
birds spend their nonbreeding year could eventually lead to
regulations that would close parts of the Southern Ocean to fishing
at certain times of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ultimate goal would be to make the fishery ecologically
inert, with no bycatch problem,'' using various mitigation
techniques, Gales said.
</P>
<P>
   John Croxall, head of higher predator research with the British
Antarctic Survey, said Weimerskirch's work was a good start. The
goal would be to gather enough location data about the various
endangered albatross species, and then to overlay it with
information about fishing patterns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then the options are to restrict location or timing or method
of fishing, or some combination of all three,'' Croxall said.
</P>
<P>
   What has limited data collection in the past is the relatively
large expense and, given the limitations of battery life, relative
unreliability, of satellite tracking over long periods.
Weimerskirch, with his colleague Rory Wilson, is the first to use a
simpler, less power-gobbling technology, to log the birds' latitude
and longitude. It is one that was previously used to track some
marine creatures, and borrows a bit from a navigational method used
by sea captains of old.
</P>
<P>
   A band around the bird's leg is fitted with a small
battery-powered device, less than one inch square and weighing
under an ounce, that includes a light sensor, a clock set to the
starting location and a memory chip for storing data. The device
records the time of dusk and dawn every day, and from that
calculates day length, which can be used to determine latitude (the
length of a given day varying with north-south location).
</P>
<P>
   By comparing the time of dusk and dawn to the time at the
starting point, the device can also log longitude, just as sea
explorers once tracked how far east or west they had traveled from
the prime meridian at Greenwich, England, by carrying a clock set
to Greenwich time and comparing it with the local time.
</P>
<P>
   While not as accurate as satellite tracking, the light-sensing
device is precise enough to show the region of the Southern Ocean
where the birds are spending their time. And, Weimerskirch said,
his data so far shows that during their off-year, males and females
go separate ways. The females head north, toward more tropical
latitudes, while the males go toward Antarctica.
</P>
<P>
   For both sexes, the activity level is far lower than during the
breeding year, when the birds are constantly circling around their
nesting region. In the sabbatical year, with no need to gather food
for their families, they can ride the winds using their 10-foot
wingspan and expend less energy. And they are molting as well,
Weimerskirch noted, which makes flying difficult, adding more
incentive to take things easy.
</P>
<P>
   Just why the birds prefer one spot over others is not known. But
Weimerskirch speculated that they might be going to an area that
they know has food and where there is less competition. Since the
birds live 50 or 60 years, they have plenty of previous experience
to rely on.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-00 1800EDT &QL; 
