<HEADER>
A0599 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-RUSSIA-BARD-MUSIC-790     09-04 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-BARD-MUSIC-790&AMP;TRIMS(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODSTOCK ON THE VOLGA: PROTEST AGES INTO SINGALONG 
</HEADLINE>
   By SOPHIA KISHKOVSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ A sea of music fanatics and thrill-seekers drink and
sway blissfully to songs of peace and love in a muddy field. It
could be a Grateful Dead concert, or Woodstock just half a world
away. Call it Woodstock on the Volga.
</P>
<P>
   Every summer, thousands of Russians make the journey to the
Grushinsky Festival, known as Grusha, held on a riverbank between
two cities, Samara and Tolyatti, Russia's auto industry center. The
festival celebrates bard music, a genre identified with the Soviet
cultural thaw of the 1960s and the subsequent growth and popularity
of allegorical songs as a creative and spiritual outlet. Today
conditions are different, but the songs of contemporary bard
musicians seem to serve a similarly comforting purpose.
</P>
<P>
   Various theories trace the origins of bard music to Soviet
prison camp songs, soldiers' ballads, prerevolutionary romances and
even the songs of the wandering minstrels of centuries ago. Some
bard songs even sound like American country music, but by any
measure, Russians are much more likely than the average American to
pick up a guitar and sing with their friends, all of whom have
dozens, sometimes hundreds of songs committed to memory. It is all
part of the seemingly infinite national capacity to recite verse.
</P>
<P>
   Fans of bard songs even sound like Deadheads when they talk
about what the music means to them. One of those soaking up the
vibes with his wife and two small sons at this year's festival was
Mikhail Ovcharenko, owner of a bodyguard service in Samara.
``People don't communicate with each other enough,'' Ovcharenko
said. ``We live in a big crowd. Here everyone is equal, everyone is
naked.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``Songs always unite,'' he added. ``Everyone sings the same
song. Everyone is singing in the same harmony, in unison. Maybe
that's why there's such energy here. These songs are kind, they're
about love and family. Maybe it's a difficult time, maybe these are
cruder times, but here we're in concert.''
</P>
<P>
   Ovcharenko enjoyed music and vodka around a makeshift picnic
table built with friends who have been going to the festival for 20
years. Their leader, Valery Klyushkin, arrives two weeks in advance
to stake out their favorite spot. Every little tent city has its
own whimsical name, usually an inside joke, and its own traditions,
united by a repertory of the best-loved bard songs and other
musical favorites, like the Beatles. ``What we hear here lasts us
for the whole year,'' Klyushkin said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   This summer's 20th anniversary of the death of Vladimir
Vysotsky, a beloved actor and bard, has produced a host of
television retrospectives and concerts in his memory. Vysotsky's
angry songs about the degradation of Soviet life, sung in his raspy
voice at private gatherings and passed around on hissing
reel-to-reel recordings, were the soundtrack to a thwarted
generation.
</P>
<P>
   ``My life, a dumb thing,'' he sang of himself in one of his last
songs. Since his death from alcohol-induced heart failure,
Vysotsky's lyrics have all been published, a monument of him in a
Christlike pose has been put up in central Moscow, and he is
regarded as a kind of people's poet, quoted as often as Alexander
Pushkin and by a broader swath of people.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the enduring popularity of Vysotsky and other bards,
the genre has been declared dead as often as rock music has in the
United States. Critics charge that it has sold out to the
saccharine dictates of the market and been taken over by a
pseudocollective spirit that undermines the music. Some critics are
especially irritated by the fashion for singing bard songs in
chorus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now bard singing is like fascism,'' said Alexander Marchenko,
a Moscow musician and composer who has created arrangements for
contemporary bards. ``It's a chamber genre meant to be sung in the
kitchen. Now they want to make it into a mass genre and say it's so
spiritual.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, ``Songs of Our Century,'' a two-part easy-listening
collection of classics performed by popular bards in chorus and
with instrumentals, has topped Spice Girl knockoffs on the Russian
pop charts and inspired knockoffs and pirated editions of its own.
Helped by word of mouth, the first recording sold nearly 100,000
cassettes and CDs a month when it was released in early 1999 _ a
figure unheard of in Russia's struggling, payola-plagued pop music
industry.
</P>
<P>
   The bards behind ``Songs of Our Century'' call their work a
mission. ``In a time when the animal instinct rules, we must stand
against this,'' Sergei Nikitin told an audience of several thousand
at the start of a concert tour promoting part two of the
collection. ``I am absolutely certain these songs will live in the
21st century.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Galina Khomchik, a singer in the project who performs cover
versions of other bards, says that Russians today suffer from a
lack of honest friendship and love and that bard songs help
compensate for the lack of spirituality.
</P>
<P>
   Such qualities, it seems, are in demand outside Russia as well.
The concert tour has gone to New York, Seattle and San Francisco,
where emigres nostalgic for the bard tradition have sung along to
their favorite songs. Even non-Russians in former Soviet republics
still sing to the bards, in Russian, underscoring that it is a
quintessentially Soviet genre. Bards from Russia also tour the
Baltic countries, and festivals are held in Ukraine and Central
Asia.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site www.bards.ru, based in Krasnoyarsk in Siberia, has
the lyrics to 17,000 bard songs. In Moscow huge halls that do not
always sell out for pop stars are packed for the bards, and several
bard cafes serve blini and vodka to accompany live performances in
an intimate setting.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, in fact, bards are becoming professional
musicians who make a living performing. But hundreds of so-called
amateur song clubs around Russia remain centers of the bard
movement, which the Communist Party once tried to control.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``Our club was closed three times in Soviet times,'' said a
Smolensk bard, Alexander Makarenkov, who recalls having to get the
censor's approval for songs to be performed at festivals. In poorer
provincial cities like Smolensk, which is near the Belorussian
border, it is now lack of money that makes life hard for local
bards. As for the words, freedom of expression sometimes means they
have less of a message to convey.
</P>
<P>
   ``If before people sang in allegories, now we can speak
openly,'' said Sergei Pogorely, a bard from Karelia, a region
bordering Finland. ``Something has even been lost with this
possibility, just as literature has suffered.'' Bard songs suffered
less, he said, because they are one of the most democratic kinds of
Russian literature. And politics and pain are not completely absent
from today's lyrics. A song about the war in Chechnya took first
place at a bard festival in St. Petersburg this spring.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Stas Stanyulevich, a wholesale dairy products distributor who
organizes a festival in a forest outside Moscow in the early
autumn, says that what used to be a way of escaping the authorities
has became a way to fill a void that money cannot satisfy. ``Before
it was dangerous to talk in the city; the authorities didn't allow
it,'' Stanyulevich said. ``So people came out into the woods, where
they could talk and sing freely. In the first years of reform,
there was such a rush to make money. Now people either have it or
they don't. If they don't, they realize they won't. If they do,
they want to relax.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nouveau-riche Russians come out here with a car full of vodka.
Adventure travel has become very popular, the more extreme the
better. Now they want something for the soul.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
