<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZMAGS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Call it arena (naming) football
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Big business in the U.S. is spelled s-p-o-r-t-s.
</P>
<P>
   The average price a corporation was willing to pay to attach its
name to a sports arena or stadium rose to $5.6 million per year in
1999 from $2.7 million just two years earlier, Business Week (Sept.
11) says.
</P>
<P>
   Two decades of this deal making has created the likes of Arco
Arena (Sacramento), 3Com Park (San Francisco), RCA Dome
(Indianapolis), Continental Airlines Arena (New Jersey) and
Phillips Arena (Atlanta), with other companies scrambling to put
their names on remaining stadiums.
</P>
<P>
   Investors are unimpressed, however. A recent survey showed that
the shares of one-third of the companies whose names adorn sports
facilities fell after the deals were made.
</P>
<P>
   On a separate issue, Forbes (Sept. 18) says the values of 31 pro
football teams range between $741 million for the Washington
Redskins to $305 million for the Arizona Cardinals. The problem for
team owners, says Forbes, is that ``with the rich prices
professional football teams command these days, owners often have
to do their own two-minute drill: quickly increase revenue and pay
down a lot of debt.''
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Forbes profiles James Kennedy, chairman and chief
executive officer of Cox Enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   The upside of a crash
</P>
<P>
   The sky was once the limit for dot-coms. Now that they are back
down to earth, their future actually looks brighter, says Bloomberg
Personal Finance (September).
</P>
<P>
   ``The survivors of the bitter (correction) will be mean and lean
and able to take the entire Internet industry to ever-greater
heights,'' writes author Paul Erdman. But Erdman tells investors to
``beware of new IPOs of companies that do not promise to produce a
positive cash flow and profits within 18 months.''
</P>
<P>
   VC flush with cash
</P>
<P>
   Can entrepreneurs with non-tech, non-Internet companies find
venture capital _ or VC, as it's called? Inc. (September) says yes.
In 1999 alone, more than $3 billion in venture capital funds were
invested in non-tech companies, and 7 percent of all companies in
which venture capitalists invested were non-tech.
</P>
<P>
   A new global business
</P>
<P>
   Hostage taking has become a lucrative business, and top
corporate executives are among the favorite targets, says The
Economist (Sept. 8). Kidnapping for ransom has risen 70 percent in
the last eight years. Most are in Latin America, but kidnappings
have risen sharply in former Soviet Union states and in Asia. The
way to reduce kidnapping is to show that it does not pay, the
magazine says. Ideally that means capturing and punishing the
kidnappers, but it may also mean making it illegal to pay a ransom,
as in Italy and some other countries.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
