<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWS ABOUT THE NET: 09.05.00
</P>
<P>
   APBOnline fails to attract bid
</P>
<P>
   Nokia develops Net-like phone
</P>
<P>
   Japan wants to compete online
</P>
<P>
   FAILED BIDDING: APBOnline, the crime news reporting service, has
failed to attract the minimum $950,000 in a bankruptcy auction. At
the public auction in U.S. Bankruptcy Court in Manhattan, no bidder
offered the minimum price. The sale of the company's assets in
partial lots will resume Thursday. The auction followed a failed
buyout agreement with SafetyTips.com.
</P>
<P>
   MOBILE CHAT: The world's largest maker of mobile phones is
introducing one that allows users to hold conversations with
multiple parties in Internet-like chat fashion. Nokia Oyj's
FriendsTalk product can also send messages, including pictures, to
others simultaneously. The phone will hit the market later this
year. Price was not diclosed.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN'S CHALLENGE: Japan's corporate leaders want the
government's help in trying to overtake the United States in
offering low-cost, high-speed Internet access. The government's IT
Strategy Council, headed by Sony President Nobuyuki Idei, is
drawing up a plan to better compete with U.S. Internet rivals
through massive investment in infrastructure and repealing laws
that inhibit e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   BY THE NUMBERS
</P>
<P>
   HANG 'EM HIGH
</P>
<P>
   In a poll of 1,155 adults, Zogby America found 64.2 percent of
respondents strongly agree that Net hackers should face felony
charges and be severly punished; 24.1 percent somewhat agreed and
8.3 percent strongly or somewhat disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   SEARCH ENGINE: 09.05.00
</P>
<P>
   SITES
</P>
<P>
   Wanted: Hackers against Balistraria Technologies
</P>
<P>
   Balistraria Technologies Inc. is looking for good hackers. The
Scottsdale, Ariz.-based firewall company will pay $1,000 to anyone
who can penetrate its latest product, netMIND. Details are on
Balistraria's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   EVENTS
</P>
<P>
   RAPID10 DISCUSSION: Lee Goldberg, network technology editor at
ChipCenter LLC, interviews Kalpesh Gala of Motorola's Networking
Systems and Computering Groups to discuss RapidIO, an emerging open
standard of interconnect architecture. The Webcast discussion would
be of interest to engineers, designers and IT personnel.
</P>
<P>
   3 p.m., Sept. 8, webevents.broadcast.com/chipcenter/rapidio0900
</P>
<P>
   Compiled by Christopher Seward
</P>
