<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-TELECOM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL OPENS LOCAL TELEPHONE AND INTERNET SERVICE TO COMPETITION
</HEADLINE>
 By WILLIAM A. ORME JR.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The Israeli government announced on Monday that it
was ending the state telephone company's monopoly on domestic
telephone and Internet service, taking a long-resisted deregulatory
move that sets the stage for the company's sale to private
investors later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Bezeq, the state-owned telephone company, will now face
competition for the first time in Israel's local telephone and
high-speed Internet market, just months before the government plans
to divest its majority stake in the $5 billion enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   Unionized telephone workers protested the decision with a
partial work stoppage, but the government vowed to proceed with
plans to grant telephone and data transmission licenses to new
wireless networks and long-established cable television operators.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is now completely open,'' Communications Minister
Benjamin Ben-Eliezer declared after signing a decree setting out
the new rules for the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Bidders for the new 15-year telecommunications licenses must be
at least 20 percent Israeli-owned and must provide service within a
year of approval, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
   The state monopoly on domestic telephone and Internet service
has come under intensifying criticism as a costly anomaly for a
country that is a spawning ground for digital telecommunications
technologies and that had long since opened its long-distance and
mobile phone service to fierce internal competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still don't have high-speed Internet access, we don't have
cable modems, we don't have all these things we hear and read
about,'' said Katrin Lemter, a telecommunications industry analyst
at Bank Hapaolim in Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
   The battle over domestic telephone deregulation and the
privatization of Bezeq pits its powerful government-allied union
against the politically influential cable television operators,
whose regional monopolies have become the cash-rich keystones of
diversified media empires.
</P>
<P>
   Though the cable companies won this round, they cannot offer
phone service unless Parliament amends current telecommunications
laws _ a protracted process even if Prime Minister Ehud Barak
manages to keep his minority coalition in power to the end of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Assuming there is a government, it could take several
months,'' Lemter said. ``If there is no government, it could take
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Before then, foreign telecommunications companies are expected
to enter the marketplace with new fixed-point wireless systems for
household telephone and high-speed Internet service. The government
said that within a month it expects to issue tenders for networks
using wireless local loop and multipoint distribution systems,
which both permit wireless phone service from fixed locations.
</P>
<P>
   Though Bezeq still hopes to be the first to offer a new
high-speed Internet connection to its customers, the government has
not yet decided whether this would give it an unfair advantage over
new entrants in the deregulated telecommunications market. Cable
television companies may also be authorized to provide high-speed
Internet service in the coming weeks, Ben-Eliezer said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Bezeq has already weathered the loss of its long-distance
monopoly and is one of three competitors in Israel's cutthroat
cellular phone market. Analysts say its stock is undervalued
compared to European state phone companies with similar reach and
revenues, but still-unresolved regulatory issues make it difficult
to assess Bezeq's market value to foreign investors, they say.
</P>
<P>
   The sale of a majority stake in Bezeq would represent the first
major privatization initiative by the Barak administration, which
inherited several stalled divestiture plans from the previous
government. Minority government holdings in commercial banks are
being gradually sold off through the stock market, but resistance
from unions and from within the prime minister's own party have
effectively halted plans for the deregulation and eventual
privatization of state-owned military companies and the national
power company.
</P>
<P>
   The Bezeq union has promised to fight privatization unless it is
satisfied with the new pension fund arrangements _ and unless Bezeq
gets a head start in the race to provide high-speed Internet
access. The union has wide support in the parliament's Finance
Committee, which must approve any privatization deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're afraid that once the company's status changes, new
owners will come, as we have seen in previous instances, and will
try to change existing agreements,'' the head of the Bezeq workers'
union, Shlomo Kfir, said Monday. ``That's why we want to safeguard
the rights of employees and retired employees. Without that I don't
think that we'll agree to any measure -- neither competition nor
privatization.''
</P>
</TEXT>
