</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-TWINS-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT EXPECTED TO DECIDE FATE OF JOINED TWINS ON TUESDAY 
</HEADLINE>
   By WARREN HOGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ England's Court of Appeal heard a request on Monday to
decide whether doctors can proceed with an operation separating
joined twins that would sacrifice the life of one to save the
other. The infants' parents have objected to the plan, even though
doctors say both children will probably die if the surgery is not
performed.
</P>
<P>
   In a case that raises conflicting moral, religious and ethical
questions, the parents are seeking to overturn a decision by the
High Court on Aug. 25 that gave surgeons the go-ahead to separate
the girls. The appeals court is widely expected to make its
decision on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Jodie and Mary, false names used by the High Court to preserve
their anonymity, were born on Aug. 8 in Manchester, joined at the
pelvis. Jodie is said to be bright and alert, but Mary is more
passive and relies on Jodie for heart and lung functions and lives
only because she is attached to her.
</P>
<P>
   The High Court judge, Robert Johnson, giving the court opinion
10 days ago, reasoned: ``For Jodie, separation means the
expectation of a normal life; for Mary it means death.''
</P>
<P>
   The Manchester medical team said there was an 80 percent to 90
percent chance that if the twins remained joined, both would die in
three to six months as Jodie's heart fails under the burden of
supporting more than just herself.
</P>
<P>
   The parents, both Roman Catholics from a remote community in an
unidentified European country, came here to have the children when
they realized that they were joined and that their home country
lacked sophisticated medical centers. The parents were not in court
Monday. But their lawyer, Simon Taylor, submitted a statement from
them that said: ``We cannot begin to accept or contemplate that one
of our children should die to enable the other one to survive. That
is not God's will. Everyone has a right to life, so why should we
kill one of our daughters to enable the other one to survive?''
</P>
<P>
   Citing a second principle arising out of the couple's religious
belief, Taylor told the three-judge appellate panel: ``They don't
want either of their daughters to be actively killed. But they also
say, `We recognize the dire prognosis without separation, and we
don't want to prolong matters by active treatment.'''
</P>
<P>
   Judith Parker, a lawyer assigned to represent Jodie, said there
was no reason to believe that the girl would not have a normal life
expectancy if separated from her sister. ``We must look at it not
that something is being done to Mary to hasten the end of her life,
but that something is being done to Jodie in order to restore to
her, her own integrity and bodily system,'' Parker said.
</P>
<P>
   But the parents argued that separation would not guarantee a
good result for Jodie and that the isolated place where they lived
could not provide the care that she might need. It would be
``arduous for her and arduous for the family,'' Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
   The case has sparked expressions of dismay and concern from
religious, judicial and medical groups. But it has also provoked
threats from more activist organizations.
</P>
<P>
   The judges on Monday agreed to a plea for official anonymity for
a witness from the Manchester hospital after hearing that doctors
there were already receiving hate mail. ``This is the sort of case
where feelings run high,'' said Adrian Whitfield, representing the
Central Manchester Healthcare Trust. ``Ethical positions can run to
extremes.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice Alan Ward called on Monday for a second medical opinion
to obtain confirmation of what he called the ``wholly bleak
prospect'' for Mary. A specialist from Great Ormond Street
Children's Hospital in London was assigned to see the twins and
report back to the court on Tuesday. Taylor said the parents'
stance reflected principles of English law that even if there was a
medically futile situation, there was no obligation for doctors to
give treatment that prolonged life.
</P>
<P>
   Ward remarked solemnly: ``Thy will be done on earth as it is in
heaven. That is their case.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
