u i BC-U.N.-PEACEKEEPING-NYT     09-04 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.N.-PEACEKEEPING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECURITY COUNCIL TO ASK FOR REASSESSMENT OF PEACKEEPING PAYMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The five permanent Security Council members
plan to use their collective influence this week to call for a
revision of how peacekeeping costs are divided among member
nations, a move that would _ at least on paper _ help Washington in
its battle to reduce U.S. assessments.
</P>
<P>
   The review of peacekeeping bills, which has to be conducted
through a committee of member nations, would be intended to help
put the faltering and cash-strapped peacekeeping department on
firmer financial footing.
</P>
<P>
   The five permanent members _ Britain, China, France, Russia and
the United States _ will meet on Thursday as part of a separate
Security Council ``summit within a summit'' during a meeting of
more than 150 government leaders. Both the full 15-member council
and its core of permanent members will issue declarations for the
day.
</P>
<P>
   The permanent members' final draft statement calls for adjusting
the payment scale for peacekeeping costs ``in light of changed
circumstances.'' The scale was established in 1973 to cover an
operation in Sinai and has never been revised.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, the permanent members, who hold veto power, were
asked to pay a premium for peacekeeping on top of their fair share
of costs based on their national economies. Other industrial
nations paid just their share. Smaller or poorer nations paid as
little as 10 percent or 20 percent of what they would usually be
charged. A complex formula of special discounts claimed by many
nations further skewed the system.
</P>
<P>
   Based on 1973 economic figures, for example, the United States
was assessed more than 30 percent and China less than 1 percent, a
gap that has rankled U.S. officials in recent years. Russia is
still assessed as if it were the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   China has generally acknowledged that the system is out of date
and unfair, given the changes in the economic fortunes of many
nations. Saudi Arabia and Singapore, for example, pay minimal
amounts. But Chinese officials have refused to agree to a
significant increase in their bill.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats say that with the economy of Hong Kong now included
with that of the rest of China, Beijing will no longer be able to
make a case for poverty, even taking into account its large
population.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Congress has already ruled that the United States
will pay no more than 25 percent of its bill _ when it pays at all.
That contributes to an ever-widening U.S. debt, because member
nations do not recognize moves like that from individual countries.
</P>
<P>
   Reopening formal debate on a new payment scale will take a long
time, diplomats said, because 189 countries will all have opinions
to offer and limits to negotiate. But lobbying by the permanent
council members will help the process.
</P>
<P>
   In general, the five permanent members will recommend in their
statement this week that the financial base of the United Nations _
both the regular budget, which is assessed separately, and
peacekeeping costs _ ``must accurately reflect the capabilities and
responsibilities of every member state.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
