<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0631 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-FBN-FALCONS05-COX     09-04 0510
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons sorely in need of defensive additions
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Just like this time a year ago, the Falcons were sore
on the day after their season opener. This time, though, the wounds
didn't seem to hurt as much.
</P>
<P>
   Winning has that effect.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Dan Reeves and his players were still uplifted by Sunday's
36-28 win over the 49ers in the Georgia Dome. There weren't a lot
of chances to gloat last season, when the Falcons were 5-11.
</P>
<P>
   ``To win an opening game against a team in our division is
really big,'' said Reeves, whose team lost its opener last year
17-14 to the Vikings. ``(But) We do have some injury situations
that are going to be key for us ... getting ready for Denver
(Sunday).''
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake, the Falcons have been getting pounded
physically.
</P>
<P>
   Already short-staffed on the defensive line and at linebacker,
the Falcons incurred more damage at both positions Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Backup weak-side linebacker Chris Draft will miss Reeves' first
trip back to Denver since the Broncos fired him after the 1992
season. Draft aggravated a hamstring injury Sunday. With rookie
reserve linebacker Mark Simoneau (groin pull) out at least two more
weeks, the Falcons have just four other linebackers.
</P>
<P>
   One, middle linebacker Jessie Tuggle, has a sprained wrist. The
only healthy reserve, Jeff Kelly, has almost no experience outside.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons are more likely to add a linebacker rather than a
defensive lineman to the roster today, but both are possible. The
Falcons are about $1 million under the salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that we can bring anybody in at that position,''
Reeves said. ``We have got to look at linebacker.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons would have to clear roster room to add players.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves said it's no sure thing that starting defensive end Brady
Smith, who has been out nearly four weeks with a groin pull, will
be back. His absence left the Falcons with just six defensive
linemen Sunday. Many teams dress eight defensive linemen; not many
dress fewer than seven.
</P>
<P>
   Starting right defensive tackle Shane Dronett was walking around
Monday with his left elbow in a sling.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of the opposite of hyperextending it,'' said
Dronett, who expects to play against the team that drafted him in
the second round in '92. ``It was fine at first, but later it got
stiff.''
</P>
<P>
   On the plus side, running back Jamal Anderson, who surprised
everyone by carrying 24 times for 77 yards in his first game since
missing the final 14 games last year with a torn right anterior
cruciate knee ligament, said he was not as sore as he had been
after his first preseason action a few weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm being smarter about it,'' Anderson said. ``I ice it after
the game, then get home, wait a couple hours, and ice it again.
It's something I'm going to have to stay on top of. A lot of times,
guys will swell up, but mine's not doing that and that's good.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
