<P>
   NEWS ABOUT THE NET: 09.05.00
</P>
<P>
   Silence not quite golden but is worth $20 a day
</P>
<P>
   Forget soap on a rope; here's one that's online
</P>
<P>
   Very unhappy woman reader starts Happy Woman site
</P>
<P>
   THE E-EMMYS: Along with weird speeches and wacky outfits,
Sunday's Primetime Emmy Awards feature the first chance for viewers
to interact with the telecast. By accessing the Enhanced TV
telecast at www.abc.com for one hour leading up to and during the
telecast, viewers can compete to correctly predict winners of each
category and chat with each other live. Emmy host Garry Shandling
also will ask the TV audience poll questions, the results of which
will be quickly displayed.
</P>
<P>
   www.abc.com
</P>
<P>
   TALK IS CHEAP: But silence could be lucrative for Brett Banfe, a
Pennsylvania teen who has taken a vow of silence for a year.
Banfe's quest is being sponsored by www.darefordollars.com, a Web
site that rewards people who ``gotta get some fast cash and are
willing to do almost anything to get it.'' A freshman at William
Paterson University in New Jersey, Banfe will get $12,300 ($20 a
day plus $5,000) for muting himself for a year. He plans to give
the money to Head Start. The site offers $1,000 to anyone who
presents ``legitimate surveillance video'' of Branfe talking. (And
if you just want to talk about how nuts you think he is, you can go
to the site and have a discussion
</P>
<P>
   www.darefordollars.com
</P>
<P>
   SOAP ONLINE: When a new Internet soap opera debuts soon, viewers
won't just be able to wallow in the melodrama. They'll be able to
buy many of the props. ``55 Mercer Street,'' the saga of four
twentysomethings living in New York's SoHo, will have its premiere
broadcast on Internet site iVillage.com by October, the Associated
Press reports. Products from Macys.com, Puma, Dickies and others
that are in the show will be available for purchase online. ``55''
will be produced by High Point, N.C.-based Down Home Entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   www.ivillage.com
</P>
<P>
   OIL OF CHEVR-OLAY?: Tired of reading self-help articles in
women's magazines about how to lose weight or improve one's sex
life, Sharon Grehan of Toronto launched the Happy Woman Magazine
Web site with satirical articles and celebrity interview spoofs.
Tongue-in-cheek pieces include instructions on how to build a piano
and the sheep shearer's workout (large dogs will do). As for making
husbands happy, it suggests: Change your perfume so you smell like
a new car or gorditas.
</P>
<P>
   www.happywomanmagazine.com
</P>
<P>
   SEARCH ENGINE:
</P>
<P>
   A look at who's who and who's reading whom
</P>
<P>
   Fans of television's ``A&AMP;E Biography'' can chat about the people
who are profiled by clicking on the biography.com/book club Web
site. This month's subject: Sidney Poitier and ``The Measure of a
Man: A Spiritual Autobiography.'' Also: Check which biographies are
the hottest-selling and peek at what celebrities have on their
nightstands (Ethan Hawke is reading ``The Raven: A Biography of Sam
Houston'' by Marquis James).
</P>
<P>
   www.biography.com/bookclub/
</P>
<P>
   Homework helpers take a page from Cliffs Notes
</P>
<P>
   Now that school is back in full swing, this site may be helpful
for your little overachievers. That is, if you don't mind that it
borders on being a little too helpful. The new homeworkspot.com
provides easy access to ``homework helpers'' for all subjects. The
site is organized into grade-appropriate categories, and there's
access to reference tools, even virtual ``field trips.'' There're
also step-by-step explanations. The minus side: Who'll bother with
explanations? When we asked for an English-to-Spanish translation
of a question, we instantly got back the correct response. The
question: ``How will kids learn anything?''
</P>
<P>
   www.homeworkspot .com
</P>
<P>
   Pining for wine country? Exit at this portal
</P>
<P>
   Battling a little post-vacation, summer-is-over syndrome today?
Try Sutter Home MoodMaker, a downloadable, interactive software
application combining animated, user-customizable blends of
wine-country sights and sounds. The mission: to offer wine-country
experiences to enjoy while using their computer
</P>
<P>
   www.sutterhome.com
</P>
