 PERSONALS: Real Estates Get Real 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file.) &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By LEAH GARCHIK &QC;  &LR; 
 &UR; c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle &LR;  &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Anne Heche &LR;  and &UR; Ellen DeGeneres &LR;  have put their 4,000-square-foot
French farmhouse-like place in Ojai on the market at $2.75 million,
reports the L.A. Times.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; OUT ON THE TOWN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Man Ray &LR; , a Parisian restaurant backed by  &UR; Johnny Depp &LR; ,
 &UR; Sean Penn &LR; ,  &UR; John Malkovich  &LR; and others, is opening a branch in New
York in November, reports New York magazine. The restaurant, named
after the painter and photographer who lived in Philadelphia,
Brooklyn, New Jersey, Manhattan, the South of France, Los Angeles
and then Paris again, will serve French and Japanese cuisine in
``an Algerian Art Deco decor,'' says the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Chris Barish &LR; , son of  &UR; Keith Barish &LR; , a founder of Planet
Hollywood, told  &UR; Baird Jones  &LR; at the New York opening party for the
movie ``Whipped'' that his dad is giving him a chunk of money _ as
much as $20 million _ to start ``a string of lounges in New York,
then Chicago, Boston and San Francisco. I want to combine the
hipness of the downtown lounge concept, where it is not a dance
club or pickup bar, but shift that toward the mainstream. I want
uptown people who are well dressed to know they will get in without
any door attitude and most importantly, be able to have fun early,
like around 9 p.m., but without it being a restaurant.'' (Watch for
this entertainment trend: Baby Boomers don't want to stay up late.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; OLIVER'S TWIST &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Museum of Modern Art in New York is paying homage to
 &UR; Oliver Stone &LR;  with a ``midcareer retrospective'' that includes
screenings of all 14 of his films, but the honor puts him in a hard
place, since the museum's staff has been on strike for four months.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Daily News reports that directors  &UR; Steven &LR; 
 &UR; Spielberg &LR; ,  &UR; Martin Scorsese &LR;  and  &UR; Quentin Tarantino &LR;  have signed a
letter urging a boycott of the museum.
</P>
<P>
   Stone said he hadn't planned on attending the festivities
because he's in Los Angeles working on his next movie, ``Beyond
Borders,'' and he hedged when the New York newspaper asked him
about the event. ``I'm not involved,'' he said, ``but I'm honored
by it.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``At a dinner party the other night, a friend said her project &LR; 
 &UR; for the next day was to drill out bigger holes in four bowling &LR; 
 &UR; balls. It turned out she's using them as feet for her bed frame; &LR; 
 &UR; she'd gotten them for $1.98 each at a thrift store. Moreover, &LR; 
 &UR; one of our two local bowling alleys was recently turned into a &LR; 
 &UR; dialysis center.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ A portrait of American culture, in which the Curmudgeon's Home
Companion notes that people are bowling less.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
