<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0646 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      09-04 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: OHIO GETS READY TO COMMIT 
</HEADLINE>
   By GAIL COLLINS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI  &UR; _  &LR; We waited a long time for the public to get
interested in this election, but now in southern Ohio you can see
the signs. Literally. The lawns are full of ads for candidates who
want to be the next congressman or state representative. This must
be what they mean when they talk about grass-roots politics.
</P>
<P>
   The signs are extremely important, says John Cranley, a
26-year-old Democratic congressional candidate. ``That's what I see
as the uniqueness of the district. People will put a sign up.''
</P>
<P>
   Cranley, a recent graduate of Harvard Law School, is the
youngest person running for the House of Representatives this year.
MTV is following him around, doing a documentary about the race.
The constant presence of the cameras has been a big help in
recruiting campaign volunteers. ``They've got a lot of very
intimate footage,'' Cranley says. ``They come when I get up and
say, `Are you going to puke this morning?' Which I do a lot. The
stress is enormous.''
</P>
<P>
   There are only a couple of dozen congressional races in this
country that the pros regard as up in the air. At this point, the
First Congressional District of Ohio isn't one of them. Last time
around, the popular mayor of Cincinnati, Roxanne Qualls, ran
against the incumbent, a conservative Republican named Steve
Chabot, and she got buried in the conservative Catholic
neighborhoods to the west of the city. Cranley, who is Catholic,
opposed to abortion and from the west side, figures he can win if
he can manage to lose the district where he grew up by only 3 to 1.
</P>
<P>
   My sister used to baby-sit for Cranley when he was a toddler, so
she gave him a party the other day, in a neighborhood where Qualls
got a grand total of 16 percent of the vote. Throwing a
meet-the-candidate party is akin to a corporal work of mercy. The
country is full of people who are dying to tell you why they'd be a
better representative/state legislator/road commissioner than the
entrenched incumbent. There is a severe shortage, however, of
places for them to give their pitch. At the Democratic convention,
Rep. Harold Ford, the keynote speaker, recalled the critical moment
when he discovered the concept of kindergarten graduations as a
turning point in his political career.
</P>
<P>
   Cranley understands. ``Church festivals are my life,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Due to the shortage of swing voters in the area, half the people
in attendance at the party were Republican friends of my parents.
They sat listening as Cranley denounced Chabot for voting against
nutrition programs for pregnant women, infants and children.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are women who opted not to have abortions. To be
pro-life we have to be consistent,'' he said. Cranley's passionate
defense of anti-poverty programs may not have had much impact on
the Republican seniors, but it did soften one Democratic woman, who
dropped her plan to yell at him for being anti-choice.
</P>
<P>
   Several guests volunteered to put up signs, but in this
neighborhood people will commit their lawns before they commit
their votes. I don't know if Cranley has a shot at the House seat _
Chabot seems pretty energetic. But it's heartening to know we still
have graduates coming out of Harvard Law worrying about the WIC
program and the earned-income tax credit.
</P>
<P>
   People in Ohio expect a lot of attention at election time, as
befits their standing as residents of a swing state. There was a
certain amount of hurt feelings the other day when George W. Bush
flew here for a fund-raiser at the home of a wealthy friend and
didn't stop to do any campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, we're used to the idea that Bush and Al Gore see us
as the motorcade route between La Guardia Airport and the Hilton
banquet hall. Wham, bam, traffic jam. But Ohio needs more tender
handling.
</P>
<P>
   A deeply unscientific survey of conservative Catholic senior
citizens on the western side of Cincinnati suggests the most
popular guy on either ticket is Joe Lieberman. ``I liked him even
better before he got partisan,'' said one of the men. The male
Republicans seem happy enough with Bush, but the women are
disappointed they can't fall in love with him the way they did with
Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   Bush had better hang around next time he swings through. The
signs are not all good.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
