<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000904.0222 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0647 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-CONGRESS-RETURN-2TAKE     09-04 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-RETURN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETURNING CONGRESS JUGGLES LEGISLATION WITH ELECTION CAMPAIGNS 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN A. HOLMES and ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Aware that what they do in the next few weeks may
help determine who controls the federal government next year,
members of Congress return from recess this week for a final
session compressed by the election campaigns and dominated by tax
cuts, education, health care and government spending.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican majority's first step will be trying to override
President Clinton's vetoes of their two top tax priorities _
repealing the marriage tax and the estate tax. But the efforts to
override the two vetoes have little chance of success, Republican
aides say. The votes, like much else that will happen this month,
are meant mainly to provide fodder for the political campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats have been pressing for concessions from the
Republicans on two health care fronts: a bill to expand patients'
rights in dealing with insurers and legislation to add payments for
prescription drugs to the Medicare program for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker J. Dennis Hastert is especially interested in
trying to broker a deal on the long-stalled patients' bill of
rights, and a one-vote shift in the Senate _ Sen. Zell Miller,
D-Ga., has been appointed to replace the late Sen. Paul Coverdell,
a Republican _ could make the difference.
</P>
<P>
   On other issues, the Senate almost surely will pass a major bill
that will establish permanent normal trade relations with China,
even though Senate Republicans are still holding back on this
priority of the Clinton administration, trying to use it as
leverage in negotiations with the White House over the broader
legislative agenda. There is also broad support for overhauling the
nation's bankruptcy laws to tighten the conditions under which
people can seek debt relief. And Congress will also likely pass a
$1 increase in the federal minimum wage, as Democrats have been
demanding.
</P>
<P>
   Battles between Congress and the White House over government
spending have been a perennial September feature since the
Republicans took control of the Legislature in 1994. This year,
however, lawmakers will be under pressure to reach early agreement
with the president so they can go home to campaign for re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Congress is likely to provide more money for education, but to
support exactly what school programs remains unclear. Many other
domestic spending bills are pending, and their final shape is in
flux. It seems likely that, as in the past, Clinton will force the
Republican-led Congress to increase domestic spending overall as
the cost of leaving town in time for down-to-the-wire campaigning
in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult to imagine we can do everything that needs to
be done, but by and large there is some prospect for successful
conclusion,'' said Sen. Tom Daschle of South Dakota, the Democratic
leader.
</P>
<P>
   And in these final days of the session, every vote cast and
every horse traded carries exceptional weight in what appears to be
a close political race.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the mother of all endgames, because the House, Senate
and presidency are all at stake,'' said Mark Isakowitz, a
Republican strategist.
</P>
<P>
   As lawmakers return from the recess that began before the
national political conventions, they confront a new political
calculus. When they left in July, George W. Bush was ahead in the
presidential polls. Now Vice President Al Gore appears to have
closed the gap.
</P>
<P>
   That suggests that control of Congress, especially the narrowly
divided House, may depend not on the coattails of the presidential
candidates, but more on what the lawmakers actually do, and how the
public perceives their work, in the closing weeks of the session.
</P>
<P>
   Yet as they enter the session, Republicans have not shown a
coordinated strategy on how to deal with the White House and
congressional Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Tom Delay, R-Texas, the Republican whip in the
House, said he was ``surprised'' by an Aug. 28 letter sent by
Hastert to Clinton proposing to work together over the next month
to find ``common ground'' on increasing the minimum wage. While
Delay refrained from criticizing Hastert, his aides made it clear
that he would not have sent such a letter.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, with the end of the fiscal year approaching on
Sept. 30, the Republicans do not appear to have settled on what
approach to take with the White House in budget negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   On the big issues of social policy, meanwhile, Democratic
leaders in Congress, the White House and the Gore campaign appear
to be working in concert and framing a unified message. But some
Republican Congress watchers said that the Bush campaign had tried
to keep congressional Republicans at arms length.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton, Gore and Gephardt have message coordination,
particularly on prescription drugs, Medicare and HMO reform;
Republicans don't,'' said Marshall Wittman, director of
congressional relations at the Heritage Foundation, a conservative
research institution. ``Bush is almost implicitly running against
Republicans on Capitol Hill.''
</P>
<P>
   The heated debate between Bush and Gore over prescription drug
benefits reduces the chance that congressional Republicans and
Democrats will resolve their differences there. While the full
House has passed a version providing subsidies to private insurers
that cover some drug costs, the Senate Finance Committee has not
voted on a bill.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats have gained strength in the Senate and could try
again to pass a patients' bill of rights like the one the House
approved, but they would still need to rely on Republican votes
that are not firm. Some compromise would probably be needed on how
many people the bill covered and what rights aggrieved patients
would have to sue their insurers.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a strong chance that Congress will restore some
money it cut from the Medicare program, increasing payments to
hospitals, nursing homes, doctors and other caretakers for the
elderly. Senate Republicans, though, do not agree with the health
care providers that there is a huge need for this step, and the
size of any increase remains uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The various policy differences and political jockeying will be
on display from the start. On Thursday, the House leadership has
scheduled a vote on overriding Clinton's Aug. 31 veto of the bill
to phase out federal inheritance taxes. Next week, there will be a
vote in the House on overriding Clinton's veto last week of the
repeal of the marriage penalty.
</P>
<P>
   The president said that ending of the federal estate tax would
be too costly and would mainly benefit wealthy people. The White
House said the federal government would lose revenues of $100
billion in the first 10 years and $750 billion more in the next 10
years.
</P>
<P>
   Because 65 Democrats voted in favor of abolishing the estate
tax, congressional Republicans initially expressed optimism that
the House would strike down Clinton's veto and hand the president
an embarrassing defeat. But it appears that some Democrats will
reverse themselves, that some who missed the first vote will side
with the president, and that the veto will be sustained.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will try overrides on the tax bills; that will be
unsuccessful,'' predicted a top aide to a Republican House leader.
``Then we'll pivot and say to Democrats and Clinton, you can't
spend it either. Our alternative will be to pay down debt and
protect Social Security.''
</P>
<P>
   But the aide added that House leaders had yet to reach an
agreement on such a course of action. ``The big dogs have to sign
off on it,'' the aide said.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Republicans must also devise a strategy to deal
with the White House on the 13 spending bills that must be enacted
by the end of the fiscal year on Sept. 30 to keep the government
functioning.
</P>
<P>
   The House has passed 12 of the 13 bills and the Senate has
approved eight. Two, a $288 billion measure for defense and a much
smaller bill for military construction, have been signed into law.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has threatened to veto eight of the spending bills,
setting the stage for fights over issues like providing money for
school construction, hiring more teachers to reduce class size and
setting aside more federal lands for wilderness areas.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are seeking to paint the administration as the
recalcitrant party, emphasizing that a mere $30 billion, out of a
budget with more than $600 billion in discretionary spending, is
what separates their bills from what the White House wants to
spend. They even note that they are providing the amounts the
president wants for his school construction and class reduction
programs, though, unlike the administration version, the Republican
bill gives local school districts an option of not spending the new
federal aid for those purposes. But White House officials say the
difference is less about amounts than about how the money is to be
spent.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans say any problems reaching agreement with the
administration will benefit them and their presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's going to work this time,'' said Sen. Mitch
McConnell, R-Ky., chairman of the Senate Republican campaign
committee. ``It's going to help Governor Bush because he will
demonstrate that he's the guy who can reach across party lines and
govern. It will illustrate the Clinton-Gore administration's
inability to govern on a bipartisan basis. Let them do it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Patrick J. Kennedy, D-R.I., said that on social policy
the standoff in Congress will help his party. ``The fact of the
matter is the American people support the Democratic caucus issues
_ prescription drugs for seniors, a patients' bill of rights,
education for our future _ and those are the issues that our
Republicans are trying to bill themselves as champions of, but it's
just not working,'' said Kennedy, who is chairman of the House
Democratic campaign committee. ``The American people know it's the
Democrats that are truly on their side.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
