<P>
   FIRESTONE-LABOR (Undated) _ Firestone, facing a crisis over
allegations its tires caused dozens of traffic deaths, reached a
tentative agreement with steelworkers early today to avert a strike
at nine plants. The union has not yet disclosed details but said it
believed the agreement was fair for both sides. The settlement
covers more than 8,000 workers at seven plants that produce tires
and two that produce tire parts. By Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move by 9 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISPLAY:
</P>
<P>
   SCULLEY-BROTHERS (Undated) _ John Sculley, the former Apple
Computer chief executive, is making a quiet comeback. For the last
five years, he has run run a small venture capital firm with his
two brothers. It is his way of fulfilling a desire to work with his
family -- and to help proselytize about the virtues of the Internet
without suffering the corporate intrigue that overwhelmed him at
both Apple and at Spectrum Information Technologies. By Hilary
Rosenberg.
</P>
<P>
   (With photo, NYT17, and a graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   (Will move by 8:30 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   RIGHT SIDE:
</P>
<P>
   DAIMLERCHRYSLER-MITSUBISHI (Munich, Germany) _ DaimlerChrysler
confirmed a Japanese report that it wants to amend the terms of its
proposed acquisition of a third of Mitsubishi Motors to obtain
greater control over the company, Japan's No. 3 automaker, which
has been buffeted by a recall scandal. DaimlerChrysler wants to
raise its Mitsubishi stake to 40 percent, altering its July plan to
buy 34 percent for almost $2 billion. It also wants more than the
current three seats on the 10-member management board.
DaimlerChrysler aims to wrest control of Mitsubishi Motors from
Mitsubishi group companies, which owned about 42 percent in March.
By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move by 8:30 p.m.)
