<P>
   FIRESTONE-VENEZUELA (Caracas) _ Facing a threat of legal action,
Bridgestone/Firestone Inc. will announce a formal recall of 62,000
Venezuelan-made tires alleged to have defects linked to at least 46
fatal accidents here. The government, however, says that the action
is not enough and that it will consider its legal options. By Larry
Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-TELECOM (Jerusalem) _ The Israeli government has ended
the state telephone company's monopoly on domestic telephone and
Internet service, taking a long-resisted deregulatory move that
sets the stage for the company, Bezeq, to sell shares to private
investors later this year. By William A. Orme Jr.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-BUSINESS (San Francisco) _ IBM, Microsoft and others
are expected to announce proposed standards this week for an
electronic directory that will make it easier for companies to
carry out business-to-business transactions. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-BOURSES (London) _ Euronext, the company that will
combine the Paris, Amsterdam and Brussels stock exchanges, has
approached French banks about the possibility of financing for a
bid for the London Stock Exchange. The London exchange was already
in merger talks with Frankfurt. By Suzanne Kapner.
</P>
