</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-AUSTRALIA-NOTEBOOK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: LOOKING PAST THE TYPICAL DOWN UNDER 
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds.: This was originally budgeted as a REVIEW) 
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For those of us steeled against an Olympic onslaught of
kangaroos, koalas and Crocodile Dundee kitsch, ``Australia: Beyond
the Fatal Shore'' offers a protective coating for the brain. Robert
Hughes' six-part series is not the only program to ride the
coattails of the Sydney games, but it is the only one to explode
the myths and cliches that others mindlessly indulge. ``Croc Hunter
Holiday,'' the title of a Travel Channel documentary, says it all
about the standard glimpse at Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes' work is of a different order, sharp cultural criticism
that is also entertaining. It is driven by a distinctive blend of
qualities. Because Hughes grew up in Australia but has lived abroad
for 35 years, he has a lovingly intimate yet detached perspective.
His ideas are enhanced by inspired visual imagery and crisp
cinematography; you might expect that, knowing that Hughes built
his reputation as an art critic.
</P>
<P>
   A bigger surprise is how well his on-screen presence holds the
series together, with an amused, probing, literate commentary that
makes him the most engaging of guides. He may be the only person
ever to emerge from a near-death experience wryer than ever, his
already acute sensibility sharpened, and not a smidgen of
sentimentality added. (The six-hour series will be shown from 9
p.m. to 11 p.m. ET, Tuesday through Thursday on PBS.)
</P>
<P>
   As Hughes says at the start, he was filming this series when he
was nearly killed in a car crash. On camera here, he walks with a
cane to observe the mangled car for the first time and seems shaken
all over again, rightly pointing out that no one should have
escaped from such a mess. His bones were shattered, but as he wrote
in a Time magazine essay last year, when he saw death there was no
``tunnel of white light with Jesus beckoning at the end, as
featured in the memoirs of a score of American K-mart mystics.'' He
emerged as skeptical as ever about an afterlife but ``crazily
happy'' to be alive in this one, determined to embrace every
minute.
</P>
<P>
   That tone pervades the series, as he flees from emotional
indulgence and quickly moves on to examine how much truth might be
behind the stereotypes of his home country, like the fun-loving
Aussie and the romanticized outback. The answers are never simple,
and the complexity is often captured by resonant images.
</P>
<P>
   Fruit bats swarm into a beautiful midnight-blue sky that turns
out to be dotted with Sydney skyscrapers. The bats are invading the
city at nightfall, ``reminding us the bush is never far away,''
Hughes says at the end of Episode 2, ``The Dead Heart.'' That
episode suggests that while the mythic Australia is about the
outback, true Australians dream of a home in the suburbs. When he
visits the remote city of Perth in Episode 3, ``Money, Class and
Power,'' he discovers that the nouveau riche mansions built during
the 1980s boom look like suburban houses ``inflated with a bicycle
pump.''
</P>
<P>
   A jumbo jet decorated with an almost psychedelic swirl of
Aboriginal art becomes the perfect metaphor for the clash of
culture and race examined in Episode 4, ``Before Trousers,'' whose
title refers to the Aborigines' term for the years before white
settlers arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Everywhere Hughes finds the push and pull of cultural forces
that goes back to Australia's days as an English penal colony
(chronicled in his absorbing 1987 book, ``The Fatal Shore''). In
tonight's opening episode, ``Body and Soul,'' he goes to Sydney's
colorful gay and lesbian Mardi Gras, a parade that recently drew
more people than the pope's visit there. But for every
``larrikin,'' the caricatured boozy hedonist, Australian history
has offered a countervailing ``wowser,'' a bluenose.
</P>
<P>
   Conflicts between the descendants of the prisoners shipped to
Australia in the 18th century and the descendants of free settlers
still echo. Hughes visits his childhood home, a large
upper-middle-class house whose new owners have maintained its
refined Georgian style. The camera approaches it from a child's
angle, so the house looks as palatial as it did to him as a boy.
Now it prods him to notice that the idea of a nearly classless
society ``is one of the great illusions Australians like to spin
for themselves.'' A nation with more than its share of gamblers,
Australians choose to believe that luck rather than heredity or
skill is the basis for success. Theirs is ``the meritocracy that
dare not speak its name,'' he says in one of the witty phrases that
glide through his narration.
</P>
<P>
   The delusion that we have no rigid class hierarchy applies to
Americans just as easily as Australians, though Hughes doesn't need
to say so. There are so many similarities, and equally revealing
differences, between the United States and Australia that at times
he allows them to speak for themselves, and sometimes makes his
point explicitly. `` `Reconciliation' is the new buzzword of
Australian politics,'' he says in his episode on Aboriginal
culture, without mentioning how the issue reverberates in the
United States, both in black-white racial tensions and the history
of American Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Aborigines want white Australians to apologize for having
taken their land. Hughes visits Ayers Rock, the monolith in the
desert, which in 1986 was returned to the Aborigines yet remains a
tourist trap. Simply mentioning the rock is a political statement,
depending on whether it is called Ayers Rock or Uluru, the
Aboriginal name that has been restored. The natural wonder has been
``reduced to a totem by political and social wrangling,'' Hughes
says. ``Before Trousers,'' one of the richest episodes, includes an
interview with a middle-aged woman from the so-called ``stolen
generation,'' Aboriginal children taken from their parents in the
first half of this century to be raised by whites.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Whatever similarities the series implies, Hughes is most
emphatic about the great defining differences between America and
Australia. In frontier America space meant freedom; in Australia
the vast space was literally one big prison. And because America
was founded as a religious utopia and utopias do not exist, we were
``doomed to disappointment.'' With its roots as a penal colony,
Australia ``had nowhere to go but up.''
</P>
<P>
   It's too bad there is no companion book to Hughes' series, but
there is a charming alternative in Bill Bryson's current best
seller, ``In a Sunburned Country'' (Broadway Books), which
approaches Australia from the opposite perspective. Where Hughes is
an insider come home, Bryson is the outsider enthusing about his
discovery of Australian culture. Though his book is not nearly as
substantial or thoughtful as the Hughes documentary, it is an
intelligent, breezy tour in which the witty author is delighted by
Australia without being blinded by its stereotypes. He especially
likes the prime minister who disappeared by walking into the sea
and was memorialized with a swimming pool. Even that much
thoughtfulness is rare, as a glance at next week's television
programs about Australia suggest.
</P>
<P>
   The Discovery Channel's ``Extreme Australia'' (9 p.m. ET,
Monday) is a snoozy documentary largely about geology, snakes and
platypuses. It is useful if you want to be reminded of why you
dozed through natural history class. The program does not actually
play the song ``Kookaburra'' (``Kookaburra sits in the old gum
tree''), but the high school aura was so severe I heard it anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The Travel Channel begins ``Australia Week'' on Monday with
``Croc Hunter Holiday'' (not available for review), a new special
in which Steve Irwin, the host of the Animal Planet show
``Crocodile Hunter,'' tours the country with his family. Then from
Tuesday through Friday ( 8 p.m. ET), the Travel Channel will repeat
an Australia-themed special. Most have that deadened travelogue
tone and one (``Freshwater Crocs'' on Thursday) has Irwin cooing at
the sweet behind of a kindly freshwater crocodile. Evidently it's
the saltwater crocs that'll kill you.
</P>
<P>
   However banal their narratives, even these lesser programs
suggest that it is nearly impossible to take a bad photograph of
Australia. Whatever the Olympics bring, there is this consolation:
At least everything will look pretty. And if the ``Kookaburra''
song gets stuck in your head, here's a hint: it can easily be
displaced by ``Waltzing Matilda.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
