<HEADLINE>
POLYMER-COATED SEEDS MAY ENABLE RELAY PLANTING FOR WHEAT AND
SOYBEAN CROPS 
</HEADLINE>
   By HENRY FOUNTAIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   M&AMP;M's melt in your mouth (and not in your hands!) because, as
the old TV commercial said, they are covered by a thin candy shell.
</P>
<P>
   A Purdue University agronomist is testing whether a similar idea
will work for seeds as a means of increasing farm efficiency. Using
a thin polymer coating developed by the Landec Corp. of Menlo Park,
Calif., the agronomist, Tony Vyn, is testing whether coated seeds
can be used to help farmers overlap winter wheat and soybeans in
the same field.
</P>
<P>
   Relay planting, as the technique is known, is practiced with
wheat and soybeans in southerly parts of the Midwest. The problem
in more northerly parts, like Wisconsin and northern parts of
Indiana and Illinois, is that planting the soybeans early enough so
that the existing wheat stalks are not damaged by the planting
machinery often results in soybean plants that are too spindly and
high when the wheat harvest occurs. Thus much of the soybean crop
is destroyed in harvesting the wheat.
</P>
<P>
   The polymer-coated seeds, which should be on the market in a few
years, work like a timed-release aspirin, delaying seed germination
by about two weeks until heat and moisture in the soil break down
the coating. That would allow farmers to plant soybeans early,
without damaging the wheat, and yet produce soybean plants that are
short enough to be missed when the wheat combine cuts through the
field.
</P>
<P>
   Vyn said that the coating could also include a fungicide to ward
off mold that can rot seeds. Fungicides maintain their activity
longer in colder soil, so putting a coated seed into the ground
earlier would have the added advantage of protecting it longer.
</P>
<P>
   NATURAL DECAFFEINATION
</P>
<P>
   Decaffeinated coffee usually gets that way through an industrial
process that uses a solvent, commonly ethyl acetate, to remove the
caffeine from the bean. But what if coffee (and tea) could be grown
without caffeine?
</P>
<P>
   That is the prospect of new research by scientists in Japan and
Scotland who have cloned the gene responsible for an enzyme that
plays an important role in caffeine production. Their work was
reported in Nature.
</P>
<P>
   The enzyme, called caffeine synthase, acts as a catalyst in the
final two steps in the caffeine-making pathway in the coffee or tea
plant. So the researchers suggest that a transgenic plant, with
this gene sequence inactivated, could produce decaf coffee beans or
tea leaves.
</P>
<P>
   That is one genetically modified plant that might actually find
favor among some members of the public.
</P>
<P>
   DYING AMPHIBIANS
</P>
<P>
   Die-offs of frogs and other amphibians are still occurring in
parts of the United States, and although researchers in some cases
have been able to pinpoint a cause, the phenomenon remains
something of a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most recent die-offs involved tiger salamanders at a
lake in North Dakota. Researchers from the U.S. Geological Survey
first noticed sick salamanders in May; by July, population counts
were far below the previous years.
</P>
<P>
   Geological service researchers have blamed a type of virus
called an iridovirus for most of the deaths in North Dakota.
Iridoviruses have also been linked to other salamander die-offs in
recent years, and the researchers say that they are probably the
cause of other die-offs this summer, including the deaths in late
June of hundreds of spring peeper frogs at Acadia National Park in
Maine and of wood frogs, bullfrogs and salamanders in North
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   What is still not known is whether the die-offs, which are not
limited to this country, are short-term events or a part of a
longer-term phenomenon that is only now coming to light. Among
theories being investigated to help explain the population declines
are increased exposure to ultraviolet radiation (due to thinning of
the ozone layer), pesticide contamination and rising temperatures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
