<SLUG> BC-OLY-JAPAN-GYMNAST-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPANESE GYMNAST STRIVES TO HONOR FATHER AND COUNTRY WITH GOLD
MEDAL 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Naoya Tsukahara bounced up and down on the trampoline
that had been lowered into the floor. Up and down and up and down
again, then suddenly, in a split second, he lofted himself high
into the air and did two graceful, twisting, vertical somersaults
before landing, like a butterfly, on his tiny feet.
</P>
<P>
   In that momentary performance, at the end of a recent, sweaty
three-hour practice session with the Japanese men's gymnastic team,
is a flash of deja vu. For that peculiar pretzeled somersault, a
hallmark of Naoya's performance, is a derivation of Japan's most
famous gymnastic stunt, the ``moon'' somersault. It was concocted
by his father, Mitsuo Tsukahara, who used it 28 years ago in Munich
to win his first individual Olympic gold medal, on the horizontal
bar, scoring a 9.9 out of 10 in the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would fold my body and somersault in the air while
twisting,'' the elder Tsukahara said. ``What Naoya does is twist
his body while keeping it straight. The style is different, but the
basic skills are those of the moon somersault.''
</P>
<P>
   Now there is a chance that Naoya will use that somersault to do
something that his father never did _ win an individual gold medal
in the all-around men's gymnastic competition. He won the silver in
the all-around at last year's world championships, and the gymnast
who beat him there, Nikolai Krukov, damaged his Achilles' tendon
this past spring and is not expected to be in peak condition in
time for the Summer Olympics in Sydney, Australia, which begin on
Sept. 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, that's a possibility,'' Naoya's father said of his son's
odds for a gold medal. ``He has a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   The younger Tsukahara's performance in Sydney may also help
restore some of Japan's glory of years past, when the country
seemed to be a breeding ground for top male gymnastic talent. In
the 1960s and 70s, when Mitsuo Tsukahara was flying around the gym,
the Japanese men's team was the only real challenger to the
powerful, state-supported gymnasts from behind the Iron Curtain.
The Japanese team won five straight gold medals from 1960 to 1976,
edging out the Soviet Union each time. Tsukahara was on the last
three of those teams, and he also won six individual Olympic medals
_ two gold, one silver and three bronze.
</P>
<P>
   A vault that still bears the father's name, the Tsukahara, was
first performed about 30 years ago by Mitsuo Tsukahara. It consists
of a cartwheel with a quarter-turn followed by a backward
somersault. The maneuver marked the first time a gymnast had
performed a 360-degree somersault while vaulting, and
revolutionized the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really unique and very original and it just changed all
of vaulting completely,'' Peter Kormann, the U.S. men's Olympic
coach, said.
</P>
<P>
   Japan has not won a gold medal for gymnastics since the Los
Angeles Olympics in 1984, when Koji Gushiken struck gold in the
all-around competition and on the still rings, and Shinji Morisue
won a gold medal on the horizontal bar. ``It will be extremely
significant if Naoya wins a gold medal,'' said Kenji Takamiya, a
reporter who covers gymnastics here at the sports newspaper Nikkan
Sports. ``Japanese people will be moved, and, more importantly,
Japanese companies will increase their support for gymnastics.''
</P>
<P>
   Gymnasts here are almost entirely dependent on corporate
sponsorship. But a decade of economic decline, coupled with the
dwindling fortunes of Japan's gymnasts, has resulted in diminished
financial support for the sport. Takamiya said that even Daiwa
Bank, long known as a backer of gymnastics here, has cut back its
support.
</P>
<P>
   A victory by Naoya Tsukahara or any other member of the Japanese
team in Sydney could change that. ``The Japanese gymnastics world
is in critical condition,'' Takamiya said. ``My guess is that the
only way to save it is for Naoya to win a gold medal.''
</P>
<P>
   The lack of air-conditioning at the Asahi Gymnastics Club, where
Naoya works out, is a telling sign of the times. The two small,
portable air-conditioning units are pushed around the gym to cool
the areas where Naoya and his team members are working out. The
chalk that the gymnasts use to coat their hands hangs heavy in the
air, irritating eyes and lungs.
</P>
<P>
   Asahi Mutual Life Co. supports the gym, which has long been home
to many of Japan's best gymnasts. It is a family affair for the
Tsukaharas, with Mitsuo serving as the director and men's head
coach and his wife, Chieko, also a former Olympic gymnast, serving
as the women's head coach.
</P>
<P>
   When Naoya travels to Sydney, he will carry along an ivory seal
bearing his name that his mother gave him, repeating one of his
father's traditions. ``I think Naoya will end up in the top 10, but
whether he wins a gold, silver or bronze medal, I can't say,''
Chieko Tsukahara said. ``The abilities of the top 10 male gymnasts
in the world are so close that a lot of it will have to do with
luck.''
</P>
<P>
   She believes the family is blessed with good luck. Her husband,
for example, won one of his gold medals for the horizontal bar on a
day when a knee injury he had suddenly subsided during the
competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in working hard on training so that you can
capitalize on luck,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Naoya follows a rigorous workout schedule, practicing for two or
three hours in the morning and two hours in the afternoon. Asked
what the family talks about over meals, he paused for a moment and
smiled before saying, ``Gymnastics, of course.'' Naoya is studying
business administration at Meiji University, but spends much of his
spare time in the gym, a habit that gives his father pause. Mitsuo
Tsukahara recalls spending more time training _ and regretting it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I practiced more, but I think you can practice too much,'' he
said. ``The thinking about this has changed since my time.`
</P>
<P>
   Naoya's coaching has also differed from his father's and it has
become something of a curiosity here. One might have expected his
father to serve as his coach, but instead, when Naoya was starting
junior high school, his father retained a Chinese coach, Wu Jie, to
train him. Wu, a top Chinese gymnast, was in Japan studying
Japanese and looking for a part-time job when Mitsuo Tsukahara
hired him.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-00 2036EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000904.0230 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0657 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s BC-OLY-JAPAN-GYMNAST &LR; - &UR; A     09-04 0562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-JAPAN-GYMNAST </SLUG>
 - ART-2NDTAKE-NYT  
 UNDATED: hired him.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Foreign coaches are still an oddity in Japan, so heads really
turned in 1994 when Tsukahara brought in his old friend and rival
Nikolai Andrianov, a chain-smoking former top gymnast from Russia,
to coach his son. Andrianov won seven medals at the Montreal
Olympics in 1976, including a gold in the all-around, leaving
Tsukahara to pick up a bronze medal in the same event. Both Naoya
and his father credit Andrianov with raising Naoya's skills to
international standards and with giving him the confidence he would
need to compete in world championships. ``I wanted Naoya to have a
proper coach, and at the time, Chinese and Russian gymnasts were on
top of the world,'' Tsukahara said.
</P>
<P>
   Now his son is a contender for similar distinction, but the
Tsukaharas deliberately downplay his talents and prospects by
severely limiting his exposure to the news media. A recent
interview with Naoya after a two-hour training session with the
Japanese team was limited to precisely 15 minutes, although his
parents were far more generous with their time.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I won my medals I was happy, of course,'' the elder
Tsukahara said. ``But before I won them, I always felt like I was
under a lot of pressure to win, like people were pushing too
hard.''
</P>
<P>
   The moon somersault that contributed to the elder Tsukahara's
lore in Japan got its name from the day he first attempted the
maneuver in competition: July 20, 1969, the day that Neil Armstrong
walked on the moon.
</P>
<P>
   The father's experiences convinced him that the biggest
contribution he now could make to Naoya is to keep reporters at a
safe distance. He is particularly wary of the idiosyncratic
Japanese television scene, with its emphasis on slap-stick humor
and embarrassment. ``They often ask things like what's your
favorite food, what hobby do you have, who's your favorite star and
would you like to teach her how to do a somersault on TV,'' Mitsuo
Tsukahara snorted. ``TV can come after the games, I hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the strategy has worked, because Naoya seems
preternaturally calm and self-possessed for one with so many hopes
resting on his exaggeratedly broad shoulders. He is famous for
telling his father that he did not need his company in the waiting
room during the Olympics in Atlanta, Naoya's first Olympic
competition. ``He sent his father back out to watch the action,
telling him, `You don't have to come with me, Papa,''' Takamiya
said.
</P>
<P>
   Naoya said he could sense that there were great expectations for
him at the Olympics. ``But my state of mind really hasn't
changed,'' he said during the brief interview, ``although having
said that, I would add that I do have higher spirits these days.''
</P>
<P>
   His biggest concern is injuries, a fear his mother shares. He
has a keen sense of his boundaries and accepts them. ``From now
until the Olympics, I will not try to stretch too much, reach too
far,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He has been practicing since first grade, deciding then to give
up a passion for soccer for his parents' sport. His father said
Naoya lost some enthusiasm for gymnastics in his adolescence, but
Naoya himself has a different recollection.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since I was little, I have been in this environment,'' he
said. ``I've played in this gym since I was young. So it feels
natural that this is what I'm doing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
