<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0666 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-BBO-PITCHERS05-COX     09-04 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-PITCHERS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Diamondbacks, Braves to square off in pitching showdown
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Sensing movement in the continental plates, the
baseball press did what is paid to do last July 31 when Curt
Schilling went back home and joined the Arizona Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   The press promptly rushed to judgement.
</P>
<P>
   The Sporting News determined Schilling and Randy Johnson as
``baseball's most formidable 1-2 punch.'' Baseball Weekly, with
Schilling giving a thumbs-up from the cover, called his move from
Philadelphia the best of trading season that ``puts the
Diamondbacks pitching staff over the top.''
</P>
<P>
   Comparisons were even made to the Sandy Koufax-Don Drysdale
reign of terror that defined the Dodgers' first years in Los
Angeles. And why not? In their final eight seasons together when
they dominated the National League, Koufax and Drysdale led the
league in strikeouts seven times. Schilling and Johnson in the last
eight years have led the NL in strikeouts six times, with Johnson
destined to make it seven this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so many writers now, that everybody has to have
something different or something new,'' Greg Maddux said. ``It was
appropriate at the time, an appropriate thing to write about and
talk about.''
</P>
<P>
   This week, the Atlanta Braves have their first opportunity to
respond. With the Diamondbacks in town for a three-game series
starting tonight, Johnson faces Tom Glavine in the first game with
a Maddux-Schilling match-up following Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, except for Glavine, the quartet has not exactly been
at the top of its game lately. But forget about that. Each has a
deep big-game history. Just recall Schilling's shutout performance
at Turner Field May 6 for the Phillies, when just six days after
coming off the DL, he was still hitting 95 mph in the ninth inning,
when he struck out the side.
</P>
<P>
   This week is a reminder that even in the midst of the game's
unprecedented offensive boom, September should be about pitching.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's rare, especially right now with the offense the way that
it is, to have a series where pitching will get so much of the
attention,'' said Glavine, whose 18 wins leads the NL.
</P>
<P>
   After losing 10-1 at Florida last Saturday, Schilling has lost
four of his last five starts, giving up 17 earned runs in 20
innings to bottom-feeders Milwaukee, Montreal and the Marlins.
Johnson, after a 14-2 first half, is 3-3 since the All-Star break
with opponents batting nearly .265 against him. In the first half,
they hit .193.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been a whole lot of fun to be around the past
month,'' Johnson said last week. ``It's been frustrating. I take a
lot of pride in what I do and feel like I'm not doing what I'm
supposed to be doing since the all-star break.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Johnson could be pitching right-handed and the same hype
that warmed up the Schilling trade would perk again this week. The
reason: the fastball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those two guys are known for being power pitchers and striking
people out and lighting up the radar gun,'' Glavine said. ``And
Greg and I don't. We get people out with ground balls or whatever.
</P>
<P>
   ``You come watch Greg and me pitch, you're not going to leave
the ballpark with this feeling of `Wow.' But with Randy and
Schilling, you might. There might be 10 or 15 punch-outs. That's
what grabs peoples' attention. Strikeouts and the long ball are the
fashionable thing in baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Schilling and Johnson make some interesting comparisons to
Koufax and Drydale. The two Dodgers over the last eight years they
pitched together struck out a combined 3,760 batters, just 149 more
than the two Diamondbacks, and made the All-Star team 12 times
compared the Schilling's and Johnson's nine.
</P>
<P>
   But Glavine and Maddux comes closer to Koufax and Drysdale in
victories (288 to 273) over those eight years and actually have a
best winning percentage (.693) of the three duos. Glavine and
Maddux's ERA (2.86) can't match Koufax and Drysdale (2.74), who
recorded more shutouts (70) in their last eight years than Glavine,
Maddux, Schilling and Johnson combined (59).
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to be surprised when someone who hit it fair off Koufax
and I'd be surprised whenever anyone would have a stable front leg
against Drysdale,'' said Braves broadcaster Don Sutton, a
21-year-old rookie in the 1966 Dodgers rotation, which wound up
being Koufax's final season.
</P>
<P>
   ``They brought two different styles of pitching. But the things
you could always count on was that they were going to make their
starts, they were going to stay out there until you took a fork
lift out there to go get them and you knew when they were out
there, you had a chance to win every ball game. Not some of them or
most of them but you had a chance to win every one.''
</P>
<P>
   All those traits will be evident these next three nights at
Turner Field, where style will clash, if not intent. Five weeks
after Schilling returned to his old hometown, the game finally gets
to grade a trade that set a million tongues wagging.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're dominant whether you get outs with fly balls, ground
balls, strikeouts,'' said Atlanta's John Burkett, who has witnessed
12 years of major league pitching. ``It doesn't matter. You're
doing it. The guys have a low-3, high-2 ERA, they're doing it every
fifth day, don't miss any starts. I think that's impressive. That's
dominant. It doesn't matter how it gets done.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
