</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-SERVICE-1140(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS DIPLOMACY LOSES LUSTER, YOUNG STARS FLEE STATE DEPARTMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   By JANE PERLEZ   
 C.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ At 32, Mona Sutphen, smart, driven and possessed of
that quality so elusive in Washington, an easy personality, was
known as one of the best and the brightest in the West Wing of the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   As executive assistant to the national security adviser, Sandy
Berger, she was trusted to work on the most sensitive foreign
policy matters. She sat through the tough crises, including whether
to bomb Iraq and how to rescue an American pilot downed in enemy
Yugoslav territory. Had she wanted, Sutphen, who was on loan from
the State Department, could have gone to the heights of the U.S.
Foreign Service: political counselor at an embassy, assistant
secretary of state or an ambassador. Perhaps even the top job one
day.
</P>
<P>
   But those peaks did not look so great to Sutphen.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of returning to the State Department and a future of
writing cables that she felt nobody important read, she took her
passion for foreign affairs to an Internet company. She is a prime
example of what policy experts say is a crippling problem at the
State Department: talented diplomats are leaving for careers that
they believe have more power and prestige in the new global
economy. And college graduates who used to rush to take the Foreign
Service exam no longer bother.
</P>
<P>
   This comes as the State Department, the institution responsible
for American diplomacy around the world, is finding it hard to
adjust to an era in which financial markets pack more punch than a
Washington-Moscow summit meeting. It is losing recruits to
investment banks, dot-com companies and the Treasury and Commerce
Departments, which have magnified their foreign policy roles. Some
are turning to idealistic private organizations that work in risky
environments abroad, a far cry from the days of the Cold War, when
the State Department was the only place to be.
</P>
<P>
   When Sutphen prepared to leave the State Department this spring,
the Foreign Service made her decision easier because, while it took
great pride in her as a woman of African-American heritage, it
offered her nothing that she found challenging.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end there was nothing on the horizon that I really
wanted,'' she said. After the hothouse of the National Security
Council at the White House, and having served in Bosnia and
Thailand, the ``idea of being the third political officer on the
Israeli desk is very difficult.'' Instead, she chose to join the
Manhattan office of Currenex, a Silicon Valley Internet company
that specializes in business-to-business foreign currency trading,
at a salary of more than $100,000 _ more than twice her government
pay _ plus stock options.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of prestige and power at the State Department has not
gone unnoticed around Washington or inside the department itself.
What to do about it has consumed study groups and consultants and
caused internal hand-wringing among the top echelon of State
Department officials.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the department was so worried about the problem that
two years ago it commissioned a study from a consulting firm,
McKinsey &AMP; Co. The results , with recommendations to be carried out
this year, were not flattering.
</P>
<P>
   Young diplomats told the consultants that they were frustrated
by slow promotions in the bureaucracy compared with promotions
based on merit in the private sector. They questioned the relevance
of their work. ``The best for what work?'' parried one respondent.
</P>
<P>
   They were dismissive of what they described as a demoralized
management. They complained that the department was unresponsive to
the demands of two-career couples, especially when sending
diplomats abroad.
</P>
<P>
   The study, titled ``The War for Talent'' _ tellingly renamed
``The War Against Talent'' in the department's corridors _ quoted
one diplomat as saying, ``You've joined the supposedly elite
Foreign Service and you have terrible managers _ people who've been
promoted to get them out of other people's hair.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside the department, the U.S. Commission on National
Security/21st Century, set up by the federal government to study
the nation's needs for its national security architecture, has
taken a particular interest in the failings of the State
Department. The commission's executive director, Gen. Charles G.
Boyd, said he had been taken aback by the difficulty the department
had in ``retaining and recruiting quality people.''
</P>
<P>
   At elite graduate schools specializing in international
relations, deans say that the Foreign Service has slipped down the
totem pole as a career choice.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, smart graduates who want to join government are heading
for the Departments of the Treasury or Commerce, said Mark L. von
Hagen, director of the Harriman Institute at Columbia University.
Others gravitate toward nongovernmental organizations and to the
World Bank. ``It reflects the generally diminished role of the
State Department in foreign policy,'' von Hagen said.
</P>
<P>
   The new director-general of the Foreign Service at the State
Department, Marc Grossman, who is in essence the department's chief
personnel officer, acknowledged the problem when he appeared before
the Commission on National Security recently.
</P>
<P>
   The dropout rate for one of the five groups of diplomats who
entered the State Department in 1992 or 1993 was 32 percent, he
said. For another group in that two-year period the dropout rate
was 23 percent, although it was only 12 percent for two other
groups. From 1994 to 1997, the dropout rate has hovered around 20
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the State Department's personnel department said
they did not have statistics to compare this dropout rate with
previous decades. Nor, they said, had the department done any
analysis to determine whether those who had left in the 1990s were
considered the most talented.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most senior officials at the State Department,
Undersecretary of States Thomas R. Pickering, who has served for
nearly 40 years and has been ambassador to eight countries, said he
did not believe that the dropout rates differed ``so wildly'' from
the past, particularly in the era of the Vietnam War when many
dissenters quit.
</P>
<P>
   But Boyd said that ``anecdotal'' evidence suggested that good
young diplomats had quit in the 1990s and that the dropout rate was
higher than in the past.
</P>
<P>
   And for all those who are leaving, there are believed to be many
who are more than qualified but are not considering the Foreign
Service. Last year, said the undersecretary for management, Bonnie
R. Cohen, there was a ``significant'' drop in the number of
candidates who, after passing the written and oral exams of the
Foreign Service and the security checks, accepted an offer to join
the department.
</P>
<P>
   ``That means young people are looking elsewhere for other
jobs,'' said Cohen, who is in charge of budgetary and personnel
matters for the department.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Money _ in particular the large financial packages from merchant
banks that also offer stimulating work in the global economy _ is
proving an important, though not overriding, reason for officials
to leave.
</P>
<P>
   The average starting salary for a new Foreign Service officer is
$32,500, Cohen said. This is less than some customer service agents
make at Verizon's union telephone company.
</P>
<P>
   Peter E. Bass, 37 _ who after a meteoric career left the State
Department this summer to join Goldman Sachs as the chief of staff
for the bank's president and chief operating officer, John L.
Thornton _ is one of half a dozen officials who have been enticed
away in the last several years by Goldman Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope to gain a knowledge of the financial world, the global
economy and capital markets, which are the key for global
prosperity,'' Bass said, explaining his decision to leave. He had
been deputy assistant secretary of state for energy and sanctions,
involved in policy toward Iran and Libya.
</P>
<P>
   But the Wall Street salary was also a lure. ``When the
difference in money is arithmetic, it's bearable; when it's
geometric, it becomes harder and harder,'' Bass said.
</P>
<P>
   One reason that Grossman is appreciated as the new face of
personnel, though, is that he acknowledges that money is not the
only reason for losing good people. He knows, he said, that in
order to attract and keep talent, the department must evolve.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Department has to change from being one that went and
observed to one that sees itself in a more active world,'' Grossman
said. ``I can't give more people more money but I can give jobs
that are seen as more active and less passive.''
</P>
<P>
   But it may be a hard argument to win. Many of the fields that
Grossman talks about being new to the State Department _
international trafficking in people, the environment, empowering
poor women _ are often handled by other American agencies operating
abroad.
</P>
<P>
   The Drug Enforcement Administration and the FBI, for example,
now operate at a number of American embassies. Rather than being
proud of this expansion, American diplomats view these agencies as
competitors for whom, they say, embassies perform the role of
``concierge.'' At the American Embassy in London, for example,
fewer than 20 percent of the officials belong to the State
Department.
</P>
<P>
   There are other hurdles: most notably, the archaic way the State
Department hires people and treats them once they get inside. It
can take up to two years before a candidate, who has taken the
written exam (general knowledge, focusing on international affairs)
and the oral exam (problem solving) and passed the security
clearance, is invited to join the Foreign Service.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats who have recently left the State Department argue that
the substance of the work must also change if good people are going
to stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got a culture where you are told to make notes and send
them forward,'' said Spence Spencer, 38, who quit this summer after
12 years and three tours abroad. ``A lot of it is staffing to make
sure your boss looks good.''
</P>
<P>
   Spencer, who celebrated his departure over several glasses of
wine at a recent lunch, left on a high note. He reached a cherished
goal: equipping 30 court buildings in Kosovo with computers, fax
machines, photocopiers, typewriters, generators and metal
detectors.
</P>
<P>
   An official in the department's Human Rights Bureau, Spencer
said there was much more in the field of human rights that he would
like to do at the State Department but felt he would be unable to
achieve.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is such disdain for the community of nongovernment
organizations at the State Department,'' said Spencer, whose
passion is elections, police, justice and the other ``soft'' issues
that crop up in regions of conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``At State, you can't talk to these organizations with ease,''
he said. ``So you are left talking to each other.'' Spencer is
joining Public Strategies Inc., a company based in Austin, Texas.
He will specialize in public affairs for European companies
exporting to the United States and plans to do pro bono work for
international nongovernmental organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Another diplomat, Cynthia R. Bunton, 46, who dreamed of joining
the State Department from age 12, speaks four languages and has
served in a number of posts abroad. Now that she is back in
Washington, the department is unable to find a way to use her new
expertise in intellectual property rights, an increasingly vital
issue for American business.
</P>
<P>
   As the consul in Naples, Italy, for political and commercial
affairs, she became an expert in property rights and for the past
year has been on loan to the Recording Industry Association of
America in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Bunton said she realized the importance of economics in
diplomacy several years ago and decided to concentrate on music
piracy. ``The question is: Do I go backward and become a political
officer again _ which I have been all my life _ or go out into
private industry?'' she said. She still feels loyalty to the State
Department, but she is leaning, she said, toward leaving.
</P>
<P>
   One of those on the U.S. Commission on National Security, Leslie
H. Gelb, said that in order to keep people like Sutphen, Bass,
Spencer and Bunton, the State Department must make fundamental
changes to regain the prestige of the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``The State Department will be able to attract anyone it wants
when once again the building becomes the center of making foreign
policy and foreign policy strategy,'' said Gelb, who is the
president of the Council on Foreign Relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good people want to work at places that are at the center of
things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
