<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0676 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-OLY-SUPPORT05-COX     09-04 1275
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SUPPORT05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GM fills the garages of some lucky Olympic hopefuls
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ On a crowded Atlanta street, Kevin Young pulls over
and lowers the passenger-side window on his Pontiac Grand Prix.
``Hey, you like my new car?'' he calls to a familiar passerby.
</P>
<P>
   Nice, yeah. And free.
</P>
<P>
   The car is a gift from General Motors. With the Sydney Games on
the horizon, GM and co-sponsor, the United Automobile Workers, put
100 has-been and wanna-be Olympians behind the wheel of new cars
since December. The promotional venture carries with it a $3.5
million price tag.
</P>
<P>
   This is as close as some lucky athletes will get to hitting the
lottery. The cars come with no strings attached. Forget about
taxes, GM is handling that. And you keep your new car whether you
made the Sydney Olympic team or not.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Young, whose best days were two Olympics ago in
Barcelona, didn't even bother to show up for the Olympic
track-and-field trials this summer to audition in the 400 hurdles.
</P>
<P>
   Stacy Dragila also was given keys to a Grand Prix _ though the
women's pole vault world record-holder earned an estimated $500,000
last year in prize money, performance bonuses and other sponsorship
from Reebok and Visa.
</P>
<P>
   Connie Price-Smith, 37, retiring after her fourth Olympics was
handed the equivalent of a gold watch by the automaker _ a GMC
Envoy.
</P>
<P>
   Pro tennis players Jill Craybus and Jackie Trail both landed
Pontiac Montanas, though neither made the Sydney team.
</P>
<P>
   Neither did Catherine Hearn, a 41-year-old kayaker who drove off
in a GMC Envoy.
</P>
<P>
   In all, 58 percent of the supposed Olympic hopefuls failed to
earn spots on the Sydney team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't really set any objectives as far as a minimium
number (of Sydney Olympians),'' offered Matt Pensinger, sports
marketing manager for General Motors.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, GM's Team Behind the Team program turned over keys to a
hodge podge of recipients, with an average age of 27 years and more
than a quarter of the athletes over 30 _ 16 of whom didn't make the
Olympic team. It also rewarded 22 past Olympians, though 10 failed
to make the Sydney team.
</P>
<P>
   A handful, like Dragila, earn a nice living in their sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is Stacy a professional athlete?'' asked Ken Holder, a UAW
spokesperson for the program. ``I guess I didn't realize that. This
is the first I've heard about her having that kind of income.''
</P>
<P>
   Holder said the JK Group., which manages corporate philanthropic
programs, was hired to weed through the 1,800 applications before
passing them on to an athlete advisory group of ex-Olympians,
co-chaired by Grant Hill and Dorothy Hamill, and including Carl
Lewis, Evelyn Ashford, Bob Mathias, Pablo Morales and Kristi
Yamaguchi.
</P>
<P>
   ``I considered whether they were (professionals) a little bit,
yeah,'' said Hill, the NBA star. ``I don't know what other people
did, but I looked more for those who were in need and could truly
benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   In that regard, the program benefitted the likes of rower Sarah
Garner (Buick Regal), who never had a chance for the 1996 team
because her old clunker blew a clutch while she was driving to the
Olympic trials.
</P>
<P>
   But the whole specter of athlete support is a dicey subject
during an Olympic year, perhaps never more so than with the U.S.
Olympic Committee under new controversial executive director, Norm
Blake, who has expressed a willingness to link dollars to Olympic
medals. His bottom-line approach is to reward the medal winners and
sports that drive up TV ratings and attract corporate sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   This year alone, the U.S. Olympic Committee will provide monthly
support totaling $12.4 million to 850 athletes (an average of about
$15,000 annually per athlete) _ three-quarters of whom were in
training for Sydney and the rest for the 2004 Winter Games. That
doesn't count another $8 million in athlete support doled out
through something called Venture 2000, nor other grants or the
hundreds of athletes employed by Olympic sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   Question is, does the performance by General Motors, with 42 of
100 recipients making the Olympic team, mirror USOC efforts?
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Olympic Committee isn't saying, but its own consulting
firm recently found that 40 percent of USOC support goes to sports
that rarely if ever win medals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not release the names of athletes who receive our
support, or the figures (they receive),'' said Mike Moran, a USOC
spokesman. ``The only time we'll release the names or figures is in
response to athletes who say in the media, `I don't get any support
from the USOC.'''
</P>
<P>
   Here, General Motors _ domestic automobile sponsor of the USOC _
couldn't be more public, going so far on its website as to publish
the athletes' application letters and photos of each of them with
their new vehicle. It's good promotion for the millions they spent,
of course.
</P>
<P>
   GM plans to award a similiar allotment of vehicles prior to the
2002 Winter Games in Salt Lake City, followed by another 100 cars
before the 2004 Athens Games.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of recent scandals afflicting the Olympic movement,
GM officials sought to provide direct help to athletes. Governing
bodies for the various sports _ such as USA Track and Field and
U.S. Swimming, for example _ were asked to provide a list of
Olympic hopefuls. That doesn't mean the governing bodies are all on
top of their game, however.
</P>
<P>
   Take hurdler Kevin Young.
</P>
<P>
   At the Barcelona Olympics, he set a world record of 46.78
seconds in the 400-meter hurdles, but he's evolved into the Howard
Hughes of the sport since 1994, rarely seen on the track and
showing his age (34 this month) when he's bothered to compete.
</P>
<P>
   It was in 1994 that Young moved from Los Angeles, buying a
sprawling ranch home on 13 secluded acres north of Atlanta for
$359,000 _ hardly the purchase of a starving athlete. His car
collection included a Mercedes-Benz, Lexus SC 300 and Honda. He
signed a $100,000-a-year contract with Nike after the Barcelona
Games.
</P>
<P>
   Then, he stopped competing and came upon hard times. He recently
moved to New York and his cars were ``sold to pay off some debts,''
Young said.
</P>
<P>
   So news that he fit the ``hopeful'' description and was awarded
a car surprised many in the sport _ including Derrick Adkins, 400
hurdles champ at the Atlanta Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's funny because I applied and I didn't get it,'' said
Adkins, who retired after being eliminated in the semis at the
Olympic trials. ``I was closer than Kevin to making (the team). He
wasn't even there.''
</P>
<P>
   If there's a flaw, GM says it's with the track federation.
``We're certainly not experts on who is a hopeful and who isn't,''
said Pensinger, GM's sports marketing manager.
</P>
<P>
   Track managed the most receipients, with 10 of the 19 new car
owners making the Sydney team _ most getting a Grand Prix. Water
sport athletes drove off in the purest luxury, Cadillac Devilles
</P>
<P>
   The best return on investment came in sailing (2), shooting (2),
tae kwon do (2), synchronized swimming (3) and men's water polo (4)
where they all made the team. The worst in boxing (2), swimming
(2), tennis (2), volleyball (3), table tennis _ where none made the
team.
</P>
<P>
   So in the future, how do you ensure car keys get in the hands of
Olympians? Grant Hill offered a solution bound to bring a smile to
athletes' faces _ give everybody that applies a car.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough and you have to have cutoff number, but it would be
nice to be able to help everybody,'' Hill said. ``And General
Motors can do that _ they have enough money.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
