<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN MEDIA MAGNATE REPORTS KREMLIN IS TRYING TO SILENCE HIM 
</HEADLINE>
   By PATRICK E. TYLER   
 c.20001995 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ One of the country's media moguls, Boris Berezovsky,
said on Monday that a senior Kremlin official had ordered him to
transfer his holdings in Russia's primary state-owned television
channel to the state, or face the prospect of going to jail.
</P>
<P>
   Berezovsky made this assertion in a letter addressed to
President Vladimir Putin that was made available on Monday to The
New York Times and other news organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I agree to the ultimatum, television information will cease
to exist in Russia and be replaced by television propaganda,
controlled by your advisers,'' Berezovsky said.
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``By issuing this ultimatum to me, you have in essence
put an important question before the country _ do non-state media
have the right to exist in Russia?''
</P>
<P>
   In the letter, Berezovsky did not detail the nature of the legal
threat he said he was facing, but said he was given two weeks to
dispose of his 49 percent holding in the television channel.
</P>
<P>
   In response, he said, he had decided to transfer that holding
``to journalists and other representatives of the creative
intelligentsia,'' for a form of ``public'' television.
</P>
<P>
   The publication of the letter was nonetheless significant
because it underscored the unrelenting campaign by the Russian
president to take large holdings away from the oligarchs who took
them over under preferential conditions during the last decade, and
wielded them on the Kremlin's behalf, but now have taken a more
critical line toward Putin and his policies.
</P>
<P>
   Putin was said to have been incensed when, during the
unsuccessful sea rescue of the nuclear submarine Kursk, the
Berezovsky station, ORT, aired interviews with family members of
the crew who were highly critical of the government's handling of
the failed operation.
</P>
<P>
   In his two-hour session with Kursk family members, Putin vented
his deep-seated anger at Russia's media barons, according to a
transcript in the weekly Vlast magazine, published by Berezovsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have embezzled enough, bought up the media and are now
manipulating public opinion,'' Putin said of them.
</P>
<P>
   In June, Putin's government arrested Vladimir Gusinsky, another
media baron, and held him at the notorious Butyrskaya Prison for
four days on embezzlement charges that were dropped after Gusinsky
met with Putin's chief-of-staff. Gusinsky then left the country and
has not returned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
