<SLUG> BC-MONEYBAG-COLUMN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   MONEYBAG (column) 
 
 Waiting to Sell Merged Stock Has No Tax Advantage 
 &HT;     BY ARTHUR M. LOUIS  
 c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Q: I purchased shares in Snyder Oil Co. many years ago. It merged
with Santa Fe Energy Resources to become Santa Fe Snyder, and now
it has merged again with Devon. Devon gave me 0.22 shares of its
stock in exchange for every share of Santa Fe Snyder I owned. I may
want to sell some of my Devon shares before long. Must I wait 12
months to take advantage of the reduced tax rate on long-term
capital gains?
<P>
   A: You can sell your shares immediately, if you wish, and you
still will be able to categorize your gain as long term. That's
because the merger was considered a nontaxable event.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally, when a corporate merger takes effect and you trade
one stock for another, it is a nontaxable event and both your cost
basis and holding period carry over,'' says Internal Revenue
Service spokesman Jesse Weller.
</P>
<P>
   The difference between the long-term and short-term tax rates
can be significant.
</P>
<P>
   If you are in the 28 percent tax bracket, the tax on your
long-term gain will be capped at 20 percent. That's a tax saving of
$800 for every $10,000 worth of gains.
</P>
<P>
   If you are in the 15 percent bracket, the long-term tax will be
capped at 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   First Sold, First Served
</P>
<P>
   Q: I know that the IRS expects you to use the first in/first out
method when you sell part of your holdings in a stock _ unless you
inform your broker in advance specifically which shares you are
selling. But what if you hold shares in the same stock with two
different brokers? If you sell shares held by Broker A, but your
earliest share purchase was with Broker B, would the IRS assume
that you are selling the shares held by Broker B?
</P>
<P>
   A: I can understand why you would ask that question, because the
tax code often seems irrational and procrustean.
</P>
<P>
   But not in this case.
</P>
<P>
   If you sell shares held by Broker A, then the shares held by
Broker B don't figure in the calculation. If you are using the
first in/ first out method, then the shares you sell would be the
shares you bought first in your Broker A account.
</P>
<P>
   As a rule, you will want to sell shares on which you have a
capital loss, to offset your taxable income. If you have only
gains, then you might find it best to sell shares on which the
gains are long term _ meaning that you have held the shares for at
least a year and one day. That's because of the markedly lower tax
rates on long-term capital gains. (See the item above.)
</P>
<P>
   As you indicate, you may also have the option of telling your
broker which shares you are selling _ assuming that you made more
than one purchase with that broker.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, that is rarely, if ever, possible if you use a
broker that operates strictly online. Most such brokers aren't set
up to accommodate customers that way.
</P>
<P>
   That is one of the penalties you pay for the opportunity to
trade securities at bargain-basement commission rates.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; Sign Over Certificates
</P>
<P>
   Q: I notice that you commented recently about the virtues and
drawbacks of holding stock certificates, rather than depositing
them in a brokerage account. I have an account with E-Trade, and
want to sell some stock for which I hold the certificate. They have
asked me to sign the certificate over to them. Must I do this?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, indeed.
</P>
<P>
   The certificate is official proof that you own your shares. If
you surrender ownership, then you must surrender the ownership
document.
</P>
<P>
   Think of it this way: Suppose you want to sell your car. Do you
think anyone would buy it if you didn't hand over your ownership
papers?
</P>
<P>
   Well, come to think of it, somewhere in this wondrous world you
might find someone who will pay for the car and let you keep the
papers. But I don't think you will ever find a stockbroker who is
quite that intellectually challenged.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of stupidity: Don't forget to demand a receipt from
your broker, indicating the name of the company whose stock you are
selling, the number of shares you signed over and the certificate
number.
</P>
<P>
   Send questions about how to manage your money to
moneybag(AT)sfchronicle.com, or to Arthur M. Louis, Moneybag
column, 901 Mission St., San Francisco, CA 94103.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-00 2105EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000904.0245 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0679 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-VOTERS-RELIGION-NYT     09-04 1218
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOTERS-RELIGION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY VOTERS WARY OF CANDIDATES' RELIGIOUS TALK 
</HEADLINE>
  By DIRK JOHNSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ All the talk of faith and religion in the presidential
campaign might be expected to gain the attention of a voter like
Sarah Dotson, 28, who rose early Sunday morning to attend Mass at
Holy Ghost Roman Catholic Church here.
</P>
<P>
   She had noticed, all right. And that was the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, it makes me a little uncomfortable,'' said Dotson,
who clutched a prayer book as church bells pealed. ``I've heard
enough from the candidates about how they pray. I want to hear how
they're going to keep the economy going.''
</P>
<P>
   Voters could scarcely miss the expressions of religious faith by
candidates in this presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the Republican nominee, declared a
``Jesus Day'' in his state. Vice President Al Gore, the Democratic
nominee, has described himself as a born-again Christian who often
asks himself, ``What would Jesus do?''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joseph Leiberman of Connecticut, the Democratic
vice-presidential nominee, who is an Orthodox Jew, has urged that
religious faith play a stronger role in American life.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the soul baring by candidates, more than three dozen
voters interviewed around the country in the past few days
expressed little interest in weighing the religious convictions of
candidates in choosing the next president.
</P>
<P>
   As Kim Cart, a 29-year-old store clerk in Vinton, La., put it,
with a chuckle, ``As long as he's not into Satanic rituals, I
really don't care about a politician's religious beliefs.''
</P>
<P>
   Even those who consider themselves religious, like Dee Bobbitt,
a 47-year-old waitress who teaches Sunday school and helps clean
the First Assembly of God Church in suburban Houston, did not place
much emphasis on the religious views of a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I care more if they're smart,'' said Bobbitt, who thinks
President Clinton ``has done a wonderful job,'' no matter that he
might not agree with her views on the sinfulness of drinking,
smoking, dancing and gambling, not to mention sex outside marriage.
``I'd like to say that it does matter if a president is religious,
but it just doesn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Those interviewed also tended to express a skepticism about the
sincerity of the religious views of candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Doby, a 41-year-old truck driver from Stockton, Calif.,
shook his head with impatience at the religious ponderings of
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a way to try to get votes, that's all,'' said Doby,
who added that he did not believe in God. ``I'm jealous of people
who can go to church and find solace. I can't. Some people can, and
that's cool. But it's got nothing whatsoever to do with running the
country. It just doesn't have any relevance, and they ought to stop
talking about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaunessy McNeely, a 21-year-old nursing student, who attended
Riverside Baptist Church here, said she could not help noticing
that politicians are mostly like to preach to the choir or keep
quiet if they think an audience is not receptive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jesus Day in Texas _ how hard is that?'' McNeely said
laughing, adding that it was scarcely a profile in religious
courage for Bush to issue such a proclamation in a state with so
many evangelical Christians. ``Is he going to go to San Francisco,
to Manhattan, and say, `Rah, rah, Jesus?' If he does, then I'll be
impressed.''
</P>
<P>
   David Carey, a 48-year-old Roman Catholic who works for an
insurance company here, said he appreciated that candidates were
trying to ``invoke a higher moral standard.'' But Carey said it was
folly to try to assess which candidate seemed to be more religious.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the candidates talk about religion, I just ignore them,''
he said. ``It says more about what the politicians think of the
voters, and what they think the voters want to hear.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, a few voters said the candidates should be talking
more about religion, not less.
</P>
<P>
   ``The morals of the country are shot, and God is the only way to
bring things back,'' said Bruce Abel, a 53-year-old kitchen
designer, who was on his way to Riverside Baptist Church here.
``Belief in God has shaped this country from the founding, and
God's hand needs to be in politics today.''
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton had been more religious, Abel said, the nation would
not have been forced to endure the sex scandal that nearly drove
him from office.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Clinton getting elected was all part of God's plan,'' he
said. ``It was part of a lesson for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Some voters said it was healthy for candidates to talk about
religion, as long as they did not push a particular faith.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Goldberg, a 57-year-old math teacher from Shawnee
Mission, Kan., said he thought it was odd that people seemed
uncomfortable talking about religion but did not so much as shrug
over the saturation of sex and violence in today's culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all that garbage out there, I would hope it would be
permissible to talk about God, too,'' Goldberg, an Orthodox Jew,
said. ``To me, religion is equated with morality. So I don't have a
problem with that. But it crosses the line when you promote a
particular religion.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the candidates, Leiberman tended to be seen as the most
sincere about his expressions of faith. ``He doesn't just say it,''
Cart said, ``he lives it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dick Rosenberg, a 61-year-old real estate investor here, who
described himself as a nonpracticing Jew, said he also admired
Leiberman. Nonetheless, Rosenberg said he wished the senator would
stop talking so much about religion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Religion shouldn't be used as a marketing tool,'' he said,
supporting the call by the Anti-Defamation League for Leiberman to
refrain from talking about his religion. ``It's a private deal, so
keep it private.''
</P>
<P>
   Even among voters who said their religion shaped their voting,
there was plenty of disagreement about the political will of God,
judging from the disparate views among people who shared pews in
the same church.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Loper, a 61-year-old secretary who attended Holy Ghost
Church, said her convictions would prevent her from voting for a
candidate who supported abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's against church teachings,'' Loper said. ``It can't be any
clearer.'' She said she would be voting for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Carrigan, 33, who also attended Holy Ghost, said his
faith also shaped his ideology.
</P>
<P>
   ``My religion inspires my politics,'' Carrigan said. ``The
church calls us to social action and justice, to take care of the
less fortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he would be voting for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Few voters seemed more troubled by the religious talk than John
Price, a 52-year-old management consultant, who was drinking coffee
at an outdoor cafe here.
</P>
<P>
   Price, a former resident of Oklahoma, recalled a conservative
politician in that state running on a campaign that focused on
``God, guns and gays.''
</P>
<P>
   He criticized Bush and Gore for making statements that ``smacked
of the cult of Jesus,'' appeals that he said risked dividing the
American public.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way religion is going to be an issue in the campaign
for me,'' Price said, ``is if somebody tries to force it on me.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he checked his watch, put down his coffee, and announced he
was in a hurry to leave.
</P>
<P>
   He was running late for church.
</P>
</TEXT>
