u f BC-FIRESTONE-LABOR-NYT     09-04 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIRESTONE-LABOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRESTONE REACHES ACCORD WITH UNION TO AVERT STRIKE 
</HEADLINE>
  By STEVEN GREENHOUSE with RICHARD A. OPPEL JR.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Negotiators for Bridgestone/Firestone and the union representing
8,000 of its workers reached a tentative settlement on Monday,
averting a strike that could have deepened the tire maker's crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement, reached at 2:30 a.m. after five days of marathon
talks, gives most union members a hefty pension increase and a
large pay raise, ranging from 12 percent to 25 percent over three
years, depending on a worker's base pay.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the United Steelworkers of America praised the
settlement for its generosity. Bridgestone/Firestone officials
hailed the accord because it would prevent a shutdown threatened at
9 of its 11 U.S. factories. ``The new agreement involves gains in
all areas,'' said Wayne Ranick, a union spokesman. He said the
ratification vote might take about two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Katz, a professor of industrial relations at Cornell
University, called the agreement ``a pretty solid package,''
adding, ``Recent union settlements have been 3 to 4 percent a year,
and this seems much stronger than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Struggling to repair its image and to recall and replace 6.5
million tires linked to accidents and scores of deaths,
Bridgestone/Firestone, a Japanese-owned concern, could have ill
afforded a strike. Union officials said a strike would have badly
delayed efforts to produce replacement tires, a process the company
says will take at least six months.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, federal officials said they were investigating
whether three Firestone brands were connected to 88 traffic deaths
in accidents possibly caused by tread loss or blowouts. In an
unusual move, federal regulators warned consumers on Friday that
1.4 million additional Bridgestone/Firestone tires the company has
refused to recall could pose safety risks and should be replaced.
</P>
<P>
   Labor experts said the union's strategy of threatening a strike
when Bridgestone/Firestone was so vulnerable appeared to have paid
off. Despite a reputation for fiercely battling unions, the
company, whose U.S. unit is based in Nashville, was far more
generous in the new settlement than one reached in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   That agreement took a rancorous 27 months, including a 10-month
strike during which the company enraged the union and the entire
labor movement by hiring 2,300 permanent replacement workers.
</P>
<P>
   Saul Solomon, Bridgestone/Firestone's chief negotiator, said the
company was pleased with the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe the settlement is very fair and competitive for
both sides,'' he said in a telephone interview. ``We believe we
will be able to maintain our competitive position.''
</P>
<P>
   The settlement, actually three different agreements covering
nine plants, will give most of the 8,000 workers a retroactive
cost-of-living raise next month of about $1.60 an hour. That money
comes from a cost-of-living reserve that the company had not
distributed for several years because workers had not achieved
certain production goals.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the workers will receive a raise of 20 cents an
hour when the contract is ratified, another 20 cents an hour on
Sept. 1, 2001 and 25 cents an hour more on Sept. 1, 2002. Beyond
that, the workers will receive quarterly cost-of-living
adjustments, no longer contingent upon their meeting production
goals.
</P>
<P>
   All told, the workers will receive raises of at least $2.25 an
hour over the contract's three years. Under the expired contract,
pay ranged from $9 an hour for new workers to $19 an hour for
experienced ones.
</P>
<P>
   At a picnic at a worker's home near the company's plant in
LaVergne, Tenn., nearly 100 union members were drinking beer,
playing volleyball and rejoicing. ``We came out real good,'' said
Mike Solomon, who has worked in the plant for 25 years. ``Now we
can get back to the business of building tires. We got a lot of
replacement tires to build. I think it's a good deal for
everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   The workers were also jubilant about the pension increase. At
most of the factories, the settlement will lift the monthly pension
for a worker who retires with 30 years' experience to $1,500 a
month, from the old level of either $1,020 or $1,230, depending on
various factors.
</P>
<P>
   Tracy Russell, who has worked for 12 years at the LaVergne
factory, said he was delighted by what would amount to an increase
of nearly 50 percent for many retirees. ``Everybody feels so good
about the contract,'' he said. ``The last eight years, they've
taken so much away from us.''
</P>
<P>
   The tentative agreement also improves death benefits and
grievance procedures, and gives more weight to a workers' seniority
when factories fill certain jobs and work shifts.
</P>
<P>
   The union had threatened strikes at six factories covered by a
master contract that expired on April 23. They are in Akron, Ohio;
Decatur, Ill., Des Moines, Iowa; Noblesville, Ind.; Oklahoma City;
and Russellville, Ark. The strike would have also involved three
other factories _ in Bloomington, Ill., LaVergne, Tenn., and Warren
County, Tenn. _ covered by separate contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Under Monday's settlement, the LaVergne factory will be covered
by the master agreement, while Bloomington and Warren will still
remain under separate contracts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
