u f BC-FIRESTONE-VENEZUELA-N     09-04 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIRESTONE-VENEZUELA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRESTONE AGREES TO RECALL 62,000 TIRES IN VENEZUELA 
</HEADLINE>
  By   LARRY ROHTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela _ Facing the threat of criminal and civil
actions here, Bridgestone/Firestone agreed on Monday to recall
62,000 tires that the Venezuelan government says had defects that
appear to have played a role in the deaths of at least 60 people in
automobile accidents.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel Ruh Rios, director of the Consumer Defense and Education
Institute, a government agency, announced the measure at a news
conference here and praised the company, which accounts for about
half of all tires sold here, calling its action ``a good sign.''
But he made it clear that Venezuela intends to press ahead with its
investigation into allegations that the company knew of defects in
tires manufactured here and in the United States and tried to cover
them up.
</P>
<P>
   ``This measure in no way exonerates Firestone from what we have
been pointing out, which is the shared responsibility of Firestone
and Ford in the design and selection of an inadequate tire,'' Ruh
said. He added that the prosecutor general will determine what
further action Venezuela's government will take.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this, the Venezuelan consumer has won a battle'' and has
been ``somewhat compensated,'' Ruh added. ``But the consumer and
Indecu,'' the Spanish-language acronym by which the agency is
known, ``are still on a war footing, because we do not feel
satisfied by this type of action.''
</P>
<P>
   All but a handful of the fatal accidents being investigated by
the consumer protection agency occurred when Ford Explorer sports
utility vehicles with Firestone tires went out of control and
flipped over on highways here after their tires shredded or
exploded. For that reason, Ruh said on Monday, Ford also has a
moral and financial responsibility to Venezuelan consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We suggest to the Ford Motor Co. that they study a series of
measures to see if they too can aid in the search for the truth,''
he said. ``We don't blame the tire alone'' for the accidents, he
added, saying that an appropriate response by Ford would be to
``withdraw this model, substitute them and pay owners'' some form
of compensation.
</P>
<P>
   The two varieties of Wilderness AT tires to be replaced, at an
estimated cost of $6.4 million, include, but are not limited to,
those often used on Ford Explorers. Ruh said the tire replacement
program would begin on Thursday and continue for about a month and
that it would affect not only Ford Explorers and other sports
utility vehicles but also some pick-up trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Telephone calls made to the Bridgestone/Firestone plant in
Valencia, about 90 miles southwest of here, were referred to the
company's public relations representatives, and Ford did not
respond to requests for comment. A Firestone spokesperson, Milagros
Hinojosa, confirmed the tire recall but deferred further comment
until after publication of an announcement that she said would be
published in Venezuelan newspapers on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Bridgestone/Firestone and Ford have been under mounting fire
here since Venezuelan officials began their inquiry, alerted by a
similar investigation in the United States. Ruh said the Firestone
recall marked a significant shift from the company's previous
position, which was that ``only 3,000 tires imported from the
United States in 1995'' had the manufacturing defects and that
tires made in Venezuela did not.
</P>
<P>
   ``We continue to investigate, because we continue to receive new
complaints'' of faulty tires on Ford Explorers, Jorge Dominguez,
chief of the consumer protection agency's investigative division,
said in an interview this morning.
</P>
<P>
   The agency now estimates the number of accidents that occurred
after Firestone tires shredded at 74 and says that at least 60
Venezuelans died as a result.
</P>
<P>
   Ruh said that while his agency did not have the power to file
criminal or civil charges, both Ford and Bridgestone/Firestone
would be sent citations on Tuesday ordering them to participate in
a ``conciliation process'' at the consumer protection agency's
offices here next week. The purpose, he said, is to see if the
companies are willing to provide compensation to complainants.
</P>
<P>
   If that process fails, Ruh said, the government would then begin
an administrative procedure that could result in fines of up to
$11,600 per violation. But that money would paid into the
government's coffers, not to the victims of tire blowouts on
highways here or to their survivors.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the consumer protection agency recommended to the
office of the federal prosecutor that an investigation into
possible criminal negligence on the part of both Ford and
Bridgestone/Firestone be started. In addition, lawyers here have
said they plan to file civil damage suits here and in the United
States on behalf of people injured or killed in Firestone tire
blowouts.
</P>
<P>
   Such a process, however, promises to be long and difficult.
Venezuela has virtually no consumer liability legislation and
notoriously corrupt courts. And lawyers say that the regulations
accompanying a new constitution approved last December have made it
even harder than in the past for victims who win civil actions to
recover damages from those responsible for their losses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-00 2126EDT &QL; 
