<HEADLINE>
WORLD BUSINESS NEWS IN BRIEF  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASIA STAKE SOLD IN SOUTH KOREAN BANK
</P>
<P>
   A consortium led by global investment firm Carlyle Group and
J.P. Morgan &AMP; Co. has become the largest shareholder in South
Korea's KorAm Bank after acquiring a 40 percent stake for 455.9
billion won ($412.6 million), the South Korean bank said. In a
statement to the Korea Stock Exchange, KorAm Bank said it had
signed an investment agreement to sell the stake to the consortium
in the form of Global Depositary Receipts. Earlier, a sole bid by
Carlyle to acquire a stake in KorAm Bank was rejected by the South
Korean government on grounds that the investment firm was not a
banking institution. Curently, Samsung Group and Bank of America
each hold a 16.8 percent stake in KorAm.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   AIR FRANCE PROFIT RISES 20 PERCENT
</P>
<P>
   The French carrier Air France said operating profit in the
quarter that ended June 30 rose 20.2 percent to 185 million euros,
or $166 million, on a 20 percent increase in revenue, to 3 billion
euros, fueled by a 33 percent rise in traffic over the North
Atlantic. Air France's president, Pierre-Henri Gourgeon, said the
increases came despite a sharp rise in fuel costs, and attributed
much of the North Atlantic growth to a recently announced alliance
with Delta. Net income in the quarter, the first in Air France's
fiscal year, rose 85 percent, to 267 million euros, helped in part
by the sale of a stake in the Amadeus reservation system.
</P>
<P>
   ELTEK TO ACQUIRE POWER CONVERSION
</P>
<P>
   Eltek ASA, a Norwegian power supply company, said it would buy
Power Conversion Products of the United States for about $330
million in stock. The deal brings together two suppliers of power
to the Internet and telecommunications industries. After the merger
the new company would derive nearly 40 percent of its revenue from
the United States. Eltek founder Alain Angelil controls 46.8
percent of the company's shares, and will need to endorse the
merger for it to take effect.
</P>
<P>
   TNT POST BUYS CTI LOGISTX
</P>
<P>
   Europe's second largest express package delivery company, TNT
Post Groep NV, said it had bought CTI Logistx from CSX Corp., the
U.S. railroad concern, for $650 million in cash. The deal was
announced in concert with TNT's first half earnings. The company
said its income, including profits on the sale of noncore business,
grew 25.1 percent to 229 million euros. Revenue jumped 19.5 percent
to 4.7 billion euros. The acquisition of CTI is TNT's largest
purchase since it went public in 1998. It brings TNT one step
closer to a transformation from a regional post office to a global
logistics company.
</P>
</TEXT>
