<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000904.0252 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 21:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0687 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-HOLLYWOOD-BOWL-NYT     09-04 0609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLYWOOD-BOWL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOW AT THE HOLLYWOOD BOWL, A FIGHT TO PRESERVE THE PAST 
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds., also filed in ``e'' categry) 
 By   DON TERRY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ No one has conducted more performances at the
Hollywood Bowl, under the stars and with the Santa Monica Mountains
as a backdrop, than John Mauceri. ``The Bowl,'' Mauceri, conductor
of the Hollywood Bowl Orchestra, says, ``is magic.''
</P>
<P>
   But there have been too many nights in the middle of a concert
when Mauceri has had to pick up the telephone at the conductor's
stand on stage and whisper into the mouthpiece to the sound
engineer that he is having trouble hearing the trumpets or the
trombones.
</P>
<P>
   For while the Bowl may be magic, the acoustics, Mauceri says,
are simply terrible in its music shell, one of the most
recognizable structures in the city's sprawling landscape. ``It's
extremely problematic,'' he said, ``when the orchestra can't hear
itself.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the decades,'' Mauceri said of the shell, ``all kinds of
things have been put on it, glued on it and hung from it to improve
the acoustics. Nothing has worked.''
</P>
<P>
   The 71-year-old shell is also too small for a 100-piece
orchestra, and so about a third of the musicians are forced to sit
outside it. Further, it is covered in asbestos and lead paint, and
its roof leaks.
</P>
<P>
   So the time has come, say Mauceri and the Los Angeles
Philharmonic Association, the Bowl's manager, for the shell to be
demolished and replaced with a state-of-the-art 21st-century
version costing $18 million.
</P>
<P>
   The money was approved by voters in 1996, and the Los Angeles
County Board of Supervisors is to discuss the association's plan on
Sept. 12. If the board approves, the project should be completed in
2002, and a shell 30 percent larger but otherwise looking very much
like the current one will be standing in its place.
</P>
<P>
   But just hold your baton a few beats, says the city's
preservation movement. So much of the city's history has already
been bulldozed under the seemingly endless rivers of freeway and
acres of development that the Los Angeles Conservancy has come out
against tearing down yet another piece of the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that the shell is the most identifiable icon of the
entire Bowl facility,'' said Ken Bernstein, the conservancy's
director of preservation issues. ``We are not trying to stand in
the way of quality music. We're just trying to raise the right
questions and ensure all the alternatives to demolition are
examined.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the current semicircular shell was erected in 1929, a
parade of musical legends have performed on its stage, from Jascha
Heifetz and Vladimir Horowitz to Frank Sinatra and Ella Fitzgerald
to Bob Dylan and the Beatles. There are dance performances, too,
and artificial stars light up the sky over the Bowl when the city
comes together every Fourth of July to celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   With all that in its past, ``we believe this is a very, very
serious step to lose the shell that has defined the Bowl for 71
years,'' Bernstein said.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few days, the conservancy has had its first chance
to study the philharmonic's environmental impact study on the
demolition and its review of alternatives. Bernstein, for one, is
impressed. ``At this point,'' he said, ``it does appear somewhat
clearer it may be difficult to reconcile saving the shell with
other needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Bernstein said, the group remains officially opposed to
demolition, at least for now. ``This is a difficult issue,'' he
said. ``It's a wonderful place to listen to music, and we're not
disrespectful of the acoustical issues. But the shell is an icon.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
