<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0700 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-ART-NYT &LR;      09-04 1135
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GORE CAMPAIGN: FIVE CITIES, 28 HOURS, ONE MESSAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT2, 3 and 21 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ The best things about a marathon are the
little events that keep people amused along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore's 28-hour spurt over Labor Day across
five cities provided several distractions, all of which contributed
to the picture that the campaign wanted to present of a
hard-working, energetic candidate on the move.
</P>
<P>
   It also afforded Gore an effortless way to show his human side.
Over mushroom omelets in Tampa, Fla., he reminisced with
firefighters about an uncle who was a firefighter and used to take
young Al to see the fire engines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone called him Uncle Punk, except me,'' Gore recalled.
And he talked about the time his furnace exploded and he had to
call the fire department, another everyman adventure that Gore
enjoyed imparting.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the events involved food, and Gore seemed to eat at
every stop.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president burst into song for hospital workers around
midnight in Flint, Mich. He was interviewed by Ed Rendell, the
former mayor of Philadelphia who is now a chairman of the
Democratic Party, for a sports program, giving him a chance to
praise the virtues of athletics, especially for girls.
</P>
<P>
   His staff sang its own lyrics to the tune of ``Route 66'' to
mark the 66 days until Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   He was praised by a speaker at a parade in Pittsburgh for
kissing his wife ``in front of millions of people'' at the
Democratic National Convention. He responded to the roar of the
crowd of 10,000, ``I like people who appreciate a proper kiss.''
</P>
<P>
   And as the hours grew wee, so did Gore's grip on his accent,
which veered toward the homespun, as in: ``I'll be durned if we're
going to go back to the old ways.''
</P>
<P>
   By hour 28, he had become a little punchy. ``I've got
approximately 75,000 cousins in Kentucky,'' he blurted out here. He
said his wife, Tipper, also had cousins here, and, mocking his
habit of asking audiences how long each person has been married, he
called out, ``How many people are related to Tipper?''
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, he derided the big drug companies, calling out,
``I've been at this for 30 straight hours _ you're going to get the
unvarnished truth here, now, you know it!''
</P>
<P>
   The tour began in a downpour in Philadelphia on Sunday
afternoon, with the traditional stop at Pat's King of Steaks for
cheesesteaks.
</P>
<P>
   It ended Monday night here at the Motor Speedway. In between,
Gore, with Sen. Joseph Lieberman, his running mate, at his side for
part of the trip, hit Flint, Mich., Tampa and Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Their message was one of alliance with working families _ and
against the tax cut proposed by Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, whose
name was rarely mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   As Gore put it to about 1,000 people who showed up at the Tampa
firehouse before dawn: ``If you give all that surplus away in the
form of a giant tax cut mainly to the wealthy, you're going to have
the top 1 percent get richer and richer, and maybe there's some
benefit to that. We're not against people getting rich; everybody
wants to be, I guess. But look at the public investment. How can we
stand by if the rich get richer and the poor get poorer, and the
public investment in schools and hospitals and the environment and
libraries all are falling into disrepair and decay? We need to
start looking out after the middle-class families.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman paid homage in his own way to organized labor.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the labor movement were a religion _ and in some ways it is
_ Flint, Mich., would be a holy city,'' he proclaimed to a
union-bolstered crowd that greeted them at the Flint airport.
</P>
<P>
   Later, at the Hurley Medical Center in Flint, Gore spoke
sorrowfully of the recent death of Joe Abraham, the head of the
local union of the American Federation of State, County and
Municipal Employees.
</P>
<P>
   He was addressing health-care workers and telling them about the
crowd at the airport. ``They said we wouldn't have a crowd close to
midnight,'' he mused, then added: ``What's that song?'' Then he
began singing, ``Close to Midnight. ...''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the tour, Gore found lines that garnered a good
response, most especially a declaration to ``make most college
tuition tax-deductible.'' He derided health maintenance
organizations by saying they were controlled by ``bean counters
behind the computer terminal.'' When he riled up the crowd, he
asked them, ``Are you with me? Are you with me?''
</P>
<P>
   He and Lieberman staged a cozy scene for the cameras Sunday
morning at 4:20 a.m., after they landed in Tampa. They walked down
the stairs of Air Force Two, picked up a newspaper that had been
placed there, then walked back up to the plane, like a couple going
back inside their house.
</P>
<P>
   The togetherness of the two has been striking over the last
several days. They tend to wear similar outfits (khakis and sports
shirts, then jeans and polo shirts), and Lieberman knows his place.
He introduces Gore, they hug heartily, then he moves to the
background and sits still, a reassuring presence.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, who has criticized the Hollywood culture, spoke with
some authority Monday in praising Gore's wife for leading a push
for warning labels on music. ``Long before it became fashionable,
Tipper led the battle to protect our children from a lot of the
violence and vulgarity in the popular culture,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And Gore covered nicely for Lieberman on Air Force Two around 2
a.m., when Gore was chirpily telling groggy reporters about his
many all-nighters (including two in a row in 1998 to write his
father's eulogy).
</P>
<P>
   Where was Lieberman?
</P>
<P>
   ``He's reflecting,'' Gore replied.
</P>
<P>
   The two made a brief appearance on NBC's ``Today Show,'' where
the subject turned to Lieberman's repeated references to his faith.
He was asked whether the emphasis on religion was the result of a
political calculation that this worked to the ticket's advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman replied: ``I spoke what naturally came from my heart
and I think reflects the feeling of the great majority of the
American people. And the man I'm lucky enough to run with shares
those points and said to me, `Joe, be yourself because that's why I
chose you to be my running mate.' And that's what I'm going to
continue to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore agreed. ``I knew he was a man of faith when I picked him,''
he said. ``I believe in what he is saying, we share commitment to
the separation of church and state, but what he is saying is right
for this country.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's right for the American people,'' Gore said, ``and you bet
we're going to keep on saying it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
