<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: SYRIA'S MAN LOSES BY A LANDSLIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN KIFNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon _ The landslide defeat of the Syrian-appointed
government by the billionaire builder Rafik Hariri in elections
that concluded on Sunday has changed the political map of Lebanon
overnight.
</P>
<P>
   But the most intriguing aspect of the sudden shift has been
speculated about in whispers under the din of celebratory
fireworks, car horns and street dancing that went on until nearly
dawn Monday. It is why Syria's new ruler, Bashar Assad, allowed
this to happen.
</P>
<P>
   Hariri's victory came less than three months after the death of
President Hafez Assad of Syria, who had run both countries with an
iron hand for the last 10 years and had meddled in the murky waters
of Lebanon since 1976.
</P>
<P>
   During those years, two Lebanese presidents and a prime minister
perished in mysterious explosions. Political opponents, critical
journalists and errant guerrilla leaders were regularly
assassinated, and countless thousands of civilians died, all as a
result of machinations universally attributed here to Syria.
</P>
<P>
   The last decade has so entrenched Syria's dominance that
virtually all of the players on the Lebanese political scene _
Hariri not least among them _ have ties to Syria. Damascus, a
foreign envoy noted, ``is in the happy situation of having to deal
with friends.''
</P>
<P>
   But the election victory by Hariri and his allies crushed
President Emile Lahoud and Prime Minister Salim Hoss. The two men
were handpicked by Bashar Assad to run Lebanon two years ago after
his father sent him to Lebanon as an internship for power.
</P>
<P>
   Bashar Assad, a 34-year-old eye doctor, was raised to power by
the ruling Baath Party, the generals and the Alawite minority
clique running Syria. Even four weeks ago, the defeat of his
candidates would have seemed unthinkable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The locals are interpreting their mandates rather more widely
than they would have under his father,'' Michael Young, a respected
political analyst here, said dryly.
</P>
<P>
   But is Bashar Assad truly, as Syria's official media said,
determined to foster a new era of freedom? Or is Assad, a
mild-mannered computer enthusiast, just not tough enough for the
job of keeping the fractious Lebanese in line? Has he shifted his
patronage, or has he let the situation slip out of control?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's going to be the most interesting question of the next
few months,'' a Western diplomat said this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   As the official tallies were counted up on Monday, Beirut
newspapers estimated that Hariri and his allies had taken 92 of the
128 seats in Parliament, an overwhelming majority that would seem
to make it impossible for Lahoud to deny him the office of prime
minister, which he held from 1992 to 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Late Sunday night, the president issued a statement saying the
new government would be formed, ``in line with the constitution,''
when the new Parliament assembles in mid-October, implying that he
would avoid a crisis by appointing his sworn enemy, Hariri, to be
prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   ``How are they going to work together?'' the Western diplomat
wondered. ``It is very difficult. These are two very strong-willed
people.''
</P>
<P>
   The overwhelming extent of Hariri's victory was shown by his
elimination of two pillars of the Sunni Muslim establishment in
West Beirut. The city had been gerrymandered into three districts
under Syrian orders to preserve the power of two traditional
leaders and to prevent the emergence of a single dominant leader.
</P>
<P>
   But that that balance was wiped out by Hariri's campaign. One of
those leaders is Hoss, a five-time prime minister, who was beaten
by 11,000 votes by an unknown computer professor, Ghanwa Jalloul,
the first woman ever elected to Parliament from the city.
</P>
<P>
   Bashar Assad did not grow up intending to rule Syria _ or
Lebanon. That role was reserved for his dashing older brother,
Basil, who died in a car crash in 1994. Bashar Assad was plucked
from his medical studies in London, sent through military training,
made a colonel and apprenticed to his father.
</P>
<P>
   He was given the task of running Lebanon in 1998 as part of his
training program. At the time, the country was the turf of the
veteran Syrian vice president, Abdul Halim Khaddam, and of Maj.
Gen. Ghazi Kanaan, of military intelligence, both of whom had been
in charge here for more than 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Both were close to _ many said in the pocket of _ Hariri, then
the free-spending prime minister. In recent weeks, he has
recemented his ties by pledging with three Saudi-based construction
agencies to carry out projects in Syria that could total as much as
$400 million.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of working through the older men, both in his father's
inner circle, Assad struck out on his own, anointing Lahoud, the
military commander, as president. That forced a power struggle in
which Hariri departed and the decent, long-suffering Hoss was named
to replace him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bashar brought this guy in,'' said Young, the Lebanese
political analyst. ``He failed. Someone, somewhere is keeping
score.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in the Syrian system are looking to see how Bashar gets
out of this one.''
</P>
<P>
   While Lahoud had accused Hariri of corruption and of running the
country into debt, matters only got worse under the new
administration.
</P>
<P>
   To voters on Sunday, Hariri suddenly seemed the economic savior,
particularly to Sunni Muslims, who had no strong leader and were
the biggest voters in Lebanon's complicated balloting, intricately
divided by religious sect. But the problems that Hariri faces are
enormous, and there is little evidence that his solutions will
work.
</P>
<P>
   As the election struggle became more bitter, most of the major
figures in Lebanon trooped to Damascus to sit with Assad, as they
had so often when summoned by his father. But the signals that came
out of the meetings seemed mixed, and the situation different. The
young Assad did not hold the icy menace of his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't go back to before '98 when every problem was solved
in Damascus,'' Young said. ``Syria has changed. We have changed.
Israel is gone from the south. I don't think the Lebanese will
willingly return to being so obviously under the Syrian thumb.''
</P>
<P>
   Young said the idea of a change ``has really entered the public
domain.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always phrased very carefully,'' he said. ``Let's
recognize a `new relationship' rather than a direct call for a
Syrian pullout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bashar is in a dilemma. He is certainly in a tight spot. Can
he find a way of operating alternatively in this country? That's at
the heart of this entire episode.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
