</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIGERIA-PRESIDENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NIGERIAN LEADER SEEKS PEACEMAKING ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
   By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Fifteen months after restoring democracy to
Africa's most populous nation for the second time in 20 years,
President Olusegun Obasanjo of Nigeria said Monday that he was
ready to step into a larger role in mediating an end to his
continent's debilitating wars, beginning with Congo.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview shortly after his arrival in New York for a
gathering of world leaders, Obasanjo, whose troops the United
States is now training for peacekeeping duties in Sierra Leone,
said he recently volunteered to go to Congo and talk to President
Laurent Kabila. Kabila has been the primary roadblock to efforts to
end the war, which involves a half dozen African nations, and has
been uncooperative with both the United Nations and the
Organization of African Unity.
</P>
<P>
   Obasanjo's offer was turned down by Secretary-General Kofi
Annan, he said. ``I wanted to go, and I told the secretary-general,
and I was told that it was not opportune yet for me to go,''
Obasanjo said.
</P>
<P>
   They agreed to send Gen. Abdulsalami Abubakar, who during a
short period as Nigeria's military ruler opened the way for the
election last year of Obasanjo.
</P>
<P>
   Obasanjo remains ready, he said. ``I will go,'' he said, adding
that his message is simple. ``Mr. Kabila, your country needs peace.
Nothing should be too much to sacrifice for peace.''
</P>
<P>
   As wars have further weakened countries in sub-Saharan Africa
already devastated by economic problems and AIDS, Annan and other
world leaders have tried to involve Africans more actively in
peacemaking. Nelson Mandela, South Africa's former president, has
negotiated a tentative peace agreement in Burundi. But tensions
between South Africa and Congo have prevented him from playing a
greater role there, where Rwanda, Uganda, Angola, Namibia and
Zimbabwe all have forces.
</P>
<P>
   Obasanjo, who said he had also been asked for advice by the
military government of the Ivory Coast, acknowledged that Nigerians
were waiting for a ``democracy dividend,'' but that this should not
mean he had to look inward.
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria, he said, was not grabbing power, ``but if a situation
comes to which we must react positively in the interest of our
sub-region, or in the interest of our continent or even in the
interest of the world, we would be less than what we should be if
we did not react.''
</P>
<P>
   Until now, Obasanjo, 65, has seemed reluctant to shoulder more
continental responsibilities because he has his own priorities in
Nigeria, now struggling to recover from another period of military
rule that left the country isolated, in debt and facing
Christian-Muslim tensions. He seemed eager to withdraw troops from
an earlier peacekeeping mission in Sierra Leone. Shortly after
taking office, he pressed for an agreement signed in Lome, Togo,
last year ending the war. But flaws in that agreement led to a
resurgence of fighting in May.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said that Nigerian troops cannot remain forever in Sierra
Leone, so we must work out some process by which Nigerian troops
could start the process of disengaging,'' he said Monday. ``That
was why we went for the Lome agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course we will always have domestic priorities,'' he said.
``But our domestic priorities must never prevent us from being a
good neighbor.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking as a general, he offered a prescription for Sierra
Leone. ``We must be strong militarily, but we must not throw
completely overboard what I call the political option,'' he said.
But he ruled out any future political role for Foday Sankoh, the
rebel leader of the Revolutionary United Front who resumed the war
this year and captured 500 U.N. peacekeepers. ``Foday Sankoh is no
longer an issue,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was also appealing to President Charles Taylor of
Liberia, who has been complicit in Sankoh's rebellion and is
accused of funneling diamonds from Sierra Leone through his country
to raise money for arms. Speaking of ``doing what needs to be done
as quickly as possible'' in Sierra Leone, he said, ``What needs to
be done is disarmament, demobilization of everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Obasanjo said speed was important in Congo also. ``We have to
move quickly to get those troops that should not have been there
out of the place,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he thought that the nations involved, including
Zimbabwe, which is propping up the Kabila government, could not
continue spending money on this war. ``The cost of maintaining
troops outside your own territory must be telling on Zimbabwe,'' he
said. ``We know from experience what it is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
