<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-POLITICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STILL POPULAR, MO MOWLAM BIDS GOODBYE TO BRITISH POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Mo Mowlam survived the bombs, bullets, and brickbats of
Belfast, but apparently she could not survive the sniping of
Whitehall, and so the most popular politician in Britain announced
Monday that she is leaving politics.
</P>
<P>
   Mowlam, who shot to international fame as the first female
secretary of state for Northern Ireland, said she would step down
as Cabinet minister within the next year and would not stand for
reelection to Parliament. She said she was considering a new career
in conflict resolution or international politics.
</P>
<P>
   While Mowlam's announcement led the BBC news, it was hardly
surprising to friends and associates of the colorful,
controversial, salty politician. Mowlam, who turns 51 next week,
had told friends that she was unhappy with her relatively
low-profile job, which Prime Minister Tony Blair forced her to take
last year so he could give his friend and confidant Peter Mandelson
the Northern Ireland portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, her friends said Mowlam was deeply wounded by what
she saw as an ungrateful slight by Blair, who had put her in the
Belfast hot seat after he led the Labor Party to a landslide
victory in May 1997. Publicly, she embraced Mandelson and played
the part of loyal soldier.
</P>
<P>
   Despite her immense popularity with ordinary people _ she
routinely topped polls as Britain's most popular politician _
Mowlam had influential enemies. Pro-British Protestant unionists in
Northern Ireland accused her of being ideologically biased toward
Irish Catholic nationalists. She denied it, but in private she told
friends it was easier to get along with nationalists. In an
interview last year, Mowlam said she found unionists more
uncomfortable dealing with a powerful woman.
</P>
<P>
   Blair, while wanting to promote his friend Mandelson, also
wanted to appease unionists by moving Mowlam, his aides concede.
</P>
<P>
   More significant than unionist opposition was Mowlam's
resistance to Blair's initial effort to reassign her in the summer
of 1999, saying she wanted to see the Northern Ireland peace
process through.
</P>
<P>
   In a parliamentary system, no individual Cabinet minister, or
even a prime minister, is considered indispensable. And in parts of
the Blair administration, her refusal to accept a reassignment was
seen as petulant.
</P>
<P>
   She was also regarded within Whitehall as something of a loose
cannon. As the government's drug czar, she recently admitted to
smoking marijuana in her youth. Last month, she suggested that the
royal family leave Buckingham Palace for privately rented
accommodation, leaving more than a few eyes rolling in Whitehall.
</P>
<P>
   But even after Mowlam accepted her reassignment, which she
privately regarded as a demotion, the sniping continued. Anonymous
advisers to Blair were quoted in all the major British papers as
saying that Mowlam's star had burned out, that she was the right
person at the right time in Belfast, but that that time had passed.
</P>
<P>
   An editorial in Monday afternoon's Evening Standard, the first
paper to weigh in on Mowlam's announcement, summarized the
arguments against her and showed that, for all her popularity, she
had many critics.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is a classic example of a politician best suited to
opposition and the back benches, a great public character rather
than a natural governor,'' opined the Standard.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt that her spontaneity and warmth made a
useful contribution to the peace process. . . . But her
indiscipline and unembarrassed vulgarity, which made the public
warm to her, also limited her usefulness as a minister. Once the
time for human gestures had passed, and the hard grind of
negotiation and administration had to be sustained, Ms. Mowlam was
out of her depth.''
</P>
<P>
   More than a few of Blair's top aides, all of them men, have
expressed similar sentiments. According to some of Mowlam's
friends, among them Joan Ruddock, a fellow member of Parliament,
that smacks of sexism.
</P>
<P>
   Seamus Mallon, the first deputy leader of the Northern Ireland
Assembly and the most senior Catholic nationalist politician in
Northern Ireland, paid a warm tribute to Mowlam's skills as a
conciliator and mediator, suggesting that those who disliked her
were envious.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one,'' said Mallon, ``should underestimate the talent of Mo
Mowlam. She is an original.''
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Mowlam met with Blair privately at 10 Downing St.
Monday for 15 minutes, then issued the formal denials that her
friends say were predictable. In an interview with the BBC, Mowlam
said her decision to leave politics was not influenced by the
sniping from anonymous Downing Street advisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nothing to do with British politics, nothing to do with
Number 10. It's a personal decision,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But, on the phone Monday night, a close friend of Mowlam didn't
buy her public explanation.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just Mo being Mo,'' the friend said. ``You and I both
know she was unhappy. I just hope she can find something she's
happy with, because she deserves it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
