u i BC-UN-SUMMIT-BOS &LR;      09-04 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-SUMMIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG CROWD, BIGGER HOPES, FOR UN MEETING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The megashow begins Tuesday. More than 150
presidents and prime ministers are arriving, some with dozens of
aides, children, and, of course, nannies. Fidel Castro is flying in
on his Soviet-made jet. The Israelis and the Palestinians will be
riding bulletproof limos to the Waldorf Astoria, knocking on
President Clinton's door.
</P>
<P>
   And on the 38th floor of UN headquarters, the host of the UN
Millennium Assembly awaits them all, hoping his out-of-this-world
plans to change the world begin to take root.
</P>
<P>
   Called together by Secretary General Kofi Annan, the largest
collection of world leaders ever is converging on New York Tuesday
and Wednesday, to take a stab at setting new goals for the
institution for decades to come.
</P>
<P>
   Last April, when Annan first said he wanted to pull at least
half of the 1.2 billion people out of extreme poverty by the year
2015, give every child at least a primary school education by 2015,
and cut the spread of HIV and AIDS by 25 percent among young people
by 2010, he admitted it ``may seem absurdly ambitious.''
</P>
<P>
   Some do think that.
</P>
<P>
   ``This assembly is essentially a dog-and-pony show,'' said
Walter Russell Mead, a senior fellow at the Council on Foreign
Relations in New York. ``The more sweeping a goal is, the less
likely it is going to be achieved in this age.''
</P>
<P>
   But Annan, who will further outline his hopes for the assembly
when he meets with reporters Tuesday, said this year that ``if the
United Nations does not attempt to chart a course for the world's
peoples in the first decades of the new millennium, who will?''
</P>
<P>
   His top aide, John Ruggie, said in an interview last week that
the expectation from this week's summit was that specific steps
would be made in the next year to overhaul the UN's peacekeeping
operations; to provide duty-free access into Western countries for
goods made in the least developed nations; and to clinch a deal on
greenhouse gases contained in the Kyoto Protocol.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he would win US Senate ratification for the protocol,
Ruggie, a US citizen, said it was bound to happen because ``sooner
or later, people are going to start connecting the melting of the
polar ice cap with the extraordinarily volatile weather conditions
in the US with greenhouse gases. The connection can only be denied
for so long.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruggie said one key to the summit will be to make progress
toward implementing a recent UN report on peacekeeping, which calls
for member states to create several multinational brigade forces so
that effective force can be swiftly deployed.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations was heavily criticized in the report for
peacekeeping failures in Bosnia, Rwanda, Angola, and Sierra Leone,
but Ruggie said much of the responsibility rests with member states
not giving the organization a mandate for a stronger force. He also
pointed to successes in peacekeeping operations in East Timor and
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United Nations is a meaningful organization to the people
of East Timor. It is a meaningful organization to the people of
Kosovo,'' he said. ``It was not a meaningful organization to the
people of Rwanda _ but for one simple reason: the permanent members
of the Security Council did not give the secretary general a
mandate in Rwanda and 800,000 people were killed.''
</P>
<P>
   He specifically noted the United States' role in arguing against
deployment of peacekeepers in Rwanda. The person articulating that
position was then-UN ambassador Madeleine K. Albright, now
secretary of state.
</P>
<P>
   The policy debates and the roll of 193 speakers before the
General Assembly this week _ each talk is limited to five minutes _
will give Americans an opportunity to hear the undeveloped world's
perspectives.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of the West's focus on failed UN peacekeeping missions
and the decision to bypass the Security Council in the wars against
Serbia and Iraq, Third World countries see the UN's mission far
differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``We focus on whose limbs were chopped in off in Sierra Leone or
Liberia, or things going to hell in Bosnia or Afghanistan, but the
bread-and-butter issues for most countries really evolve around
economic and social betterment,'' said Thomas G. Weiss,
presidential professor at City University of New York and author of
``The United Nations and Changing World Politics.''
</P>
<P>
   That means leaders will be talking about 1.2 billion people
living on less than $1 a day. Or confronting the water crisis of
the developing world. Or finding new markets for the poorest
countries.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, much of the attention this week is likely to be
off-site.
</P>
<P>
   Cuba's Castro, who announced only last Friday that he would be
attending the assembly, last came in 1995 and will be making his
fourth appearance at the United Nations since he came to power in
1959. Five years ago, he received more than 400 invitations for
meals and receptions; this time the requests also have been pouring
in.
</P>
<P>
   At the Waldorf Astoria, Clinton's one-on-one meetings with
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat on Wednesday will unfold with much of the world watching to
see if they can rebuild the collapsed Camp David peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   And then there will be the spectacle of it all, from buses and
telephone kiosks bearing banner ads carrying UN messages, to major
traffic jams, to the trails of aides and families of heads of
state.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would not believe the lists of people we are hearing about
from some of the delegations,'' said a US diplomat in New York,
speaking on condition of anonymity. ``It's not just spouses, it's
children and all these nannies. Hotel rooms are booked.''
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line, said Mead, the Council on Foreign Relations
fellow, is to keep expectations low. ``The fact that you have an
organization that heads of state want to appear at, and that you
have a high-profile meeting like this to raise the UN profile
around the world, is a good thing. But don't think much is going to
happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
