<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 22:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0719 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-U.N.-SUMMIT-CLINTON-1     09-04 1343
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.N.-SUMMIT-CLINTON-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TO USE U.N. SUMMIT TO PUSH FOR ONE LAST FOREIGN POLICY
SCORE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also U.N.-PEACEKEEPING) 
 (Eds: Subs 2nd graf to add summit opens Wednesday.) 
 (ART ADV: Photo NYT11 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   President Clinton's foreign policy aides say he plans a
diplomatic whirlwind in New York over the next three days,
including what one senior official called ``the last real chance''
to jump-start the failed talks between Israel and the Palestinians
and what may be prove to be a tense session with China's president
over Beijing's continued missile exports to Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   Those meetings are part of a jammed schedule for Clinton, who
arrives in Manhattan on Tuesday for one of his last opportunities
for major foreign policy accomplishments. Wednesday, he is to open
a three-day series of speeches and discussions by more than 150
world leaders at the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly intent on not sitting on the sidelines while the
presidential campaign speeds into its last two months, Clinton
plans to announce American support for a plan to establish a
permanent United Nations operation, based in New York, for planning
and preparing peacekeeping operations that could be deployed
quickly. At present, they have to be organized on an ad hoc basis.
But Clinton also plans to use the U.N. meeting to insert himself in
an array of simmering world conflicts _ from the Middle East to
Cyprus to the Korean Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Berger, Clinton's national security adviser, said in a
lengthy interview over the weekend that much of Clinton's time will
be spent on one last effort to reconstruct a deal between the
Palestinian leader, Yasser Arafat, and Prime Minister Ehud Barak of
Israel. Clinton is said to want that foreign policy achievement
more than any other in his short time left in office, and he
watched in frustration and anger as it slipped from his grasp at
Camp David in the early morning hours of July 25.
</P>
<P>
   He put most of the blame on Arafat, who was unwilling to sign on
to any agreement that gave him only partial sovereignty over
contested parts of Jerusalem. Arafat also was apparently unwilling
to go along with Clinton's alternative proposal, to announce a
settlement on all issues except Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton later likened the sessions to ``going to the dentist
without having your gums deadened.''
</P>
<P>
   In advance of this week's meetings Clinton dispatched Dennis
Ross, his special Middle East envoy, and CIA Director George Tenet
to try out new formulations. ``There needs to be some flexibility
that would indicate we have some chance of getting real momentum
here,'' Berger said. ``If we are not any further than we were in
Camp David, it will be tough to get this done.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Clinton and Berger have contended that Arafat's
inflexibility was the chief obstacle to an agreement at Camp David.
American officials have made it clear that little has changed since
then.
</P>
<P>
   Berger said that currently there are no plans for three-way
meetings between Arafat, Barak and Clinton. Instead, the president
will shuttle between the two at the Waldorf-Astoria Hotel, starting
Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   No other meetings are formally scheduled, but Clinton's aides
have already laid out a plan for at least two more days of talks.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the atmosphere of the chaotic week at the United
Nations may work against Clinton's hopes. In the seclusion of Camp
David, the president could shut out distractions and some of the
outside pressures bearing down on the leaders in the heat of their
talks. News blackouts were easy to manage, because the press was
kept miles away. Cell phones do not work at Camp David, leaving
just a few land lines for each delegation.
</P>
<P>
   New York will be the opposite: Arafat will be negotiating with
other Arab leaders just blocks away, and Barak will be talking as
he entertains American Jewish groups and others with a strong
interest in how a deal is constructed. Thousands of reporters will
be milling about; the delegations will have every form of
communication at their fingertips.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an ideal atmosphere,'' one former senior official who
was deeply involved in past negotiations said recently. ``I think
the effort is to get enough progress to justify more meetings or
maybe whisking them back to Camp David at the end of the week.''
Berger said he believes any thought of reconvening at Camp David is
premature; nonetheless, Clinton's schedule for week's end has been
left vague, save for a few New York appearances on behalf of his
wife's candidacy for the New York Senate seat.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's meeting on Friday with President Jiang Zemin of China
may be Clinton's last chance to show that he has made a lasting
imprint on American relations with China. He has not seen Jiang in
more than a year, and not since the two countries reached agreement
over China's entry into the World Trade Organization. Although
Clinton contended that the trade accord would yield broader
diplomatic benefits, encouraging China to be more cooperative in
dealing with hot spots around the globe, so far there has been
little evidence of a change in China's attitude.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang, under increasing political pressure at home because of
the scope of China's market-opening concessions, is not likely to
be in a mood to offer Clinton much. Moreover, while the House
approved the WTO accord in the spring by a surprisingly large
margin, the Senate has yet to act. Passage there seems all but
assured, but the Republican leadership has yet to schedule a vote,
part of an elaborate maneuver for political advantage in the last
days of the congressional session.
</P>
<P>
   Berger said that even as the administration works to secure
Senate passage of the trade bill, ``we will be pressing the Chinese
on the question of implementation'' of the WTO accord. Those are
code words for American concern that China will drag its feet on
market openings and continue its efforts _ stepped up in recent
months _ to control Internet content in China.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said earlier this year that such efforts were fruitless
and that eventually, the openness spawned by increased commercial
contacts would undermine the Communist Party's power. He is
unlikely to repeat that prediction, which presumably angered
China's leaders, to Jiang.
</P>
<P>
   One focus of the Friday meeting will be to win Jiang's assurance
that China's missile exports to Pakistan, its longtime ally against
India, will cease. ``We have to get this resolved and we are
seeking further commitments on restraint,'' Berger said. But he
quickly added that he did not expect an accord at this meeting. The
two men are expected to see each other again after the presidential
election, at a meeting of Asian leaders. But by then Clinton's
powers will be all the more diminished in China's eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Berger also said that the two men will discuss Taiwan at some
length, for the first time since the island's longtime opposition
won the presidential election. China made threatening indications
to Taiwan before the election, in an effort to keep independence
forces far from power, but has been far more moderate since the
Nationalist Party lost. Still, there has been little communication
between Beijing and the new government in Taipei.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been urging flexibility, restraint and dialogue and we
have had more success on one and two than three,'' Berger said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's U.N. speech on Wednesday will also endorse a report,
issued by a special advisory group to Secretary-General Kofi Annan,
that a permanent peacekeeping structure be created in New York.
That would sidestep the awkward process of re-creating a
peacekeeping structure each time U.N. forces are needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``In principle we are supportive of what is in the report for a
peacekeeping operation,'' Berger said. ``It parallels what we have
been recommending for several years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-00 2216EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
