<HEADLINE>
ERSTAD MIGHT BE BACK IN LEFT FIELD TONIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Joe Haakenson  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ A strained muscle in his ribcage relegated Angels
outfielder Darin Erstad to designated hitter for the 10th
consecutive game Monday. He missed four games before returning as
the DH.
</P>
<P>
   But manager Mike Scioscia hopes Erstad can return to left field
for tonight's game. Erstad's problem has been throwing the ball,
but Monday he worked out with coach Ron Roenicke in left field and
said it improved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's broken through,'' Scioscia said. ``You've got to
cover some real estate here.''
</P>
<P>
   Comerica Park's outfield is spacious, particularly between left
and center field. It's 398 feet to left center and 420 feet to
straight-away center.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad went 1 for 3 Monday to extend his hitting streak to 10
games. Even though his batting average fell from .363 to .362, he
took over the lead in the race for the A.L. batting title from the
Blue Jays' Carlos Delgado, who fell to .361.
</P>
<P>
   The lone batting champion in Angels history is Alex Johnson, who
batted .329 in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   FYHRIE OFF DL: Pitcher Mike Fyhrie was activated from the
disabled list Monday after recovering from an inflamed right elbow.
His presence was needed because relievers Al Levine and Shigetoshi
Hasegawa were unavailable, having pitched three innings and two
innings, respectively, Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   WELCOME TO THE SHOW: The Angels will call up pitchers Juan
Alvarez (Triple-A Edmonton) and Ben Weber (Double-A Erie) today. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
