<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 22:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0728 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-DAIMLERCHRYSLER-MITSU     09-04 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAIMLERCHRYSLER-MITSUBISHI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAIMLERCHRYSLER ANGLING FOR MORE CONTROL AT MITSUBISHI MOTORS 
</HEADLINE>
   By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ DaimlerChrysler AG, which has based its
hopes for Asian expansion on a partnership with Mitsubishi Motors
Corp. of Japan, is demanding more control in the wake of a scandal
over defective cars that has engulfed Mitsubishi.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief statement Monday, a spokeswoman for DaimlerChrysler
in Stuttgart confirmed that ``we are in talks about the future of
the alliance'' in the context of ``the current challenges facing
Mitsubishi Motor Co.''
</P>
<P>
   Daimler executives said they wanted more control over
Mitsubishi, in which the German automobile manufacturer had been
planning to pay $2 billion for a 34 percent stake.
</P>
<P>
   But they refused to say what form that control might take. NHK,
a Japanese television network, reported Monday that Daimler
executives were demanding that their stake be increased at no extra
cost to 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   That would make Daimler the biggest shareholder in Mitsubishi
Motors, bigger even that Mitsubishi's parent company, Mitsubishi
Corp. But other options include increasing the number of Daimler
executives on Mitsubishi's board from three to four and winning the
right to oust and name a replacement for Mitsubishi's president,
Katsuhiko Kawasoe.
</P>
<P>
   Two of Daimler's top executives, Eckhard Cordes and Manfred
Bischoff, met last Friday with Minoru Makihara, the chairman of
Mitsubishi Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of what happens, the Mitsubishi scandal poses
Daimler's chairman, Juergen Schrempp, with major problems on
opposite sides of the world.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, the merger and de facto takeover of
Chrysler Corp. two years ago has been followed by steadily
dwindling profit margins and the resignations of many top Chrysler
executives, including its chairman, Robert Eaton, and its
president, Thomas Stallkamp.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, DaimlerChrysler surprised and irritated industry
analysts by abruptly canceling a meeting with them scheduled for
this week. The cancellation stirred speculation that Daimler is
either planning another management shake-up or pondering the
release of more bad financial news.
</P>
<P>
   In Asia, Mitsubishi was supposed to strengthen DaimlerChrysler's
minuscule presence. But last month, just a few weeks after the two
companies agreed on the final details of their pact, Mitsubishi
announced the recall of nearly 1 million cars and was forced to
admit that it started keeping defects secret two decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   The defects included faulty fuel tanks, clutches, crankshafts
and brakes. Since 1977, Mitsubishi admitted two weeks ago, managers
had suppressed information about consumer complaints, making
repairs in secret and keeping record of the repairs on separate
books that were concealed from government inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   And the scandal is not over yet. On Sunday, Japanese police
raided Mitsubishi offices for the second time in search of
documents that might provide the basis for charges of a criminal
cover-up.
</P>
<P>
   Financially, the problems with Mitsubishi are much less
threatening to Daimler than the slump at Chrysler, which has caused
Daimler shares to be among the worst performing of Germany's
blue-chip stocks.
</P>
<P>
   But Mitsubishi could prove much more difficult for Daimler to
turn around and use as a base for expanding its Asian presence.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the problems could give Daimler executives leverage
that they have not been able to acquire so far.
</P>
<P>
   Although acquiring 34 percent of Mitsubishi Motors' shares as
originally planned would give Daimler a veto over major board
decisions, it would not give Schrempp or his lieutenants the power
to dictate the details of a tough restructuring plan.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, when Renault SA of France acquired a similar stake
in Nissan Motor in 1999, one of its top executives, Carlos Ghosn,
became tantamount to chief executive of the Japanese company and is
now putting Nissan through a wide-ranging overhaul.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the difference between the two cases is that Nissan has
much more dispersed shareholders, making it easier for Renault to
take command.
</P>
<P>
   As chairman of DaimlerChrysler, Schrempp has repeatedly shown a
determination to seize control. Though the deal with Chrysler was
touted as a ``merger of equals,'' Schrempp overshadowed Eaton from
the first day and Chrysler is now merely the American subsidiary of
a Stuttgart corporation.
</P>
<P>
   Tighter control has not yet brought Schrempp greater rewards,
however. Though the Mercedes-Benz operations are generally
thriving, the Chrysler business has been hammered by competition in
the United States and the company has only been able to maintain
sales growth by giving customers ever-more generous discounts and
thereby sacrificing profitability.
</P>
<P>
   The steady erosion of Chrysler's clout within DaimlerChrysler
could also hinder the restructuring of Mitsubishi. For more than a
decade, Chrysler has had a broad working relationship with
Mitsubishi that included a jointly owned factory in Normal, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   That experience could give Chrysler executives better insight
into Mitsubishi's problems and people. But given Schrempp's
frustrations with Chrysler, it is doubtful he will trust
Mitsubishi's recovery to its managers.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, DaimlerChrysler faces a potentially ticklish legal
issue if it pushes for too much control of Mitsubishi.
</P>
<P>
   Christian Breitsprecher, an automobile analyst at Deutsche Bank,
said that if Daimler were perceived to have taken control of
Mitsubishi, the United States Securities and Exchange Commission
could force it to consolidate Mitsubishi's results with its own.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be a disaster, because it would mean that Daimler
would have to consolidate all of Mitsubishi's debt,'' Breitsprecher
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Karin Funke, a spokeswoman for DaimlerChrysler, said talks with
Mitsubishi have been ``fruitful and cooperative'' and should result
in an agreement in ``the very near future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
