<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 22:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0731 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-R-SCI-CAVE-VISITORS-A     09-04 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-SCI-CAVE-VISITORS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GLORIES OF THE UNDERWORLD ARE UNDER SIEGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeats to add photos to art advisory.)  (ART ADV: Graphic and photos NYT 22, 23 are being sent to NYT
graphics clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(The Science Times) 
 By SANDRA BLAKESLEE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BENSON, Ariz. _ Take a sopping wet underground cavern in a
remote corner of Arizona. Add a man-made entrance with heavy steel
doors to keep out the hot desert air, a misting system to keep the
cavern damp and lights to show off a wonderland of spires,
flowstone, soda straws and other phantasmagorical cave formations.
</P>
<P>
   Then add a human being who, in a one-hour visit, sloughs off
some 60,000 skin fragments, 160 million dust particles, 20,000
clothing-lint particles, 25 quarts of carbon dioxide gas and 170
watts of body heat. Multiply this by 183,000 visitors to the cave
each year.
</P>
<P>
   The result is an ad hoc experiment now under way at Kartchner
Caverns near Benson, Ariz., to learn if it is possible to bring
thousands of people into the fragile environment of a pristine cave
without destroying the cave in the process. Kartchner is the first
major show cave to open in the United States in several decades.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona State Parks system, which owns the land, is trying,
with some difficulty, to balance the interests of visitors with
those of preservationists. Arizona has spent more than $28 million
on monitoring systems and on a visitors center, two man-made
entrances, 1,100 feet of concrete tunnels and 1,225 feet of trails
that lead visitors to large showrooms inside the cavern. One of
these, the Throne Room, is now open. A second, the Big Room,
probably will not open for a few years.
</P>
<P>
   Already, there are signs that the cave is drying out _ compared
with years before the cave opened last November, the average
temperature is up 1 degree and in some spots humidity dropped by
half a percent and evaporation rates quadrupled. And without enough
moisture, Kartchner's formations will stop growing and their colors
will fade.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Travous, director of Arizona State Parks, said that the
changes could be explained by the construction, which is still
under way, and the severe drought in the area.
</P>
<P>
   But a number of leading cave scientists and the two men who
discovered the cavern 26 years ago are worried that park officials
are not heeding signs that the cavern may be in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Kerbo, a leading authority on cave management for the
National Park Service, recently visited Kartchner Caverns. Although
he praised the commitment of the state park officials, he pointed
out problems with lighting, misting, air locks, data collection and
a new proposal to sample cave air and moisture with a system of
plastic tubing called cave suckers. ``It would be better to install
electronic sensors'' to understand changes in cave microclimates,
Kerbo said in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Tufts, co-discoverer of the cave who now does lunar and
planetary research at the University of Arizona in Tucson, said:
``Our main concern is that they don't seem to be on top of data
collection. It's one thing to have a problem and know it and
another to have a problem and not know it.''
</P>
<P>
   Tufts and his caving buddy, Gary Tenen, who today owns two Alpha
Graphics stores in Tucson, found the cave in 1974 when they crawled
into a cavity in the Whetstone Mountains and smelled ``eau de bat
guano'' coming from a three-inch hole in a wall of limestone. They
widened the hole, crawled in and discovered an untouched,
two-and-a-half-mile long, richly decorated ``living'' cave, meaning
its formations were still growing.
</P>
<P>
   Worried that large numbers of amateur cavers would destroy the
pristine cavern simply by exploring it, the two kept the cave's
existence a secret. In 1978, they told the Kartchner family, which
owned the land, about the cave, and in 1988 the family sold it to
the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ironically, we realized that the best way to preserve the
cavern was to develop it as a commercial show cave so that it would
remain under watchful eyes,'' Tenen said. In unsupervised caves,
people cannot seem to stop themselves from breaking off stalactites
that took 10,000 years to grow, writing on walls and strewing
garbage, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In opening the nation's newest cave, the developers of Kartchner
have been able to employ state-of-the-art principles of cave
conservation that are being used to maintain and restore older
caves in other parts of the United States and in Australia, France
and Spain.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Kartchner Caverns is a twisted maze of passageways that open
into two main galleries with 100-foot-high ceilings and 26 smaller
rooms. Apart from spectacular stalactites, stalagmites and columns,
many of the formations sound good enough to eat or put in a living
room at home: fried eggs, bacon, popcorn, turnip shields, soda
straws, draperies, cave cotton, coral pipes, birdnests and miles of
moonmilk, a soft, white claylike substance on cave walls. Some of
the formations are blood red. A viscous mud of unknown depth lies
in many passages, holding water from past floods.
</P>
<P>
   From April to September each year, 1,000 to 2,000 myotis bats
turn one corner of the cave into a bat maternity ward. That corner
will be off limits to visitors then, Travous said. A variety of
microbial life plus 38 invertebrate species munch on bat guano or
each other year round.
</P>
<P>
   Like most limestone caves in the world, Kartchner was formed
when rain water combined with carbon dioxide in the air and carbon
in the soil to form a weak acid solution similar to soda pop. As
this acidic water trickled through limestone, it picked up calcium
in the rock. When it reached air in underground passages carved by
water running underground, each droplet gave up carbon dixode gas
and left calcium carbonate in tiny rings that grew into the yummy
sounding cave formations.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge at Kartchner is that this wet underworld lies in a
desert where the surface evaporation rate is 800 times greater than
inside the cave. If completely opened to surface air, the cave
would dry out in a week, Travous said.
</P>
<P>
   Before opening it to the public, scientists spent two years
taking baseline measurements of air and soil temperatures, relative
humidity, evaporation rates, gases and airflow patterns within the
cave.
</P>
<P>
   It is an extremely fragile environment, said Robert Buecher, a
civil engineer who led the monitoring study and is a leading
authority on cave climates. The original entrance allowed very
little air exchange with the surface, he said. If the humidity were
to drop just 0.7 percent from its average before development, to
98.7 percent, he said, the evaporation rate would double and start
to dry out the cave.
</P>
<P>
   Cave climates are tricky and often counterintuitive, Buecher
said. For example, one winter the cave flooded and the relative
humidity went down instead of up. This was because the flood water
was slightly colder than the cave air and, just as a glass of iced
tea in summer collects moisture, the cold water condensed moisture
out of the cave air.
</P>
<P>
   But people are the biggest threat to cave health, Kerbo said. At
Carlsbad Caverns in New Mexico, people snap off and carry away
2,000 to 3,000 pieces of cave formation each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone who goes into a cave leaves behind a belly button
full of lint, skin cells and dust,'' said Tom Aley, owner and
director of the Ozark Underground Laboratory, a cavern dedicated to
teaching and research in Protem, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   People carry enough dust on the surface of their clothing fibers
to cover the area of two tennis courts, said Neville Michie, a cave
climate expert at Macquarie University in Marsfield, Australia.
Walking through a cave, each person drops one microgram of dust per
second, Michie said. The dust travels to the corners of a cavern
and dulls the formations. Skin cells and lint, which are heavier
than dust, accumulate near trails in nasty-looking grayish black
mats or can even hang from the ceiling in ``lintcicles.''
</P>
<P>
   Flakes of skin are little life rafts for bacteria that float
into the cave and compete with native bacteria, often taking over.
Moreover, most lint contains phosphates from detergents, and
phosphates are essentially fertilizers for algae, which can take
root in the cave formations and cause them to disintegrate.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, people breathe out carbon dioxide, which can change the
deposition rate of calcium carbonate, slowing the growth of
formations. And, of course, people add heat.
</P>
<P>
   All of these problems were anticipated at Kartchner, Travous
said. The entrances and tunnels were dug at the same level of the
natural opening, which prevents air from leaving the cave in a
chimney effect. The visitor center, parking lot and other
structures were built downhill within a different drainage system.
Two huge walk-in freezer doors at each entrance serve as airlocks
to the entrance tunnel and prevent surface air from coming into the
cave.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the tunnel, visitors pass through a smaller third
door that leads to trails for viewing cave formations. Misters,
like those used on vegetables in a supermarket, are on round the
clock, adding two to three gallons of water per hour to the cave.
</P>
<P>
   The trails have 18-inch-high curbs for catching lint and skin
cells, which tend to fall straight to the ground. Trails are hosed
down every night. Lights are turned on only when tours pass through
an area.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most important, Travous said, only 20 people at a time
are allowed on a tour and are watched by two guides.
</P>
<P>
   As for keeping an eye on the cave's climate, 13 monitoring
stations for temperature, humidity and evaporation rate are located
along the tour route and in deeper recesses of the cave. The ``cave
sucker'' system of tubing is being installed in hope of automating
data collection.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if all these measures were working to protect the cave,
Travous said, ``We sure hope so,'' but added, ``We still don't know
what is acceptable change.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The cave is one degree warmer and the humidity is lower in
some places,'' Travous said. ``But if we go back and look at
monitoring data from the past, we've seen these higher temperatures
before. Plus the cave will flood again.''
</P>
<P>
   But many scientists familiar with Kartchner Caverns are worried
that some of the steps taken to protect the cave may ultimately
contribute to its drying out. While the freezer doors keep hot air
out of the cave entrance, the tunnels contain so much air that they
may significantly alter air flow inside the cave, Kerbo said.
</P>
<P>
   The misters might change air flow patterns and temperatures,
Kerbo said. Introduced water could concentrate on mudflats and
other surfaces in a way that interferes with natural processes, he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Buecher said he was worried that data now being collected by
hand were not being compared to baseline. ``If they were, someone
would have sounded the alarm,'' he said. ``The cave is definitely
drying out.''
</P>
<P>
   Travous said that he planned to hire a cave specialist and a
cave scientist to improve monitoring. Scientific advisers will be
invited back at some point, and the idea for cave suckers is being
re-assessed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're under pressure from the Legislature to finish
construction and be fully open to the public,'' he said. ``But we
won't neglect good science in the process.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
