<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-RETURN-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: remains uncertain. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The various policy differences and political jockeying will be
on display from the start. On Thursday, the House leadership has
scheduled a vote on overriding Clinton's Aug. 31 veto of the bill
to phase out federal inheritance taxes. Next week, there will be a
vote in the House on overriding Clinton's veto last week of the
repeal of the marriage penalty.
</P>
<P>
   The president said that ending of the federal estate tax would
be too costly and would mainly benefit wealthy people. The White
House said the federal government would lose revenues of $100
billion in the first 10 years and $750 billion more in the next 10
years.
</P>
<P>
   Because 65 Democrats voted in favor of abolishing the estate
tax, congressional Republicans initially expressed optimism that
the House would strike down Clinton's veto and hand the president
an embarrassing defeat. But it appears that some Democrats will
reverse themselves, that some who missed the first vote will side
with the president, and that the veto will be sustained.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will try overrides on the tax bills; that will be
unsuccessful,'' predicted a top aide to a Republican House leader.
``Then we'll pivot and say to Democrats and Clinton, you can't
spend it either. Our alternative will be to pay down debt and
protect Social Security.''
</P>
<P>
   But the aide added that House leaders had yet to reach an
agreement on such a course of action. ``The big dogs have to sign
off on it,'' the aide said.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Republicans must also devise a strategy to deal
with the White House on the 13 spending bills that must be enacted
by the end of the fiscal year on Sept. 30 to keep the government
functioning.
</P>
<P>
   The House has passed 12 of the 13 bills and the Senate has
approved eight. Two, a $288 billion measure for defense and a much
smaller bill for military construction, have been signed into law.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has threatened to veto eight of the spending bills,
setting the stage for fights over issues like providing money for
school construction, hiring more teachers to reduce class size and
setting aside more federal lands for wilderness areas.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are seeking to paint the administration as the
recalcitrant party, emphasizing that a mere $30 billion, out of a
budget with more than $600 billion in discretionary spending, is
what separates their bills from what the White House wants to
spend. They even note that they are providing the amounts the
president wants for his school construction and class reduction
programs, though, unlike the administration version, the Republican
bill gives local school districts an option of not spending the new
federal aid for those purposes. But White House officials say the
difference is less about amounts than about how the money is to be
spent.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans say any problems reaching agreement with the
administration will benefit them and their presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's going to work this time,'' said Sen. Mitch
McConnell, R-Ky., chairman of the Senate Republican campaign
committee. ``It's going to help Governor Bush because he will
demonstrate that he's the guy who can reach across party lines and
govern. It will illustrate the Clinton-Gore administration's
inability to govern on a bipartisan basis. Let them do it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Patrick J. Kennedy, D-R.I., said that on social policy
the standoff in Congress will help his party. ``The fact of the
matter is the American people support the Democratic caucus issues
_ prescription drugs for seniors, a patients' bill of rights,
education for our future _ and those are the issues that our
Republicans are trying to bill themselves as champions of, but it's
just not working,'' said Kennedy, who is chairman of the House
Democratic campaign committee. ``The American people know it's the
Democrats that are truly on their side.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
