While in Pittsburgh, the vice president then noted a number of
achievements since he and President Bill Clinton took office in
1993, including replacing record federal deficits with record
federal surpluses and building ``the strongest economy in
history.'' (Paul Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) PITTSBURGH -- Sept. 4, 2000 -- GORE -- Democratic
presidential nominee Al Gore took his around-the-clock tribute to
working families to Pittsburgh Monday where he was embraced by a
Labor Day rally of more than 10,000 people, many of them union
steelworkers, boilermakers, teachers and painters. ``I want you to
know that I will fight for you and so will my running mate Joseph
Lieberman,'' Gore told a Labor Day crowd in Pittsburgh. Gore
running to greet supporters while on his way to a rally in Point
State Park. (Paul Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NAPERVILLE, Ill. -- Sept. 4, 2000 -- BUSH -- Opening his
fall campaign with a weeklong tour, Gov. George W. Bush taunted
rival Al Gore on Monday for rejecting his offer of three
presidential debates. ``All of a sudden the words 'anytime,
anywhere' don't mean anything,'' Bush told a Labor Day rally in the
heavily Republican Chicago suburb of Naperville, Ill. Bush and
running mate Cheney walking in the Labor Day parade in Naperville.
(Stephen Crowley/The New York Times)
</P>
