PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
213-237-4577 or PressLink at 800-888-6195. Non-clients can make
individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 4, 2000 -- PODESTA-BROTHERS --
Anthony T. Podesta, right, and Jeffrey Ricchetti, partners in a
lobbying firm, each have a brothers who is a high White House
official. Steve Ricchetti's chief assignment in late 1998 was to
keep Congressional Democrats from voting to impeach or convict the
president. John Podesta, 51, has served as staff secretary, scandal
handler and chief of staff in the Clinton White House. Podesta and
Riccchetti at Podesta.com, in Washington. (Paul Hosefros/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) NEW YORK -- Sept. 4, 2000 -- FOREIGN-SERVICE -- At 32,
Mona Sutphen, was a rising star in the U.S. Foreign Service, but
has recently opted for a career in business-to-business foreign
currency trading with Currenex, an Internet company. This comes as
the State Department is finding it hard to adjust to an era in
which financial markets pack more punch than a career in the
Foreign Service. Sutphen is now the Director of Strategic Planning
and Policy for Currenex. Sutphen in her office in Manhattan.
(Marilyn K. Yee/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) BENSON, Ariz. -- Sept. 4, 2000 -- SCI-CAVE-VISITORS-2 --
At Kartchner Caverns in Benson, Ariz., 1,225 feet of trails lead to
large showrooms. The challenge here is to preserve humidity at a
site that lies under the desert. Skin cells and lint from visitors
can accumulate and after many years can dull a cave's formations.
Lint accumulated in one section of Kartchner Caverns. (Arizona
State Parks/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) BENSON, Ariz. -- Sept. 4, 2000 -- SCI-CAVE-VISITORS --
At Kartchner Caverns in Benson, Ariz., 1,225 feet of trails lead to
large showrooms. The challenge here is to preserve humidity at a
site that lies under the desert. Skin cells and lint from visitors
can accumulate and after many years can dull a cave's formations.
(Arizona State Parks/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) LOUISVILLE, Ky. -- Sept. 4, 2000 -- GORE-3 -- Democratic
presidential nominee Al Gore wrapped up a nonstop 27-hour tribute
to working families Monday with a Labor Day rally at Louisville
Motor Speedway where 1,500 pom-poms waving backers serenaded him
with chants of ``Al Gore, Al Gore.'' Gore, who began a four-state,
Labor Day campaign trek on Sunday afternoon, told the crowd he
would work to raise the minimum wage, reduce middle-income taxes,
expand health care, upgrade schools and keep the economy roaring.
``Are you with me?'' Gore asked. ``Yes,'' the crowd roared. (Paul
Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) CAMDEN, Maine -- Sept. 4, 2000 -- SCULLEY-BROTHERS --
For the last five years John Sculley, center, now 61, has run a
small venture capital firm with his two brothers, Arthur and David.
Previously Sculley ran the domestic soft-drink unit of PepsiCo, and
most recently was the CEO of Apple Computers. He says he is now
content to work with his family and stay clear of corporate
ladders. From left, Arthur, John, and David Sculley, on a dock in
Camden Harbor, Me. (Herb Swanson/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) RONKONKOMA, N.Y. -- Sept. 4, 2000 -- FLIGHT-DELAYS-2 --
Tuesday ends the second straight summer travel season of chronic
flight delays and cancellations across the United States, and
despite spending billions of dollars and repeated warnings in the
last decade of impending air traffic gridlock, there is no solution
in sight. Most experts now believe that delays, which have risen
nearly 50 percent during the last five years, will become worse,
not better. An air traffic controller studying flight patterns at
an FAA facility in Ronkonkoma, N.Y. (Ruby Washington/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) RONKONKOMA, N.Y. -- SEPT. 4, 2000 -- FLIGHT-DELAYS-1 --
Tuesday ends the second straight summer travel season of chronic
flight delays and cancellations across the United States, and
despite spending billions of dollars and repeated warnings in the
last decade of impending air traffic gridlock, there is no solution
in sight. Most experts now believe that delays, which have risen
nearly 50 percent during the last five years, will become worse,
not better. Air traffic controllers studying flight patterns at an
FAA facility in Ronkonkoma, N.Y. (Ruby Washington/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- Sept. 4, 2000 -- N.Y.-SENATE-CAMPAIGN -- On
the streets of Brooklyn Senate candidate Hillary Rodham Clinton
kicked off a Labor Day push for votes Monday, marching in the 33rd
annual West Indian American Day Carnival Parade. Clinton received a
rousing welcome at the parade where supporters by the thousands
shouted out ``Hillary'' and screamed in adoration. Meanwhile,
Clinton's opponent Rick Lazio marched alongside a group of
prominent Erie County Republicans at the Clarence Center Volunteer
Fire Company Labor Day parade near Buffalo. (James Estrin/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- Sept. 4, 2000 -- NY-WEST-INDIAN-PARADE-2 --
Hundreds of thousands of spectators gathered Monday to celebrate
West Indian pride at the 33rd West Indian American Carnival Parade
on on Eastern Parkway in Brooklyn, N.Y. At the celebration Parade
goers were treated to West Indian such culinary specialties as jerk
chicken and Jamaican meat patties, and washed it all down with
sugar cane juice. Participants getting into the rythm of things at
the parade. (Earl Wilson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- Sept. 4, 2000 -- NY-WEST-INDIAN-PARADE-1 --
Hundreds of thousands of spectators gathered Monday to celebrate
West Indian pride at the 33rd West Indian American Carnival Parade
on on Eastern Parkway in Brooklyn, N.Y. At the celebration Parade
goers were treated to West Indian such culinary specialties as jerk
chicken and Jamaican meat patties, and washed it all down with
sugar cane juice. A participant getting into the rythm of the
parade. (Nicole Bengiveno/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) UNDATED -- Sept. 4, 2000 -- ARCTIC-ICE-2 -- During World
War II, when Henry Larsen took a Royal Canadian Mounted Police
ship, the St. Roch, into the fabled Northwest Passage, his boat was
frozen in Arctic ice through two winters, only emerging at the
eastern end after 27 months. The Nadon, renamed the St. Roch II
completed a voyage over the same route in one month, including
leisurely overnight stops at communities visited by the namesake
boat half a century ago. The St. Roch II docked near the Vancouver
Coast. (The Vancouver Maritime Museum/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) UNDATED -- Sept. 4, 2000 -- ARCTIC-ICE-1 -- During World
War II, when Henry Larsen took a Royal Canadian Mounted Police
ship, the St. Roch, into the fabled Northwest Passage, his boat was
frozen in Arctic ice through two winters, only emerging at the
eastern end after 27 months, because it was trapped in ice for two
winters. The original Royal Canadian Mounted Police ship, the St.
Roch, in the 1930s. (The Vancouver Maritime Museum/The New York
Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- Sept. 4, 2000 -- OBIT-RUSSIANOFF -- Penelope
Russianoff, a psychotherapist, writer and lecturer who advised
women on how to assert themselves, died on Aug. 28 at her home on
the Upper West Side of Manhattan. She was 82 and also had a home
and practice in Sherman, Conn. Her practice always included some
celebrity clientele. It grew after the director Claudia Weill
suggested to Paul Mazursky that he cast her as a therapist in his
1978 film ``An Unmarried Woman.'' (Chester Higgins Jr./The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- Sept. 4, 2000 -- U.N.-SUMMIT -- All the
world's problems will be put on the table for discussion at the
U.N. Millennium Summit, running through Friday, as more than 150
kings, presidents and prime ministers arrive in New York. The
summit is billed as the largest-ever gathering of world leaders,
even bigger than the world body's 50th anniversary celebrations
five years ago, which drew some 118 heads of state and government.
Iran's President Mohammad Khatami, center, along with members of
the Iranian delegation at the U.N., Monday. (Richard Perry/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- Sept. 4, 2000 -- N.Y.-PUERTO-RICO-PREACHER
-- The Rev. Yiye Avila, a 74-year-old Puerto Rican and former
bodybuilder turned faith healer, is widely known as the
Spanish-speaking Billy Graham. Avila is a crowd-pleasing force
behind one of the major religious shifts among American Hispanics
in the last quarter century. His satellite-powered ministry, heard
on television and radio across much of the United States and Latin
America, has played a significant role in converting hundreds of
thousands of Roman Catholic Latinos to evangelical Protestant
denominations. Avila in St. Mary's Park in the South Bronx, N.Y.,
Sunday. (Rebecca Cooney/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- Sept. 4, 2000 -- TEN-USOPEN-6 -- Four-time
champion Pete Sampras advanced to the quarter-finals of the U.S.
Open on Monday with a 7-6 (7-4), 6-2, 6-4 victory over South Korean
qualifier Lee Hyung-Taik. The fourth-seeded Sampras had to wait
through a two-hour, 25-minute interruption due to rain before
finishing off his fourth-round victory. Sampras in action against
Taik. (Vincent Laforet/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- Sept. 4, 2000 -- TEN-USOPEN-5 -- Four-time
champion Pete Sampras advanced to the quarter-finals of the U.S.
Open on Monday with a 7-6 (7-4), 6-2, 6-4 victory over South Korean
qualifier Lee Hyung-Taik. The fourth-seeded Sampras had to wait
through a two-hour, 25-minute interruption due to rain before
finishing off his fourth-round victory. Sampras in action against
Taik. (Vincent Laforet/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- Sept. 4, 2000 -- TEN-USOPEN-4 -- Jelena
Dokic, 17, a Wimbledon semifinalist this year, lost a tense
tiebreaker with defending U.S. Open champion Serena Williams 7-6
(9-7), 6-0, Monday, allowing Williams to move within two wins of
playing her sister Venus in an all-Williams U.S. Open final. Dokic
during her match with Williams. (Ozier Muhammmad/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- Sept. 4, 2000 -- TEN-USOPEN-3 -- Jelena
Dokic, 17, a Wimbledon semifinalist this year, lost a tense
tiebreaker with defending U.S. Open champion Serena Williams 7-6
(9-7), 6-0, Monday, allowing Williams to move within two wins of
playing her sister Venus in an all-Williams U.S. Open final. Dokic
during her match with Williams. (Vincent Laforet/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Sept. 4, 2000 -- TEN-USOPEN-2 -- Serena
Williams, 18, last year's U.S. Open champion, captured a
quarter-final berth on Monday, and won a battle of nerves with
Australian teenager Jelena Dokic, saving three set points in a
tense first-set tie-break before storming to a 7-6 (9-7) 6-0
victory, Monday. Just two wins away each from an all-Williams
final, Serena could hardly contain her enthusiasm for the
possibility. Williams in action against Dokic. (Vincent Laforet/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Sept. 4, 2000 -- TEN-USOPEN-1 -- Serena
Williams, last year's U.S. Open champion, captured a quarter-final
berth on Monday, and won a battle of nerves with Australian
teenager Jelena Dokic, saving three set points in a tense first-set
