<HEADLINE>
DISPARAGING A REPORTER; DEMOCRATS APPEAL TO WORKERS; POLKA AND
KIELBASA 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DISPARAGING A REPORTER
</P>
<P>
   At an appearance in Naperville, Ill., on Monday, while waiting
to speak, Gov. George W. Bush, the Republican nominee, leaned over
to his running mate, Dick Cheney, and used an obscenity to describe
a New York Times correspondent, Adam Clymer, who was there. Bush,
his aides said, thought he was speaking privately. But his words
were picked up by a television microphone. Asked later about the
comment, Bush said, ``Well, I regret that a private comment I made
to the vice-presidential candidate made it to the public
airwaves.'' When asked if he wanted to apologize, Bush repeated
that he was sorry the comment was heard. Bush's director of
communications, Karen P. Hughes, said of Clymer: ``There's been a
series of articles that the governor has felt have been very
unfair.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Lelyveld, the paper's executive editor, said: ``This is
at least Adam's eighth campaign. He knows what he is doing. His
work is both fair and accurate. The Times has never heard from the
Bush campaign about Adam. If they have a complaint, they should
convey it to us and we will review it as we do all serious
complaints about our coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Vice President Al Gore, Mark Fabiani, said that
Bush had ``portrayed himself as a person who wants to change the
tone and has broken his promise twice, with negative ads and by
using an expletive in referring to a New York Times reporter.''
</P>
<P>
   DEMOCRATS APPEAL TO WORKERS
</P>
<P>
   Completing a grueling round-the-clock trip to three swing
states, Sen. Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut made a series of Labor
Day appeals on Monday to working-class voters, including an
appearance at an AFL-CIO Labor Day festival in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Lieberman made a visit to workers at Alessi's bakery in
Tampa, Fla., telling them of his father's experience working the
night shift at a bakery. On Sunday, Gore and Lieberman visited
workers at a construction site in Philadelphia, a hospital and a
General Motors plant in Flint, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   POLKA AND KIELBASA
</P>
<P>
   Dick Cheney danced the polka with a Polish beauty queen, spoke a
little Polish and dished out a few plates of kielbasa and stuffed
cabbage in Chicago on Monday. Cheney, whose campaign style has
sometimes been described as aloof in recent weeks, shed his
motorcade and rode the El to the Taste of Polonia festival. At the
festival, Cheney greeted the crowd in Polish. ``Sto lat,'' he said
_ may you live 100 years. Then he spoke about his role as the
secretary of defense under President Bush. ``We were proud to work
with all of you to help bring down the wall and free the peoples of
Eastern Europe,'' he said, to applause.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
TUESDAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH and DICK CHENEY: Allentown, Bethlehem and
Scranton, Pa. AL GORE: Louisville, Ky., and Columbus, Ohio. JOSEPH
I. LIEBERMAN: West Peoria, Ill., and Mehlville and Kansas City, Mo.
</P>
