<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 22:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0742 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TEN-USOPEN-ART-NYT &LR;      09-04 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-USOPEN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME'S UP FOR QUALIFIER AS SAMPRAS ASSERTS HIMSELF 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT 4,5,6,7,8,9 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was just after the rain delay, in between the
exiting day crowd and the incoming night-session fans, when
Hyung-Taik Lee's made-for-television adventure began to unfold in a
studio setting of sorts.
</P>
<P>
   As bright lights flooded Arthur Ashe Stadium Monday night and
cameras traced every move made by Lee, this miracle qualifier,
against the ominous Pete Sampras, only a few extras to this surreal
scene remained in their seats.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, an entire nation was watching Lee's fourth-round match
at the U.S. Open. Before sunrise in Seoul, South Korea, people were
assembling in front of their television sets to watch their
unlikely star on the country's first live broadcast of an Open. On
Sunday afternoon in Queens, diners in a Korean-owned sushi
restaurant stopped him for autographs.
</P>
<P>
   Under this crush of attention, Lee never gave into stage fright.
He was feeling the good vibes from his good-luck buddies in the
friend's box flashing signs like ``Positive-Lee'' and
``Absolute-Lee'' and ``Unquestionab-Lee.'' And before the clouds
unleashed a downpour on Day 8 of the tournament, he was giving
Sampras fits with daring passing shots that whistled in the air.
</P>
<P>
   But on a freakish play in the first-set tie breaker, the
flashbulb-quick Lee raced toward the net to put away a desperate
half-volley by Sampras at 6-4. But as Lee crushed the ball for a
winner, he touched the net with his foot. Instead of a minibreak of
Sampras, the set was over. One two-hour rain delay later, and Lee's
improbable journey was finished as well. The unflustered Sampras
had decoded the unknown threat and advanced to the quarterfinals,
7-6 (4), 6-2, 6-4. Still, Lee, ranked 187th, left with his head
held high.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before, when I would play a ranked player, I would be more
concerned with his ranking and I would be a little afraid,'' Lee
said through his interpreter. ``I might consider myself a coward.
But after this experience, I feel that I can play anyone on any
given day.''
</P>
<P>
   He did not seem nervous at all. During the second-set rain
delay, Lee was spotted in the players' lounge, laughing with his
coach and friends, and popping french fries for a snack. It was
this kind of nothing-to-lose demeanor that Sampras had to guard
against.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always difficult playing someone you've never seen
play,'' Sampras said. ``He came out playing well. He wasn't
overwhelmed by the situation. He came out and held his own.''
</P>
<P>
   He may have been handcuffed by the serve of Sampras, crestfallen
after his blown opportunity in the first-set tie breaker, but his
loss was not due to the distractions whirling around him. The
fourth-seeded Sampras was just too much.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras was just one of the household names to advance Monday.
Depositing her ground strokes with characteristic precision,
top-seeded Martina Hingis completed her postponed match left over
from a soggy Sunday night in a simple 6-2, 6-1 victory against
11th-seeded Sandrine Testud.
</P>
<P>
   The Round of 16 did not unfold as well for other seeded players
in the women's draw. After missing six weeks of play following
Wimbledon with a sore shoulder, fourth-seeded Mary Pierce felt the
pain surface again the moment she delivered her first serve against
Anke Huber.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of blasting away with her typical catapult force, Pierce
could barely put a firm punch on her serve. She could not go on
like that. Once she lost the first set, 6-4, Pierce, the French
Open champion, retired with tendinitis in her right shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what I am thinking right now,'' said Huber, who
is a friend of Pierce's. ``I am happy that I am in the
quarterfinals, but I feel sorry for her. I saw her in the locker
room. She didn't look very happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Pierce's mood was in stark contrast to the smile stretching
across the face of Serena Williams like a banner after she escaped
the unflappable Jelena Dokic, 7-6 (7), 6-0. Last Wednesday, Dokic
was in tears while witnessing a tirade by her father, Damir Dokic,
who was banned for the rest of the tournament. Monday, Dokic was in
position to push aside the defending U.S. Open champion.
</P>
<P>
   But on her second set point in the tie breaker, Dokic was left
with her hands on her hips in dismay when she whipped a backhand
that appeared to clip the line for a winner only to see the
linesman call it out. Instead of set point, the score was 6-6 in
the tie breaker, and Williams closed it out from there. Dokic never
recovered from the questionable call, but exited under sympathetic
applause by a crowd that appreciated her ability to cope under
duress this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to be able to deal with situations,'' said Dokic,
who seems older than 17. ``I did that at Wimbledon, did it here.
You've got to block things out.''
</P>
<P>
   In his own way, Lee managed to do this, too. For a week, his
story had become the center of attention on the grounds of the
National Tennis Center. With his every victory, more nuggets of his
life were uncovered.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great to play on such a great court,'' Lee said through
his interpreter. ``I'm an athlete, whereas a lot of my friends back
home, they're students. I think I would tell them that I learned a
lot about confidence here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
