A0855 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MCDONALDS-AD-COLUMN-N     09-04 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCDONALDS-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: MCDONALD'S BETS OLYMPIC-RELATED IMAGE SATURATION WILL
BOOST SALES 
</HEADLINE>
   By BERNARD STAMLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Though its brand is quintessentially American, its business,
increasingly, is not. So McDonald's is turning these days to
international promotional opportunities _ like the Summer Olympic
Games, coming soon to a television set near you _ and to nearly
everybody else's on the planet, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``We estimate that 65 percent of the world's population will be
watching the Olympics, at one time or another,'' said David Green,
senior vice president and marketing officer for McDonald's
International.
</P>
<P>
   To tap that enormous audience, McDonald's, which first began
sponsoring the Olympics on a national level in 1976, signed on in
1997 as a ``TOP Sponsor'' _ TOP stands for The Olympic Partnership
program. That gave the burger chain a global exclusive to
advertising Olympic tie-ins for its product category, as well as
the right to a physical presence at the games. The company ran its
first exclusive advertisements and served its first official
Olympic burgers in Nagano, Japan, at the 1998 Winter Games; this
month's events in Sydney are the first summer games where it will
have the same rights.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald's operators in the United States and 97 of the 115
locations outside the country will participate in the campaign .
Certain symbols will be used by all McDonald's everywhere _ the
Olympic rings, for example _ and there will be some joint
activities, like the agreement by restaurants in 19 countries to
send workers to help their Australian counterparts flip burgers at
the Olympic Village. But each country has otherwise been encouraged
to develop a regionally appropriate marketing campaign on its own.
</P>
<P>
   That has resulted in several different approaches. In Germany
and Austria, for example, a promotion called ``5 weeks, 5
Continents, 5 burgers'' begins this week. It features one
differently flavored sandwich each week through the end of
September, with each supposedly representing a different area of
the world. (McAmerica, the first sandwich, has ``two beef patties
with cooked onions, two slices of cheese and barbecue sauce.'')
</P>
<P>
   In Asia, children's Happy Meals will include toy characters like
Ronald McDonald playing Olympic sports. Australians will be given
cards with meal purchases that will be good for free food if
Australia's team wins the event specified on the card. And local
Olympic athletes will be featured on bags and on cups in France,
where the company has had its share of public relations problems of
late (anti-globalization activists vandalized an unfinished
McDonald's there last year).
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, Happy Meals will offer ``Olympic-themed
Barbie,'' said Green, and she will be ``trying out for different
events, including one paralympic event,'' where the doll will be in
a wheelchair. There will also be ``taste trials'' of newly flavored
products. This week, McDonald's begins running a new ``Olympic
Smiles'' commercial, which plays off its new theme, ``We love to
see you smile.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about bringing the fun of the Olympics right down to
the customer,'' Green said.
</P>
<P>
   It's also about business, of course. McDonald's and other TOP
sponsors like Coca-Cola, IBM, Visa and Xerox, are estimated to have
paid $40 million apiece for their sponsorships of the 1998 Winter
Games and now the Summer Games in Sydney. And that does not include
the cost of the actual advertising to be done throughout the world,
on television, in print and otherwise, which surely will run to
many, many millions of dollars more.
</P>
<P>
   ``In most countries we are among the biggest national
advertisers,'' Green said.
</P>
<P>
   Is it worth it? McDonald's apparently seems to think so.
Although IBM, for one, has dropped out of TOP, McDonald's has just
signed on for the 2002 Salt Lake City Olympics and the 2004 Athens
summer games, at a reported cost of about $55 million. This even
though it hasn't any single new product on which to focus its
worldwide advertising, which is often a justification for such
costly, flashy advertising buys.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a feel-good campaign,'' said Bob Goldin, executive vice
president of Technomic, , a food industry and restaurant research
and consulting company based in Chicago. He puts the total,
worldwide McDonald's sponsorship and advertising expenditures at
``easily more than $100 million'' for the Sydney Olympics, a sum he
called ``expensive and high risk.''
</P>
<P>
   ``With a lot of companies vying for share of mind, McDonald's is
banking on a lot of image to provide a sales boost,'' he said.
``And that can be tricky and hard to measure.''
</P>
<P>
   But will it work?
</P>
<P>
   Very possibly, according to Goldin.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know how to pull the heartstrings as well as anyone
else,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-00 2315EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000904.0288 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 23:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0858 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-SCULLEY-BROTHERS-ART-     09-04 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCULLEY-BROTHERS-ART-2TAKES-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCULLEY BROTHERS USE CORPORATE SEASONING TO FULFILL DREAM OF FAMILY
FIRM 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Subs to correct John Scully's length of time at Spectrum)  
(ART ADV: Photo NYT20 is being sent to NYT photo clients. A graphic
is being sent to NYT Graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) By HILARY
ROSENBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One evening last summer, Dennis Lynch, a young entrepreneur, was
waiting to meet two potential investors at his company headquarters
in Edgewood, N.Y., where he sells used computer and office
equipment through the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're small-time investors,'' he remembers telling
his associate, Michael Browne. ``John and David Sculley.''
</P>
<P>
   ``John Sculley?'' Browne replied. ``He's the former CEO of
Apple.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynch, who is 30, might be excused for not recognizing John
Sculley's name. The last time Sculley was in the news was in 1994 _
when, just four months after resigning as chief executive of Apple
Computer, he then quit after just four months as chief executive of
Spectrum Information Technologies, a Long Island
wireless-technology company where accounting irregularities had
occurred before Sculley arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Sculley, now 61, has maintained uncharacteristically
low visibility. A Wharton-trained executive, who at 38 was running
PepsiCo's domestic soft-drinks unit, and in 1983 jumped to Apple,
he has for the last five years run a small venture capital firm
with his two brothers, Arthur and David. It is his way of
fulfilling a desire to work with his family _ and to help
proselytize people about the virtues of the Internet without
suffering the corporate intrigue that overwhelmed him at both Apple
and Spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   Now John Sculley focuses on start-ups like Techsmart, the
company founded by Lynch, and serves as mentor and friend as well
as investor. Minutes after starting their meeting, Sculley and his
younger brother were drinking beer with the entrepreneurs and
trading tales about growing up on Long Island. By the end of the
evening, the Sculleys had tentatively committed themselves to
invest $1 million and promised to offer guidance on how to build a
small company into a much bigger one.
</P>
<P>
   Sculley may still be licking his wounds, but he said he is far
happier in his new career. And so are his brothers, who are also
veterans of corporate America. Arthur Sculley, 55, ran J.P. Morgan
&AMP; Co.'s $80 billion private bank until 1995, and David Sculley, 54,
was president of the H.J. Heinz Co.'s domestic operations until
1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the absolute most wonderful time of our lives,'' said
John Sculley, sitting in his Park Avenue office. ``We're in total
control of our ground rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Having fun while teaching young entrepreneurs, he said, now
takes priority over earning maximum returns. By using their own
assets, they do not subject themselves to the pressure of
performing for investors. Nonetheless, he said, they expect high
returns over the long run.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Sculley Brothers LLC has invested in 26 start-ups. Four
are either profitable or breaking even, John said. But their track
record so far, at least as it can be judged from the outside,
leaves something to be desired. Three of the five companies they
backed that have gone public _ like many other Web-based businesses
since the Nasdaq shakeout in April _ now trade at rock-bottom
prices.
</P>
<P>
   One of them, Buy.com, an Internet retailer, closed on Friday at
$2.81, down more than 90 percent from last February's initial
public offering at $30. Another, Talk City, a builder of online
communities, has also plunged, closing on Friday at $1.56 compared
with $12 when shares were first sold to the public in July 1999.
John Sculley said both are doing well but suffering in the market
along with other Internet companies.
</P>
<P>
   Another is NetObjects, which helps businesses build Web sites
and, like other software companies, has been shifting from selling
products to providing online services. Its shares, offered at $12
in April 1999, closed on Friday at $2.97, down by more than 75
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Not to worry, John Sculley said: Before the share prices of
NetObjects and Talk City plunged, Sculley Brothers sold some
holdings at a profit. And since they invested early, they acquired
equity in all three companies well below the price set at the
initial public offering. So the brothers said they remain in the
black.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the collegiality, one reason John Sculley said he enjoys
working with his brothers is that they protect him from a tendency
to take people at their word, which he said had hurt him in the
corporate boardrooms. They also keep him, he said, from being so
dazzled by technology that he does not watch the bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   At Apple, for example, his record of memorable marketing and
increased sales was partly undone by his focus on Newton, a
hand-held computer that was a forerunner of the Palm Pilot but
which never sold well because its technology was flawed. Critics
said that by spending so much time on Newton _ and on trying to
become an industry luminary _ Sculley did not prepare for a price
war that cut revenue of Apple's core product, the Macintosh
computer. The board fired him in 1993. ``I was ambushed at Apple
and pushed out,'' Sculley said.
</P>
<P>
   David Hancock, Apple's former marketing chief, remarked of
Sculley: ``He can be distracted by neat new stuff and can jump at
it. He can get fooled by people. He needs people who can refocus
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Those people are his brothers, Sculley said. ``I have been too
trusting in the past, so it's great to have my brothers there to
help me on this.'' Where John and David, the enthusiastic marketing
guys, can be swept away by an idea, for example, Arthur, the
no-nonsense banker, often plays devil's advocate.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   They first dreamed about working together in the late 1980s
while walking on a beach in Bermuda, where they were attending the
annual meeting of a perfume factory founded by a grandfather. The
idea of banding together in venture capital took shape after John
Sculley left Spectrum and began searching for a new career. While
visiting companies and attending technology conferences, he decided
that the Internet was creating a revolution and that he wanted to
be part of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of John's marketing experience, he understood the
power of the Internet as a business tool and a marketing tool,''
said Joshua Ruch, managing partner of Rho Ventures, a New York
venture capital firm that has invested in some of the same
companies as the Sculleys.
</P>
<P>
   John Sculley also appreciated that this revolution, in its early
days, involved small, private companies out of the public eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really aren't looking for any publicity,'' he said, after
having first declined to be interviewed. ``We aren't trying to
prove anything to anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   He began investing in start-ups and in 1995 became nonexecutive
chairman of LivePictures, an Internet imaging company. Several
months after he gave up the chairmanship in 1998, the company went
bankrupt, though it was then sold to the Toronto-based MGI
Software, allowing investors to break even. (He attributes the
company's failure to ``weak management'' too distant for him to
watch closely.)
</P>
<P>
   But other projects were thriving, including Cambridge Display
Technology, a developer of flat-screen video displays; Veon, which
provides interactive video services; and Sirius Thinking, creator
of the PBS children's program ``Between the Lions.'' Cambridge
Display was sold last year to two private venture capital firms,
delivering a ``very high return'' to the Sculleys and other early
investors, John Sculley said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Arthur joined John to form Sculley Brothers. Arthur
Sculley, also a Wharton graduate, had spent 25 years at J.P.
Morgan, where he said he contracted ``the entrepreneur's bug''
while setting up offices in Hong Kong and Singapore.
</P>
<P>
   John and Arthur pursued projects based on their individual
interests. Arthur co-founded IntraLinks, which distributes
prospectuses for syndicated loans over the Web, and served as
chairman of the Bermuda Stock Exchange as it adopted electronic
trading. That led him to specialize in business-to-business
exchanges, and Sculley Brothers has invested in four _ including
Catex, which trades catastrophe-reinsurance contracts, and
BigMachines.com, where companies can buy and sell industrial
equipment. Another investment, CreditTrade, which serves as an
exchange for credit derivatives, just turned profitable, John said.
</P>
<P>
   David Sculley, 54, joined the family firm in 1996. After 22
years at Heinz in Pittsburgh, four as head of Heinz USA, he said he
became drawn to ``building companies rather than managing
companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Anthony O'Reilly, the Heinz chairman, said he was sorry to see
David Sculley leave, adding: ``He's a great motivator of people.
There's a pulse about him, whether he's talking about ketchup or
the Internet.'' And David Sculley is attentive to profitability,
O'Reilly said.
</P>
<P>
   In creating their business, the Sculley brothers made it a
priority to keep things simple. They dress casually and have no
other partners, working with a few assistants in a spacious office.
</P>
<P>
   Their approach to selecting investments is also straightforward:
They meet only with people they know well or have been referred to
by someone they trust. ``We don't solicit,'' Arthur Sculley said.
``We don't want any business plans.''
</P>
<P>
   Several investments have resulted from John Sculley's Apple
connections. One is Presenter.com, an online conference center
founded in 1998 by Eric Chen, a former Apple engineer. Chen, in
turn, referred the Sculleys to the man who founded Gizmoz, a
company that builds Internet broadcast networks. Sculley Brothers
invested in Cambridge Display Technology on the advice of Herman
Hauser, an engineer who worked on the Newton.
</P>
<P>
   The Sculleys declined to say how much money they have to invest,
only that they put an average of $1 million into each venture. But
they offer services beyond that _ serving as mentors for some
entrepreneurs, attracting new investment for others, and often
ending up on the boards of the companies in which they have
invested.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look for board members with thoughtful ideas and
connections, and they have both,'' said Tom Hirschfeld, a general
partner at Patricoff &AMP;  &UR; Co. &LR;  Ventures of New York, who is a
director of IntraLinks and TalkCity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've all run big divisions,'' Arthur Sculley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we're hands-on.'' John said, ``We've learned lessons from
both our successes and our mistakes that any CEO would have to deal
with.''
</P>
<P>
   Take Gizmoz, for example: Captivated by the potential of the
technology, John Sculley became nonexecutive chairman and persuaded
the founder, Eyal Gever, 30, to move to New York from Israel.
Today, John speaks with Gever nearly every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bring John with me to open doors, but mostly to negotiate,''
Gever said. ``He's guided me on multiple levels.'' John's pitch
helped to persuade America Online to invest in Gizmoz earlier this
year. Sculley also accompanies Gever on television programs, as he
does with other entrepreneurs, using his own celebrity to draw
media attention.
</P>
<P>
   All three brothers have become involved in BigMachines.com, an
industrial-equipment exchange based in Foster City, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   David Sculley helped the founders _ Goerdt Abel, a neighbor of
his in Pittsburgh, and his son, Godard _ develop a business plan.
Arthur guided them on how the exchange would work. John establishes
connections with potential partners and investors.
</P>
<P>
   The three have also contributed to PeoplePC, an Internet
membership buyers' club that went public on Aug. 15 at $10 a share.
Even though it has since fallen to $6.50, the Sculleys' 4 percent
stake, which they acquired for $2.1 million, is now worth about $28
million.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Sculley has made introductions that led to group
memberships. David brought in consultants.
</P>
<P>
   And John advised on marketing and operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of complex operational issues that he just
nailed Day 1,'' said Michael J. Price, a former investment banker
at Lazard Freres, who serves on the PeoplePC board. ``He's got some
of the soundest operating judgment I've ever seen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
