</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-REDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS STILL SEEK SEPTEMBER VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ If the Mets' punchless hitters need an example,
they might want to look to Timoniel Perez. Perez, a 23-year-old
outfielder, is in his first week in the major leagues and may not
know what it means to press.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can tell the new guys are free and easy,'' Tom Robson, the
Mets' hitting coach, said Monday after watching his team flail away
futilely again in a 6-2 loss to the Cincinnati Reds. ``They don't
know about this. Perez is awesome. He's up there swinging. That's
what we've got to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez had two doubles and drove in a run at Cinergy Field and is
three for 10 since his call-up. The rest of the Mets managed only
four hits Monday as the journeyman Elmer Dessens mastered them. It
was the Mets' fourth straight defeat, and they are batting .196 in
their last nine games _ six of them losses.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets hold a four-game lead in the National League wild-card
race, but they trail the Atlanta Braves by one game in the NL East.
The Mets' position is still relatively comfortable, but if their
slump continues, they will quickly be confronted with the notion
that they have entered another September swoon.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Bobby Valentine sees no evil and says no evil. A
scuffling offense? Sure, Valentine said, if that's what you call it
when good pitchers make good pitches against you. Valentine chose
to heap praise on Dessens, who has pitched two good games against
the Mets. He allowed four hits and one run in six and two-third
innings Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like he makes a relatively perfect pitch every time
he pitches against us,'' Valentine said. ``He'd be a Cy Young
winner if he pitched like that every game.''
</P>
<P>
   Robson saw something different. Taking nothing away from Dessens
_ or Rick Ankiel, Darryl Kile, Wade Miller and the others who have
subdued the Mets lately _ this slump is the Mets' doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's us, it's not the pitcher,'' Robson said. ``We're just not
centering the pitches the way we should, we're fouling them off
when we should've hit them and then chasing bad pitches when we get
two strikes. That's what we're doing, and all that leads to not
very much.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' starters have a 4.18 earned run average, the best in
the majors. When the Mets went 25-9 from late July to late August,
they did so largely by winning close, low-scoring games and
rewarding their starting pitchers with victories.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, the pattern has changed, and the Mets are losing
games like that. Al Leiter had a bad feeling when he gave up a
two-run, first-inning home run to Ken Griffey Jr. Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being down 2-zip in the first inning makes their pitcher a
little more comfortable,'' he said, ``and if your lineup is already
pressing, they're going to press a little bit more.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time Griffey struck, swatting an outside slider over the
left-field fence for his 37th home run, the Mets had already missed
one big chance. Perez led off the game with a double, but Dessens
retired the next three Mets and Perez never left second.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds went ahead by 3-0 in the third when Dmitri Young drove
a slider into right field with two outs, bringing in Pokey Reese,
who had singled, stolen second and gone to third on a groundout.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds got their fourth run in the sixth inning, when the
rookie Chris Sexton doubled, again off a first-pitch slider with
two outs, again scoring a runner who had stolen second. ``That was
dumb,'' Leiter said, noting that Dessens was on deck. ``I don't
know what I was thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets had scored in the fifth when a sacrifice fly by Perez
brought home Darryl Hamilton, who had doubled. After that, their
offense continued to slumber.
</P>
<P>
   Edgardo Alfonzo and Mike Piazza drew walks to lead off the
sixth. But Robin Ventura and Todd Zeile flied out and Jay Payton
bounced to Dessens. In all, the Mets were 0 for 14 with runners on
base.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura went 0 for 4, his average dropping below .230 for the
first time since April 24. Zeile is also slumping, his average
under .280 for the first time since May 12.
</P>
<P>
   With little production from their fifth and sixth hitters, the
Mets leave Piazza scant protection. If Ventura and Zeile continue
to slump, that weakness will be exposed in games against the Braves
at the end of this month and, possibly, in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The later you get into the season against certain teams, when
teams get closer to you, they're not going to get beat by Mike,''
said Ventura, who says he feels fine and does not know why he is
struggling. ``They're going to get beat _ if they get beat _ by the
guys behind him.''
</P>
<P>
   To Piazza, who hit his 34th homer in the eighth, the memory of
last September's swoon is ``ancient history.'' But there is no
mistaking it, he said: the Mets' hitters are trying too hard,
pressing. They need to get back to the basics, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this club is resilient,'' Piazza said. ``We've worked
hard to get to this point. We have to dig down deep and find a way
to get it done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
