<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PUERTO-RICO-PREACHER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HISPANIC EVANGELICALS FLOCK TO HEAR A FORCE IN THEIR FAITH 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo NYT10 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By BLAINE HARDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In wheelchairs, on crutches and standing
shoelace-deep in the mud, several thousand Latino evangelicals
waited nearly all afternoon on Monday in a South Bronx park for a
former bodybuilder turned faith healer who is widely known as the
Spanish-speaking Billy Graham.
</P>
<P>
   When the Rev. Yiye Avila, a wiry 74-year-old Puerto Rican with
steel gray hair, finally showed up on stage in St. Mary's Park, he
was more than two hours late. But the wait was far from over. He
had hardly begun to speak when the sky darkened and a late summer
shower exploded into a drenching downpour.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to pray so that God will bring out the sun, the
moon and the stars,'' said Avila, who retreated from the rain to
pray beneath a canopy as his followers, soaked and muddy, waited
patiently for yet another hour. No one complained or even seemed
discouraged.
</P>
<P>
   Avila, a fiery preacher who paces the stage feverishly, speaking
of God, the devil and miracles of faith, is a crowd-pleasing force
behind one of the major religious shifts among American Hispanics
in the last quarter century.
</P>
<P>
   His satellite-powered ministry, heard on television and radio
across much of the United States and Latin America, has played a
significant role in converting hundreds of thousands of Roman
Catholic Latinos to evangelical Protestant denominations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The equivalent of one out of seven Hispanics has left
Catholicism in a little more than a quarter of a century,'' the
Rev. Andrew M. Greeley wrote two years ago in America, the Catholic
weekly. He estimated that about 600,000 Hispanics are lost to the
church every year, adding that ``if this hemorrhage should continue
for the next 25 years, half of all American Hispanics will not be
Catholic.''
</P>
<P>
   Greeley described the loss as ``the worst defection in the
history of the Catholic Church in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   A report last year by the National Conference of Catholic
Bishops acknowledged that the migration of Catholic Hispanics to
other denominations was a substantial threat to the future of the
church in the United States. The report said that evangelical
preachers were succeeding by skillfully linking Scripture to
everyday experience and by instructing believers on a strict code
of behavior that gives sense to their lives.
</P>
<P>
   When the rain finally stopped on Monday and Avila resumed
speaking, he told the audience of his conversion to evangelical
Christianity when he was a young man in Puerto Rico, where he had
been a minor-league baseball player and a professional bodybuilder.
He won the North America title in 1954.
</P>
<P>
   Rheumatoid arthritis was threatening to cripple him until the
night he caught the evangelist Oral Roberts preaching on
television. He then dedicated his life to God and, he said, his
arthritis disappeared. Avila told the crowd in the Bronx on Monday
that sometimes it is good to watch television.
</P>
<P>
   Among the soggy celebrants, there was no shortage of former
Catholics eager to explain the appeal of preachers like Avila.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found that when I went to Catholic church it was like they
were reading a book,'' said Sonia Castro, 40, a bank teller in
Brooklyn who travels three hours each way by subway, train and bus
to attend the Christian Charismatic Church in Elizabeth, N.J. ``But
at my church, it is like I feel the Holy Spirit wrapping his arms
around me.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there were the miracles, or at least the promise of
miracles, that brought dozens of believers in wheelchairs to listen
to Avila, who for nearly four decades has been preaching in major
Latino urban centers across the United States. In the park, those
hoping for miracles sat close to the stage, on Avila's left.
</P>
<P>
   Alicia Santiago, 40, a home-care provider who lives in the
Bronx, took Janice Santos, who is 6 and has cerebral palsy, to the
park.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came to see if he does work miracles,'' said Santiago, who
grew up Catholic. ``Maybe he can work a miracle for her.''
</P>
<P>
   Many others in the crowd spoke of the clarity that evangelical
beliefs bring to their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Catholics, they drink and they dance,'' said Pablo
Padillo, 68, a retired truck driver from the Bronx who was raised a
Catholic but now describes himself as a Pentecostal. ``When you
accept Jesus, you don't do any of those things.''
</P>
<P>
   The essence of Avila's appeal, especially for recent immigrants,
is that he makes sense of what for many is a hard and confusing
life in the United States, according to the Rev. Isaac J. Canales,
a pastor and theologian in Carson, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``His is a very simple, hopeful and conservative message,'' said
Canales, who has spent a number of years analyzing Avila's
ministry. ``He preaches the value of hard work, success and
prosperity in a message that is Christ-centered and
miracle-oriented.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
