<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-WEST-INDIAN-DAY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK'S WEST INDIAN DAY PARADE ROLLS ON ALCOHOL-FREE 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photos NYT15 and NYT16 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JENNIFER STEINHAUER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As they have for years on Labor Day, tens of
thousands of New Yorkers, and the politicians who court them,
descended on Brooklyn on Monday for the West Indian American
Carnival Parade.
</P>
<P>
   As in other years, people ate Caribbean food and danced along
the sidewalks to music blaring from all corners. They wore bright
costumes native to Caribbean islands and rode on floats festooned
with bamboo, crepe paper and silver paint.
</P>
<P>
   But, for the first time, they did not drink alcohol at the
parade _ at least not legally _ because of a ban imposed by the
city last month.
</P>
<P>
   Some participants appreciated the alcohol-free parade.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be out here without having people throwing beer cans at you
is kind of nice as far as I'm concerned,'' said Errol Hassell, a
mechanic from the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   While the parade was generally free of trouble, five people were
arrested, including a women charged with biting a Secret Service
agent protecting Hillary Rodham Clinton, and two men charged with
sexual abuse.
</P>
<P>
   When the city announced the alcohol ban and other new rules for
large parades last month, officials said they were in part a
response to accidents that killed three people at last year's
parade. Two 11-year-old dancers were killed, and another child
hurt, when they were struck by a van, and an 18-year-old man was
killed by a sound truck. Parade organizers protested that alcohol
use was not implicated in any of the accidents.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the opposition to his administration's decision, Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani marched on Monday, and was was greeted with a
cascade of catcalls and boos as he made his way down Eastern
Parkway. ``What are you doing here? We don't need you here,''
yelled Hugh Gardner, a 37-year-old Flatbush resident, as the mayor
walked by his spot along the parkway. ``You're a bum.''
</P>
<P>
   By parade's end, the authorities said, 21 bottle of alcoholic
beverages and 20 cases of beer had been confiscated, and 35
open-container summonses issued.
</P>
<P>
   The woman accused of biting a Secret Service agent in the arm
was identified by the police as Yolande Bobb, 55, of Brooklyn, who
was charged with second-degree assault. The incident occurred as
Bobb was approaching Clinton and the agent interceded, the
authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Claudis Jacob, 40, of Brooklyn, was charged with abusing a
13-year-old girl and held on sexual abuse charges. Cecil Wayland of
Brooklyn, 40, was also charged with sexual abuse, accused of
abusing a 24-year-old woman.
</P>
<P>
   Brooklyn's West Indian parade draws an estimated two million
people, about twice that drawn by the Macy's Thanksgiving Day
Parade in Manhattan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-00 2330EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
