<HEADER>
A0870 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-TECH-GAP-NYT &LR;      09-04 0377
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-TECH-GAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: TECHNOLOGY'S GENDER GAP 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, Sept. 5:
</P>
<P>
   The barriers that keep minorities from enjoying full access to
the technological revolution have been widely commented on. Less
talked about is another ``digital divide:'' The fact that fewer
women are entering today's booming technology fields.
</P>
<P>
   Studies show that women are active users of the new technology
and that female Internet users slightly outnumber male users. But
the paucity of women creating that technology is cause for concern.
The most recent National Science Foundation statistics show that
between 1984 and 1997, the proportion of women receiving bachelor's
degrees in computer science dropped from 37 percent to 27 percent.
Currently, women make up only 20 percent of the information
technology work force.
</P>
<P>
   Because the industry serves the broader needs of society, the
technology workplace ought to reflect the interests of both men and
women. The technology industry badly needs more workers. Women
represent a major untapped source of talent that could solve the
shortage.
</P>
<P>
   Why are there few women in these fields? One reason is that
girls receive little encouragement to explore computers early in
their schooling. Most computer games are male-oriented, and there
are few female role models in technical industries. Women who
perform well in high school math and science are often put off by
male-dominated lecture halls in college. Women who do end up
joining the technology work force have complained about a lack of
opportunity for advancement and an absence of support and
mentoring.
</P>
<P>
   Changes in grade school curriculums could help redress the
imbalance by, for example, using computer programs as tools and
teaching aids in all disciplines, from history to music to biology.
Mentoring programs at all levels of education, from middle school
to college, can also provide women with needed support. The
National Science Foundation is dedicating $2 million in grant money
to find ways of increasing women's participation in technological
fields. Without this and other steps, women will continue to be
discouraged from entering the world of high technology.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-00 2331EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000904.0295 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 23:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0872 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-JOURNALISTS-NYT &LR;      09-04 0510
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-JOURNALISTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: JOURNALISTS UNDER SIEGE  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, Sept. 5:
</P>
<P>
   The editors of two opposition newspapers in Congo are facing the
death penalty. Emile-Aime Kakekese Vinalu's crime was writing two
articles that analyzed a tiff between high-level officials,
complained of disunity in the opposition and said that those who
speak their minds get arrested for crimes against state security.
The government of Laurent Kabila then proved him right. Then
Jean-Pierre Ekanga Mukuna was arrested, apparently for refusing to
give authorities Vinalu's home address. Both men are charged with
high treason.
</P>
<P>
   The beleaguered editors in Congo have plenty of company. A
Serbian journalist, Miroslav Filipovic, is now serving a seven-year
sentence for espionage and disseminating false information after he
reported on the Yugoslav army's war crimes in Kosovo. As
parliamentary elections approach in Azerbaijan, authorities have
arrested the editor of an opposition newspaper on trumped-up
charges that he participated in a hijacking attempt. In Paraguay a
reporter was run over by a car driven by the security chief of the
nation's former comptroller, who is accused of corruption.
</P>
<P>
   The world is seeing an epidemic of government attempts to
silence independent journalists, less through murders than through
legal harassment and physical threats. Paradoxically, the new
repression is in some ways a sign of progress. Azerbaijan was not
persecuting independent journalists 10 years ago, because it had
none. Most nations now attacking journalists are quasi-democracies
and so must put up with at least some independent media. But their
leaders use libel suits and threats to stop reporters from
investigating corruption, and often jail journalists and shut media
down for tax offenses or other pretexts during political campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, respect for a free press comes with democratic
development and economic growth, in part because only a robust
private sector can provide enough advertising to give the media
independence. But a free press is also an integral part of both
kinds of progress and needs more help from the outside today.
Several international groups provide lawyers for accused
journalists, and independent media in places like Yugoslavia get a
big percentage of their budgets from Western governments and
nongovernmental groups. But these donors tend to concentrate on
high-profile nations.
</P>
<P>
   Another strategy is to try to discourage attacks by exposing
them. Turkey, whose bid to join the European Union depends on its
civil rights record, has responded to visits from the Committee to
Protect Journalists by releasing some jailed writers and reporters.
But exposure only works when governments take press freedom
seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Liberia recently arrested a British TV crew investigating
reports of diamond smuggling by President Charles Taylor. When
African leaders, including Nelson Mandela, complained, Taylor
released the four men.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-00 2333EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
