<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USCNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC TURNS DOWN CHANCE TO GET EX-VOLS BACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Scott Wolf  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ There were few high school players USC thought
more of last season than running back Marcus Houston, who spurned
the Trojans to attend this week's opponent, Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Houston's presence as a stark reminder of the runner
they almost had, USC recently turned down a second chance at
getting one of the most highly touted prep tailbacks from two years
ago. Onterrio Smith, who was dismissed from Tennessee by coach Phil
Fulmer after one season, contacted USC and asked for a scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans hotly recruited the Sacramento native two years ago,
when he decided to attend Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted him to spend a year at a junior college to get his
academics and personal life back in order,'' USC coach Paul Hackett
said. ``He clearly wasn't interested in that.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith has since enrolled at Oregon, where he will sit out this
season before he becomes eligible.
</P>
<P>
   Smith made headlines off the field last January because he was
charged with misdemeanor battery after being accused of striking
the mother of his 3-year-old daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Helping hands: USC wide receiver Steve Stevenson, defensive
tackle Bernard Riley, defensive tackle Malcolm Wooldridge and
safety Kyle Matthews of Westlake High came to the aid of an injured
USC student last week.
</P>
<P>
   A female student fell out of her second-story apartment window
and became stuck on top of security bars covering a first-floor
window.
</P>
<P>
   The four players held the student up to relieve pressure until
the fire department could arrive and cut the bars from the window.
The tips of the bars were removed from the student's legs when she
got to the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we did was try to get her to calm down and relax,''
Stevenson said. ``We were holding her for about 10 minutes. At
first, we heard a big scream and we thought someone was messing
around. Then we saw her hanging down.
</P>
<P>
   ``But she came back (Sunday) and is all right,'' Stevenson said.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado connections: USC quarterback Carson Palmer welcomes
this week's game for a special reason: He will be playing against
one of his closest friends, former Santa Margarita High teammate
John Minardi, who is a wide receiver for the Buffaloes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked trash back and forth about who's going to win,''
Palmer said. ``I told him he's lucky he doesn't play defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Minardi briefly played safety for Colorado before returning to
wide receiver. The pair discussed attending Colorado together
before Palmer chose USC.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about it, but it's tough because we had different
interests,'' Palmer said. ``But we talk all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Grootegoed ailing: Hackett said he is concerned over the health
of freshman strong safety Matt Grootegoed, who has missed the past
two practices and is questionable for this week's game after
showing flu-like symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's rundown,'' Hackett said. ``He's not feeling
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensive end Jamaal Williams, who broke his leg in August, had
the cast removed and could begin practicing within two weeks. He
will still redshirt.
</P>
<P>
   Offensive guard Trevor Roberts (sprained foot) will start
running Wednesday, but is expected to miss the game.
</P>
</TEXT>
